ABBAS.d: Plural of ABBA: Father; religious superior; in the Syriac, Coptic, and Ethiopic churches, a title given to the bishops, and by the bishops to the patriarch; a title given to Jewish scholars in the Talmudic period.
ABBAS.e: From Middle English, from Latin, from Ancient Greek, from Aramaic אבא/ܐܒܐ (ʼaḇā, “father”); see abbot.

ABBES.d: Plural of ABBE: Alternative spelling of abbé.

ABETS.d: Plural of ABET: To incite; to assist or encourage by aid or countenance in crime.
ABETS.e: From Middle English abetten, abette, from Old French abeter (“to entice”), from a- (“to”) + beter (“hound on, urge, to bait”), either from Middle Dutch bētan (“incite”) or from Old Norse beita (“to cause to bite, bait, incite”), from Proto-Germanic *baitijaną (“to cause to bite”)...

ABLED.d: Past tense of ABLE: Having the necessary powers or the needed resources to accomplish a task.
ABLED.e:
From Middle English able, from Old Northern French able, variant of Old French abile, habile, from Latin habilis (“easily managed, held, or handled; apt; skillful”), from habeō (“have, possess”) + -ibilis.
Broadly ousted the native Old English magan, which has taken a different m...

ABLES.d: Plural of ABLE: Having the necessary powers or the needed resources to accomplish a task.
ABLES.e:
From Middle English able, from Old Northern French able, variant of Old French abile, habile, from Latin habilis (“easily managed, held, or handled; apt; skillful”), from habeō (“have, possess”) + -ibilis.
Broadly ousted the native Old English magan, which has taken a different m...

ABOUT.e: From Middle English aboute, from Old English onbūtan, from on + būtan (outside of).

ABOVE.d: In or to a higher place.
ABOVE.e: From Middle English above, from Old English abufan, onbufan.

ABUSE.e: From Old French abus, from Latin abūsus (misuse), from abūtor (misuse, consume).

ABUTS.d: Plural of ABUT: To touch by means of a mutual border, edge or end; to border on; to lie adjacent (to); to be contiguous (said of an area of land)
ABUTS.e: From Middle English abutten, from Medieval Latin abuttare and Old French abuter, aboter, abouter (“to touch at one end, to come to an end, aim, reach”), from Old French but (“end, aim, purpose”); akin to Old Norse butr (“piece of wood”). Equivalent to a- (“to”) + butt (“boundary ...

ABYES.d: Plural of ABYE: Alternative form of aby.

ACHED.d: Past tense of ACHE: To suffer pain; to be the source of, or be in, pain, especially continued dull pain; to be distressed.
ACHED.e:
From Middle English aken (verb), and ache (noun), from Old English acan (verb) (from Proto-West Germanic *akan, from Proto-Germanic *akaną (“to ache”)) and æċe (noun) (from Proto-West Germanic *aki, from Proto-Germanic *akiz), both from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eg- (“sin, crime”).
...

ACIDS.d: Plural of ACID: Sour, sharp, or biting to the taste; tart; having the taste of vinegar.
ACIDS.e: From French acide, from Latin acidus (“sour, acid”), from aceō (“I am sour”). Doublet of agita and acetic.

ACING.d: Present participle of ACE: A playing card showing a single pip, typically the highest or lowest ranking card in a game.
ACING.e: Inherited from Middle English as, from Old French as, from Latin as, assis (“unity, copper coin, the unit of coinage”), probably borrowed from Etruscan. Doublet of as. Likely related or deriving ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₁éǵʰs, or otherwise taking from Proto-Indo-Euro...

ACMES.d: Plural of ACME: A high point: the highest point of any range, the most developed stage of any process, or the culmination of any field or historical period.
ACMES.e: Directly borrowed from Ancient Greek ἀκμή (akmḗ, “point, high point”).

ACNED.d: Past tense of ACNE: A skin condition, usually of the face, that is common in adolescents. It is characterised by red pimples, and is caused by the inflammation of sebaceous glands through bacterial infection.
ACNED.e: From New Latin acnē, probably a corruption of Ancient Greek ἀκμή (akmḗ, “point, top”).

ACNES.d: Plural of ACNE: A skin condition, usually of the face, that is common in adolescents. It is characterised by red pimples, and is caused by the inflammation of sebaceous glands through bacterial infection.
ACNES.e: From New Latin acnē, probably a corruption of Ancient Greek ἀκμή (akmḗ, “point, top”).

ACRED.d: Past tense of ACRE: An English unit of land area (symbol: a. or ac.) originally denoting a day's ploughing for a yoke of oxen, now standardized as 4,840 square yards or 4,046.86 square metres.
ACRED.e:
From Middle English acre, aker, from Old English æcer (“field where crops are grown”), from Proto-West Germanic *akr, from Proto-Germanic *akraz (“field”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵros (“field”).
Cognate with Scots acre, aker, acker (“acre, field, arable land”), North Frisia...

ACRES.d: Plural of ACRE: An English unit of land area (symbol: a. or ac.) originally denoting a day's ploughing for a yoke of oxen, now standardized as 4,840 square yards or 4,046.86 square metres.
ACRES.e:
From Middle English acre, aker, from Old English æcer (“field where crops are grown”), from Proto-West Germanic *akr, from Proto-Germanic *akraz (“field”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éǵros (“field”).
Cognate with Scots acre, aker, acker (“acre, field, arable land”), North Frisia...

ACTED.d: Past tense of ACT: Initialism of the Australian Capital Territory: a federal territory of Australia.

ACTOR.d: A person who performs in plays, films, or television.
ACTOR.e: From Latin āctor (doer), from agere (to do, act).

ACYLS.d: Plural of ACYL: Any of class of organic radicals, RCO-, formed by the removal of a hydroxyl group from a carboxylic acid.

ADITS.d: Plural of ADIT: A horizontal or nearly horizontal passage from the surface into a mine, as contrasted with a shaft or vertical entry passage, used for ventilation, haulage, drainage, or other purposes.
ADITS.e: Borrowed from Latin aditus (“entrance, access”), from ad (“to, up to”) + itus (“going, departure”).

ADMIT.d: To allow entry; to confess to be true.
ADMIT.e: From Latin admittere (to send to, let in).

ADOPT.d: To legally take another's child as one's own.
ADOPT.e: From Latin adoptāre (to choose for oneself).

ADULT.d: A fully grown person or animal.
ADULT.e: From Latin adultus, past participle of adolēre (to grow up).

AEONS.d: Plural of AEON: Commonwealth standard spelling of eon.
AEONS.e: From Latin aeon, from Ancient Greek αἰών (aiṓn, “age, era”).

AFROS.d: Plural of AFRO: hairstyle characterized by tightly curled locks and a rounded shape.
AFROS.e: From Afro-. In relation to the sense 2, see latino and anglo.

AGARS.d: Plural of AGAR: A gelatinous material obtained from red algae, especially Gracilaria species, used as a bacterial culture medium, in electrophoresis and as a food additive.
AGARS.e: From Malay agar or agar-agar, both meaning jelly.

AGING.d: Present participle of AGE: The amount of time that some being has been alive, or that some thing has been in existence, as measured from its birth or origin until the present or until some other given reference point. (Often measured in number of years; alternatively in months, days, hours, etc.; see also the usage notes)
AGING.e: From Middle English age, Old French aage, eage, edage, from an assumed Vulgar Latin *aetāticum, derived from Latin aetātem, itself derived from aevum (“lifetime”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eyu- (“vital force”). Compare French âge. Displaced native Old English ieldu....

AGIOS.d: Plural of AGIO: The premium or percentage on a better sort of money when it is given in exchange for an inferior sort. The premium or discount on foreign bills of exchange is sometimes called agio.

AGREE.d: To have the same opinion; to consent.
AGREE.e: From Old French agreer (to receive with favor).

AGUES.d: Plural of AGUE: An acute fever.
AGUES.e:
From Middle English agu, ague, borrowed from Middle French (fievre) aguë, “acute (fever)” (Modern French fièvre aiguë), from Late Latin (febris) acuta (“acute fever”), from Latin acūtus (“sharp, acute”) + febris (“fever”).
Doublet of acute.

AHEAD.d: In or toward the front; forward.

AHEMS.d: Plural of AHEM: The sound of a quiet cough or of clearing one's throat.

AIDED.d: Past tense of AIDE: An assistant.
AIDED.e: Borrowed from French aide ("aid; assistant", as in aide-de-camp (“field assistant”)). More at aid.

AIDES.e: Borrowed from French aide ("aid; assistant", as in aide-de-camp (“field assistant”)). More at aid.

AIMED.d: Past tense of AIM: The pointing of a weapon, as a gun, a dart, or an arrow, or object, in the line of direction with the object intended to be struck; the line of fire; the direction of anything, such as a spear, a blow, a discourse, a remark, towards a particular point or object, with a view to strike or affect it.
AIMED.e: The verb is from Middle English amen, aimen, eimen (“to guess at, to estimate, to aim”), borrowed from Old French esmer, aesmer, asmer, from Latin ad- plus aestimare (“to estimate”), the compound perhaps being originally formed in Medieval Latin (adaestimare), perhaps in Old Fren...

AKEES.d: Plural of AKEE: Alternative spelling of ackee.

ALARM.e: From Old French alarme, from Italian all'arme (to arms!).

ALBAS.d: Plural of ALBA: A type of lyrical poetry, traditionally Provençal, about lovers who must part at dawn.
ALBAS.e: First attested in 1821; borrowed from Occitan alba, ultimately from Latin albus (“white”); compare Spanish alba (“dawn”).

ALBUM.d: A book for photographs or stamps; a collection of recordings.
ALBUM.e: From Latin album (white tablet for public notices).

ALGAS.d: Plural of ALGA: Any of many aquatic photosynthetic organisms, including the seaweeds, whose size ranges from a single cell to giant kelps and whose biochemistry and forms are very diverse, some being eukaryotic.

ALIEN.d: A foreigner; a being from another world.

ALIGN.d: To arrange in a straight line.
ALIGN.e: From French aligner, from à ligne (into line).

ALIVE.e: From Old English on līfe (in life).

ALLOW.e: From Old French alouer, from Latin allaudāre (to praise).

ALOED.d: Past tense of ALOE: The resins of the tree Aquilaria malaccensis (syn. Aquilaria agallocha), known for their fragrant aroma, produced after infection by the fungus Phialophora parasitica.
ALOED.e: From Old English alwe (“fragrant resin of an East Indian tree”), from Latin aloē, from Ancient Greek ἀλόη (alóē), from Hebrew אָהָל (ʾāhāl) or related Aramaic forms, ultimately from Tamil அகில் (akil); reinforced in Middle English by Old French aloes.

ALOES.d: Plural of ALOE: The resins of the tree Aquilaria malaccensis (syn. Aquilaria agallocha), known for their fragrant aroma, produced after infection by the fungus Phialophora parasitica.
ALOES.e: From Old English alwe (“fragrant resin of an East Indian tree”), from Latin aloē, from Ancient Greek ἀλόη (alóē), from Hebrew אָהָל (ʾāhāl) or related Aramaic forms, ultimately from Tamil அகில் (akil); reinforced in Middle English by Old French aloes.

ALONG.d: Moving forward on; through the length of.

ALTOS.d: Plural of ALTO: A musical part or section higher than tenor and lower than soprano, formerly the part that performed a countermelody above the tenor or main melody.
ALTOS.e: Borrowed from Italian alto (“high”). Doublet of old.

ALUMS.d: Plural of ALUM: An astringent salt, usually occurring in the form of pale crystals, much used in the dyeing and tanning trade and in certain medicines, and now understood to be a double sulphate of potassium and aluminium (K₂SO₄·Al₂(SO₄)₃·24H₂O).
ALUMS.e: From Middle English alum, alum, alym, alyme, from Anglo-Norman alum, alun, from Latin alūmen.

AMENS.d: Plural of AMEN: At the end of religious prayers: so be it.
AMENS.e: Inherited from Middle English amen, from Old English āmen, from Ecclesiastical Latin āmēn, from Ancient Greek ἀμήν (amḗn), from Biblical Hebrew אָמֵן (ʾāmēn, “certainly, verily”) (cognate with Arabic آمِينَ (ʔāmīna), Classical Syriac ܐܡܝܢ (ʾāmên)). In Old English, it was used onl...

AMIRS.d: Plural of AMIR: Alternative form of emir.
AMIRS.e: From Arabic أَمِير (ʔamīr, “commander, prince”). Doublet of Amir, emir, admiral, and amira.

AMYLS.d: Plural of AMYL: Synonym of pentyl.
AMYLS.e: From Latin amylum (“starch”), from Ancient Greek ἄμυλον (ámulon, “starch”) from ἀ- (a-, “privative”) + μύλη (múlē, “mill”).

ANGEL.d: A spiritual being serving as a messenger of God.
ANGEL.e: From Latin angelus, from Greek ángelos (messenger).

ANGLE.d: The space between two intersecting lines.

ANKHS.d: Plural of ANKH: A cross shaped like a T with a loop at the top, the Egyptian hieroglyph representing the Egyptian triliteral ꜥnḫ (“life”) and often used as an amulet or charm for this concept.
ANKHS.e: From Egyptian anx-Z1 (ꜥnḫ, “life, to live, symbol for life”).

ANTED.d: Past tense of ANTE: A price or cost, as in up the ante.
ANTED.e: Learned borrowing from Latin ante (“before”). Doublet of and.

ANTES.d: Plural of ANTE: A price or cost, as in up the ante.
ANTES.e: Learned borrowing from Latin ante (“before”). Doublet of and.

ANTIS.d: Plural of ANTI: Opposed to something.
ANTIS.e: Conversion of the prefix anti- to an adjective.

APING.d: Present participle of APE: A primate of the superfamily Hominoidea, generally larger than monkeys and distinguished from them by having no tail.
APING.e: From Middle English ape, from Old English apa (“ape, monkey”), from Proto-West Germanic *apō, from Proto-Germanic *apô (“monkey, ape”), possibly derived from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ep- (“water”), compare Proto-Celtic *abū (“river”) (hence English place name Avon, Irish abha, Wels...

APPLE.d: A round fruit with red, green, or yellow skin.

APPLY.d: To make a formal request; to put to use.
APPLY.e: From Old French aplier, from Latin applicāre.

APSES.d: Plural of APSE: A semicircular projection from a building, especially the rounded east end of a church that contains the altar.
APSES.e: From Latin apsis, hapsis, from Ancient Greek ἁψίς (hapsís, “arch, vault”), from ἅπτω (háptō, “I bind, join”).

AQUAS.d: Plural of AQUA: The compound water.
AQUAS.e: From Middle English aqua (“water”), borrowed from Latin aqua. Perhaps also a learned borrowing directly from Latin. Doublet of ea, Eau, eau, and yeo.

ARCED.d: Past tense of ARC: That part of a circle which a heavenly body appears to pass through as it moves above and below the horizon.
ARCED.e: Inherited from Middle English ark, from Old French arc, from Latin arcus (“a bow, arc, arch”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂erkʷos (“bow, arrow”). Doublet of arch, arco, and arrow.

ARCOS.d: Plural of ARCO: A note in string instrument musical notation indicating that the bow is to be used in the usual way, usually following a passage that is played pizzicato.
ARCOS.e: From Italian arco (“bow”). Doublet of arch and arc.

AREAS.d: Plural of AREA: A measure of the extent of a surface; it is measured in square units.

ARENA.d: A central area for sports or entertainment.
ARENA.e: From Latin arēna (sand), referring to the sand-covered floor.

ARGUE.d: To give reasons for or against something.
ARGUE.e: From Old French arguer, from Latin argūtāre.

ARIAS.d: Plural of ARIA: A musical piece written typically for a solo voice with orchestral accompaniment in an opera or cantata.
ARIAS.e: From Italian aria, metathesis from Latin āerem, accusative of āēr, from Ancient Greek ἀήρ (aḗr, “air”). Doublet of air.

ARILS.d: Plural of ARIL: A tissue surrounding the seed in certain fruits such as pomegranates.
ARILS.e: 1785. From New Latin arillus (compare modern French arille and the English doublet arillus), from Medieval Latin arilli.

ARISE.d: To get up; to come into being.

ARRAY.d: An impressive display; an ordered arrangement.

ARROW.d: A projectile shot from a bow.

ARUMS.d: Plural of ARUM: A flower or plant in the genus Arum
ARUMS.e: From the botanical name Arum, from Latin arum, from Ancient Greek ἄρον (áron).

ARYLS.d: Plural of ARYL: Any univalent organic radical derived from an aromatic hydrocarbon by removing a hydrogen atom.

ASHED.d: Past tense of ASH: Solid remains of a fire.
ASHED.e:
From Middle English asshe, from Old English æsċe, from Proto-West Germanic *askā, from Proto-Germanic *askǭ (compare West Frisian jiske, Dutch as, Low German Asch, German Asche, Danish aske, Swedish aska, Norwegian aske), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eHs-; see it for cognates.
The...

ASHES.d: Plural of ASH: Solid remains of a fire.
ASHES.e:
From Middle English asshe, from Old English æsċe, from Proto-West Germanic *askā, from Proto-Germanic *askǭ (compare West Frisian jiske, Dutch as, Low German Asch, German Asche, Danish aske, Swedish aska, Norwegian aske), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eHs-; see it for cognates.
The...

ASIDE.d: To one side; out of the way.

ASKED.d: Past tense of ASK: To request or petition.
ASKED.e: From Middle English asken, axen, from Old English āscian, from Proto-West Germanic *aiskōn, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eys- (“to wish; request”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian aaskje (“to ask, demand, require”), West Frisian easkje (“to ask, demand, require”), Dutch eisen (“to ...

ASSES.d: Plural of ASS: Any of several species of horse-like animals, especially Equus asinus, the domesticated of which are used as beasts of burden.
ASSES.e: From Middle English asse, from Old English assa, back-formed from assen (“she-ass”), from Celtic (compare Old Irish asan, Old Cornish asen), from Latin asinus. Displaced Old English esol, from Proto-West Germanic *asil, also a loanword from the same Latin word. Sense “stupid pers...

ASSET.d: A useful or valuable thing or person.

ATING.d: Present participle of ATE: simple past of eat
ATING.e:
Probably a remodelling of earlier eat by analogy with other strong verbs such as break:†brake, give:gave, speak:†spake; compare the same process in rare Middle English at (“ate”) besides more usual et.
However, the pronunciation /ɛt/ likely continues Middle English et, from Old E...

ATOMS.d: Plural of ATOM: The smallest possible amount of matter which still retains its identity as a chemical element, now known to consist of a nucleus surrounded by electrons.
ATOMS.e: From Middle English attome, from Middle French athome, from Latin atomus (“smallest particle”), from Ancient Greek ἄτομος (átomos, “indivisible”), from ἀ- (a-, “not”) + τέμνω (témnō, “to cut”, o-grade in τομ-) + -ος (-os). Atoms are so named because they were historically thought...

AUNTS.d: Plural of AUNT: The sister or sister-in-law of one’s parent.
AUNTS.e: From Middle English aunte, from Anglo-Norman aunte, from Old French ante, from Latin amita (“father's sister”). Displaced native Middle English modrie (“aunt”) (from Old English mōdriġe (“maternal aunt”); compare Old English faþu, faþe (“paternal aunt”)). The digraph ⟨au⟩ represe...

AURAS.d: Plural of AURA: A subtle emanation or exhalation of any substance, such as an aroma or odour.
AURAS.e: Borrowed from Latin aura (“a breeze, a breath of air, the air”), from Ancient Greek αὔρα (aúra, “breeze, soft wind”), from ἀήρ (aḗr, “air”). Doublet of east, auster, air, and aria. The slang sense originated in the early 2020s and was popularized on TikTok around May 2024.

AUTOS.d: Plural of AUTO: Clipping of automatic (of a gearbox/transmission).
AUTOS.e: From Ancient Greek αὐτός (autós, “self”), metanalyzed from auto- in words such as automatic, autopilot, and automobile.

AVERS.d: Plural of AVER: To assert the truth of (something); to affirm (something) with confidence; to declare (something) in a positive manner.
AVERS.e: From Middle English averren, from Old French averer, from Early Medieval Latin advērō, a verb derived from Latin vērus (“true”). Compare Modern French avérer.

AVOID.d: To keep away from; to prevent.

AVOWS.d: Plural of AVOW: To declare openly and boldly, as something believed to be right; to own, acknowledge or confess frankly.
AVOWS.e: From Middle English avowen, from Old French avouer, from Latin advocare (“to call to, call upon, hence to call as a witness, defender, patron, or advocate”), from ad (“to”) + vocare (“to call”). Doublet of advoke, avouch, and advocate. Not related to vow.

AWARE.d: Having knowledge or perception of something.

AWING.d: Present participle of AWE: A feeling of fear and reverence.
AWING.e: From Middle English aw, awe, agh, awȝe, borrowed from Old Norse agi, from Proto-Germanic *agaz (“terror, dread”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂egʰ- (“to be upset, afraid”). Displaced native Middle English eye, eyȝe, ayȝe, eȝȝe, from Old English ege, æge (“fear, terror, dread”), fr...

AWNED.d: Past tense of AWN: The bristle or beard of barley, oats, grasses, etc., or any similar bristlelike appendage; arista.
AWNED.e: Inherited from Middle English aw(u)ne, agune, from Old Norse ǫgn (compare Danish avne), from Proto-Germanic *aganō, *ahanō (“chaff”) (compare Old English agnu, Dutch agen, German Ahne, Agen), from Proto-Indo-European *aḱanā (compare Latin agna (“ear of wheat”), Lithuanian ašni̇̀s...

AXELS.d: Plural of AXEL: A jump that includes one (or more than one) complete turn and a half turn while in the air.
AXELS.e: Named after Norwegian skater Axel Paulsen (1855–1938), who in 1882 became the first to perform the jump.

AXILS.d: Plural of AXIL: The angle or point of divergence between the upper side of a branch, leaf, or petiole, and the stem or branch from which it springs.
AXILS.e: From Latin axilla. Doublet of axilla.

AXING.d: Present participle of AXE: A tool for felling trees or chopping wood etc. consisting of a heavy head flattened to a blade on one side, and a handle attached to it.
AXING.e: From Middle English ax, axe, ex, from Old English æx, from Proto-West Germanic *akusi, from Proto-Germanic *akwisī, probably from a Proto-Indo-European *h₂egʷsih₂ (“axe”), from *h₂eḱ- (“sharp, pointed”). Compare German Axt, Dutch aks, Danish økse, Icelandic öxi, and also Latin as...

AXLED.e: From Middle English axel, axle, eaxle, from Old English eaxl (“shoulder, armpit”), from Proto-West Germanic *ahslu (“shoulder”), from Proto-Germanic *ahslō (“shoulder”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱs-l-eh₂, from *h₂eḱs- (“axis, axle”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian acsle (“sho...

AXLES.e: From Middle English axel, axle, eaxle, from Old English eaxl (“shoulder, armpit”), from Proto-West Germanic *ahslu (“shoulder”), from Proto-Germanic *ahslō (“shoulder”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱs-l-eh₂, from *h₂eḱs- (“axis, axle”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian acsle (“sho...

AXONS.d: Plural of AXON: A nerve fibre which is a long slender projection of a nerve cell, and which conducts nerve impulses away from the body of the cell to a synapse.
AXONS.e: From Ancient Greek ἄξων (áxōn, “axis”). Via Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱs- cognate with inherited English axle and other borrowed axis, aisle, ala, atelier.

AYAHS.d: Plural of AYAH: A South Asian female servant, maid or nanny, historically, often one working for Europeans in South Asia.
AYAHS.e: From various Indian languages (e.g. Hindi आया (āyā, “dry nurse, nanny”)), from Portuguese aia (“nurse, governess”), from Latin avia (“grandmother”).

BAAED.d: Past tense of BAA: The characteristic cry or bleating of a sheep.
BAAED.e:
Compare German bäh, mäh; an imitative word.
Notes on phonological development
The pronunciation /bɑː/ is perhaps a development from earlier /bæː/ reflecting the shift of /æː/ to /ɑː/ during the 18th and 19th centuries. Compare Early Modern English bae, bea, both "to baa", respect...

BABAS.d: Plural of BABA: A kind of sponge cake soaked in rum-flavoured syrup.
BABAS.e:
As one of the first utterances many babies are able to say, baba (like mama, papa, and dada) has come to be used in many languages as a term for various family members:
* father: Albanian, Arabic, Western Armenian, Chinese, Hindi, Urdu, Punjabi, Bengali, Greek, Marathi, Mingrelia...

BABES.d: Plural of BABE: A baby or infant; a very young human or animal.
BABES.e:
From Middle English babe, a variant of earlier baban, perhaps from Old English *baba (“boy, child”), from Proto-West Germanic *babō, from Proto-Germanic *babô, reduplicated variant of *ba-, *bō- (“father, brother, close male relation”).
cognates and related terms
Related to Old F...

BACKS.d: Plural of BACK: At or near the rear.
BACKS.e:
From Middle English bak, from Old English bæc, from Proto-West Germanic *bak, from Proto-Germanic *baką, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeg- (“to bend”). The adverb represents an aphetic form of aback.
Compare Middle Low German bak (“back”), from Old Saxon bak, and West Fris...

BACON.d: Cured meat from the back or sides of a pig.
BACON.e: From Old French bacon, from Germanic bakō.

BAHTS.d: Plural of BAHT: The official currency of Thailand, equal to 100 satang.

BAILS.d: Plural of BAIL: Security, usually a sum of money, exchanged for the release of an arrested person as a guarantee of that person's appearance for trial.
BAILS.e: From Middle English baille, from the Old French verb bailler (“to deliver or hand over”) and noun bail (“lease”), from Latin bāiulāre (“carry or bear”), from baiulus (“porter; steward”) (English: bailiff).

BAITS.d: Plural of BAIT: Any substance, especially food, used in catching fish, or other animals, by alluring them to a hook, snare, trap, or net.
BAITS.e: From Middle English bayte, bait, beite, from Old Norse beita (“food, bait”), from Proto-Germanic *baitō (“that which is bitten, bait”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“to cleave, split, separate”). Cognate with German Beize (“mordant, corrosive fluid; marinade”), Old English b...

BAKED.d: Past tense of BAKE: To cook (something) in an oven (for someone).
BAKED.e:
From Middle English baken, from Old English bacan (“to bake”), from Proto-West Germanic *bakan, from Proto-Germanic *bakaną (“to bake”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeh₃g- (“to roast, bake”).

BAKES.d: Plural of BAKE: To cook (something) in an oven (for someone).
BAKES.e:
From Middle English baken, from Old English bacan (“to bake”), from Proto-West Germanic *bakan, from Proto-Germanic *bakaną (“to bake”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeh₃g- (“to roast, bake”).
Cognate with West Frisian bakke (“to bake”), Dutch bakken (“to bake”), Low German backen ...

BALDS.d: Plural of BALD: Having little or no hair, fur, or feathers.
BALDS.e:
From Middle English balled, ballid, bald (“bald”), of uncertain origin. Probably formed from Middle English bal, balle (“ball, round object, knoll, head”). Compare Old Danish bældet (“bald”).
An alternate etymology has Old English bǣl (“fire, flame; funeral pyre”) (from Proto-Ger...

BALED.d: Past tense of BALE: Evil, especially considered as an active force for destruction or death.
BALED.e:
From Middle English bale (“evil”), from Old English bealu, from Proto-West Germanic *balu, from Proto-Germanic *balwą.
Cognate with Low German bal- (“bad, ill”), Gothic 𐌱𐌰𐌻𐍅𐌴𐌹𐌽𐍃 (balweins, “torture”), Old High German balo (“destruction”), Old Norse bǫl (“disaster”).

BALES.d: Plural of BALE: Evil, especially considered as an active force for destruction or death.
BALES.e:
From Middle English bale (“evil”), from Old English bealu, from Proto-West Germanic *balu, from Proto-Germanic *balwą.
Cognate with Low German bal- (“bad, ill”), Gothic 𐌱𐌰𐌻𐍅𐌴𐌹𐌽𐍃 (balweins, “torture”), Old High German balo (“destruction”), Old Norse bǫl (“disaster”).

BALKS.d: Plural of BALK: An uncultivated ridge formed in the open field system, caused by the action of ploughing.
BALKS.e: From Middle English balke, from Old English balca, either from or influenced by Old Norse bálkr (“partition, ridge of land”), from Proto-Germanic *balkô. Cognate with Dutch balk (“balk”), German Balken (“balk”), Italian balcone (“balcony”).

BALLS.d: Plural of BALL: A solid or hollow sphere, or roughly spherical mass.
BALLS.e: From Middle English bal, ball, balle, from an unattested Old English *beall, *bealla (“round object, ball”) or Old Norse bǫllr (“a ball”), both from Proto-Germanic *balluz, *ballô (“ball”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰol-n- (“ball, bubble”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel- (“to b...

BALMS.d: Plural of BALM: Any of various aromatic resins exuded from certain plants, especially trees of the genus Commiphora of Africa, Arabia and India and Myroxylon of South America.
BALMS.e: Inherited from Middle English bawme, borrowed from Anglo-Norman and Middle French baume, from Old French basme, from Latin balsamum, itself from Ancient Greek βάλσαμον (bálsamon). Spelling modified 16th c. to conform to Latin etymology. Doublet of balsam and desman.

BANDS.d: Plural of BAND: A strip of material used for strengthening or coupling.
BANDS.e: Inherited from Middle English band (also bond), from Old English beand, bænd, bend (“bond, chain, fetter, band, ribbon, ornament, chaplet, crown”), from Proto-Germanic *bandą, *bandiz (“band, fetter”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰendʰ- (“to tie, bind”). Middle English band reinfo...

BANED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English bane (“person or thing that destroys life, murderer, slayer; person who destroys the soul; destruction of life, death, doom; poison”), from Old English bana (“person or thing that causes death, murderer”), from Proto-West Germanic *banō, fr...

BANES.d: Plural of BANE: A cause of misery or ruin.
BANES.e: The noun is derived from Middle English bane (“person or thing that destroys life, murderer, slayer; person who destroys the soul; destruction of life, death, doom; poison”), from Old English bana (“person or thing that causes death, murderer”), from Proto-West Germanic *banō, fr...

BANGS.d: Plural of BANG: A sudden percussive noise.
BANGS.e: From Middle English *bangen, from Old English *bangian or borrowed from Old Norse banga (“to pound, hammer”); both from Proto-Germanic *bangōną (“to beat, pound”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰen- (“to beat, hit, injure”). Cognate with Scots bang, bung (“to strike, bang, hurl, thr...

BANKS.d: Plural of BANK: An institution where one can place and borrow money and take care of financial affairs.
BANKS.e: From Middle English banke, from Middle French banque, from Italian banca (“counter, moneychanger's bench or table”), from Lombardic bank (“bench, counter”), from Proto-West Germanic *banki, from Proto-Germanic *bankiz (“bench, counter”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeg- (“to turn,...

BARBS.d: Plural of BARB: The point that stands backward in an arrow, fishhook, etc., to prevent it from being easily extracted. Hence: Anything which stands out with a sharp point obliquely or crosswise to something else.
BARBS.e:
PIE word
 *bʰardʰéh₂
From Middle English barbe, from Middle French barbe, from Old French barbe (“beard, beard-like element”). Doublet of beard.

BARDS.d: Plural of BARD: A professional poet and singer, like among the ancient Celts, whose occupation was to compose and sing verses in honor of the heroic achievements of princes and brave men.
BARDS.e: (15th c.) from Scottish Gaelic bàrd, from Old Irish bard, from Proto-Celtic *bardos (“bard, poet”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷerH- (“praise”), and reinforced by Latin bardus, borrowed from Celtic. Cognate with Latin grātus (“grateful, pleasant, delightful”), Sanskrit गृणाति (gṛ...

BARED.d: Past tense of BARE: Minimal; that is or are just sufficient.
BARED.e:
From Middle English bare, bar, from Old English bær (“bare, naked, open”), from Proto-West Germanic *baʀ, from Proto-Germanic *bazaz (“bare, naked”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰosós, from *bʰos- (“bare, barefoot”).
Cognate with Scots bare, bair (“bare”), Saterland Frisian bar (“...

BARES.d: Plural of BARE: Minimal; that is or are just sufficient.
BARES.e:
From Middle English bare, bar, from Old English bær (“bare, naked, open”), from Proto-West Germanic *baʀ, from Proto-Germanic *bazaz (“bare, naked”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰosós, from *bʰos- (“bare, barefoot”).
Cognate with Scots bare, bair (“bare”), Saterland Frisian bar (“...

BARKS.d: Plural of BARK: To make a short, loud, explosive noise with the vocal organs (said of animals, especially dogs).
BARKS.e: From Middle English barken, berken, borken, from Old English beorcan (“to bark”), from the Proto-West Germanic *berkan (“to bark”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerg- (“to make a noise, growl, bark”), from *bʰer- (“to drone, hum, buzz”). Cognate with Icelandic berkja (“to bark, blu...

BARNS.d: Plural of BARN: A building, often found on a farm, used for storage or keeping animals such as cattle.
BARNS.e: From Middle English barn, bern, bærn, from Old English bearn, bern, contracted forms of Old English berern, bereærn (“barn, granary”), compound of bere (“barley”) and ærn, ræn (“dwelling, barn”), from Proto-West Germanic *raʀn, from Proto-Germanic *razną (compare Old Norse rann),...

BASED.d: Past tense of BASE: Something from which other things extend; a foundation.
BASED.e: From Middle English base, bas, baas, from Old French base, from Latin basis, from Ancient Greek βάσις (básis). Doublet of basis and bass.

BASES.d: Plural of BAS: plural of ba

BASIS.e: From Latin basis, from Greek básis (step, base).

BASKS.d: Plural of BASK: To bathe in warmth; to be exposed to pleasant heat.
BASKS.e: Inherited from Middle English basken, from Old Norse baðask (“to take a bath”, literally “to bathe oneself”), mediopassive form from underlying baða (“to bathe”) + sik (“oneself”), from Proto-Germanic *baþōną and *sek. Doublet of English bathe.

BASTS.d: Plural of BAST: Inner bark of a tree from which rope is traditionally made.
BASTS.e: From Middle English bast, from Old English bæst (“bast, inner bark of trees from which ropes were made”), from Proto-West Germanic *bast, from Proto-Germanic *bastaz (“bast, rope”) (compare the Swedish bast, Dutch bast, German Bast), perhaps an alteration of Proto-Indo-European *...

BATED.d: Past tense of BATE: To reduce the force of something; to abate.
BATED.e: Inherited from Middle English baten (“to abate”), an apheretic form of abaten, from Old French abatre (“to knock down”).

BATES.d: Plural of BATE: To reduce the force of something; to abate.
BATES.e: Inherited from Middle English baten (“to abate”), an apheretic form of abaten, from Old French abatre (“to knock down”).

BATHS.d: Plural of BATH: A tub or pool which is used for bathing: bathtub.
BATHS.e: From Middle English bath, baþ, from Old English bæþ (“bath”), from Proto-West Germanic *baþ, from Proto-Germanic *baþą (“bath”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeh₁- (“to warm”). Corresponding inherited verbs are beath and bathe.

BATTS.d: Plural of BATT: Pieces of fabric or fibre used for stuffing; as for batting or insulation
BATTS.e: Late Middle English in the sense "piece, lump," of uncertain origin, but possibly related to the noun bat with the sense of "beaten" fabric.

BAUDS.d: Plural of BAUD: A unit of data transmission symbol rate; the number of signalling events per second.
BAUDS.e: Borrowed from French baud. Named for French inventor Jean-Maurice-Émile Baudot (1845-1903).

BAWDS.d: Plural of BAWD: One who keeps a brothel, or procures women for prostitution; a procurer or madam.
BAWDS.e: From Middle English bawde, baude, from Old French baud (“bold, lively, jolly, gay”). Doublet of bold. An association with Welsh bawddyn (“dirty fellow, scoundrel”), from baw (“dirt”), was suggested by the Rev. Henry Todd.

BAWLS.d: Plural of BAWL: To shout or utter in a loud and intense manner.
BAWLS.e: From Middle English baulen, from Old Norse baula (“to bellow”) and/or Medieval Latin baulō (“to bark”), both from Proto-Germanic *bau- (“to roar”), conflated with Proto-Germanic *bellaną, *ballijaną, *buljaną (“to shout, low, roar”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel- (“to sound, ro...

BAYED.d: Past tense of BAY: A body of water (especially the sea) contained by a concave shoreline.
BAYED.e: From French baie, from Late Latin baia, probably ultimately from Iberian or Basque badia. Partly displaced native Old English byht, whence bight.

BEADS.d: Plural of BEAD: Prayer, later especially with a rosary.
BEADS.e:
From Middle English bede (“a prayer”), also “a bead for counting prayers” in a peire of bedes (literally “a pair of beads”), from Old English bedu, bed, ġebed (“a request, entreaty, prayer”), from Proto-West Germanic *bedu, *bed, *gabed, from Proto-Germanic *bedō, *bedą.
Cognate ...

BEAKS.d: Plural of BEAK: A rigid structure projecting from the front of a bird's face, used for pecking, grooming, foraging, carrying items, eating food, etc.
BEAKS.e: From Middle English bec, borrowed from Anglo-Norman bec, Old French bec, from Latin beccus, from Gaulish *bekkos, from Proto-Celtic *bekkos (“beak, snout”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bak-, *baḱ- (“pointed stick, peg”). Cognate with Breton beg (“beak”). Compare Saterland ...

BEAMS.d: Plural of BEAM: Any large piece of timber or iron long in proportion to its thickness, and prepared for use.
BEAMS.e:
From Middle English beem, from Old English bēam (“tree, cross, gallows, column, pillar, wood, beam, splint, post, stock, rafter, piece of wood”), from Proto-West Germanic *baum, from Proto-Germanic *baumaz (“tree, beam, balk”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰew- (“to grow, swell”).
...

BEANS.d: Plural of BEAN: Any plant of several genera of the taxonomic family Fabaceae that produces large edible seeds or edible seedpods.
BEANS.e: From Middle English bene, from Old English bēan, from Proto-West Germanic *baunu, from Proto-Germanic *baunō (“bean”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰabʰ- (“bean”). Cognate with Scots bene, bein (“bean”), North Frisian buan (“bean”), Saterland Frisian Boone (“bean”), West Frisian be...

BEARD.d: Hair growing on a man's chin and cheeks.

BEARS.d: Plural of BEAR: A large, generally omnivorous mammal (a few species are purely carnivorous or herbivorous), having shaggy fur, a very small tail, and flat feet; a member of the family Ursidae.
BEARS.e:
From Middle English bere, from Old English bera, from Proto-West Germanic *berō, from Proto-Germanic *berô, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰerH- (“brown”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Boar, Boare (“bear”), West Frisian bear (“bear”), Cimbrian, Mòcheno per (“bear”), Dutch beer (“be...

BEATS.d: Plural of BEAT: A stroke; a blow.
BEATS.e: From Middle English beten, from Old English bēatan (“to beat, pound, strike, lash, dash, thrust, hurt, injure”), from Proto-West Germanic *bautan, from Proto-Germanic *bautaną (“to push, strike”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰewd- (“to hit, strike”). Cognate with dialectal Dutch b...

BEAUS.d: Plural of BEAU: A man with a reputation for fine dress and etiquette; a dandy or fop.
BEAUS.e: From Middle English beau, beu, bew, bewe, from Old French beau, from Latin bellus (“beautiful”). Doublet of bello and boo.

BECKS.d: Plural of BECK: A stream or small river.
BECKS.e:
From Middle English bek, bekk, becc, from Old English bæc, bec, bæċe, beċe (“beck, brook”), from Proto-Germanic *bakiz (“stream”).
Cognate with Old Norse bekkr (“a stream or brook”), Low German bek, beck, German Bach, Dutch beek, Swedish bäck, Doublet of batch. More at beach.

BEEFS.d: Plural of BEEF: The meat from cattle or other bovines.
BEEFS.e:
PIE word
 *gʷṓws
From Middle English beef, bef, beof, borrowed from Anglo-Norman beof, Old French buef, boef (“ox”) (modern French bœuf); from Latin bōs (“ox”), from Proto-Italic *gʷōs, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *gʷṓws. Doublet of cow.
Beef in the sense of “a grudge, ar...

BEEPS.d: Plural of BEEP: The sound produced by the horn of a car, or any similar sound.

BEETS.d: Plural of BEET: Beta vulgaris, a plant with a swollen root which is eaten or used to make sugar.
BEETS.e: From Middle English bete, from Old English bēte, from Latin bēta, possibly of Celtic origin.

BEGIN.d: To start; to come into being.

BELLS.d: Plural of BELL: A percussive instrument made of metal or other hard material, typically but not always in the shape of an inverted cup with a flared rim, which resonates when struck.
BELLS.e: From Middle English belle, from Old English belle (“bell”), from Proto-Germanic *bellǭ. Cognate with West Frisian belle, bel, Dutch bel, Low German Belle, Bel, Danish bjælde, Swedish bjällra, Norwegian bjelle, Icelandic bjalla.

BELOW.d: At a lower level or position.

BELTS.d: Plural of BELT: A band worn around the waist to hold clothing to one's body (usually pants), hold weapons (such as a gun or sword), or serve as a decorative piece of clothing.
BELTS.e: From Middle English belt, from Old English belt (“belt, girdle”), from Proto-West Germanic *baltī̆, from Proto-Germanic *baltijaz (“girdle, belt”), from Latin balteus (“belt, sword-belt”), of Etruscan origin. Cognate with Scots belt (“belt”), Dutch belt, German Balz (“belt”), Dan...

BEMAS.d: Plural of BEMA: A platform from which speakers addressed an assembly.
BEMAS.e: From Ancient Greek βῆμα (bêma, “a step”). Doublet of bima.

BENDS.d: Plural of BEND: To cause (something) to change its shape into a curve, by physical force, chemical action, or any other means.
BENDS.e:
From Middle English benden, from Old English bendan (“to bind or bend (a bow), fetter, restrain”), from Proto-West Germanic *bandijan, from Proto-Germanic *bandijaną (“to bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰendʰ- (“to bind, tie”).
Cognate with Middle High German benden (“to fette...

BERMS.d: Plural of BERM: A narrow ledge or shelf, as along the top or bottom of a slope.
BERMS.e: From Dutch berm (“strip of roadside grass, verge”), probably via French berme, from Middle Dutch barm, baerm, barem (“verge, bank”), from Old Dutch *barm, from Proto-West Germanic *barm, from Proto-Germanic *barmaz (“edge, border, seam”).

BESTS.d: Plural of BEST: superlative form of good: most good.
BESTS.e:
From Middle English beste, best, from Old English betst, betest, from Proto-Germanic *batistaz.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots best (“best”), Cimbrian peste, péste (“best”), Dutch best (“best”), German beste (“best”), Yiddish בעסט (best, “best”), Danish bedst (“best”), Faroese bestu...

BETAS.d: Plural of BETA: The second letter of the Greek alphabet (Β, β), preceded by alpha (Α, α) and followed by gamma, (Γ, γ). In modern Greek it represents the voiced labiodental fricative sound of v found in the English words have and vase.
BETAS.e: From Ancient Greek βῆτα (bêta). Doublet of beth.

BIDED.e: From Middle English biden, from Old English bīdan (“to stay, continue, live, remain, delay; wait for, await, expect; endure, experience, find; attain, obtain; own”), from Proto-West Germanic *bīdan (“to wait”), from Proto-Germanic *bīdaną (“to wait”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰ...

BIDES.d: Plural of BIDE: To bear; to endure; to tolerate.
BIDES.e: From Middle English biden, from Old English bīdan (“to stay, continue, live, remain, delay; wait for, await, expect; endure, experience, find; attain, obtain; own”), from Proto-West Germanic *bīdan (“to wait”), from Proto-Germanic *bīdaną (“to wait”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰ...

BIERS.d: Plural of BIER: A litter to transport the corpse of a dead person.
BIERS.e:
From Middle English beer, beere, bere, from Old English bēr, (West Saxon) bǣr (“stretcher, bier”), from Proto-West Germanic *bāru, from Proto-Germanic *bērō, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer- (“to carry, bear”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Beere (“stretcher, bier”), Dutch baar (...

BIFFS.d: Plural of BIFF: A sudden, sharp blow or punch.

BILES.d: Plural of BILE: A bitter brownish-yellow or greenish-yellow secretion produced by the liver, stored in the gall bladder, and discharged into the duodenum where it aids the process of digestion.
BILES.e: Mid 16th century, via Middle French, from Latin bīlis (“bile”).

BILKS.d: Plural of BILK: The spoiling of someone's score in the crib.
BILKS.e: Uncertain; perhaps a variant form of balk.

BILLS.d: Plural of BILL: A written list or inventory. (Now obsolete except in specific senses or set phrases; bill of lading, bill of goods, etc.)
BILLS.e: From Middle English bille, from Anglo-Norman bille, from Old French bulle, from Medieval Latin bulla (“seal, sealed document”). Doublet of bull (“papal bull; bubble”) and bulla.

BINDS.d: Plural of BIND: To tie; to confine by any ligature.
BINDS.e:
From Middle English binden, from Old English bindan, from Proto-West Germanic *bindan, from Proto-Germanic *bindaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰéndʰ-e-ti, from *bʰendʰ- (“to tie”).
See also West Frisian bine, Dutch binden, Low German binnen, binden, German binden, Danish binde; ...

BINES.d: Plural of BINE: A climbing plant, as hops, which climbs by its shoots growing in a helix around a support (distinct from a vine, which climbs using tendrils or suckers).

BINTS.d: Plural of BINT: A woman, a girl.
BINTS.e:
Borrowed from Arabic بِنْت (bint, “girl, daughter”), from Proto-Semitic *bint-, used to denote a patronym.
The term entered the British lexicon during the occupation of Egypt at the end of the 19th century, where it was adopted by British soldiers to mean "girlfriend" or "bit on ...

BIRDS.d: Plural of BIRD: An animal of the clade (traditionally class) Aves in the phylum Chordata, characterized by being warm-blooded, having feathers and wings usually capable of flight, having a beaked mouth, and laying eggs.
BIRDS.e: From Middle English bird, brid, from Old English bridd (“chick, fledgling, chicken”), of uncertain origin (see Old English bridd for more). Originally from a term used of birds that could not fly (chicks, fledglings, chickens) as opposed to the general Old English term for flying...

BIRTH.d: The emergence of a baby from its mother's body.

BITED.d: Past tense of BITE: To cut into something by clamping the teeth.
BITED.e:
From Middle English biten, from Old English bītan (“bite”), from Proto-West Germanic *bītan, from Proto-Germanic *bītaną (“bite”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“split”).
Cognates include Saterland Frisian biete (“bite”), West Frisian bite (“bite”), Dutch bijten (“bite”), Ger...

BITES.d: Plural of BITE: To cut into something by clamping the teeth.
BITES.e:
From Middle English biten, from Old English bītan (“bite”), from Proto-West Germanic *bītan, from Proto-Germanic *bītaną (“bite”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“split”).
Cognates include Saterland Frisian biete (“bite”), West Frisian bite (“bite”), Dutch bijten (“bite”), Ger...

BIZES.d: Plural of BIZ: Business, especially showbusiness.

BLABS.d: Plural of BLAB: To tell tales; to gossip without reserve or discretion.
BLABS.e: From Middle English blabben (“to talk foolishly”), perhaps from Middle English blabbe (“idle talk; talebearer”). Compare Middle English blaberen (“to blabber, babble”), Middle High German blabezen (“to stammer, babble”).

BLACK.d: The darkest colour, opposite of white.

BLAHS.d: Plural of BLAH: Nonsense; drivel; idle, meaningless talk.
BLAHS.e:
* Sense “Idle, meaningless talk” (1940), probably imitative or echoic in origin. Compare Ancient Greek βαρ-βαρ (bar-bar, “unintelligible sounds”)
* Adjective sense “bland, dull” (1919), perhaps influenced by French blasé (“bored, indifferent”).
* The blahs (“boredom, mild depress...

BLAME.d: To hold responsible for a fault.

BLANK.d: Empty; not written or printed on.

BLATS.d: Plural of BLAT: To cry, as a calf or sheep; bleat.
BLATS.e: Imitative. First attested in 1846 in the intransitive sense of "bleat". Compare English bleat, Old English blǣtan (“to bleat”).

BLEBS.d: Plural of BLEB: A bubble, such as in paint or glass.
BLEBS.e: Possibly onomatopoeic, similarly to blob and blubber.

BLIPS.d: Plural of BLIP: A small dot registered on electronic equipment, such as a radar or oscilloscope screen.

BLOBS.d: Plural of BLOB: A shapeless or amorphous mass; a vague shape or amount, especially of a liquid or semisolid substance; a clump, group or collection that lacks definite shape.
BLOBS.e: From Middle English *blob (“attested in blobby”). Possibly onomatopoeic, similarly to bleb and blubber.

BLOCK.d: A solid piece of material; to obstruct.

BLOCS.d: Plural of BLOC: A group of voters or politicians who share common goals.
BLOCS.e: Borrowed from French bloc (“group, block”), ultimately of Old Dutch origin, from Frankish or Proto-West Germanic *blokk, from Proto-Germanic *blukką (“beam, log”). Doublet of block.

BLOOD.d: The red liquid flowing through the body.

BLOTS.d: Plural of BLOT: A blemish, spot or stain made by a coloured substance.
BLOTS.e: From Middle English blot (“blot, spot, stain, blemish”). Perhaps from Old Norse *blettr (“blot, stain”) (only attested in documents from after Old Norse transitioned to Icelandic blettur), or from Old French bloche (“clod of earth”).

BLOWS.d: Plural of BLOW: To produce an air current.
BLOWS.e: From Middle English blowen, from Old English blāwan (“to blow, breathe, inflate, sound”), from Proto-West Germanic *blāan, from Proto-Germanic *blēaną (“to blow”) (compare German blähen), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰleh₁- (“to swell, blow up”) (compare Latin flō (“to blow”) and O...
