BLUED.e: From Middle English blewe, from Anglo-Norman blew (“blue”), from Middle French bleu, from Old French blöe, bleve, blef (“blue”), from Frankish *blāu (“blue”) (perhaps through a Late Latin blāvus, blāvius (“blue”) attested from Isidore of Seville), from Proto-Germanic *blēwaz (“bl...

BLUES.d: Plural of BLUE: Of a blue hue.
BLUES.e: From Middle English blewe, from Anglo-Norman blew (“blue”), from Middle French bleu, from Old French blöe, bleve, blef (“blue”), from Frankish *blāu (“blue”) (perhaps through a Late Latin blāvus, blāvius (“blue”) attested from Isidore of Seville), from Proto-Germanic *blēwaz (“bl...

BLURS.d: Plural of BLUR: To make indistinct or hazy, to obscure or dim.
BLURS.e: From earlier blurre, probably an alteration of blear, from Middle English bleren, from Old English *blerian (attested in āblered (“made bare, made bald”)), from Proto-West Germanic *blaʀjan, from Proto-Germanic *blazjaną (“to make pale”), from Proto-Germanic *blasaz (“pale”). Com...

BOARD.d: A flat piece of wood; a group of directors.

BOARS.d: Plural of BOAR: A wild boar (Sus scrofa), the wild ancestor of the domesticated pig.
BOARS.e: From Middle English bor, boor, from Old English bār, from Proto-West Germanic *bair.

BOATS.d: Plural of BOAT: A craft used for transportation of goods, fishing, racing, recreational cruising, or military use on or in the water, propelled by oars or outboard motor or inboard motor or by wind.
BOATS.e: From Middle English bot, boot, boet, boyt (“boat”), from Old English bāt (“boat”), from Proto-West Germanic *bait, from Proto-Germanic *baitaz, *baitą (“boat, small ship”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyd- (“to break, split”) (whence also fissure via Latin). Cognate with Old Nors...

BOCKS.d: Plural of BOCK: A strong dark beer brewed in the fall and aged through the winter for spring consumption.

BODED.d: Past tense of BODE: To indicate by signs, as future events; to be an omen of; to portend or foretell.
BODED.e:
Verb from Middle English boden, from Old English bodian (“announce, foretell”), from Proto-West Germanic *bodōn, from Proto-Germanic *budōną (“to proclaim, announce, lere, instruct”). See bid.
Noun from Middle English bod, from Old English bod, from Proto-Germanic *budą (“message...

BODES.d: Plural of BODE: To indicate by signs, as future events; to be an omen of; to portend or foretell.
BODES.e:
Verb from Middle English boden, from Old English bodian (“announce, foretell”), from Proto-West Germanic *bodōn, from Proto-Germanic *budōną (“to proclaim, announce, lere, instruct”). See bid.
Noun from Middle English bod, from Old English bod, from Proto-Germanic *budą (“message...

BOFFS.d: Plural of BOFF: To have sexual intercourse with (someone).

BOILS.d: Plural of BOIL: A localized accumulation of pus in the skin, resulting from infection.
BOILS.e:
From Middle English bile, büle (“boil, tumor”), from Old English bȳl, bȳle (“boil, swelling”), from Proto-Germanic *būlijō, *būlō (“boil”).
Akin to Dutch buil (“boil, swelling”), German Beule (“boil, hump”), Icelandic beyla (“swelling, hump”). The expected form is bile; the round...

BOLAS.d: Plural of BOLA: A throwing weapon made of weights on the ends of a cord.

BOLED.d: Past tense of BOLE: The trunk or stem of a tree.
BOLED.e: From Middle English bole, from Old Norse bolr, akin to Danish bul and German Bohle (“plank”). See also bulwark (“defensive wall”).

BOLES.d: Plural of BOLE: The trunk or stem of a tree.
BOLES.e: From Middle English bole, from Old Norse bolr, akin to Danish bul and German Bohle (“plank”). See also bulwark (“defensive wall”).

BOLLS.d: Plural of BOLL: The rounded seed-bearing capsule of a cotton or flax plant.
BOLLS.e: From Middle English bolle (“pod; shell”) and Middle Dutch bolle (“round object”); both ultimately from Proto-Germanic *bullô (“round object; bowl”). More at bowl.

BOLTS.d: Plural of BOLT: A (usually) metal fastener consisting of a cylindrical body that is threaded, with a larger head on one end. It can be inserted into an unthreaded hole up to the head, with a nut then threaded on the other end; a heavy machine screw.
BOLTS.e: From Middle English bolt, from Old English bolt, from Proto-West Germanic *bolt, from Proto-Germanic *bultaz, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeld- (“to knock, strike”). Compare Lithuanian beldu (“I knock”), baldas (“pole for striking”). Akin to Dutch and West Frisian bout, Ge...

BOMBS.d: Plural of BOMB: An explosive device used or intended as a weapon, especially, one dropped from an aircraft.
BOMBS.e: From French bombe, from Italian bomba, from Latin bombus (“a booming sound”), from Ancient Greek βόμβος (bómbos, “booming, humming, buzzing”), imitative of the sound itself. Doublet of bombe. Compare boom.

BONDS.d: Plural of BOND: A document constituting evidence of a long-term debt, by which the bond issuer (the borrower) is obliged to pay interest when due, and repay the principal at maturity, as specified on the face of the bond certificate. The rights of the holder are specified in the bond indenture, which contains the legal terms and conditions under which the bond was issued. Bonds are available in two forms: registered bonds, and bearer bonds.
BONDS.e: From Middle English bond, a variant of band, from Old English beand, bænd, bend (“bond, chain, fetter, band, ribbon, ornament, chaplet, crown”), from Proto-Germanic *bandaz, *bandiz (“band, fetter”). Cognate with Dutch band, German Band, Swedish band. Doublet of Bund. Related to ...

BONED.d: Past tense of BONE: A composite material consisting largely of calcium phosphate and collagen and making up the skeleton of most vertebrates.
BONED.e:
From Middle English bon, from Old English bān (“bone, tusk; the bone of a limb”), from Proto-Germanic *bainą (“bone”), from *bainaz (“straight”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyh₂- (“to hit, strike, beat”).
Cognate with Scots bane, been, bean, bein, bain (“bone”), North F...

BONES.d: Plural of BONE: A composite material consisting largely of calcium phosphate and collagen and making up the skeleton of most vertebrates.
BONES.e:
From Middle English bon, from Old English bān (“bone, tusk; the bone of a limb”), from Proto-Germanic *bainą (“bone”), from *bainaz (“straight”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *bʰeyh₂- (“to hit, strike, beat”).
Cognate with Scots bane, been, bean, bein, bain (“bone”), North F...

BONGS.d: Plural of BONG: The clang of a large bell.

BONKS.d: Plural of BONK: To strike or collide with something.
BONKS.e: Of imitative origin. Compare English bang, bounce, bump.

BOOBS.d: Plural of BOOB: An idiot; a fool.
BOOBS.e: Clipped form of booby (“fool”). Appeared near the beginning of the twentieth century; more information at booby § Etymology 1.

BOOED.d: Past tense of BOO: A loud exclamation intended to scare someone. Usually used when one has been hidden from the target, and then appears unexpectedly.
BOOED.e: From earlier (15c.) boh, coined to create a loud and startling sound. Compare Middle English bus! (“bang!”, interjection), Latin boō (“cry aloud, roar, shout”, verb), Ancient Greek βοάω (boáō, “shout”, verb).

BOOKS.d: Plural of BOOK: A collection of sheets of paper bound together to hinge at one edge, containing printed or written material, pictures, etc.
BOOKS.e: From Middle English bok, book, from Old English bōc, from Proto-West Germanic *bōk, from Proto-Germanic *bōks. Bookmaker sense by clipping.

BOOMS.d: Plural of BOOM: To make a loud, hollow, resonant sound.
BOOMS.e: Onomatopoeic, perhaps borrowed; compare German bummen, Dutch bommen (“to hum, buzz”). The sense "a period of economic growth" is generally taken to derive from the sense "a rapid expansion", although other origins have also been suggested.

BOONS.d: Plural of BOON: A good thing; a thing to be thankful for or to appreciate duly.
BOONS.e: From Middle English boon (“prayer”), from Old Norse bón (“prayer, petition”), from Proto-Germanic *bōniz (“supplication”), influenced by boon (“good, favorable”, adjective). Doublet of ben; see there for more.

BOORS.e:
Borrowed from Dutch boer (“peasant”). Doublet of bauer, Boer, and bower (“peasant, farmer”).
For the meaning development compare with Russian обыва́тель (obyvátelʹ, “the average man/citizen, the man in the street, philistine, resident, inhabitant”), Polish bydło (“cattle, rabble”...

BOOTS.d: Plural of BOOT: A heavy shoe that covers part of the leg.
BOOTS.e: From Middle English boote, bote (“shoe”), from Old French bote (“a high, thick shoe”). Of obscure origin, but probably related to Old French bot (“club-foot”), bot (“fat, short, blunt”), from Old Frankish *butt, from Proto-Germanic *buttaz, *butaz (“cut off, short, numb, blunt”),...

BORED.d: Past tense of BORE: To inspire boredom in somebody.
BORED.e:
From Middle English boren, from Old English borian (“to pierce”), from Proto-West Germanic *borōn, from Proto-Germanic *burōną.
Compare Danish bore, Norwegian Bokmål bore, Dutch boren, German bohren, Old Norse bora. Cognate with Latin forō (“to bore, to pierce”), Latin feriō (“st...

BORES.d: Plural of BORE: To inspire boredom in somebody.
BORES.e:
From Middle English boren, from Old English borian (“to pierce”), from Proto-West Germanic *borōn, from Proto-Germanic *burōną.
Compare Danish bore, Norwegian Bokmål bore, Dutch boren, German bohren, Old Norse bora. Cognate with Latin forō (“to bore, to pierce”), Latin feriō (“st...

BOUTS.d: Plural of BOUT: A period of something, especially one painful or unpleasant, like an illness.
BOUTS.e: From Middle English bout, bowt, bught (whence also modern English bought (“bend, curve”)), probably from Old English *buht (“bend, turn”), an unrecorded variant of Old English byht (“a bend, curve”), from Proto-West Germanic *buhti, from Proto-Germanic *buhtiz (“a bend”). Equival...

BOWLS.d: Plural of BOWL: A roughly hemispherical container used to hold, mix or present food, such as salad, fruit or soup, or other items.
BOWLS.e:
From Middle English bolle, from Old English bolla, bolle (“bowl, cup, pot, beaker, measure”), from Proto-West Germanic *bollā, from Proto-Germanic *bullǭ (“ball, round vessel, bowl”).
Cognate with North Frisian bol (“bun, bread roll”), Middle Low German bolle, bole (“round object...

BOXED.d: Past tense of BOX: Senses relating to a three-dimensional object or space.
BOXED.e: From Middle English box (“container, box, cup”), from Old English box (“box, case”), from Proto-West Germanic *buhsā (“box”) from Late Latin buxis (“box”), Latin pyxis (“small box for medicines or toiletries”), of uncertain origin; compare Ancient Greek πυξίς (puxís, “box or tabl...

BOXES.d: Plural of BOX: Senses relating to a three-dimensional object or space.
BOXES.e: From Middle English box (“container, box, cup”), from Old English box (“box, case”), from Proto-West Germanic *buhsā (“box”) from Late Latin buxis (“box”), Latin pyxis (“small box for medicines or toiletries”), of uncertain origin; compare Ancient Greek πυξίς (puxís, “box or tabl...

BOYOS.d: Plural of BOYO: A boy or lad.

BOZOS.d: Plural of BOZO: A stupid, foolish, or ridiculous person, especially a man.
BOZOS.e: Attested since the 1910s in American English, of uncertain origin. The term may derive from Spanish bozal, a term originally for a recently-imported slave and then "someone who speaks (Spanish) poorly". The term is older than Bozo the Clown, introduced in 1946. It is used as an i...

BRADS.d: Plural of BRAD: A thin, small nail, with a slight projection at the top on one side instead of a head, or occasionally with a small domed head, similar to that of an escutcheon pin.
BRADS.e: Late Middle English brad, variant of brod(d), from Old Norse broddr (“spike, shaft”), from Proto-Germanic *bruzdaz (compare Old English brord, Old High German brort), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrusdʰos (compare Welsh brath (“sting, prick”), Albanian bredh (“fir-tree”), Lithuania...

BRAES.d: Plural of BRAE: The sloping bank of a river valley.
BRAES.e:
From Middle English bro, bra (“bank of a stream; raised edge of a ditch or pit”), from Old Norse brá (“eyebrow; eyelash”) (probably in the sense of the brow of a hill), from Proto-Germanic *brēwō (“eyebrow”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃bʰrúHs (“eyebrow”).
The English word is cog...

BRAGS.d: Plural of BRAG: A boast or boasting; bragging; ostentatious pretence or self-glorification.
BRAGS.e: From Middle English braggen (“to make a loud noise; to speak boastfully”) of uncertain origin. Possibly related to the Middle English adjective brag (“prideful; spirited”), which is probably of Celtic origin; or from Old Norse bragr (“best; foremost; poetry”); or through Old Engl...

BRAIN.d: The organ inside the head that controls the body.

BRAND.d: A type of product; a mark of ownership.

BRANS.d: Plural of BRAN: The broken coat of the seed of wheat, rye, or other cereal grain, separated from the flour or meal by sifting or bolting; the coarse, chaffy part of ground grain.
BRANS.e: From Middle English bran, branne, bren, from Old French bren, bran (“bran, filth”), from Gaulish brennos (“rotten”), from Proto-Celtic *bragnos (“rotten, foul”) (compare Welsh braen (“stench”), Irish bréan (“rancid”), Walloon brin (“excrement”)), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰreHg-...

BRASS.d: Plural of BRAS: Acronym of broadband remote access server.

BRATS.d: Plural of BRAT: A human child.
BRATS.e: Early Modern English (c. 1500) slang term meaning "beggar's child". Possibly from Scots bratchet (“bitch, hound”). Another possibility is that it was originally a dialectal word, from northern and western England and the Midlands, for a "makeshift or ragged garment," from Old Eng...

BRAVE.e: From French brave, from Italian bravo.

BRAYS.d: Plural of BRAY: Of an animal (now chiefly of animals related to the ass or donkey, and the camel): to make its cry.
BRAYS.e: The verb is derived from Middle English brayen, brai, bray, braye (“of a person or animal: to vocalize loudly; of the weather: to make a loud sound, howl, roar”), from Old French brai, braire (“of an animal: to bray; of a person: to cry or shout out”) (modern French braire (“of a...

BREAD.d: Food made from flour, water, and yeast.

BREAK.d: To separate into pieces; an interruption.

BREWS.d: Plural of BREW: To make tea or coffee by mixing tea leaves or coffee beans with hot water.
BREWS.e:
From Middle English brewen, from Old English brēowan, from Proto-West Germanic *breuwan, from Proto-Germanic *brewwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrewh₁-. Doublet of burn.
Cognate with
Dutch brouwen, German brauen, Swedish brygga, Norwegian Bokmål brygge; also Ancient Greek φρέα...

BRICK.d: A block of baked clay used in building.

BRIGS.d: Plural of BRIG: A two-masted vessel, square-rigged on both foremast and mainmast
BRIGS.e: Abbreviated from brigantine, from Italian brigantino; in sense “jail”, from the use of such ships as prisons.

BRIMS.d: Plural of BRIM: Originally, a border or edge of a sea, a river, or other body of water; now, any border or edge.
BRIMS.e: The noun is derived from Middle English brem, brim, brimme (“bank, edge, or margin of a lake or river; shore of a sea; brink; rim”); further etymology uncertain, probably related to Middle High German brem, breme (“border, edge, brim”) and Old Norse barmr (“rim”), ultimately from...

BRIOS.d: Plural of BRIO: Vigour or vivacity.
BRIOS.e: From Italian brio (“finesse, talent”), from Spanish brío, ultimately from Proto-Celtic *brīgos.

BROWN.d: A colour produced by mixing red, yellow, and black.

BROWS.d: Plural of BROW: The bony ridge over the eyes, upon which the eyebrows are located.
BROWS.e:
From Middle English browe, from Old English brū, from Proto-West Germanic *brāwu, from Proto-Germanic *brūwō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃bʰrúHs (“brow”).
Cognate with Scots broo (“brow”), Dutch brauw (“brow”), German Braue (“eyebrow”), Danish, Norwegian Nynorsk and Swedish bryn ...

BUBOS.d: Plural of BUBO: An inflamed swelling of a lymph node, especially in the armpit or groin, due to an infection such as bubonic plague, gonorrhea, tuberculosis, or syphilis.
BUBOS.e: Late Middle English, from Medieval Latin būbō, from Ancient Greek βουβών (boubṓn, “groin, swelling”).

BUCKS.d: Plural of BUCK: A male deer, antelope, sheep, goat, rabbit, hare, and sometimes the male of other animals such as the hamster, ferret, salmonid, shad and kangaroo.
BUCKS.e:
From Middle English bukke, bucke, buc, from Old English buc, bucc, bucca (“he-goat, stag”), from Proto-West Germanic *bukk, *bukkō, from Proto-Germanic *bukkaz, *bukkô (“buck”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰuǵ- (“ram”). Doublet of puck (“billy goat”).
Currency-related senses hail ...

BUFFS.d: Plural of BUFF: Undyed leather from the skin of buffalo or similar animals.
BUFFS.e: From buffe (“leather”), from Middle French buffle (“buffalo”).

BULBS.d: Plural of BULB: The bulb-shaped underground portion of a plant such as a tulip, consisting of a shortened stem and many fleshy scale leaves, from which the rest of the plant may be regrown.
BULBS.e:
Etymology tree
Ancient Greek βολβός (bolbós)bor.
Latin bulbusder.
English bulb
Inherited from Middle English bulb, bolbe, from Latin bulbus (“bulb, onion”), from Ancient Greek βολβός (bolbós, “plant with round swelling on underground stem”).

BULKS.d: Plural of BULK: Size, specifically, volume.
BULKS.e: From Middle English bulk, bolke (“a heap, cargo, hold; heap; bulge”), borrowed from Old Norse búlki (“the freight or the cargo of a ship”), from Proto-Germanic *bulkô (“beam, pile, heap”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰelǵ- (“beam, pile, prop”). Compare Icelandic búlkast (“to be bu...

BULLS.d: Plural of BULL: An adult male of domesticated cattle or oxen.
BULLS.e: From Middle English bole, bul, bule, from a conflation of Old English bula (“bull, steer”) and Old Norse boli, both from Proto-Germanic *bulô (“bull”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰl̥no-, from *bʰel- (“to blow, swell up”). Cognate with West Frisian bolle, Dutch bul, German Low Ger...

BUMFS.d: Plural of BUMF: Useless papers; now especially official documents, standardized forms, sales and marketing print material, etc.

BUMPS.d: Plural of BUMP: A light blow or jolting collision.
BUMPS.e:
From Early Modern English bump (“a shock, blow from a collision”), probably of North Germanic origin; compare Danish bump (“a thump”), Danish bumpe (“to thump”), Old Danish bumpe (“to strike with a clenched fist”), all probably of imitative origin.
Apparently related to Middle En...

BUNGS.d: Plural of BUNG: A stopper, alternative to a cork, often made of rubber, used to prevent fluid passing through the neck of a bottle, vat, a hole in a vessel etc.
BUNGS.e: From Medieval Dutch bonge, bonne or bonghe (“stopper”), or perhaps from French bonde, which may itself be either of Germanic origin or from Proto-Celtic *bunda—either way probably from puncta (“hole”), the feminine singular form of Latin punctus, perfect passive participle of pun...

BUNKS.d: Plural of BUNK: One of a series of berths or beds placed in tiers.
BUNKS.e:
Sense of sleeping berth possibly from Scottish English bunker (“seat, bench”), origin is uncertain but possibly Scandinavian.
Compare Old Swedish bunke (“boards used to protect the cargo of a ship”).
See also boarding, flooring and compare bunch.

BUNTS.d: Plural of BUNT: The middle part, cavity, or belly of a sail; the part of a furled sail which is at the center of the yard.
BUNTS.e: Unknown. Perhaps a nasalised variant of butt.

BUOYS.d: Plural of BUOY: A float moored in water to mark a location, warn of danger, indicate a navigational channel or for other purposes
BUOYS.e: From Middle English boy, boye, from Middle Dutch boeye (“float, buoy”), from Old French boue (“piece of wood or cork that floats above an anchor to indicate where it is anchored”) (modern French bouée), ultimately from Frankish *baukn (“beacon”). Doublet of beacon. Same root as E...

BURLS.d: Plural of BURL: A tree growth in which the grain has grown in a deformed manner; a burr knot.
BURLS.e: From Middle English burle (“a knot or flaw in cloth”), from Old French bourle (“flocks or ends of threads which disfigure cloth”), diminutive of Old French bourre, from Medieval Latin burra (“flock of wool, coarse hair”).

BURNS.d: Plural of BURN: A physical injury caused by heat, cold, electricity, radiation or caustic chemicals.
BURNS.e:
From Middle English bernen (collateral form of brennen), from Old English birnan (“to burn”), metathesis from Proto-West Germanic *brinnan, from Proto-Germanic *brinnaną (“to burn”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰrenw-, present stem from *bʰrewh₁-. Doublet of brew.
Cognate with Cim...

BURPS.e: Originally from American English, of imitative origin.

BURRS.d: Plural of BURR: A sharp, pointy object, such as a sliver or splinter.
BURRS.e: From Middle English burre, perhaps related to Old English byrst (“bristle”). Cognate with Danish burre, borre (“burdock, burr”), Swedish borre (“sea-urchin”).

BURYS.d: Plural of BURY: To ritualistically inter in a grave or tomb.
BURYS.e:
Middle English burien, berien, from Old English byrġan, from Proto-West Germanic *burgijan, from Proto-Germanic *burgijaną (“to keep safe”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *bʰergʰ- (“to defend, protect”).
Cognate with Icelandic byrgja (“to cover, shut; to hold in”); West Fri...

BUSED.d: Past tense of BUS: A motor vehicle for transporting large numbers of people along roads.
BUSED.e: Clipping of omnibus. Superseded earlier 'bus, where the apostrophe indicated a clipping. The shift in spelling likely reflects the fact that modern speakers no longer perceive this term as a clipping. The electrical sense is derived from figurative application of the automotive s...

BUSES.d: Plural of BUS: A motor vehicle for transporting large numbers of people along roads.
BUSES.e: Clipping of omnibus. Superseded earlier 'bus, where the apostrophe indicated a clipping. The shift in spelling likely reflects the fact that modern speakers no longer perceive this term as a clipping. The electrical sense is derived from figurative application of the automotive s...

BUSKS.d: Plural of BUSK: To solicit money by entertaining the public in the street or in public transport.
BUSKS.e: Apparently from French busquer or Spanish buscar.

BUSTS.e: From a non-rhotic pronunciation of burst, which goes back to Middle English busten, a variant of bursten, bresten (“to burst”). Compare Low German basten, a variant of barsten (“to burst”).

BUTTS.d: Plural of BUTT: The larger or thicker end of something; the blunt end, in distinction from the sharp or narrow end
BUTTS.e: From Middle English but, butte (“goal, mark, butt of land”), from Old English byt, bytt (“small piece of land”) and *butt (attested in diminutive Old English buttuc (“end, small piece of land”) > English buttock), from Proto-West Germanic *butt, from Proto-Germanic *buttaz (“end,...

BYRES.d: Plural of BYRE: A barn, especially one used for keeping cattle in.
BYRES.e: From Middle English bire, bier, byr, from Old English bȳre.

BYTES.d: Plural of BYTE: A short sequence of bits (binary digits) that can be operated on as a unit by a computer; the smallest usable machine word.
BYTES.e: An alteration of the word bite so it would not be accidentally misspelled as bit. Coined by Werner Buchholz in 1956, during the early design phase for the IBM 7030 Stretch computer.

CAFES.d: Plural of CAFE: Alternative form of café.

CAGED.d: Past tense of CAGE: An enclosure made of bars, normally to hold animals.
CAGED.e: From Middle English cage, from Old French cage, from Latin cavea. Doublet of cadge and cavea and related to jail.

CAGES.d: Plural of CAGE: An enclosure made of bars, normally to hold animals.
CAGES.e: From Middle English cage, from Old French cage, from Latin cavea. Doublet of cadge and cavea and related to jail.

CAKED.d: Past tense of CAKE: A rich, sweet dessert food, typically made of flour, sugar, and eggs and baked in an oven, and often covered in icing.
CAKED.e: From Middle English cake, from Old Norse kaka (“cake”) (compare Norwegian kake, Icelandic/Swedish kaka, Danish kage), from Proto-Germanic *kakǭ, of disputed origin. Likely a distant cognate with kaak. Perhaps related to cookie, kuchen, and quiche. Doublet of coca (pastry).

CAKES.d: Plural of CAKE: A rich, sweet dessert food, typically made of flour, sugar, and eggs and baked in an oven, and often covered in icing.
CAKES.e: From Middle English cake, from Old Norse kaka (“cake”) (compare Norwegian kake, Icelandic/Swedish kaka, Danish kage), from Proto-Germanic *kakǭ, of disputed origin. Likely a distant cognate with kaak. Perhaps related to cookie, kuchen, and quiche. Doublet of coca (pastry).

CALFS.d: Plural of CALF: A young cow or bull of any bovid, such as domestic cattle or buffalo.
CALFS.e:
From Middle English calf, from Anglian Old English cælf, calf (West Saxon ċealf), from Proto-Germanic *kalbaz, further etymology unknown.
Cognates

* Scots caff (“calf”)
* Scots calf (“calf”)
* Scots cauf (“calf”)
* Scots cawf (“calf”)
* North Frisian Kualev (“calf”)
* North Fris...

CALLS.d: Plural of CALL: To reach out with one's voice.
CALLS.e: From Middle English callen, from Old English ċeallian (“to call, shout”) and Old Norse kalla (“to call; shout; refer to as; name”); both from Proto-Germanic *kalzōną (“to call, shout”), from Proto-Indo-European *golH-so- (“voice, cry”), from *gel(H)- (“to vocalize, call, shout”)....

CALMS.d: Plural of CALM: Peaceful, quiet, especially free from anger and anxiety.
CALMS.e: From Middle English calm, calme, from Middle French calme, probably from Old Italian calma, of uncertain origin. Calma may derive from Late Latin cauma (“heat of the midday sun”), from Ancient Greek καῦμα (kaûma, “heat, especially of the sun”), from καίω (kaíō, “I burn”), or poss...

CAMES.d: Plural of CAME: simple past of come

CAMPS.d: Plural of CAMP: An outdoor place acting as temporary accommodation in tents or other simple structures.
CAMPS.e: From Middle English kampe (“battlefield, open space”), from Old English camp (“battle, contest, battlefield, open space”), from Proto-West Germanic *kamp (“open field where military exercises are held, level plain”), from Latin campus (“open field, level plain”), from Proto-Indo-...

CANED.d: Past tense of CANE: A plant with simple stems, like bamboo or sugar cane, or the stem thereof:
CANED.e: From Middle English cane, canne, from Old French cane (“sugar cane”), from Latin canna (“reed”), from Ancient Greek κάννα (kánna), from Akkadian 𒄀 (qanû, “reed”), from Sumerian 𒄀𒈾 (gi.na). Doublet of canna and kaneh. Related to channel and canal.

CANES.d: Plural of CANE: A plant with simple stems, like bamboo or sugar cane, or the stem thereof:
CANES.e: From Middle English cane, canne, from Old French cane (“sugar cane”), from Latin canna (“reed”), from Ancient Greek κάννα (kánna), from Akkadian 𒄀 (qanû, “reed”), from Sumerian 𒄀𒈾 (gi.na). Doublet of canna and kaneh. Related to channel and canal.

CANTS.d: Plural of CANT: An argot, the jargon of a particular class or subgroup.
CANTS.e: From Latin cantō probably via Old Northern French canter (“sing, tell”). Doublet of chant.

CAPED.d: Past tense of CAPE: A piece or point of land, extending beyond the adjacent coast into a sea or lake; a promontory; a headland.
CAPED.e:
From Middle English cape, gappe, cap, from Old French cap (“cape, headland”), from Latin caput (“head”).
Doublet of capo, caput, chef, and chief, and distantly with head and Howth.
For sense development, compare English ness (“a promontory point, cape”) from a root related to nos...

CAPES.d: Plural of CAPE: A piece or point of land, extending beyond the adjacent coast into a sea or lake; a promontory; a headland.
CAPES.e:
From Middle English cape, gappe, cap, from Old French cap (“cape, headland”), from Latin caput (“head”).
Doublet of capo, caput, chef, and chief, and distantly with head and Howth.
For sense development, compare English ness (“a promontory point, cape”) from a root related to nos...

CAPOS.d: Plural of CAPO: A movable bar placed across the fingerboard of a guitar and used to raise the pitch of all strings.

CARDS.d: Plural of CARD: A playing card.
CARDS.e: From Middle English carde (“playing card”), from Old French carte, from Latin charta, from Ancient Greek χάρτης (khártēs, “paper, papyrus”). Doublet of chart.

CARED.d: Past tense of CARE: Close attention; concern; responsibility.
CARED.e: From Middle English care, from Old English caru, ċearu (“care, concern, anxiety, sorrow, grief, trouble”), from Proto-West Germanic *karu, from Proto-Germanic *karō (“care, sorrow, cry”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵeh₂r- (“shout, call”). Cognate with Old Saxon cara, kara (“concer...

CARES.d: Plural of CARE: Close attention; concern; responsibility.
CARES.e: From Middle English care, from Old English caru, ċearu (“care, concern, anxiety, sorrow, grief, trouble”), from Proto-West Germanic *karu, from Proto-Germanic *karō (“care, sorrow, cry”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵeh₂r- (“shout, call”). Cognate with Old Saxon cara, kara (“concer...

CARKS.d: Plural of CARK: To be filled with worry, solicitude, or troubles.
CARKS.e:
From Middle English carken (“to be anxious, worry”, intransitive), from Old English *carcian ("to be sorrowful, worry"; found in becarcian (“to worry about, care for”)), a frequentative form of Old English carian (“to care”), equivalent to care + -k.
The Middle English carken, al...

CARLS.d: Plural of CARL: A rude, rustic man; a churl.
CARLS.e: From Middle English carl, from Old English carl, a borrowing from Old Norse karl (“man, husband”), from Proto-Germanic *karilaz. Doublet of ceorl, churl, and karl.

CARPS.d: Plural of CARP: Any of various freshwater fish of the family Cyprinidae; specifically the common carp, Cyprinus carpio.
CARPS.e: From Late Middle English carpe (“the common carp (Cyprinus carpio)”), from Old French carpe, from Late Latin carpa, possibly from Proto-West Germanic *karpo (possibly due to the introduction from the fish from the Danube into England in the 14th century; whence Middle Low German ...

CARRY.d: To transport from one place to another.

CARTS.d: Plural of CART: A small, open, wheeled vehicle, drawn or pushed by a person or animal, often with two wheels on one axle, more often used for transporting goods than passengers.
CARTS.e: From Middle English cart, kart, from Old Norse kartr (“wagon; cart”), merged with native Old English cræt (“a chariot; cart”), from Proto-Germanic *krattaz, *krattijô, *kradō, from Proto-Indo-European *gret- (“tracery; wattle; cradle; cage; basket”), from *ger- (“to turn, wind”)....

CASED.d: Past tense of CASE: An actual event, situation, or fact.
CASED.e: From Middle English cas, from Old French cas (“an event”), from Latin cāsus (“a falling, a fall; accident, event, occurrence; occasion, opportunity; noun case”), perfect passive participle of cadō (“to fall, to drop”).

CASES.d: Plural of CASE: An actual event, situation, or fact.
CASES.e: From Middle English cas, from Old French cas (“an event”), from Latin cāsus (“a falling, a fall; accident, event, occurrence; occasion, opportunity; noun case”), perfect passive participle of cadō (“to fall, to drop”).

CASKS.d: Plural of CASK: A large barrel for the storage of liquid, especially of alcoholic drinks. (See a diagram of cask sizes.)
CASKS.e: From Middle French casque. Doublet of casco and casque.

CASTS.d: Plural of CAST: To move, or be moved, away.
CASTS.e: From Middle English casten, from Old Norse kasta (“to throw, cast, overturn”), from Proto-Germanic *kastōną (“to throw, cast”), of unknown origin.

CAVED.d: Past tense of CAVE: A large, naturally-occurring cavity formed underground or in the face of a cliff or a hillside.
CAVED.e: From Middle English cave, borrowed from Old French cave, from Latin cava (“cavity”), from cavus (“hollow”). Cognate with Tocharian B kor (“throat”), Albanian cup (“odd, uneven”), Ancient Greek κύαρ (kúar, “eye of needle, earhole”), Old Armenian սոր (sor, “hole”), Sanskrit शून्य (...

CAWED.d: Past tense of CAW: The harsh cry of a crow.

CEDED.d: Past tense of CEDE: To give up; yield to another.
CEDED.e: Borrowed from Middle French ceder, from Old French ceder, from Latin cēdō (“to yield”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱyesdʰ- (“to drive away; to go away”). Cognate with Tocharian B kätk- (“to cross, pass”).

CEDES.d: Plural of CEDE: To give up; yield to another.
CEDES.e: Borrowed from Middle French ceder, from Old French ceder, from Latin cēdō (“to yield”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱyesdʰ- (“to drive away; to go away”). Cognate with Tocharian B kätk- (“to cross, pass”).

CELLS.d: Plural of CELL: A single-room dwelling for a hermit.
CELLS.e: From Middle English celle, selle, from Old English cell (attested in inflected forms), from Latin cella (“chamber, small room, compartment”), later reinforced by Old French cel, sele, Old French cele. Ultimately from Proto-Italic *kelnā, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱelneh₂, from Pr...

CENTS.d: Plural of CENT: A subunit of currency equal to one-hundredth of the main unit of currency in many countries. Symbol: ¢.
CENTS.e: From Middle English cent, from Old French cent, from Latin centum, from Proto-Indo-European *ḱm̥tóm.

CHADS.d: Plural of CHAD: A male given name from Old English; also a modern nickname for Charles, Chadwick and similar-sounding names.
CHADS.e:
From Middle English Chadde, from Old English Ċeadda, of obscure meaning; name of a seventh-century Anglo-Saxon saint, revived in the 20th century.
The sense of “alpha male” originates from an apparent stereotype that men with such a name tend to bear that temperament, first attes...

CHAIN.e: From Old French chaine, from Latin catēna.

CHAIR.e: From Old French chaiere, from Latin cathedra.

CHAPS.d: Plural of CHAP: A man, a fellow.
CHAPS.e: Clipping of chapman (“dealer, customer”) in 16th-century English.

CHARS.d: Plural of CHAR: To burn something to charcoal; to be burnt to charcoal.

CHATS.d: Plural of CHAT: To be engaged in informal conversation.
CHATS.e: Clipping of chatter. The bird sense refers to the sound of its call.

CHEAP.d: Low in price; of poor quality.

CHECK.d: To examine; a pattern of squares.

CHEFS.d: Plural of CHEF: The presiding cook in the kitchen of a large household.
CHEFS.e: Unadapted borrowing from French chef (from the positions of chef d'office and chef de cuisine), from Old French chief (“head, leader”) (English chief), from Vulgar Latin capus (“head”) (from which also captain, chieftain), from Latin caput (“head”) (possibly related to English ca...

CHEST.d: The front of the body; a storage box.
CHEST.e: From Old English cest, from Latin cista.

CHEWS.d: Plural of CHEW: To crush with the teeth by repeated closing and opening of the jaws; done to food to soften it and break it down by the action of saliva before it is swallowed.
CHEWS.e: From Middle English chewen, from Old English ċēowan, from Proto-West Germanic *keuwan, from Proto-Germanic *kewwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵyewh₁-. Cognate with West Frisian kôgje, Low German käwwen, Dutch kauwen, German kauen; also Latin gingīva (“gums”), Tocharian B śuwaṃ (...

CHIAS.d: Plural of CHIA: A Mexican sage grown for its edible seeds, Salvia hispanica.
CHIAS.e: Borrowed from Spanish chía, from Classical Nahuatl chiyan (“seed of the chia plant”).

CHIEF.e: From Old French chief, from Latin caput (head).

CHINA.d: A country in East Asia; fine ceramic ware.
CHINA.e: From Persian Chīn, from Sanskrit Cīna.

CHINS.d: Plural of CHIN: The bottom of a face, (specifically) the typically jutting jawline below the mouth.
CHINS.e:
From Middle English chyn, from Old English ċinn (“chin”), from Proto-West Germanic *kinnu, from Proto-Germanic *kinnuz (“chin”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵénus (“chin, jaw”).
Compare West Frisian/Dutch kin, Low German/German Kinn, Danish kind, Icelandic kinn, Welsh gen, Latin ge...

CHIPS.d: Plural of CHIP: A small piece broken from a larger piece of solid material.
CHIPS.e: Noun from Middle English chip, chippe, from Old English ċipp (“chip; small piece of wood, shaving”), from Old English *ċippian (“to cut; hew”) – attested in Old English forċippian (“to cut off”) –, from Proto-West Germanic *kippōn (“to cut; carve; hack; chop”), from Proto-Germani...

CHITS.d: Plural of CHIT: A child or babe; a young, small, or insignificant person or animal.
CHITS.e:
From Middle English chitte (“a young animal, cub, whelp”), from Old English *ċytten, *ċietten, *ċitten, from Proto-West Germanic *kittīn, from Proto-Germanic *kittīną (“young animal, fawn, kid”).
Cognate with Scots chit (“chit”), Low German kitte (“young animal”), German Kitz (“f...

CHOPS.d: Plural of CHOP: A cut of meat, often containing a section of a rib.
CHOPS.e:
From Middle English choppen, chappen (“to chop”), of uncertain origin, possibly onomatopoeic, or a variant of chap (“to become cracked”).
Cognate with Scots chap (“to chop”). Compare also Saterland Frisian kappe, kapje (“to hack; chop; lop off”), Dutch kappen (“to chop, cut, hew”...

CHOWS.d: Plural of CHOW: Food, especially snacks.
CHOWS.e: Shortened from chow-chow, from Chinese Pidgin English chow-chow. Compare Macanese chau-cháu. See also English chow fun, chow mein, etc.

CHUBS.d: Plural of CHUB: One of various species of freshwater fish of the Cyprinidae or carp family, especially:
CHUBS.e: From chub (“short, thick fish species used as bait"; used metaphorically since 1558 for "lazy person”), from Middle English chubbe (“chub (the river fish)”), recorded since c.1450, probably an assibilated form of cub (“a lump, heap, mass”) and cob, from Middle English *cubbe (fou...

CHUGS.d: Plural of CHUG: A dull, fairly quick explosive or percussive sound, as if made by a labouring engine.
CHUGS.e: Onomatopoeic, in imitation of a working steam engine. The racial slur sense derives from the stereotype of Native Americans chugging alcohol.

CHUMS.d: Plural of CHUM: A friend; a pal.
CHUMS.e: 1675–85; of uncertain origin, possibly from cham, shortening of chambermate, or from comrade. Less likely from Welsh cymrawd (“fellow”), compare brawd (“brother”).

CINES.e: Clipping of cinefilm, from Ancient Greek κῑνέω (kīnéō, “to move”).

CITED.d: Past tense of CITE: To quote; to repeat, as a passage from a book, or the words of another.
CITED.e: From Old French citer, from Latin citare (“to cause to move, excite, summon”), frequentative of ciēre (“to rouse, excite, call”). Sense 4 is the original one.

CITES.d: Plural of CITE: To quote; to repeat, as a passage from a book, or the words of another.
CITES.e: From Old French citer, from Latin citare (“to cause to move, excite, summon”), frequentative of ciēre (“to rouse, excite, call”). Sense 4 is the original one.

CLADS.d: Plural of CLAD: simple past and past participle of clothe
CLADS.e: From Middle English clad, cladde, cled(e), cledde, past tense and past participle forms of clethen (“(also figurative) to put clothing on, clothe, dress; to provide clothing to; to arm, equip; to cover, envelop; to conceal; to adorn”), from Old English clǣþan (past tense clǣþde, ...

CLAIM.d: To assert; a demand for something.
CLAIM.e: From Old French clamer, from Latin clāmāre (to cry out).

CLAMS.d: Plural of CLAM: A bivalve mollusk of many kinds, especially those that are edible; for example soft-shell clams (Mya arenaria), hard clams (Mercenaria mercenaria), sea clams or hen clams (Spisula solidissima), and other species, possibly originally applied to clams of species Tridacna gigas, a huge East Indian bivalve.
CLAMS.e: From Middle English clam (“pincers, vice, clamp”), from Old English clamm (“bond, fetter, grip, grasp”), from Proto-West Germanic *klammjan (“press, squeeze together”). The sense “dollar” may allude to wampum. The sense "Scientologist" alludes to the Scientologist belief that hum...

CLANS.d: Plural of CLAN: A group of people all descended from a common ancestor, in fact or belief, especially when the exact genealogies are not known.
CLANS.e: Borrowed from Irish clann (“offspring, children of the family”) and Scottish Gaelic clann, both from Old Irish cland, borrowed from Old Welsh plant, itself borrowed from Latin planta (“shoot, offspring”). Doublet of plant and planta.

CLAPS.d: Plural of CLAP: The act of striking the palms of the hands, or any two surfaces, together.
CLAPS.e: From Middle English clappen, from Old English clæppan, from Proto-Germanic *klappōną. Cognate with Dutch klappen, Icelandic klappa, Faroese klappa and Danish klappe.

CLASS.d: A group; a lesson; social rank.

CLAWS.d: Plural of CLAW: A curved, pointed, horny projection on each digit of the foot of a mammal, reptile, or bird.
CLAWS.e: From Middle English clawe, from Old English clawu, from Proto-Germanic *klawō. Compare West Frisian klau, Dutch klauw, German Klaue, Danish klo, Norwegian klo, and Swedish klo.

CLAYS.d: Plural of CLAY: A mineral substance made up of small crystals of silica and alumina, that is ductile when moist; the material of pre-fired ceramics.
CLAYS.e:
From Middle English cley, clay, from Old English clǣġ (“clay”), from Proto-West Germanic *klaij, from Proto-Germanic *klajjaz (“clay”), from Proto-Indo-European *gley- (“to glue, paste, stick together”).
Cognate with Dutch klei (“clay”), Low German Klei (“clay”), German Klei, Dan...

CLEAN.d: Free from dirt; to remove dirt.

CLEAR.e: From Old French cler, from Latin clārus.

CLEFS.d: Plural of CLEF: A symbol found on a musical staff that indicates the pitches represented by the lines and the spaces on the staff
CLEFS.e: Borrowed from Middle French clef, from Latin clāvis (“a key”). Doublet of clave and clavis.

CLEWS.d: Plural of CLEW: A roughly spherical mass or body.
CLEWS.e: From Middle English clewe, from Old English cleowen, cliewen, cliwen (“sphere, ball, skein; ball of thread or yarn; mass, group”), from Proto-Germanic *kliuwiną, *klewô (“ball, bale”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to conglomerate, gather into a mass; clump, ball, bale”). Aki...

CLIPS.d: Plural of CLIP: To grip tightly.
CLIPS.e: From Middle English clippen, cleppen, clüppen, from Old English clyppan (“to hug, embrace, cherish, clasp”), from Proto-Germanic *klumpijaną, from Proto-Indo-European *glemb-, *glembʰ- (“lump, clump, clod, clamp”). Cognate with Old Frisian kleppa, klippa (“to hug, embrace”), Midd...

CLODS.d: Plural of CLOD: A lump of something, especially earth or clay.
CLODS.e:
From Middle English clod, a late by-form of clot, from Old English clot, from Proto-West Germanic *klott (“mass, ball, clump”). Compare clot and cloud; cognate to kloot (“clod”).
Alternatively, Middle English clod may derive from Old English *clod (found in Old English clodhamer ...

CLOGS.d: Plural of CLOG: A type of shoe with an inflexible, often wooden sole sometimes with an open heel.
CLOGS.e: Unknown; perhaps from Middle English clog (“weight attached to the leg of an animal to impede movement”). Perhaps of North Germanic origin and derived from Proto-Germanic *klumpô (“lump, mass, clasp”); compare Old Norse klugu, klogo (“knotty tree log”), Dutch klomp.

CLOPS.d: Plural of CLOP: The sound of a horse's shod hoof striking the ground.
CLOPS.e: Perhaps from German or Dutch kloppen (“to hit, knock”), from Middle Dutch cloppen (“to make a clopping sound”), of onomatopoeic origin. See also clap.

CLOSE.e: From Old French clos, from Latin clausus.

CLOTS.d: Plural of CLOT: A thrombus, solidified mass of blood.
CLOTS.e: From Middle English clot, clotte, from Old English clott, from Proto-West Germanic *klott (“lump”). Cognate with German Klotz (“block”). Doublet of clod and klutz.

CLOUD.d: A mass of water vapor in the sky.

CLOYS.d: Plural of CLOY: To fill up or choke up; to stop up.
CLOYS.e: From an aphetic form of Middle English acloyen, from Old French enclouer, encloer, from Vulgar Latin *inclāvāre, from Late Latin clāvāre, from Latin clāvus.

CLUBS.d: Plural of CLUB: A heavy object, often a kind of stick, intended for use as a bludgeoning weapon or a plaything.
CLUBS.e: Inherited from Middle English clubbe, from Old Norse klubba, klumba (“cudgel”), from Proto-Germanic *klumpô (“clip, clasp; clump, lump; log, block”). Cognate with English clump, cloud, Latin globus, glomus; and perhaps related to Middle Low German kolve (“bulb”), German Kolben (“...

CLUED.d: Past tense of CLUE: A strand of yarn etc. as used to guide one through a labyrinth; something which points the way, a guide.
CLUED.e: Variant of clew (“a ball of thread or yarn”), from Middle English clewe, from Old English clīewen (“ball”), from Proto-West Germanic *kliuwīn, from Proto-Germanic *kliuwīną, *klewô (“ball, bale”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to amass, conglomerate; clump, ball, bale”). Sens...

CLUES.d: Plural of CLUE: A strand of yarn etc. as used to guide one through a labyrinth; something which points the way, a guide.
CLUES.e: Variant of clew (“a ball of thread or yarn”), from Middle English clewe, from Old English clīewen (“ball”), from Proto-West Germanic *kliuwīn, from Proto-Germanic *kliuwīną, *klewô (“ball, bale”), from Proto-Indo-European *glew- (“to amass, conglomerate; clump, ball, bale”). Sens...

COALS.d: Plural of COAL: A black or brownish black rock formed from prehistoric plant remains, composed largely of carbon and burned as a fuel.
COALS.e:
From Middle English cole, from Old English col, from Proto-West Germanic *kol, from Proto-Germanic *kulą, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵwelH- (“to burn, shine”).
Cognate with West Frisian koal (“coal”), Cimbrian kholl (“coal”), Dutch kool (“coal; carbon”), German Kohle (“coal”), Lux...

COAST.e: From Old French coste, from Latin costa (rib, side).

COATS.d: Plural of COAT: An outer garment covering the upper torso and arms.
COATS.e:
From Middle English cote, coate, cotte, from Old French cote, cotte (“outer garment with sleeves”), from Latin cotta (“undercoat, tunic”), from Proto-Germanic *kuttô, *kuttǭ (“cowl, woolen cloth, coat”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷewd-, *gud- (“woolen clothes”).
Cognate with Old...

COCAS.d: Plural of COCA: Any of the four cultivated plants which belong to the family Erythroxylaceae, native to western South America.
COCAS.e: Borrowed from Spanish coca, from Quechua kuka, perhaps from Aymara.

COCKS.d: Plural of COCK: A male bird, especially:
COCKS.e:
From Middle English cok, from Old English coc, cocc (“cock, male bird”), from Proto-West Germanic *kokk, from Proto-Germanic *kukkaz (“cock”), probably of onomatopoeic origin.
Cognate with Middle Dutch cocke (“cock, male bird”) and Old Norse kokkr ("cock"; whence Danish kok (“coc...

COCOS.e: From Portuguese/Spanish coco (“grinning face”) (due to the three holes in the shell resembling a human face). Doublet of coque.

CODAS.d: Plural of CODA: A passage that brings a movement or piece to a conclusion through prolongation.
CODAS.e: Borrowed from Italian coda (literally “tail”), from Latin cauda. Doublet of queue and cola.

CODED.d: Past tense of CODE: A short textual designation, often with little relation to the item it represents.
CODED.e: From Middle English code (“system of law”), from Old French code (“system of law”), from Latin cōdex, later form of caudex (“the stock or stem of a tree, a board or tablet of wood smeared over with wax, on which the ancients originally wrote; hence, a book, a writing.”). Doublet ...

CODES.d: Plural of CODE: A short textual designation, often with little relation to the item it represents.
CODES.e: From Middle English code (“system of law”), from Old French code (“system of law”), from Latin cōdex, later form of caudex (“the stock or stem of a tree, a board or tablet of wood smeared over with wax, on which the ancients originally wrote; hence, a book, a writing.”). Doublet ...

COEDS.d: Plural of COED: Alternative form of co-ed.

COHOS.d: Plural of COHO: An anadromus and semelparous salmon, Oncorhynchus kisutch, found in the coastal regions of the northern Pacific Ocean, used as a symbol by several Native American tribes.
COHOS.e: The earlier spelling "cohose" was re-interpreted as a plural form (for a similar development, see pea). From Halkomelem.

COIFS.e: From Middle English coif, coife, coyf, coyfe, coyffe, from Old French coife, coiffe, from Late Latin cofia, from Proto-West Germanic *kuffju, related to Old High German kupphia, kupha, kupfe (“mug, hood, cap”), from Proto-Germanic *kuppijǭ (“cap, hat, bonnet, headpiece”), Proto-G...

COILS.d: Plural of COIL: Something wound in the form of a helix or spiral.
COILS.e: From Middle English coilen, from Old French coillir, cuillir (“to gather, pluck, pick, cull”) (modern French cueillir), from Latin colligō (“to gather together”), past participle collectus, from com- (“together”) + legō (“to gather”); compare legend. Doublet of cull.

COINS.d: Plural of COIN: A piece of currency, usually metallic and in the shape of a disc, but sometimes polygonal, or with a hole in the middle.
COINS.e: From Middle English coyn, from Old French coigne (“wedge, cornerstone, die for stamping”), from Latin cuneus (“wedge”). Doublet of coign and cuneus. See also quoin (“cornerstone”). Displaced Middle English mynt, from Old English mynet (whence modern English mint), which was deriv...

COKED.d: Past tense of COKE: Solid residue from roasting coal in a coke oven; used principally as a fuel and in the production of steel and formerly as a domestic fuel.
COKED.e: The origin is not certain. The OED says it is first attested in 1669. The MED has an earlier attestation in the related sense of "charcoal" in 1430: Middle English coke. This may be the same word as colk (“core”) (perhaps from the notion that coke is the core of the material left...

COKES.d: Plural of COKE: Solid residue from roasting coal in a coke oven; used principally as a fuel and in the production of steel and formerly as a domestic fuel.
COKES.e: The origin is not certain. The OED says it is first attested in 1669. The MED has an earlier attestation in the related sense of "charcoal" in 1430: Middle English coke. This may be the same word as colk (“core”) (perhaps from the notion that coke is the core of the material left...

COLAS.d: Plural of COLA: The kola plant, genus Cola, famous for its nut, or one of these nuts.
COLAS.e: From a Niger-Congo language, compare Temne kola, Mandinka kola. The beverage "Coca-Cola" was what made the term widely known, and popularized the spelling with c instead of k.

COLDS.d: Plural of COLD: Having a low temperature.
COLDS.e: From Middle English cold, from Anglian Old English cald. The West Saxon form, ċeald (“cold”), survived as early Middle English cheald, cheld, or chald. Both descended from Proto-West Germanic *kald, from Proto-Germanic *kaldaz, a participle form of *kalaną (“to be cold”), from Pr...

COLTS.d: Plural of COLT: A young male horse.
COLTS.e: From Middle English colt, from Old English colt, from Proto-Germanic *kultaz (“plump; stump; thick shape, bulb”), from Proto-Indo-European *gelt- (“something round, pregnant belly, child in the womb”), from *gel- (“to ball up, amass”). Cognate with Faroese koltur (“colt, foal”) N...

COMAS.d: Plural of COMA: A state of unconsciousness from which one may not wake up, usually induced by some form of trauma.
COMAS.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek κῶμα (kôma, “deep sleep”).

COMBS.d: Plural of COMB: A toothed implement:
COMBS.e:
From Middle English comb, from Old English camb (“comb”), from Proto-West Germanic *kamb, from Proto-Germanic *kambaz (“comb”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵómbʰos (“tooth”), a doublet of cam. The verb is derived from the noun and displaced the older verb kemb.
Cognates
Compare Sat...

COMES.d: Plural of COME: To move nearer to the point of perspective.
COMES.e:
From Middle English comen, cumen, from Old English cuman, from Proto-West Germanic *kweman, from Proto-Germanic *kwemaną (“to come”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷémt (“to step”), from *gʷem- (“to step”).
Cognates
Cognate from Proto-Germanic with Scots cum (“to come”), Saterland F...

COMPS.d: Plural of COMP: Clipping of complimentary.

CONED.d: Past tense of CONE: A surface of revolution formed by rotating a segment of a line around another line that intersects the first line.
CONED.e: From Middle English cone (“corner, angle”) and conoun (“cone”), from Medieval Latin cōnus, cōnon (“cone, wedge, peak”), from Ancient Greek κῶνος (kônos, “cone, spinning top, pine cone”). Reinforced by Middle French cone, from the same Graeco-Latin source.

CONES.d: Plural of CONE: A surface of revolution formed by rotating a segment of a line around another line that intersects the first line.
CONES.e: From Middle English cone (“corner, angle”) and conoun (“cone”), from Medieval Latin cōnus, cōnon (“cone, wedge, peak”), from Ancient Greek κῶνος (kônos, “cone, spinning top, pine cone”). Reinforced by Middle French cone, from the same Graeco-Latin source.

CONKS.d: Plural of CONK: The shelf- or bracket-shaped fruiting body of a bracket fungus (also called a shelf fungus), i.e. a mushroom growing off a tree trunk.
CONKS.e: Variant or figurative use of conch. Attested since the nineteenth century.

COOED.d: Past tense of COO: The murmuring sound made by a dove or pigeon.

COOKS.d: Plural of COOK: A person who prepares food.
COOKS.e:
From Middle English cook, from Old English cōc (“a cook”), from Latin cocus, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *pekʷ- (“to cook, become ripe”).
Cognate with Low German kokk, Dutch kok, German Koch, Danish kok, Norwegian kokk, Swedish kock, Icelandic kokkur (“cook”). Also compar...

COOLS.d: Plural of COOL: Of a mildly low temperature.
COOLS.e:
From Middle English cool, from Old English cōl (“cool, cold, tranquil, calm”), from Proto-West Germanic *kōl(ī), from Proto-Germanic *kōlaz, *kōluz (“cool”), from Proto-Indo-European *gel- (“cold”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian köil (“cool”), West Frisian koel (“cool”), Dutch k...

COOPS.d: Plural of COOP: A basket, pen or enclosure for birds or small animals.
COOPS.e: From Middle English cǒupe, cupe, from Old English cȳpe (“basket, cask”) or possibly from Middle Dutch cûpe (compare modern Dutch kuip, Saterland Frisian kupe, Middle Low German kûpe), from Old Saxon *kûpa, côpa (“cask”) (compare Middle Low German kôpe, Old High German chôfa, chuo...

COOTS.d: Plural of COOT: Any of various aquatic birds of the genus Fulica that are mainly black with a prominent frontal shield on the forehead.
COOTS.e: From Middle English cote, coote, cute, cuytt (“coot”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from an unrecorded Old English word, or borrowed from Middle Dutch coet, cuut, kuut (“coot”) (whence modern Dutch koet and meerkoet (“coot”)). Possibly related to Middle High German kūz, kūze (mod...

COPED.d: Past tense of COPE: To deal effectively with something, especially if difficult.
COPED.e: From Middle English coupen, from Old French coper, couper (“to strike, to cut”). The noun use went mainstream around 2020.

COPES.d: Plural of COPE: To deal effectively with something, especially if difficult.
COPES.e: From Middle English coupen, from Old French coper, couper (“to strike, to cut”). The noun use went mainstream around 2020.

CORDS.d: Plural of CORD: A long, thin, flexible length of twisted yarns (strands) of fibre (a rope, for example).
CORDS.e: From Middle English corde, from Old French corde, from Latin chorda, from Ancient Greek χορδή (khordḗ, “string of gut, the string of a lyre”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰerH- (“bowels, intestines”)). Doublet of chord and cuerda. More at yarn and hernia.

CORED.d: Past tense of CORE: In general usage, an essential part of a thing surrounded by other essential things.
CORED.e: From Middle English core, kore, coor (“apple-core, pith”), of obscure and uncertain origin. Possibly of native English origin, from Old English *cor, related to Old English *coruc, *corc (diminutive) (> Middle English cork, crok (“core of an apple or other fruit, heart of an onio...

CORES.d: Plural of CORE: In general usage, an essential part of a thing surrounded by other essential things.
CORES.e: From Middle English core, kore, coor (“apple-core, pith”), of obscure and uncertain origin. Possibly of native English origin, from Old English *cor, related to Old English *coruc, *corc (diminutive) (> Middle English cork, crok (“core of an apple or other fruit, heart of an onio...

CORKS.d: Plural of CORK: The dead protective tissue between the bark and cambium in woody plants, with suberin deposits making it impervious to gasses and water.
CORKS.e: From Middle English cork (“oak bark, cork”), from Middle Dutch curc (“cork (material or object)”), either from Spanish corcho (“cork (material or object)”) (also corcha or corche) or from Old Spanish alcorque (“cork sole”). Doublet of cortex.

CORMS.d: Plural of CORM: A short, vertical, swollen, underground stem of a plant (usually one of the monocots) that serves as a storage organ to enable the plant to survive winter or other adverse conditions such as drought.
CORMS.e: From scientific Latin cormus, from Ancient Greek κορμός (kormós, “trunk stripped of its boughs”).

CORNS.d: Plural of CORN: Any cereal plant (or its grain) that is the main crop or staple of a country or region.
CORNS.e:
Inherited from Middle English corn, from Old English corn, from Proto-West Germanic *korn, from Proto-Germanic *kurną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵr̥h₂nóm (“grain; worn-down”), from *ǵerh₂- (“grow old, mature”).
Cognate with Dutch koren, German Low German Koorn, German Korn, Danis...

COSES.d: Plural of COS: Synonym of romaine lettuce, a long-leaved variety of lettuce.
COSES.e: Clipping of cos lettuce, variously derived from the Greek island of Kos and from Arabic خس (ḵass, “lettuce”).

COSTS.d: Plural of COST: To incur a charge of; to require payment of a (specified) price.
COSTS.e: From Middle English costen, from Old French coster, couster (“to cost”), from Medieval Latin cōstō, from Latin cōnstō (“stand together”).

COTED.d: Past tense of COTE: A cottage or hut.
COTED.e: From Middle English cote, from the Old English cote, the feminine form of cot (“small house”); doublet of cot (in the sense of “cottage”) and more distantly related to cottage. Cognate to Dutch kot.

COTES.d: Plural of COTE: A cottage or hut.
COTES.e: From Middle English cote, from the Old English cote, the feminine form of cot (“small house”); doublet of cot (in the sense of “cottage”) and more distantly related to cottage. Cognate to Dutch kot.

COUNT.e: From Old French conter, from Latin computāre.

COUPS.d: Plural of COUP: A quick, brilliant, and highly successful act.
COUPS.e: Reborrowed in modern times from modern French coup (“blow, strike”), from Old French coup, colp, from Late Latin colpus, from Latin colaphus. Doublet of cope and colpus. The same Old French word had been borrowed into Middle English as coupe, caupe (with different pronunciation).

COURT.d: A place for legal proceedings; a royal residence.
COURT.e: From Old French cort, from Latin cohors.

COVED.d: Past tense of COVE: A hollow in a rock; a cave or cavern.
COVED.e: From Middle English cove, from Old English cofa (“chamber; den”), from Proto-West Germanic *kobō, from Proto-Germanic *kubô. Cognate with Dutch koof (“cove”), German Low German Koov (“small room”), German Koben (“nook, shed”), Icelandic kofi (“hut, shack”). This word has probably...

COVER.d: To place something over; a lid.
COVER.e: From Old French covrir, from Latin cooperīre.

COVES.d: Plural of COVE: A hollow in a rock; a cave or cavern.
COVES.e: From Middle English cove, from Old English cofa (“chamber; den”), from Proto-West Germanic *kobō, from Proto-Germanic *kubô. Cognate with Dutch koof (“cove”), German Low German Koov (“small room”), German Koben (“nook, shed”), Icelandic kofi (“hut, shack”). This word has probably...

COWED.d: Past tense of COW: An adult female of the species Bos taurus, especially one that has calved.
COWED.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *gʷṓws
Proto-Germanic *kōz
Proto-West Germanic *kō
Old English cū
Middle English cow
English cow
Inherited from Middle English cow, cou, from Old English cū (“cow”), from Proto-West Germanic *kō, from Proto-Germanic *kōz (“cow”), from Proto-Indo...

COWLS.d: Plural of COWL: A monk's hood that can be pulled forward to cover the face; a robe with such a hood attached to it.
COWLS.e: From Middle English coule, from Old English cūle, from earlier cugele (“hood, cowl”), from Ecclesiastical Latin cuculla (“monk's cowl”), from Latin cucullus (“hood”), of uncertain origin. Doublet of cagoule.

COXED.d: Past tense of COX: A coxswain of a boat, especially of a racing crew.

COXES.d: Plural of COX: A coxswain of a boat, especially of a racing crew.

COYED.d: Past tense of COY: Bashful, shy, retiring.
COYED.e: From Middle English coy, from Old French coi, earlier quei (“quiet, still”), from Latin qu(i)ētus (“resting, at rest”). Doublet of quit, quiet, quite, and quietus.

CRABS.d: Plural of CRAB: Any crustacean of the infraorder Brachyura, having five pairs of legs, the foremost of which are in the form of claws, and a carapace.
CRABS.e: From Middle English crabbe, from Old English crabba (“crab; crayfish; cancer”), from Proto-West Germanic *krabbō, from Proto-Germanic *krabbô, from *krabbōną (“to creep, crawl”), from Proto-Indo-European *grobʰeh₂yéti (“scratch, claw at”), a metathesised o-grade of *gerbʰ-. More ...

CRACK.d: A narrow break; to break without separating.

CRAFT.d: A skill; a vehicle; to make by hand.

CRAGS.d: Plural of CRAG: A rocky outcrop; a rugged steep cliff or rock.
CRAGS.e: From 13th century Middle English crag, from Middle Irish crec, a contracted form of Middle Irish carrac (compare Irish creig, Scottish Gaelic creag), possibly ultimately from the late Proto-Indo-European/substrate *kar (“stone, hard”); see also Old Armenian քար (kʻar, “stone”), S...

CRAMS.d: Plural of CRAM: To press, force, or drive, particularly in filling, or in thrusting one thing into another; to stuff; to fill to superfluity.
CRAMS.e: From Middle English crammen, from Old English crammian (“to cram; stuff”), from Proto-West Germanic *krammōn, from Proto-Germanic *krammōną, a secondary verb derived from *krimmaną (“to stuff”), from Proto-Indo-European *ger- (“to assemble; collect; gather”). Compare Old English ...

CRAPS.d: Plural of CRAP: The husk of grain; chaff.
CRAPS.e: From Middle English crappe, also in plural: crappys, craps (“chaff; buckwheat”), from Middle French crape, from Old French crappe, crapin (“chaff”) (compare Medieval Latin crappa pl, also crapinum), from Old Dutch krappen (“to cut off, pluck off”) (whence Middle Dutch crappe, cra...

CRAWS.d: Plural of CRAW: The stomach of an animal.
CRAWS.e: Late Middle English, also attested as craue, from or related to Middle Dutch crāghe or Middle Low German crāghe (“collar, neck”), from Proto-Germanic *kragô (“throat”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *gʷrogʰ- or *gʷrh₃-gʰ- (“throat, gullet”), whence also Proto-Celtic *brāgants...

CREAM.d: The fatty part of milk; a pale yellow colour.

CREWS.d: Plural of CREW: A group of people together
CREWS.e: From Middle English crue, from Old French creue (“an increase, recruit, military reinforcement”), the feminine past participle of creistre (“grow”), from Latin crescere (“to arise, grow”).

CRIBS.d: Plural of CRIB: A baby’s bed with high, often slatted, often moveable sides, suitable for a child who has outgrown a cradle or bassinet.
CRIBS.e: From Middle English crib, cribbe, from Old English crib, cryb, cribb, crybb (“couch, bed; manger, stall”), from Proto-West Germanic *kribbjā, from Proto-Germanic *kribjǭ (“crib, wickerwork”), from Proto-Indo-European *grebʰ-, *gerbʰ- (“bunch, bundle, tuft, clump”), from *ger- (“t...

CRIED.d: Past tense of CRY: To shed tears; to weep. Especially in anger or sadness
CRIED.e: The verb is from Middle English crien (13th century), from Old French crier, from Vulgar Latin *crītāre, generally thought to derive from Classical Latin quirītāre (Proto-West Germanic *krītan has also been suggested as a source). The noun corresponds to Middle English cry, crie,...

CRIER.d: Comparative form of CRY: To shed tears; to weep. Especially in anger or sadness
CRIER.e: The verb is from Middle English crien (13th century), from Old French crier, from Vulgar Latin *crītāre, generally thought to derive from Classical Latin quirītāre (Proto-West Germanic *krītan has also been suggested as a source). The noun corresponds to Middle English cry, crie,...

CRIES.d: Plural of CRY: To shed tears; to weep. Especially in anger or sadness
CRIES.e: The verb is from Middle English crien (13th century), from Old French crier, from Vulgar Latin *crītāre, generally thought to derive from Classical Latin quirītāre (Proto-West Germanic *krītan has also been suggested as a source). The noun corresponds to Middle English cry, crie,...

CROPS.d: Plural of CROP: A plant, grown for it, or its fruits or seeds, to be harvested as food, livestock fodder, or fuel or for any other economic purpose.
CROPS.e: From Middle English crop, croppe, from Old English crop, cropp, croppa (“the head or top of a plant, a sprout or herb, a bunch or cluster of flowers, an ear of corn, the craw of a bird, a kidney”), from Proto-West Germanic *kropp, from Proto-Germanic *kruppaz (“body, trunk, crop”...

CROSS.d: A shape with intersecting lines; to go across.
CROSS.e: From Old Irish cross, from Latin crux.

CROWN.d: A royal headdress; the top of the head.
CROWN.e: From Anglo-Norman coroune, from Latin corōna.

CROWS.d: Plural of CROW: A bird, usually black, of the genus Corvus, having a strong conical beak, with projecting bristles; it has a harsh, croaking call.
CROWS.e: From Middle English crowe, from Old English crāwe, from Proto-West Germanic *krāā, from Proto-Germanic *krēǭ (compare West Frisian krie, Dutch kraai, German Krähe), from *krēaną (“to crow”). See below.

CRUDS.d: Plural of CRUD: Dirt, filth or refuse.
CRUDS.e: From Middle English crud, crudde (“coagulated milk; curd; any coagulated or thickened substance; dregs”), from Old English crūdan (“to press”). Doublet of curd.

CUBED.d: Past tense of CUBE: A regular polyhedron having six identical square faces.
CUBED.e: From Old French cube, from Latin cubus, from Ancient Greek κύβος (kúbos).

CUBES.d: Plural of CUBE: A regular polyhedron having six identical square faces.
CUBES.e: From Old French cube, from Latin cubus, from Ancient Greek κύβος (kúbos).

CUFFS.e: From Middle English cuffe, coffe (“glove, mitten”), of obscure origin. Perhaps from Old English cuffie (“hood, cap”), from Medieval Latin cofia, cofea, cuffa, cuphia (“helmet, headdress, hood, cap”), from Frankish *kuf(f)ja (“headdress”), from Proto-West Germanic *kuffju, from Pr...

CUING.d: Present participle of CUE: The name of the Latin-script letter Q/q.
CUING.e: From Middle English cu (used for half a farthing, from q as an abbreviation for Latin quadrāns (“quarter of an as”)), from Latin cū, kū. Compare French ku.

CULLS.d: Plural of CULL: To pick or take someone or something (from a larger group).
CULLS.e: From Middle English cullen, cuilen, coilen, from Old French cuillir (“collect, gather, select”), from Latin colligō (“gather together”). Doublet of coil.

CULMS.d: Plural of CULM: Waste coal, used as a poor quality fuel.
CULMS.e: From Middle English culme, colme (“fragments of coal”), of uncertain origin. Probably from Old English *colm, related to Old English col (“coal”). Alternatively, perhaps from Welsh cwlm (“knot or tie”), applied to this species of coal, which is much found in balls or knots in som...

CULTS.d: Plural of CULT: The veneration, devotion, and religious rites given to a deity (especially in a historical polytheistic context), or (in a Christian context) to a saint; a subset of worship.
CULTS.e: Derived from French culte, from Latin cultus (“care, adoration; cult”), from colō (“cultivate; protect”).

CUNTS.d: Plural of CUNT: The female genitalia, especially the vulva.
CUNTS.e: From Middle English cunte, queynt, queynte, from Old English *cunte, from Proto-West Germanic *kuntā, from Proto-Germanic *kuntǭ. Cognate with West Frisian kunte, Middle Dutch conte (Dutch kont (“butt”)), dialectal Swedish kunta, dialectal Danish kunte, and Icelandic kunta. A rel...

CURBS.d: Plural of CURB: A concrete margin along the edge of a road; a kerb (UK, Australia, New Zealand).
CURBS.e: From Middle French courbe (“curve, curved object”), from Latin curvus (“bent, crooked, curved”). Doublet of curve.

CURDS.d: Plural of CURD: The part of milk that coagulates when it sours or is treated with enzymes; used to make cottage cheese, dahi, etc.
CURDS.e: From Middle English curd, a metathetic variant of crud, crudde (“coagulated substance”). Doublet of crud.

CURED.d: Past tense of CURE: A method, device or medication that restores good health.
CURED.e: From Middle English cure, borrowed from Old French cure (“care, cure, healing, cure of souls”), from Latin cura (“care, medical attendance, cure”). Displaced native Old English hǣlu, but survived as heal.

CURES.d: Plural of CURE: A method, device or medication that restores good health.
CURES.e: From Middle English cure, borrowed from Old French cure (“care, cure, healing, cure of souls”), from Latin cura (“care, medical attendance, cure”). Displaced native Old English hǣlu, but survived as heal.

CURLS.d: Plural of CURL: A curving piece or lock of hair; a ringlet.
CURLS.e: From metathesis of Middle English crulle (“curled, curly”), of uncertain origin but probably from an unrecorded Old English word or from Middle Dutch crul, crulle (“curl”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *kruzlǭ (“bent or crooked object, curl”), connected to *krūsą (“curl”), of u...

CUSPS.d: Plural of CUSP: A sharp point or pointed end.
CUSPS.e: From Latin cuspis (“a point, spear, pointed end”); first used in astrology. Doublet of cuspid and cuspis.

CUTES.d: Plural of CUTE: Possessing physical features, behaviors, personality traits or other properties that are mainly attributed to infants and small or cuddly animals; e.g. fair, dainty, round, and soft physical features, disproportionately large eyes and head, playfulness, fragility, helplessness, curiosity or shyness, innocence, affectionate behavior.
CUTES.e: Aphetic form of acute, originally meaning “keenly perceptive or discerning, shrewd” (1731). Meaning transferred to “pretty, fetching” by US students (slang) c. 1834. Meaning drifted further to describe the pleasing attraction to features usually possessed by the young.

CYANS.d: Plural of CYAN: An additive secondary colour midway between green and blue, evoked by wavelengths between ~490 and ~520 nm.
CYANS.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek κύανος (kúanos), a shade of blue variously described as similar to cornflower, copper carbonate, and lapis lazuli, Mycenaean Greek 𐀓𐀷𐀜 (ku-wa-no), possibly from Hittite [script needed] (kuwannan-, “a precious stone; copper; shade of blue”). Co...

CYMAS.d: Plural of CYMA: The wavelike, curved shape of a cymatium, consisting of a concave and a convex line; (loosely) the cymatium itself.
CYMAS.e:
From New Latin cȳma (“young sprout or shoot of cabbage”) (whence the botanic usage of cyme), from Ancient Greek κῦμα (kûma, “swell, wave”, “cyma”, “sprout of a plant”), from κύω (kúō, “I conceive, I become pregnant”).

CYSTS.d: Plural of CYST: A pouch or sac without opening, usually membranous and containing morbid matter, which develops in one of the natural cavities or in the substance of an organ.
CYSTS.e: From Late Latin cystis, from Ancient Greek κύστις (kústis, “anatomical sac”).

CZARS.d: Plural of CZAR: Alternative spelling of tsar (especially common in American English)
CZARS.e:

Proto-Germanic *kaisarazder.
Proto-Slavic *cěsařь
Old East Slavic цѣсарь (cěsarĭ)
Old East Slavic цьсарь (cĭsarĭ)
Russian царь (carʹ)bor.
English czar
See tsar. The spelling czar, the older spelling in English, comes from the book Notes on Muscovit...

DACES.d: Plural of DACE: A shoal-forming fish of species Leuciscus leuciscus, common to swift rivers in England and Wales and in Europe.
DACES.e:
Old variant of earlier darse, from Late Middle English darse (also as dace already), from Old French darz, oblique plural form of dart (“spear; javelin”).
For a similar loss of r, compare bass, while for the pronunciation with /eɪ/, see scarce.

DADOS.d: Plural of DADO: The section of a pedestal above the base.
DADOS.e: From Italian dado, first attested in 1664.

DAFFS.d: Plural of DAFF: A fool; an idiot; a blockhead.
DAFFS.e: From Middle English daf, daffe (“fool, idiot”), from Old Norse daufr (“deaf, stupid”), from Proto-Germanic *daubaz (“deaf, stunned”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, whirl, smoke, be obscure”). Doublet of deaf, dof, and dowf. Cognate with Swedish döv (“deaf”), Danis...

DAGOS.d: Plural of DAGO: A person of Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, Greek, or other Mediterranean or Latin descent.
DAGOS.e: Alteration of diego (“Spaniard”), from Spanish Diego (common Spanish name) by law of Hobson-Jobson.

DALES.d: Plural of DALE: A valley, often in an otherwise hilly area.
DALES.e: From Middle English dale, from Old English dæl, from Proto-West Germanic *dal, from Proto-Germanic *dalą.

DAMES.d: Plural of DAME: Usually capitalized as Dame: a title equivalent to Sir for a female knight.
DAMES.e: From Middle English dame, dam (“noble lady”), from Old French dame (“lady; term of address for a woman; the queen in card games and chess”), from Latin domina (“mistress of the house”), feminine form of dominus (“lord, master, ruler; owner of a residence”), or from Latin domus (“...

DAMNS.e: From Middle English dampnen, from Old French damner, from Latin damnāre (“to condemn, inflict loss upon”), from damnum (“loss”).

DAMPS.d: Plural of DAMP: In a state between dry and wet; moderately wet; moist.
DAMPS.e: From Middle English dampen (“to stifle; suffocate”). Akin to Low German damp, Dutch damp, and German Dampf (“vapor, steam, fog”), Icelandic dampi, Swedish damm (“dust”), and to German dampf imperative of dimpfen (“to smoke”). Also Middle English dampen (“to extinguish, choke, suf...
