DARED.e: From Middle English durren, from Old English durran, from Proto-West Germanic *durʀan, from Proto-Germanic *durzaną (“to dare”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰedʰórse (“to dare”), reduplicated stative of the root *dʰers- (“to be bold, to dare”), an *-s- extension of *dʰer- (“to hol...

DARES.d: Plural of DARE: To have enough courage (to do something).
DARES.e: From Middle English durren, from Old English durran, from Proto-West Germanic *durʀan, from Proto-Germanic *durzaną (“to dare”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰedʰórse (“to dare”), reduplicated stative of the root *dʰers- (“to be bold, to dare”), an *-s- extension of *dʰer- (“to hol...

DARKS.d: Plural of DARK: Having an absolute or (more often) relative lack of light.
DARKS.e: From Middle English derk, from Old English deorc, from Proto-West Germanic *derk (“dark”), of uncertain origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerg- (“dim, dull”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰer- (“dull, dirty”).

DARTS.d: Plural of DART: A pointed missile weapon, intended to be thrown by the hand; for example, a short lance or javelin.
DARTS.e:
From Middle English dart, from Old French dart, dard (“dart”), from Medieval Latin dardus, from Frankish *darōþu (“dart, spear”), from Proto-Germanic *darōþuz (“dart, spear”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerh₃- (“to leap, spring”).
Compare Old High German tart (“javelin, dart”), O...

DATES.d: Plural of DATE: The fruit of the date palm, Phoenix dactylifera, somewhat in the shape of an olive, containing a soft, sweet pulp and enclosing a hard kernel.
DATES.e: From Middle English date, from Old French date, datil, datille, from Latin dactylus (likely via Old Provençal datil), from Ancient Greek δάκτυλος (dáktulos, “finger”) (from the resemblance of the date to a human finger), probably a folk-etymological alteration of a word from a Se...

DAUBS.d: Plural of DAUB: Excrement or clay used as a bonding material in construction.
DAUBS.e: From Middle English daub (noun), from Middle English dauben (“to plaster or whitewash; cover with clay; bespatter”, verb), from Old Northern French dauber (“to whitewash; plaster”), of uncertain origin. Probably from Latin dealbāre (“to whiten thoroughly”).

DAWNS.d: Plural of DAWN: To begin to brighten with daylight.
DAWNS.e: From Middle English dawnen, either a back-formation from dawnynge or a modification of dawen (“to dawn”) after it. The noun is from the verb.

DAZED.d: Past tense of DAZE: The state of being dazed
DAZED.e:
From Middle English, back-formation from dazed.
Compare Old Norse dasask (“to become weary”), with reflexive suffix -sk, Swedish dasa (“lie idly”), and Icelandic dasask (“to make weary with cold”). Also compare Proto-Germanic *dusāną, to slumber.
Alternatively from Middle Dutch d...

DAZES.d: Plural of DAZE: The state of being dazed
DAZES.e:
From Middle English, back-formation from dazed.
Compare Old Norse dasask (“to become weary”), with reflexive suffix -sk, Swedish dasa (“lie idly”), and Icelandic dasask (“to make weary with cold”). Also compare Proto-Germanic *dusāną, to slumber.
Alternatively from Middle Dutch d...

DEADS.d: Plural of DEAD: No longer living; deceased. (Also used as a noun.)
DEADS.e: From Middle English ded, deed, from Old English dēad, from Proto-West Germanic *daud, from Proto-Germanic *daudaz. Compare West Frisian dead, dea, Dutch dood, German tot, Danish, Norwegian død, Norwegian Nynorsk daud.

DEALS.d: Plural of DEAL: A division, a portion, a share, a part, a piece.
DEALS.e: From Middle English del, dele, from Old English dǣl (“part, share, portion”), from Proto-West Germanic *daili, from Proto-Germanic *dailiz (“part, deal”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰ(h₁)-oy-lo- (“part, watershed”). Cognate with Scots dele (“part, portion”), West Frisian diel (“p...

DEANS.d: Plural of DEAN: A senior official in a college or university, who may be in charge of a division or faculty (for example, the dean of science) or have some other advisory or disciplinary function (for example, the dean of students).
DEANS.e: From Middle English den, deen (“dean”), from Anglo-Norman deen and continental Old French deien (modern French doyen), from Latin decānus. Doublet of doyen.

DEARS.d: Plural of DEAR: High in price; expensive.
DEARS.e: From Middle English dere, from Old English dīere (“of great value or excellence, expensive, beloved”), from Proto-West Germanic *diurī, from Proto-Germanic *diurijaz (“dear, precious, expensive”). Cognate with Scots dere, deir (“of great value or worth, highly valued, precious, b...

DEBTS.d: Plural of DEBT: An action, state of mind, or object one has an obligation to perform for another, adopt toward another, or give to another.
DEBTS.e: From Middle English dette, dett, borrowed from Old French dete (French dette), from Medieval Latin dēbita, from Latin dēbitum (“what is owed, a debt, a duty”), neuter of dēbitus, perfect passive participle of dēbeō (“I owe”), contraction of *dehibeō (“I have from”), from de (“fro...

DECKS.d: Plural of DECK: Any raised flat surface that can be walked on: a balcony; a porch; a raised patio; a flat rooftop.
DECKS.e: From Middle English dekke, borrowed from Middle Dutch dec (“roof, covering”), from Middle Dutch decken, from Old Dutch thecken, from Proto-West Germanic *þakkjan, from Proto-Germanic *þakjaną. Formed the same: German Decke (“covering, blanket”). Doublet of thatch and thack.

DEEDS.d: Plural of DEED: An action or act; something that is done.
DEEDS.e:
From Middle English dede, from Old English dēd, dǣd (“deed, act”), from Proto-West Germanic *dādi, from Proto-Germanic *dēdiz (“deed”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰéh₁tis (“deed, action”). Analyzable through Proto-Germanic as do + -th. Doublet of thesis.
The real estate sense der...

DEEMS.d: Plural of DEEM: To judge, to pass judgment on; to doom, to sentence.
DEEMS.e: From Middle English dēmen (“to judge; to criticize, condemn; to impose a penalty on, sentence; to direct, order; to believe, think, deem”), from Old English dēman (“to decide, decree, deem”), from Proto-West Germanic *dōmijan, from Proto-Germanic *dōmijaną (“to judge, think”), fr...

DEEPS.d: Plural of DEEP: Extending, reaching or positioned far from a point of reference, especially downwards.
DEEPS.e: From Middle English depe, deep, dep, deop, from Old English dēop (“deep, profound; awful, mysterious; heinous; serious, solemn, earnest; extreme, great”), from Proto-West Germanic *deup, from Proto-Germanic *deupaz (“deep”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ-nós, from *dʰewbʰ- (“d...

DEERS.d: Plural of DEER: A ruminant mammal with hooves and often antlers, of the family Cervidae, or one of several similar animals from related families of the order Artiodactyla, such as the musk deer or mouse deer.
DEERS.e:
From Middle English der, deer (“animal, deer”), from Old English dēor (“animal”), from Proto-West Germanic *deuʀ, from Proto-Germanic *deuzą, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewsóm (“living thing”), from *dʰéws (“breath”), full-grade derivative of *dʰwes-.
Cognate with Scots deer (“de...

DEKED.d: Past tense of DEKE: A feint, fake, or other move made by the player with the puck to deceive a goaltender or defenceman.
DEKED.e: Canadian English, a contraction of decoy.

DEKES.d: Plural of DEKE: A feint, fake, or other move made by the player with the puck to deceive a goaltender or defenceman.
DEKES.e: Canadian English, a contraction of decoy.

DELED.d: Past tense of DELE: To delete.
DELED.e: From Latin dēlē, second person singular imperative of dēleo (“delete”). Alternatively, a clipping of deleatur.

DELES.e: From Latin dēlē, second person singular imperative of dēleo (“delete”). Alternatively, a clipping of deleatur.

DELIS.d: Plural of DELI: A shop that sells cooked or prepared food ready for serving.
DELIS.e: Attested since 1954. Clipping of delicatessen, from German Delikatessen, plural of Delikatesse (“delicacy, fine food”), from French délicatesse, derived from the adjective délicat, from Latin delicatus.

DELLS.d: Plural of DELL: A small, deep, and wooded valley or sunken area of ground, especially in the form of a natural hollow.
DELLS.e: From Middle English delle, del, from Old English dell (“small dale”), from Proto-West Germanic *dalljā, from Proto-Germanic *daljō. Cognate to Proto-Slavic *dolъ (“below, down; valley, pit”), Welsh dôl (“meadow, dale”) and English dale.

DEMOS.d: Plural of DEMO: A demonstration or visual explanation.
DEMOS.e: Clipping of demonstration and various other words beginning with "demo-".

DENTS.d: Plural of DENT: A shallow deformation in the surface of an object, produced by an impact.
DENTS.e: From Middle English dent, dente, dint (“a blow; strike; dent”), from Old English dynt (“blow, strike, the mark or noise of a blow”), from Proto-Germanic *duntiz (“a blow”). Akin to Old Norse dyntr (“dint”). Doublet of dint.

DEPTH.d: The distance from top to bottom.

DESKS.d: Plural of DESK: A table, frame, or case, in past centuries usually with a sloping top but now usually with a flat top, for the use of writers and readers. It often has a drawer or repository underneath.
DESKS.e: From Middle English deske, desque, from Medieval Latin desca, modified from Old Italian desco, from Latin discus. Doublet of dais, disc, discus, dish, disk, and diskos. See also German Tisch, "table".

DEWED.d: Past tense of DEW: Any moisture from the atmosphere condensed by cool bodies upon their surfaces.
DEWED.e:
From Middle English dew, from Old English dēaw (“dew”), from Proto-West Germanic *dauw, from Proto-Germanic *dawwaz, *dawwą (“dew, moisture”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“smoke, haze”).
Cognate with German Tau, Dutch dauw and Afrikaans dou. Doublet of dag.

DHOWS.d: Plural of DHOW: A traditional sailing vessel used along the coasts of Arabia, East Africa, and the Indian Ocean, generally having a single mast and a lateen sail.

DIALS.d: Plural of DIAL: A graduated, circular scale over which a needle moves to show a measurement (such as speed).
DIALS.e: The original meaning was 'sundial' and/or 'clock dial'; from Middle English diall, from Middle French dyal, from Latin diālis (“daily, concerning the day”), because of its use in telling the time of day, from Latin diēs (“day”). Compare Spanish dial and día (“day”).

DICED.d: Past tense of DICE: Gaming with one or more dice.
DICED.e: From Middle English dys, plural of dy. See the etymology of die (etymology 2) for further information. The voiceless /s/ was most likely retained because the word felt like a collective term rather than a plural form (compare pence), and the spelling dice is a result of the pronu...

DICES.d: Plural of DICE: Gaming with one or more dice.
DICES.e: From Middle English dys, plural of dy. See the etymology of die (etymology 2) for further information. The voiceless /s/ was most likely retained because the word felt like a collective term rather than a plural form (compare pence), and the spelling dice is a result of the pronu...

DICKS.d: Plural of DICK: A male person.
DICKS.e: Ultimately from Dick, pet form of the name Richard. The name Dick came to mean "everyman", whence the word acquired its other meanings.

DIETS.d: Plural of DIET: The food and beverage a person or animal consumes.
DIETS.e: From Middle English diet, dyet, diete, from Old French diete, from Medieval Latin dieta (“regimen, regulation; assembly”), from Latin diaeta, from Ancient Greek δίαιτα (díaita).

DIKED.d: Past tense of DIKE: Alternative spelling of dyke: ditch; embankment; waterway; etc.

DIKES.d: Plural of DIKE: Alternative spelling of dyke: ditch; embankment; waterway; etc.

DILLS.d: Plural of DILL: Anethum graveolens (the type species of the genus Anethum), a herb, the seeds of which are moderately warming, pungent, and aromatic, formerly used as a soothing medicine for children; also known as dillseed.
DILLS.e:
From Middle English dile, from Old English dile (“dill, anise”); from Proto-Germanic *deliz, of uncertain, probably non-Indo-European origin, possibly a west European substrate.
Cognate with Old Saxon dilli, Dutch dille, Swedish dill, German Dill.

DIMES.d: Plural of DIME: A coin worth one-tenth of a dollar.
DIMES.e: From Middle English dime, from Anglo-Norman disme (“one tenth, tithe”) (modern French dîme), from Medieval Latin decima, from Latin decima (pars) (“tenth (part)”). Doublet of decim, decima, and decime.

DINED.d: Past tense of DINE: To eat; to eat dinner or supper.
DINED.e: From Middle English dynen, from Old French disner (“to dine, eat the main meal of the day”), from Vulgar Latin *disiūnāre (“to eat breakfast”), from *disieiūnāre (“to break the fast”), from Late Latin, from dis- + iēiūnō (“to fast”), from Latin ieiūnus.

DINES.d: Plural of DINE: To eat; to eat dinner or supper.
DINES.e: From Middle English dynen, from Old French disner (“to dine, eat the main meal of the day”), from Vulgar Latin *disiūnāre (“to eat breakfast”), from *disieiūnāre (“to break the fast”), from Late Latin, from dis- + iēiūnō (“to fast”), from Latin ieiūnus.

DINGS.d: Plural of DING: Very minor damage caused by being struck; a small dent or chip.
DINGS.e:
From Middle English dingen, dyngen (strong verb), from Old English *dingan (“to ding”), from Proto-West Germanic *dingwan, from Proto-Germanic *dingwaną (“to beat”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰen- (“to beat, push”).
Related to Old English denġan, denċġan (“to ding, knock, beat, ...

DINTS.d: Plural of DINT: A blow, stroke, especially dealt in a fight.
DINTS.e: From Middle English dint, dent, dünt, from Old English dynt (“dint, blow, strike, stroke, bruise, stripe; the mark left by a blow; the sound or noise made by a blow, thud”), from Proto-Germanic *duntiz (“a blow”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰen- (“to strike, hit”). Cognate with S...

DIRKS.d: Plural of DIRK: A long Scottish dagger with a straight blade.
DIRKS.e:
Etymology unknown, apparently from Scots dirk.
First attested in 1602 as dork, in the later 17th century as durk. The spelling dirk is due to Johnson's Dictionary of 1755.
Early quotations as well as Johnson 1755 suggest that the word is of Scottish Gaelic origin, but no such Gae...

DIRTS.d: Plural of DIRT: Soil or earth.
DIRTS.e: From Middle English drit (“excrement”), from Old Norse drit (“excrement”), from Proto-Germanic *dritą, *dritō (“excrement”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰreyd-, *treydʰ- (“to have diarrhea”). Cognate with Norwegian dritt (“excrement”), dialectal Swedish dret (“shit”), Icelandic dr...

DISCS.d: Plural of DISC: A thin, flat, circular plate or similar object.
DISCS.e: From French disque, from Latin discus, from Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “disk, quoit, platter”). Doublet of dais, desk, discus, dish, disk, and diskos.

DISKS.d: Plural of DISK: A thin, flat, circular plate or similar object.
DISKS.e: From Ancient Greek δίσκος (dískos, “a circular plate suited for hurling”), from δικέω (dikéō, “to hurl, to launch”). Doublet of dais, desk, disc, discus, dish, and diskos.

DIVAS.d: Plural of DIVA: Any female celebrity, usually a well known singer or actress.
DIVAS.e: From Italian diva (“diva, goddess”), from Latin dīva (“goddess”), female of dīvus (“divine, divine one; notably a deified mortal”), from Old Latin deivā, from Proto-Italic *deiwā (“goddess”), feminine of *deiwos (“god”), from Proto-Indo-European *deywós (“god”).

DIVED.d: Past tense of DIVE: To swim under water.
DIVED.e: From Middle English diven, duven, from the merger of Old English dȳfan (“to dip, immerse”, transitive weak verb) (from Proto-Germanic *dūbijaną) and dūfan (“to duck, dive, sink, penetrate”, intransitive strong verb) (past participle ġedofen). Cognate with Icelandic dýfa (“to dip,...

DOCKS.d: Plural of DOCK: Any of the genus Rumex of coarse weedy plants with small green flowers related to buckwheat, especially bitter dock (Rumex obtusifolius), and used as potherbs and in folk medicine, especially in curing nettle rash.
DOCKS.e: From Middle English dokke, from Old English docce, from Proto-West Germanic *dokkā, from Proto-Germanic *dukkǭ (compare Old Danish dokke (“water-dock”), West Flemish dokke, dokkebladeren (“coltsfoot, butterbur”)), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰew- (“dark”) (compare Latvian duga (“s...

DODOS.d: Plural of DODO: A large, flightless bird, †Raphus cucullatus, related to the pigeon, that is now extinct (since the 1600s) and was native to Mauritius.
DODOS.e: Uncertain. Perhaps from obsolete Portuguese doudo (“fool, simpleton, silly, stupid”) or Dutch dodaars. First attested in the 17th century.

DOFFS.d: Plural of DOFF: To remove or take off (something worn on the body such as armour or clothing, or something carried).
DOFFS.e:
PIE word
 *h₂epó
The verb is derived from Late Middle English doffen (“to take off (clothing); to remove (headwear) as a sign of respect; to remove (grease) by skimming”), a contraction of Middle English do off, don off, from Old English dōn of, from dōn (“to do; to put; to take ...

DOGES.d: Plural of DOGE: The chief magistrate in the republics of Venice and Genoa.
DOGES.e: Partly from Middle French doge and partly from its etymon, Italian doge, from Venetan doxe, from Latin ducem, accusative of dux (“leader; commander; ruler”). Doublet of duc, duce, duke, and dux.

DOING.d: Present participle of DOE: A female deer; also used of similar animals such as antelope (less commonly a goat, as nanny is also used).
DOING.e:
From Middle English do, from Old English dā (“female deer”), from Proto-West Germanic *daijā, from Proto-Germanic *dajjǭ (“female deer, mother deer”), from Proto-Germanic *dajjaną (“to suckle”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁(y)- (“to suck (milk), to suckle”).
Cognate with Scots...

DOITS.d: Plural of DOIT: A small Dutch coin, equivalent to one-eighth of a stiver.
DOITS.e: Borrowed from Middle Low German doyt, cognate with Middle Dutch duit. Doublet of thwaite.

DOJOS.d: Plural of DOJO: A training facility, usually led by one or more sensei; a hall or room used for such training.
DOJOS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 道場 (dōjō, literally “place of the ways”). Doublet of dojang.

DOLED.d: Past tense of DOLE: To distribute in small amounts; to share out small portions of a meager resource.
DOLED.e: From Middle English dol, from Old English dāl (“portion, share, division, allotment”), from Proto-Germanic *dailą (“part, deal”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰayl- (“part, watershed”). Cognate with Old Church Slavonic дѣлити (děliti, “divide”). More at deal.

DOLES.d: Plural of DOLE: To distribute in small amounts; to share out small portions of a meager resource.
DOLES.e: From Middle English dol, from Old English dāl (“portion, share, division, allotment”), from Proto-Germanic *dailą (“part, deal”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰayl- (“part, watershed”). Cognate with Old Church Slavonic дѣлити (děliti, “divide”). More at deal.

DOLLS.d: Plural of DOLL: A small figure resembling a human being that is used as a toy.
DOLLS.e:
From Doll, pet form of the given name Dorothy.
The drug sense was coined and popularized by by American writer Jacqueline Susann in 1966 through her book Valley of the Dolls (1966) or the film Valley of the Dolls (1967).

DOLTS.d: Plural of DOLT: A stupid person; a blockhead or dullard.
DOLTS.e: First used as a noun in Early Modern English, from dialectal English dold (“stupid, confused”), from Middle English dold, a variant of dulled, dult (“dulled”), past participle of dullen, dollen (“to make dull, make stupid”), from dull, dul, dwal (“stupid”). More at dull.

DOMED.d: Past tense of DOME: A structural element resembling the hollow upper half of a sphere.
DOMED.e: Borrowed from Middle French dome, domme (modern French dôme), from Italian duomo, from Latin domus (ecclesiae) (literally “house (of the church)”), a calque of Ancient Greek οἶκος τῆς ἐκκλησίας (oîkos tês ekklēsías). Doublet of domus and duomo.

DOMES.d: Plural of DOME: A structural element resembling the hollow upper half of a sphere.
DOMES.e: Borrowed from Middle French dome, domme (modern French dôme), from Italian duomo, from Latin domus (ecclesiae) (literally “house (of the church)”), a calque of Ancient Greek οἶκος τῆς ἐκκλησίας (oîkos tês ekklēsías). Doublet of domus and duomo.

DONAS.d: Plural of DONA: Alternative form of donah.

DONGS.d: Plural of DONG: The currency of Vietnam, 100 xus. Symbol: ₫
DONGS.e: Borrowed from Vietnamese đồng, from Middle Chinese 銅 (duwng, “copper”), from Old Chinese 銅 (*doːŋ). Cognate with Mandarin 銅 /铜 (tóng, “copper”).

DOOMS.d: Plural of DOOM: Destiny, especially terrible.
DOOMS.e:
From Middle English doom, dom, from Old English dōm (“judgement”), from Proto-West Germanic *dōm, from Proto-Germanic *dōmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰóh₁mos.
Cognates
Compare Dutch doem (“condemnation, doom; judgement”), Danish, Norwegian Bokmål, Norwegian Nynorsk, and Swedis...

DOORS.d: Plural of DOOR: A portal of entry into a building, room, or vehicle, typically consisting of a rigid plane movable on a hinge. It may have a handle to help open and close, a latch to hold it closed, and a lock that ensures it cannot be opened without a key.
DOORS.e:
From Middle English dore, dor, from Old English duru (“door”), dor (“gate”), from Proto-West Germanic *dur, from Proto-Germanic *durz, from Proto-Indo-European *dʰwṓr, from *dʰwer- (“doorway, door, gate”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots door (“door”), Saterland Frisian Doore (“door”...

DOPAS.d: Plural of DOPA: The amino acid dihydroxyphenylalanine that is generated in the liver from tyrosine and then converted into dopamine in the brain.

DOPED.d: Past tense of DOPE: Any viscous liquid or paste, such as a lubricant, used in preparing a surface.
DOPED.e:
From Dutch doop (“thick dipping sauce”), from Dutch dopen (“to dip”), from Middle Dutch dopen, from Old Dutch *dōpen, from Frankish *daupijan, from Proto-Germanic *daupijaną.
“Doop” in the sense “narcotic drug” ultimately refers to viscous opium juice, the drug of choice of the a...

DOPES.d: Plural of DOPE: Any viscous liquid or paste, such as a lubricant, used in preparing a surface.
DOPES.e:
From Dutch doop (“thick dipping sauce”), from Dutch dopen (“to dip”), from Middle Dutch dopen, from Old Dutch *dōpen, from Frankish *daupijan, from Proto-Germanic *daupijaną.
“Doop” in the sense “narcotic drug” ultimately refers to viscous opium juice, the drug of choice of the a...

DORMS.d: Plural of DORM: Clipping of dormitory.

DORPS.d: Plural of DORP: A village or small town; a town considered provincial.
DORPS.e: Borrowed from Dutch dorp, which see for more. Doublet of dorf and thorp, and possibly also of troop and troupe.

DOSED.d: Past tense of DOSE: A measured portion of medicine taken at any one time.
DOSED.e: Borrowed from Middle French dose, from Late Latin dosis, from Ancient Greek δόσις (dósis, “a portion prescribed”, literally “a giving”), used by Galen and other Greek physicians to mean an amount of medicine, from δίδωμι (dídōmi, “to give”). Doublet of doos.

DOSES.d: Plural of DOS: Initialism of date of service.

DOTED.d: Past tense of DOTE: To be weakly or foolishly fond of somebody.
DOTED.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English doten, from Middle Low German doten (“to be foolish”) or Middle Dutch doten (“to be silly”). Doublet of doit (Scottish English).
The noun in the sense of "imbecile" is derived from Middle English dote (“simpleton”), itself from doten (see a...

DOTES.d: Plural of DOTE: To be weakly or foolishly fond of somebody.
DOTES.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English doten, from Middle Low German doten (“to be foolish”) or Middle Dutch doten (“to be silly”). Doublet of doit (Scottish English).
The noun in the sense of "imbecile" is derived from Middle English dote (“simpleton”), itself from doten (see a...

DOUBT.e: From Old French douter, from Latin dubitāre.

DOVES.d: Plural of DOVE: A pigeon, especially one smaller in size and white-colored; a bird (often arbitrarily called either a pigeon or a dove or both) of more than 300 species of the family Columbidae.
DOVES.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ-der.?
Proto-Germanic *dūbaną?
Proto-Germanic *dūbǭ
Proto-West Germanic *dūbā
Old English *dūfe
Middle English douve
English dove
Inherited from Middle English douve, dove, duve, from Old English *dūfe (“dove, pigeon”), from Proto-West Ge...

DOWNS.d: Plural of DOWN: From a higher position to a lower one; downwards.
DOWNS.e: From Middle English doun, doune, from Old English dūne (“down”), aphetic form of adūne (“down, downward”), from earlier ofdūne (“down”, literally “off the hill”), from of (“of, off of”) + dūn (“hill, mount, dune, down”). More at Etymology 2 below. For the development from directi...

DOZED.d: Past tense of DOZE: To sleep lightly or briefly; to nap, snooze.
DOZED.e:
From Middle English *dosen, from Old Norse dúsa (“to doze, rest, remain quiet”), from Proto-Germanic *dusāną (“to be dizzy”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰews- (“to fly, whirl”), from *dʰew- (“to fly, shake, reek, steam, smolder”).
Cognate with Old Frisian dusia (“to be dizzy”), G...

DRABS.d: Plural of DRAB: A fabric, usually of thick cotton or wool, having a dull brownish yellow, dull grey, or dun colour.
DRABS.e:
Probably from Middle French and Old French drap (“cloth”), either:
* from Late Latin drappus (“drabcloth, kerchief; piece of cloth”), most likely from Gaulish *drappo, from Proto-Indo-European *drep- (“to scratch, tear”); or
* from Frankish *drapi, *drāpi (“that which is fulled, ...

DRAFT.d: A preliminary version; a current of air.

DRAGS.d: Plural of DRAG: Resistance of a fluid to something moving through it.
DRAGS.e: From Middle English draggen (“to drag”), early Middle English dragen (“to draw, carry”), confluence of Old English dragan (“to drag, draw, draw oneself, go, protract”) and Old Norse draga (“to draw, attract”); both from Proto-Germanic *draganą (“to draw, drag”), from Proto-Indo-E...

DRAMS.d: Plural of DRAM: A small unit of weight, variously:
DRAMS.e: From Middle English dragme, dramme, from Old French dragme, drame, from Late Latin dragma, from Latin drachma, from Ancient Greek δραχμή (drakhmḗ, “unit of weight; a handful”). Doublet of drachma, diram, dirham, dirhem, and adarme.

DRATS.d: Plural of DRAT: To damn or curse.
DRATS.e: An aphetism of od-rat (“God rot”) as a minced oath.

DRAWS.d: Plural of DRAW: Senses relating to exerting force or pulling.
DRAWS.e: The verb is derived from Middle English drauen, drawen, draȝen, dragen (“to drag, pull; to draw (out); to attract; to entice, lure; to lead; to make a drawing; to move, travel; etc.”), from Old English dragan (“to drag, draw”), from Proto-West Germanic *dragan (“to carry; to haul...

DRAYS.d: Plural of DRAY: Any of various forms of low horse-drawn cart or wagon, often without sides or with removable sides, and used especially for heavy loads.
DRAYS.e: From Middle English draye, dreye, from Old English dræġe (“dragnet”), from Proto-Germanic *dragǭ. Cognate with Middle Low German drāge (“stretcher; dray”), Middle High German trage (“a litter”). Related to Old English dragan (“to pull; draw”). More at draw.

DREGS.d: Plural of DREG: singular of dregs (“sediment in a liquid”)
DREGS.e: Borrowed from Old Norse dregg (“sediment”), from Proto-Germanic *dragjō (whence also Icelandic dregg, Swedish drägg), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰrā́ks (“sediment”); see also Latin fraces (“lees of oil”), Albanian ndrag (“to make dirty, foul”), dra (“sediments of dairy products o...

DRESS.d: A garment; to put on clothes.

DRIBS.d: Plural of DRIB: To cut off; chop off.
DRIBS.e: From dialectal English drib (compare also drub), a variant from Middle English drepen (“to hit, strike, slay”), from Old English drepan (“to strike, kill, overcome”), from Proto-Germanic *drepaną (“to hit, strike”).

DRIED.d: Past tense of DRY: Free from or lacking moisture.
DRIED.e: Adjective and noun from Middle English drye, dryge, drüȝe, from Old English drȳġe (“dry; parched, withered”), from Proto-West Germanic *drūgī, *draugī, from Proto-Germanic *drūgiz, *draugiz (“dry, hard”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard”), from *dʰe...

DRIER.d: Comparative form of DRY: Free from or lacking moisture.
DRIER.e: Adjective and noun from Middle English drye, dryge, drüȝe, from Old English drȳġe (“dry; parched, withered”), from Proto-West Germanic *drūgī, *draugī, from Proto-Germanic *drūgiz, *draugiz (“dry, hard”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard”), from *dʰe...

DRIES.d: Plural of DRY: Free from or lacking moisture.
DRIES.e: Adjective and noun from Middle English drye, dryge, drüȝe, from Old English drȳġe (“dry; parched, withered”), from Proto-West Germanic *drūgī, *draugī, from Proto-Germanic *drūgiz, *draugiz (“dry, hard”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰerǵʰ- (“to strengthen; become hard”), from *dʰe...

DRIPS.d: Plural of DRIP: To fall one drop at a time.
DRIPS.e:
From Middle English drippen, druppen, from Old English drypan, from Proto-Germanic *drupjaną (“to fall in drops, drip”), from Proto-Germanic *drupô (“drop”). Akin to West Frisian drippe (“to drip”),
Dutch druipen, druppelen (“to drip”), German Low German drüppen (“to drip”), Germ...

DRIVE.d: To operate a vehicle; a journey by car.

DROPS.d: Plural of DROP: A small quantity of liquid, just large enough to hold its own round shape through surface tension, especially one that falls from a source of liquid.
DROPS.e: From Late Middle English droppe, Middle English drope (“small quantity of liquid; small or least amount of something; pendant jewel; dripping of a liquid; a shower; nasal flow, catarrh; speck, spot; blemish; disease causing spots on the skin”) [and other forms], from Old English ...

DRUBS.d: Plural of DRUB: Carbonaceous shale; small coal; slate, dross, or rubbish in coal.
DRUBS.e: From Middle English *drob, drof, from Old English *drōb, drōf (“turbid; dreggy; dirty”), from Proto-West Germanic *drōbī, from Proto-Germanic *drōbuz (“turbid”).

DRUGS.d: Plural of DRUG: A substance used to treat an illness, relieve a symptom, or modify a chemical process in the body for a specific purpose.
DRUGS.e: From Middle English drogge (“medicine”), from Middle French drogue, drocque (“tincture, pharmaceutical product”) (c. 1462), from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German droge, as in droge vate (“dry vats, dry barrels”), mistaking droge for the contents, which were usually dried herbs, ...

DRUMS.d: Plural of DRUM: A percussive musical instrument spanned with a thin covering on at least one end for striking, forming an acoustic chamber; a membranophone.
DRUMS.e:
Perhaps back-formation from drumslade (“drummer”), from Middle Dutch trommelslach (“drumbeat”), from trommel (“drum”) + slach (“beat”) (Dutch slag).
Or perhaps borrowed directly from a continental Germanic language; compare Middle Dutch tromme (“drum”), Middle Low German trumme (...

DUALS.d: Plural of DUAL: Characterized by having two (usually equivalent) components.
DUALS.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
Borrowed from Latin dualis (“two”), from duo (“two”) + adjective suffix -alis.

DUCKS.d: Plural of DUCK: To quickly lower (the head or body), often in order to prevent it from being struck by something.
DUCKS.e:
From Middle English ducken, duken, douken (“to duck, plunge under water, submerge”), from Old English *dūcan (“to dip, dive, duck”), from Proto-West Germanic *dūkan, from Proto-Germanic *dūkaną (“to dip, dive, bend down, stoop, duck”).
Cognates
Related to Scots dulk (“to duck”), ...

DUCTS.d: Plural of DUCT: A pipe, tube or canal which carries gas or liquid from one place to another.
DUCTS.e: Borrowed from Latin ductus (“leading, conducting”, noun), from dūcō (“to lead, conduct, draw”) + -tus (action noun suffix). Doublet of ductus and douit. Also via Medieval Latin ductus (“a conveyance of water; a channel”), which itself has the first mentioned etymology.

DUDES.d: Plural of DUDE: A man, generally a younger man.
DUDES.e: Uncertain, though likely a clipping of doodle (“fool, simpleton, mindless person”), perhaps with reference to the fashionable “Yankee Doodle dandy” in the 18th-century lyrics of the song “Yankee Doodle”; the word is first attested in 1883 as a New York City slang term of contempt...

DUELS.d: Plural of DUEL: Arranged, regular combat between two private persons, often over a matter of honor.
DUELS.e:
From Medieval Latin duellum (“fight between two men, duel”), itself from Old Latin duellum (“war, fight”), which survived in Classical Latin as a rare byform of bellum and was later reinterpreted as “duel” by unetymological association with duo (“two”).
May have entered English t...

DUETS.d: Plural of DUET: A musical composition in two parts, each performed by a single voice (singer, instrument or univoce ensemble).
DUETS.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Italian duetto (“short musical composition for two voices”), diminutive of due (“two”).

DUFFS.e: Representing a northern England and Scots pronunciation of dough.

DUKES.d: Plural of DUKE: The male ruler of a duchy (female equivalent: duchess).
DUKES.e:
From Old French duc, through Middle English duk, duke, from Latin dux, ducis. Displaced native Old English heretoga. Was present as duc in late Old English, from the same Latin source. Doublet of doge, duc, duce, and dux.
The “fist” sense is thought to be Cockney rhyming slang wh...

DULLS.d: Plural of DULL: Lacking the ability to cut easily; not sharp.
DULLS.e: From Middle English dull, dul (also dyll, dill, dwal), from Old English dol (“dull, foolish, erring, heretical; foolish, silly; presumptuous”), from Proto-West Germanic *dol, from Proto-Germanic *dulaz, from earlier *dwulaz, a variant of *dwalaz (“stunned, mad, foolish, misled”),...

DUMBS.d: Plural of DUMB: Unable to speak; lacking power of speech.
DUMBS.e: From Middle English dumb (“silent, speechless, mute, ineffectual”), from Old English dumb (“silent, speechless, mute, unable to speak”), from Proto-West Germanic *dumb, from Proto-Germanic *dumbaz (“dull, dumb”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewbʰ- (“to whisk, smoke, darken, obscur...

DUMPS.d: Plural of DUMP: A place where waste or garbage is left; a ground or place for dumping ashes, refuse, etc.; a disposal site.
DUMPS.e: From Middle English dumpen, dompen, probably from Old Norse dumpa (“to thump”) (whence Danish dumpe (“to fall suddenly”)), of uncertain origin, possibly imitative of falling, similar to thump.

DUNES.d: Plural of DUNE: A ridge or hill of sand piled up by currents of wind or water.
DUNES.e: Partly from a dialectal form of down; and partly from French dune (from Old French dune), or from Middle Dutch dūne (modern Dutch duin), or from Middle Low German dûne; all ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *dūn, *dūnā, probably from Proto-Celtic *dūnom (“stronghold, rampart”),...

DUNGS.d: Plural of DUNG: Manure; animal excrement.
DUNGS.e: From Middle English dung, dunge, donge, from Old English dung (“dung; excrement; manure”), from Proto-West Germanic *dungu, from Proto-Germanic *dungō (“dung”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰengʰ- (“to cover”).

DUNKS.d: Plural of DUNK: To submerge briefly in a liquid.
DUNKS.e:
From Pennsylvania German dunke, from Middle High German dunken, from Old High German dunkōn (“to dip, submerge, dunk”), from Proto-West Germanic *þunkōn (“to make wet”), possibly from Proto-Germanic *þunkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *teng- (“to moisten, wet”).
Cognate with Germa...

DUPED.d: Past tense of DUPE: A person who has been deceived.
DUPED.e: From French duper, from Middle French duppe, alteration of huppe (“hoopoe”), from Latin, onomatopoeic.

DUPES.d: Plural of DUPE: A person who has been deceived.
DUPES.e: From French duper, from Middle French duppe, alteration of huppe (“hoopoe”), from Latin, onomatopoeic.

DUSKS.d: Plural of DUSK: Tending to darkness or blackness; moderately dark or black; dusky.
DUSKS.e: From Middle English dosk, dusk(e) (“dusky”, adj.), from Old English dox (“dark, swarthy”), from Proto-Germanic *duskaz (“dark, smoky”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰwes-, related to *dʰewh₂- (“smoke, mist, haze”). Cognate to Latin fuscus (“dark, dusky”), Sanskrit धूसर (dhūsara, “d...

DUSTS.e: From Middle English dust, doust, from Old English dūst (“dust, dried earth reduced to powder; other dry material reduced to powder”), from the fusion of Proto-Germanic *dustą (“dust”) and *dunstą (“mist, dust, evaporation”), both from Proto-Indo-European *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, rais...

DYADS.d: Plural of DYAD: A set of two elements treated as one; a pair.
DYADS.e: From Ancient Greek δυάς (duás), δυάδ- (duád-) from δύο (dúo, “two”), from Proto-Indo-European *duwó, *duwéh₃ (*dwóh₁). The mathematics sense was coined by American scientist Josiah Willard Gibbs in 1884 in the second half of his book Elements of Vector Analysis.

DYKED.d: Past tense of DYKE: A long, narrow hollow dug from the ground to serve as a boundary marker.
DYKED.e:
A variant of dike, from Northern Middle English dik and dike (“ditch”), from Old Norse díki (“ditch”). Influenced by Middle Dutch dijc (“ditch; dam”) and Middle Low German dīk (“dam”). See also
ditch.

DYKES.d: Plural of DYKE: A long, narrow hollow dug from the ground to serve as a boundary marker.
DYKES.e:
A variant of dike, from Northern Middle English dik and dike (“ditch”), from Old Norse díki (“ditch”). Influenced by Middle Dutch dijc (“ditch; dam”) and Middle Low German dīk (“dam”). See also
ditch.

DYNES.d: Plural of DYNE: A unit of force in the CGS system; the force required to accelerate a mass of one gram by one centimetre per second per second. Symbol: dyn.
DYNES.e: From the French dyne, from the Ancient Greek δῠ́νᾰμῐς (dŭ́nămĭs, “force”).

EARED.d: Past tense of EAR: The organ of hearing, consisting of the pinna or auricle, auditory canal, eardrum, malleus, incus, stapes and cochlea.
EARED.e: From Middle English ere, eare, from Old English ēare (“ear”), from Proto-West Germanic *auʀā, from the voiced Verner alternant of Proto-Germanic *ausô (“ear”) (compare Scots ear, West Frisian ear, Dutch oor, German Ohr, Swedish öra, Danish øre), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ṓws (c...

EARLS.d: Plural of EARL: A British or Irish nobleman next in rank above a viscount and below a marquess; equivalent to a European count. A female using the style is termed a countess.
EARLS.e: From Middle English erl, erle, from Old English eorl, from Proto-West Germanic *erl, from Proto-Germanic *erlaz (compare Old Saxon erl, Old Norse jarl), from Proto-Germanic *erōną, *arōną (compare Old Norse jara (“fight, battle”)). Doublet of eorl and jarl. Unrelated to ealdorman...

EARLY.d: Near the beginning of a period.

EARNS.d: Plural of EARN: To gain (success, reward, recognition) through applied effort or work.
EARNS.e: From Middle English ernen, from Old English earnian, from Proto-West Germanic *aʀanōn, from Proto-Germanic *azanōną. This verb is denominal from the noun *azaniz (“harvest”).

EARTH.d: The planet we live on; soil.

EASED.d: Past tense of EASE: Lack of difficulty; the ability to do something easily.
EASED.e: From Middle English ese, eise, aise, from Anglo-Norman ese (“ease”), from Old French eise, aise (“elbow room; opportunity”), of uncertain and obscure origin. Apparently related to Provençal ais, Italian agio and asio, Sicilian aciu and Portuguese azo. Sometimes ascribed to Vulgar...

EASES.d: Plural of EASE: Lack of difficulty; the ability to do something easily.
EASES.e: From Middle English ese, eise, aise, from Anglo-Norman ese (“ease”), from Old French eise, aise (“elbow room; opportunity”), of uncertain and obscure origin. Apparently related to Provençal ais, Italian agio and asio, Sicilian aciu and Portuguese azo. Sometimes ascribed to Vulgar...

EASTS.d: Plural of EAST: The direction of the earth's rotation, specifically 90°.
EASTS.e:
From Middle English est, from Old English ēast, from Proto-West Germanic *austr, from Proto-Germanic *austrą, from Proto-Germanic *austraz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂éwsteros (“east”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots aist (“east”), North Frisian uast, ååst, ööst (“east”), Saterland...

EAVED.d: Past tense of EAVE: Alternative form of eaves (“the underside of a roof that extends beyond the external walls of a building”)
EAVED.e: A back-formation from eaves, from a misinterpretation of the -s ending as forming a plural.

EAVES.d: Plural of EAVE: Alternative form of eaves (“the underside of a roof that extends beyond the external walls of a building”)
EAVES.e: A back-formation from eaves, from a misinterpretation of the -s ending as forming a plural.

EBBED.d: Past tense of EBB: The receding movement of the tide.
EBBED.e:
From Middle English ebbe, from Old English ebba (“ebb, tide”), from Proto-West Germanic *abbjā, from Proto-Germanic *abjô, *abjǭ, from Proto-Germanic *ab (“off, away”), from Proto-Indo-European *apó.
See also West Frisian ebbe, Dutch eb, German Ebbe, Danish ebbe, Old Norse efja (...

ECHOS.d: Plural of ECHO: A reflected sound that is heard again by its initial observer.
ECHOS.e: From Middle English eccho, ecco, ekko, from Medieval Latin ēccō, from Latin ēchō, from Ancient Greek ἠχώ (ēkhṓ), from ἠχή (ēkhḗ, “sound”). Possibly from the same Proto-Indo-European root as sough.

ECRUS.d: Plural of ECRU: A beige colour.

EDGED.d: Past tense of EDGE: The boundary line of a surface.
EDGED.e:
From Middle English egge, from Old English eċġ, from Proto-West Germanic *aggju, from Proto-Germanic *agjō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱ- (“sharp”).
See also Dutch egge, German Ecke, Swedish egg, Norwegian egg; also Welsh hogi (“to sharpen, hone”), Latin aciēs (“sharp”), acus (...

EDGES.d: Plural of EDGE: The boundary line of a surface.
EDGES.e:
From Middle English egge, from Old English eċġ, from Proto-West Germanic *aggju, from Proto-Germanic *agjō, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eḱ- (“sharp”).
See also Dutch egge, German Ecke, Swedish egg, Norwegian egg; also Welsh hogi (“to sharpen, hone”), Latin aciēs (“sharp”), acus (...

EDITS.d: Plural of EDIT: A change to the text of a document.
EDITS.e: Back-formation from editor, influenced by French éditer (“edit, publish”) and Latin editus.

EKING.d: Present participle of EKE: An addition.
EKING.e: The noun is derived from Middle English eke (“addition, increase, enlargement”), from Old English ēaca, from Proto-Germanic *aukô, from *aukaną (“to increase, add, enlarge”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ewg- (“to enlarge, increase”). The English noun is cognate with Ol...

ELANS.d: Plural of ELAN: Uncommon spelling of élan.

ELITE.d: A select group of superior people.
ELITE.e: From French élite, from élire (to elect).

ELVES.d: Plural of ELF: A supernatural being or spirit associated with illness, mischief, and harmful or dangerous magical influence; in later Norse sources, sometimes divided into benevolent light elves (inhabiting Álfheimr) and malevolent dark elves.
ELVES.e: From Middle English elf, from Old English ielf, ælf, from Proto-West Germanic *albi, from Proto-Germanic *albiz. Ultimately probably derived from Proto-Indo-European *h₂elbʰós (“white”). Doublet of alf, awf, and oaf. The modern fantasy literature sense was popularised by the work...

EMIRS.d: Plural of EMIR: A prince, commander or other leader or ruler in an Islamic nation.
EMIRS.e: From Middle French emir, from Ottoman Turkish امیر (emir), from Arabic أَمِير (ʔamīr, “commander, prince”). Doublet of amir, Amir, admiral, and amira.

EMITS.d: Plural of EMIT: To send out or give off.

ENEMY.d: A person who is hostile to another.
ENEMY.e: From Old French enemi, from Latin inimīcus.

ENTER.e: From Old French entrer, from Latin intrāre.

ENTRY.d: An act of entering; an item recorded.

EPICS.d: Plural of EPIC: Acronym of explicitly parallel instruction computing.

EQUAL.d: The same in quantity or value.

ERNES.d: Plural of ERNE: A sea eagle (Haliaeetus), especially the white-tailed eagle (Haliaeetus albicilla)
ERNES.e:
From Middle English ern, erne, earn, from Old English earn (“eagle”), from Proto-West Germanic *arnu (“eagle”), from Proto-Germanic *arnuz (“eagle”), from Proto-Germanic *arô (“eagle”) (whence also Arnold), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃érō (“large bird, eagle”).
Cognate with North...

ERROR.e: From Latin error, from errāre (to wander).

EUROS.d: Plural of EURO: The currency unit of the European Monetary Union. Symbol: €
EUROS.e: The name euro was the winner of a contest open to the general public to propose names for the new European currency, and as such is technically a neologism, although it obviously alludes to the common root of geographical names for the continent Europe, derived from Latin Europa,...

EVENS.d: Plural of EVEN: Flat and level.
EVENS.e:
From Middle English even, from Old English efn (“flat; level, even, equal”), from Proto-West Germanic *ebn, from Proto-Germanic *ebnaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(h₁)em-no- (“equal, straight; flat, level, even”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian íeuwen (“even, flat”), West Frisian ...

EVENT.e: From Latin ēventus, from ēvenīre (to happen).

EVILS.d: Plural of EVIL: Intending to harm; malevolent.
EVILS.e:
From Middle English yvel, evel, ivel, uvel, from Old English yfel, from Proto-West Germanic *ubil, from Proto-Germanic *ubilaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂up(h₁)élos, a deverbal derivative of *h₂wep(h₁)-, *h₂wop(h₁)- (“treat badly”). See -le for the supposed suffix.
Alternativel...

EWING.d: Present participle of EWE: A female sheep, as opposed to a ram.
EWING.e:
From Middle English ewe, from Old English eowu, from Proto-West Germanic *awi, from Proto-Germanic *awiz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂ówis (“sheep”).
Cognates
See also Old English ēow (“sheep”), West Frisian ei, Dutch ooi, German Aue); also Old Irish oí, Latin ovis, Tocharian B ā...

EXACT.e: From Latin exactus, from exigere (to demand).

EXAMS.d: Plural of EXAM: Clipping of examination, especially when meaning “test” or in compound terms.

EXECS.d: Plural of EXEC: An executive; a person employed at the executive level.

EXITS.d: Plural of EXIT: An act of going out or going away, or leaving; a departure.
EXITS.e: From Middle English exit, from Latin exitus (“departure, going out; way by which one may go out, egress; (figuratively) conclusion, termination; (figuratively) death; income, revenue”), from exeō (“to depart, exit; to avoid, evade; (figuratively) to escape; of time: to expire, ru...

EXPOS.d: Plural of EXPO: An exposition (type of public exhibition).

EYRAS.d: Plural of EYRA: A slender, reddish-yellow wild cat (Puma yagouaroundi eyra) ranging from southern Brazil to Texas.

FACED.d: Past tense of FACE: The front part of the head of a human or other animal, featuring the eyes, nose, and mouth, and the surrounding area.
FACED.e: From Middle English face, from Old French face, from Late Latin facia, from Latin faciēs (“form, appearance”). Doublet of facies. Displaced native onlete (“face, countenance, appearance”), anleth (“face”), from Old English anwlite, andwlita, compare German Antlitz; Old English an...

FACES.d: Plural of FACE: The front part of the head of a human or other animal, featuring the eyes, nose, and mouth, and the surrounding area.
FACES.e: From Middle English face, from Old French face, from Late Latin facia, from Latin faciēs (“form, appearance”). Doublet of facies. Displaced native onlete (“face, countenance, appearance”), anleth (“face”), from Old English anwlite, andwlita, compare German Antlitz; Old English an...

FACTS.d: Plural of FACT: Something actual as opposed to invented.
FACTS.e: From Old French fact, from Latin factum (“an act, deed, feat, etc.”); also Medieval Latin for “state, condition, circumstance”; neuter of factus (“done or made”), perfect passive participle of faciō (“do, make”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁- (“to put, place, set”)....

FADED.d: Past tense of FADE: Weak; insipid; tasteless.
FADED.e: From Middle English fade, vad, vade (“faded, pale, withered, weak”), from Middle Dutch vade (“weak, faint, limp”), from Old French fade (“weak, witless”), of obscure origin. Probably from Vulgar Latin *fatidus, from Latin fatuus (“insipid”).

FADES.d: Plural of FADE: Weak; insipid; tasteless.
FADES.e: From Middle English fade, vad, vade (“faded, pale, withered, weak”), from Middle Dutch vade (“weak, faint, limp”), from Old French fade (“weak, witless”), of obscure origin. Probably from Vulgar Latin *fatidus, from Latin fatuus (“insipid”).

FADOS.d: Plural of FADO: A Portuguese folk song, usually featuring a single vocalist, Portuguese guitar and sometimes classical guitar. Lyrical themes are often melancholic in nature; the structure of the song is of greater importance.
FADOS.e: From Portuguese fado (“fate”), from Latin fātum. Doublet of fate.

FAILS.d: Plural of FAIL: To be unsuccessful.
FAILS.e:
Inherited from Middle English failen, borrowed from Old French falir, from Vulgar Latin *fallire, alteration of Latin fallere (“to deceive, disappoint”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰāl- (“to lie, deceive”) or Proto-Indo-European *sgʷʰh₂el- (“to stumble”).
Compare Alemannic German...

FAIRS.d: Plural of FAIR: Beautiful, of a pleasing appearance, with a pure and fresh quality.
FAIRS.e:
From Middle English fayr, feir, fager, from Old English fæġer (“beautiful”), from Proto-West Germanic *fagr, from Proto-Germanic *fagraz (“suitable, fitting, nice”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ḱ- (“to fasten, place”).
Cognate with Scots fayr, fare (“fair”), Danish feir, faver,...

FAITH.e: From Old French feid, from Latin fidēs.

FAKED.d: Past tense of FAKE: Not real; false, fraudulent.
FAKED.e: The origin is not known with certainty, although first attested in 1775 C.E. in British criminals' slang. It is probably from feak, feague (“to give a better appearance through artificial means, spruce up, embellish”), itself from German Low German fegen, from Middle Low German v...

FAKES.d: Plural of FAKE: Not real; false, fraudulent.
FAKES.e: The origin is not known with certainty, although first attested in 1775 C.E. in British criminals' slang. It is probably from feak, feague (“to give a better appearance through artificial means, spruce up, embellish”), itself from German Low German fegen, from Middle Low German v...

FALLS.d: Plural of FALL: To be moved downwards.
FALLS.e:
Verb from Middle English fallen, from Old English feallan (“to fall, fail, decay, die, attack”), from Proto-West Germanic *fallan (“to fall”), from Proto-Germanic *fallaną (“to fall”).
Cognate with West Frisian falle (“to fall”), Low German fallen (“to fall”), Dutch vallen (“to f...

FAMED.d: Past tense of FAME: Something said or reported; gossip, rumour.
FAMED.e: From Middle English fame, from Old French fame (“celebrity, renown”), itself borrowed from Latin fāma (“talk, rumor, report, reputation”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰéh₂-meh₂, from *bʰeh₂- (“to speak, say, tell”). Cognate with Ancient Greek φήμη (phḗmē, “talk”). Related also to ...

FAMES.d: Plural of FAME: Something said or reported; gossip, rumour.
FAMES.e: From Middle English fame, from Old French fame (“celebrity, renown”), itself borrowed from Latin fāma (“talk, rumor, report, reputation”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰéh₂-meh₂, from *bʰeh₂- (“to speak, say, tell”). Cognate with Ancient Greek φήμη (phḗmē, “talk”). Related also to ...

FANES.d: Plural of FANE: A weathercock, a weather vane.
FANES.e: From Middle English fane, from Old English fana (“cloth, banner”), from Proto-West Germanic *fanō, from Proto-Germanic *fanô (“cloth, flag”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂n- (“to weave; something woven; cloth, fabric, tissue”). Doublet of fanon and vane.

FANGS.d: Plural of FANG: A long, pointed canine tooth used for biting and tearing flesh.
FANGS.e: From an abbreviation of fangtooth, from Middle English *fangtooth, *fengtooth, from Old English fengtōþ (“canine tooth”, literally “snag-tooth, catch-tooth”). Cognate with German Fangzahn (“fang”, literally “catch-tooth”) and Dutch vangtand.

FARED.d: Past tense of FARE: A going; journey; travel; voyage; course; passage.
FARED.e: From Middle English fare, from a merger of Old English fær (“journey, road”) and faru (“journey, companions, baggage”), from Proto-Germanic *farą and *farō (“journey, fare”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“a going, passage”).

FARES.d: Plural of FARE: A going; journey; travel; voyage; course; passage.
FARES.e: From Middle English fare, from a merger of Old English fær (“journey, road”) and faru (“journey, companions, baggage”), from Proto-Germanic *farą and *farō (“journey, fare”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“a going, passage”).

FARLS.d: Plural of FARL: A quarter of a thin oatmeal or flour cake.
FARLS.e: Contraction of fardel, probably with some influence from the Irish fearann meaning a fourth, especially of land or oatcakes. In this specific sense, fearann itself may be a possible cognate from a Norse or Old English root.

FARMS.d: Plural of FARM: A place where agricultural and similar activities take place, especially the growing of crops or the raising of livestock.
FARMS.e: Inherited from Middle English ferme, farme (“rent, revenue, produce, factor, stewardship, meal, feast”), influenced by Anglo-Norman ferme (“rent, lease, farm”), from Medieval Latin ferma, firma. There is debate as to whether Medieval Latin acquires this term from Old English feor...

FAROS.d: Plural of FARO: A game of chance played by betting on the order in which certain cards will appear when taken singly from the top of the pack.
FAROS.e: Presumably an alteration of pharaoh, itself a transcription of French pharaon, perhaps as a name for the King of Hearts.

FARTS.d: Plural of FART: To emit digestive gases from the anus; to flatulate.
FARTS.e:
From Middle English ferten, farten, from Old English *feortan, from Proto-West Germanic *fertan, from Proto-Germanic *fertaną, from Proto-Indo-European *perd-.
The noun is from Middle English fert, fart, from the verb.

FASTS.d: Plural of FAST: Firmly or securely fixed in place; stable.
FASTS.e:
From Middle English fast, fest, from Old English fæst (“firm, secure”), from Proto-West Germanic *fast, from Proto-Germanic *fastuz; see it for cognates and further etymology.
The development of “rapid” from an original sense of “secure” apparently happened first in the adverb an...

FATED.d: Past tense of FATE: The presumed cause, force, principle, or divine will that predetermines events.
FATED.e: From Middle English fate, from Latin fāta (“prediction”), plural of fātum, from fātus (“spoken”), from for (“to speak”). In this sense, displaced native Old English wyrd, whence Modern English weird.

FATES.d: Plural of FATE: The presumed cause, force, principle, or divine will that predetermines events.
FATES.e: From Middle English fate, from Latin fāta (“prediction”), plural of fātum, from fātus (“spoken”), from for (“to speak”). In this sense, displaced native Old English wyrd, whence Modern English weird.

FAULT.d: A defect; responsibility for a mistake.
FAULT.e: From Old French faute, from Latin fallere (to deceive).

FAUNS.d: Plural of FAUN: A woodland creature with pointed ears, legs, and short horns of a goat and a fondness for unrestrained revelry.
FAUNS.e: From Middle English fawn, from Latin faunus.

FAWNS.d: Plural of FAWN: A young deer.
FAWNS.e: From Middle English fawne, fowne, foun, from Old French faon, foon, feon, from Vulgar Latin *fētōnem, from Latin fētus (“offspring, young”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁(y)- (“to suckle, nurse”). Displaced native Old English hindċealf (literally “deer calf”). Doublet of fetus.

FAXED.d: Past tense of FAX: The hair of the head.
FAXED.e: From Middle English fax, from Old English feax (“hair, head of hair”), from Proto-West Germanic *fahs, from Proto-Germanic *fahsą (“hair, mane”), from Proto-Indo-European *poḱsom (“hair”, literally “that which is combed, shorn, or plucked”), from Proto-Indo-European *peḱ- (“to co...

FAXES.d: Plural of FAX: The hair of the head.
FAXES.e: From Middle English fax, from Old English feax (“hair, head of hair”), from Proto-West Germanic *fahs, from Proto-Germanic *fahsą (“hair, mane”), from Proto-Indo-European *poḱsom (“hair”, literally “that which is combed, shorn, or plucked”), from Proto-Indo-European *peḱ- (“to co...

FAYED.d: Past tense of FAY: To fit.
FAYED.e: Inherited from Middle English feyen, feien, from Old English fēġan (“to join, unite”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōgijan, from Proto-Germanic *fōgijaną (“to join”), from *fōgō (“joint, slot”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ḱ- (“to fasten, place”). Akin to Saterland Frisian fougje...

FAZED.d: Past tense of FAZE: To frighten or cause hesitation; to daunt, put off (usually used in the negative); to disconcert, to perturb.
FAZED.e: From English dialectal (Kentish) feeze, feese (“to alarm, discomfit, frighten”), from Middle English fēsen (“to chase, drive away; put to flight; discomfit, frighten, terrify”), from Old English fēsan, fȳsan (“to send forth; to hasten, impel, stimulate; to banish, drive away, put...

FAZES.e: From English dialectal (Kentish) feeze, feese (“to alarm, discomfit, frighten”), from Middle English fēsen (“to chase, drive away; put to flight; discomfit, frighten, terrify”), from Old English fēsan, fȳsan (“to send forth; to hasten, impel, stimulate; to banish, drive away, put...

FEARS.d: Plural of FEAR: A strong, unpleasant emotion or feeling caused by actual or perceived danger or threat.
FEARS.e: From Middle English feer, fere, fer, from Old English fǣr, ġefǣr (“calamity, sudden danger, peril, sudden attack, terrible sight”), from Proto-Germanic *fērō, *fērą (“danger”), from Proto-Indo-European *per- (“to go through, carry forth, try”). Cognate with Dutch gevaar (“danger,...

FEAST.e: From Old French feste, from Latin festa.

FEATS.d: Plural of FEAT: A relatively rare or difficult accomplishment.
FEATS.e: From Middle English [Term?], from Anglo-Norman fet (“action, deed”), from Old French fait, from Latin factum, from facere (“to do, to make”). Doublet of fact.

FEEDS.d: Plural of FEED: To give (someone or something) food to eat.
FEEDS.e: From Middle English feden, from Old English fēdan (“to feed”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōdijan, from Proto-Germanic *fōdijaną (“to feed”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to guard, graze, feed”). Cognate with West Frisian fiede (“to nourish, feed”), Dutch voeden (“to feed”), ...

FEELS.d: Plural of FEEL: To use or experience the sense of touch.
FEELS.e: From Middle English felen, from Old English fēlan, from Proto-West Germanic *fōlijan.

FELLS.d: Plural of FELL: To make something fall; especially to chop down a tree.
FELLS.e: From Middle English fellen, from Old English fellan, fiellan (“to cause to fall, strike down, fell, cut down, throw down, defeat, destroy, kill, tumble, cause to stumble”), from Proto-West Germanic *fallijan, from Proto-Germanic *fallijaną (“to fell, to cause to fall”), causative...

FELTS.d: Plural of FELT: A cloth or stuff made of matted fibres of wool, or wool and fur, fulled or wrought into a compact substance by rolling and pressure, with lees or size, without spinning or weaving.
FELTS.e: From Middle English felt, from Old English felt, from Proto-West Germanic *felt (compare Dutch vilt, German Filz, Danish filt, French feutre), from Proto-Indo-European *pilto, *pilso 'felt' (compare Latin pilleus (“felt”, adjective), Old Church Slavonic плъсть (plŭstĭ), Albanian ...

FENDS.d: Plural of FEND: To take care of oneself; to take responsibility for one's own well-being.
FENDS.e: From Middle English fenden (“defend, fight, prevent”), shortening of defenden (“defend”), from Old French deffendre (Modern French défendre), from Latin dēfendō (“to ward off”), from dē- + *fendō (“hit, thrust”), from Proto-Italic *fendō, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰen- (“strike...

FERNS.d: Plural of FERN: Any of a group of some twenty thousand species of vascular plants classified in the division Pteridophyta that lack seeds and reproduce by shedding spores to initiate an alternation of generations.
FERNS.e:
From Middle English fern, from Old English fearn, from Proto-West Germanic *farn, from Proto-Indo-European *pornóm (“feather, wing; fern, leaf”), from *p(t)erH- (“fern”).
Cognate with Scots fairn (“fern”), West Frisian fear (“fern”), Dutch varen (“fern”), German Farn, Farm (“fern...

FETAS.d: Plural of FETA: A variety of curd cheese made from sheep’s or goat’s milk and originating from Greece.
FETAS.e: Borrowed from Greek φέτα (féta), from Italian fetta (“slice”).

FETED.d: Past tense of FETE: A festival open to the public, the proceeds from which are often given to charity.
FETED.e:
* The noun derives from French fête. Doublet of feast, fiesta, and fest.
* The verb derives from French fêter.

FETES.d: Plural of FETE: A festival open to the public, the proceeds from which are often given to charity.
FETES.e:
* The noun derives from French fête. Doublet of feast, fiesta, and fest.
* The verb derives from French fêter.

FEUDS.d: Plural of FEUD: A state of long-standing mutual hostility.
FEUDS.e:
Inherited from Northern Middle English fede, feide, from Old French faide, feide, fede, from Proto-West Germanic *faihiþu (“hatred, enmity”) (corresponding to foe + -th), from Proto-Indo-European *peyḱ- (“hostile”).
Cognate to Old English fǣhþ, fǣhþu, fǣhþo (“hostility, enmity, v...

FEZES.d: Plural of FEZ: A felt hat in the shape of a truncated cone, having a flat top with a tassel attached.
FEZES.e: From Ottoman Turkish فس (fes) (modern Turkish fes), named after Fez, Morocco, (capital of the Kingdom of Morocco until 1927), where the dye to color the hat was extracted from crimson berries.

FIATS.d: Plural of FIAT: An arbitrary or authoritative command or order to do something; an effectual decree.
FIATS.e: From Latin fīat (“let it be done”).

FIEFS.d: Plural of FIEF: Land held of a superior, particularly on condition of homage, fealty, and personal service, especially military service.
FIEFS.e: From Middle French fief, from Old French fief, from Medieval Latin fevum, a variant of feudum (whence also Old French fieu, fied), from Old Frankish *fehu (“cattle, livestock”), from Proto-Germanic *fehu (“cattle, sheep”), from Proto-Indo-European *peku-, *peḱu- (“sheep”). Double...

FIELD.d: An area of open land; a subject of study.

FIFED.d: Past tense of FIFE: A small shrill pipe, resembling the piccolo flute, used chiefly to accompany the drum in military music
FIFED.e: From German Pfeife (“whistle, smoking pipe”). Doublet of pipe.

FIFES.d: Plural of FIFE: A small shrill pipe, resembling the piccolo flute, used chiefly to accompany the drum in military music
FIFES.e: From German Pfeife (“whistle, smoking pipe”). Doublet of pipe.

FIGHT.d: A violent struggle; to engage in combat.

FILED.d: Past tense of FILE: A collection of papers collated and archived together.
FILED.e: From Old French fil (“thread”), from Latin fīlum (“thread”). Doublet of filum.

FILES.d: Plural of FILE: A collection of papers collated and archived together.
FILES.e: From Old French fil (“thread”), from Latin fīlum (“thread”). Doublet of filum.

FILLS.d: Plural of FILL: To make full
FILLS.e:
From Middle English fillen, fullen, from Old English fyllan (“to fill, fill up, replenish, satisfy; complete, fulfill”), from Proto-West Germanic *fullijan, from Proto-Germanic *fullijaną (“to make full, fill”), from *fullaz (“full”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós (“full”).
...

FILMS.d: Plural of FILM: A thin layer of some substance; a pellicle; a membranous covering, causing opacity.
FILMS.e: From Middle English filme, from Old English filmen (“film, membrane, thin skin, foreskin”), from Proto-West Germanic *filmīn-, from Proto-Germanic *filmīn- (“thin skin, membrane”) (compare Proto-Germanic *felma- (“skin, hide”)), from Proto-Indo-European *pél-mo- (“membrane”), fro...

FINDS.e:
From Middle English finden, from Old English findan, from Proto-West Germanic *finþan, from Proto-Germanic *finþaną, a secondary verb from Proto-Indo-European *pent- (“to go, pass; path bridge”).
See also West Frisian fine, Low German finden, Dutch vinden, German finden, Danish f...

FINED.d: Past tense of FINE: Senses referring to subjective quality.
FINED.e: From Middle English fin, fyn, from Old French fin (“fine, minute, exact”), of obscure origin, but probably derived from Latin fīnīre (“to finish”) or fīnis (“boundary, limit, end”), with an abstract sense of fine or thin also arising in many Romance languages (compare Spanish, Po...

FINES.d: Plural of FINE: Senses referring to subjective quality.
FINES.e: From Middle English fin, fyn, from Old French fin (“fine, minute, exact”), of obscure origin, but probably derived from Latin fīnīre (“to finish”) or fīnis (“boundary, limit, end”), with an abstract sense of fine or thin also arising in many Romance languages (compare Spanish, Po...

FIRED.d: Past tense of FIRE: A (usually self-sustaining) chemical reaction involving the bonding of oxygen with carbon or other fuel, with the production of heat and the presence of flame or smouldering.
FIRED.e:
From Middle English fyr, from Old English fȳr (“fire”), from Proto-West Germanic *fuir, from *fuïr, a regularised form of Proto-Germanic *fōr (“fire”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *péh₂wr̥.
Cognates
See also Scots feier, fyre (“fire”), Yola vier, vire (“fire”), Saterland ...

FIRES.d: Plural of FIRE: A (usually self-sustaining) chemical reaction involving the bonding of oxygen with carbon or other fuel, with the production of heat and the presence of flame or smouldering.
FIRES.e:
From Middle English fyr, from Old English fȳr (“fire”), from Proto-West Germanic *fuir, from *fuïr, a regularised form of Proto-Germanic *fōr (“fire”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *péh₂wr̥.
Cognates
See also Scots feier, fyre (“fire”), Yola vier, vire (“fire”), Saterland ...

FIRMS.d: Plural of FIRM: A business partnership; the name under which it trades.
FIRMS.e: From Italian firma (“signature”), from firmare (“to sign”), from Latin firmāre (“to make firm, to confirm (by signature)”), from firmus (“firm, stable”). The contemporary sense developed in the 18th century simultaneously with German Firma (“business, name of business”). There ar...

FISCS.d: Plural of FISC: The public treasury of Rome.
FISCS.e: Partly from Middle French fisc and partly from its etymon, Latin fiscus (“basket, money-bag, public treasury”); see fiscal.

FISTS.d: Plural of FIST: A hand with the fingers clenched or curled inward.
FISTS.e:
From Middle English fist, from Old English fȳst (“fist”), from Proto-West Germanic *fūsti, of uncertain origin.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola fest, hist (“fist”), Saterland Frisian Fäste, Fääste (“fist”), Central Franconian Fuus (“fist”), Cimbrian bòista, vòista (“fist”), Dutch vuis...

FIVES.d: Plural of FIFE: A small shrill pipe, resembling the piccolo flute, used chiefly to accompany the drum in military music
FIVES.e: From German Pfeife (“whistle, smoking pipe”). Doublet of pipe.

FIXES.d: Plural of FIX: To pierce; now generally replaced by transfix.
FIXES.e: From Middle English fixen, borrowed from Old French *fixer (attested only as ficher, fichier; > English fitch), from fix (“fastened; fixed”), from Latin fīxus (“immovable; steady; stable; fixed”), from fīgō (“to drive in; stick; fasten”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeygʷ- (“to ja...

FLABS.d: Plural of FLAB: Soft, loose flesh on a person's body; fat.

FLAGS.d: Plural of FLAG: A piece of cloth, often decorated with an emblem, used as a visual signal or symbol.
FLAGS.e: From Middle English flag, flagge (“flag”), further etymology uncertain. Perhaps from or related to early Middle English flage (name for a baby's garment) and Old English flagg, flacg (“cataplasm, poultice, plaster”). Or, perhaps ultimately imitative, or otherwise drawn from Proto...

FLANS.d: Plural of FLAN: Baked tart with sweet or savoury filling in an open-topped pastry case. (Compare quiche.)
FLANS.e: Borrowed around 1846 from French flan (“cheesecake, custard tart, flan”), or in some uses (in reference to Spanish/Latin American flans) later from Spanish flan (itself from the French), both from Old French flaon (whence also Middle English flaon, flaun (“pie; cake”)), from Late...

FLAPS.d: Plural of FLAP: Anything broad and flexible that hangs loose, or that is attached by one side or end and is easily moved.
FLAPS.e: From Middle English flap, flappe (“a slap; blow; buffet; fly-flap; something flexible or loose; flap”), related to Saterland Frisian Flappert (“wing, flipper”), Middle Dutch flabbe (“a blow; slap on the face; fly-flap; flap”) (modern Dutch flap (“flap”)), Middle Low German flabbe...

FLASH.d: A sudden brief light; to shine suddenly.

FLATS.d: Plural of FLAT: Having no variations in height.
FLATS.e: From Middle English flat, a borrowing from Old Norse flatr (compare Norwegian and Swedish flat, Danish flad), from Proto-Germanic *flataz, from Proto-Indo-European *pleth₂- (“flat”); akin to Saterland Frisian flot (“smooth”), German Flöz (“a geological layer”), Ancient Greek πλατ...

FLAWS.d: Plural of FLAW: A flake, fragment, or shiver.
FLAWS.e:
From Middle English flawe, flay (“a flake of fire or snow, spark, splinter”), probably from Old Norse flaga (“a flag or slab of stone, flake”), from Proto-Germanic *flagō (“a layer of soil”), from Proto-Indo-European *plok- (“broad, flat”).
Cognate with Icelandic flaga (“flake”),...

FLAYS.d: Plural of FLAY: To cause to fly; put to flight; drive off (by frightening).
FLAYS.e: From Middle English flayen, flaien, fleien, from Old English *flīeġan ("to cause to fly, put to flight, frighten"; found only in compounds: āflīeġan), from Proto-Germanic *flaugijaną (“to let fly, cause to fly”), causative of Proto-Germanic *fleuganą (“to fly”).

FLEAS.d: Plural of FLEA: A small, wingless, parasitic insect of the order Siphonaptera, renowned for its bloodsucking habits and jumping abilities.
FLEAS.e: From Middle English fle, from Old English flēah, flēa, from Proto-West Germanic *flauh, from Proto-Germanic *flauhaz (compare West Frisian flie, Low German Flo, Flö, Dutch vlo, German Floh, Icelandic fló), from pre-Germanic *plóukos, *plówkos, from or akin to Proto-Indo-European ...

FLEES.d: Plural of FLEE: To run away; to escape.
FLEES.e:
From Middle English flen, from Old English flēon, from Proto-Germanic *fleuhaną, from Proto-Indo-European *plewk-, *plew- (“to fly, flow, run”).
Cognate with Dutch vlieden, German fliehen, Icelandic flýja, Swedish fly, Gothic 𐌸𐌻𐌹𐌿𐌷𐌰𐌽 (þliuhan). Within English, related to fly and ...

FLEWS.d: Plural of FLEW: simple past of fly
FLEWS.e: From Middle English flew, flow, from Old English flēag, flug-, from Proto-Germanic *flaug, *flug-, past tense forms of Proto-Germanic *fleuganą (“to fly”). Compare Saterland Frisian flooch (“flew”), West Frisian fleach (“flew”), Dutch vloog (“flew”), German flog (“flew”), Danish ...

FLIED.d: Past tense of FLY: Any insect of the order Diptera; characterized by having two wings (except for some wingless species), also called true flies.
FLIED.e: From Middle English flye, flie, from Old English flȳġe, flēoge (“a fly”), from Proto-Germanic *fleugǭ (“a fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”). Cognate with Scots flee, Saterland Frisian Fljooge, Dutch vlieg, German Low German Fleeg, German Fliege, Danish flue, Norw...

FLIER.d: Comparative form of FLY: Any insect of the order Diptera; characterized by having two wings (except for some wingless species), also called true flies.
FLIER.e: From Middle English flye, flie, from Old English flȳġe, flēoge (“a fly”), from Proto-Germanic *fleugǭ (“a fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”). Cognate with Scots flee, Saterland Frisian Fljooge, Dutch vlieg, German Low German Fleeg, German Fliege, Danish flue, Norw...

FLIES.d: Plural of FLY: Any insect of the order Diptera; characterized by having two wings (except for some wingless species), also called true flies.
FLIES.e: From Middle English flye, flie, from Old English flȳġe, flēoge (“a fly”), from Proto-Germanic *fleugǭ (“a fly”), from Proto-Indo-European *plewk- (“to fly”). Cognate with Scots flee, Saterland Frisian Fljooge, Dutch vlieg, German Low German Fleeg, German Fliege, Danish flue, Norw...

FLIPS.d: Plural of FLIP: A maneuver which rotates an object end over end.
FLIPS.e: Alteration of earlier fillip, from Middle English filippen (“to make a signal or sound with thumb and right forefinger, snap the fingers”), an attenuated variation of flappen (“to flap, clap, slap, strike”). Cognate with Dutch flappen (“to flap”), German flappen (“to flap”).

FLITS.d: Plural of FLIT: A fluttering or darting movement.
FLITS.e:
From Middle English flitten, flytten, from Old Norse flytja (“to move”), from Proto-Germanic *flutjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *plewd- (“to flow; run”).
Cognate Icelandic flytja, Swedish flytta, Danish flytte, Norwegian flytte, Faroese flyta. Compare also Saterland Frisian flit...

FLOCS.d: Plural of FLOC: A floccule; a soft or fluffy particle suspended in a liquid, or the fluffy mass of suspended particles so formed.
FLOCS.e: From Latin floccus (“tuft of wool”), or from French floc (“floc”), from the same Latin source.

FLOES.d: Plural of FLOE: A low, flat mass of floating ice.
FLOES.e: Early 19th century. Probably from Norwegian Nynorsk flo (“layer, slab”), from Old Norse fló (“layer”).

FLOGS.d: Plural of FLOG: To whip or scourge as punishment.
FLOGS.e:
From Middle English *floggen (suggested by flogge (“hammer, sledge”), from Old English *floggian, a stem variant of Proto-Germanic *flukkōną (“to beat”), itself a secondary zero-grade iterative with unetymological -u-, derived from *flōkaną.
The original zero-grade iterative *fla...

FLOOR.d: The lower surface of a room.

FLOPS.d: Plural of FLOP: To fall heavily due to lack of energy.
FLOPS.e: Recorded since 1602, probably a variant of flap with a duller, heavier sound

FLOWS.d: Plural of FLOW: Movement in people or things characterized with a continuous motion, involving either a non solid mass or a multitude.
FLOWS.e: From Middle English flowe, from the verb (see below). The psychology sense “state of focus” was coined by Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi in 1975.

FLUBS.d: Plural of FLUB: An error; a mistake in the performance of an action.
FLUBS.e: Possibly suggested by fluff and flop. First appeared in the US as a verb c. 1924, and as a noun c. 1953.

FLUED.d: Past tense of FLUE: A pipe or duct that carries gaseous combustion products away from the point of combustion (such as a furnace).
FLUED.e: From Middle English flue, flewe (“mouthpiece of a hunting horn”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps a back-formation from Middle English *flews (mistaken as a plural), from Old English flēwsa (“a flow, flowing, flux”). Alternatively, perhaps an alteration of Middle English floute, fle...

FLUES.d: Plural of FLUE: A pipe or duct that carries gaseous combustion products away from the point of combustion (such as a furnace).
FLUES.e: From Middle English flue, flewe (“mouthpiece of a hunting horn”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps a back-formation from Middle English *flews (mistaken as a plural), from Old English flēwsa (“a flow, flowing, flux”). Alternatively, perhaps an alteration of Middle English floute, fle...

FLUID.d: A substance that flows; able to flow.
FLUID.e: From Latin fluidus, from fluere (to flow).

FOALS.d: Plural of FOAL: A young horse or other equine, especially just after birth or less than a year old.
FOALS.e: From Middle English fole, from Old English fola, from Proto-West Germanic *folō, from Proto-Germanic *fulô, from pre-Germanic *pl̥Hon-, from Proto-Indo-European *pōlH- (“animal young”) (cognate with Saterland Frisian Foole, West Frisian fôle, foalle, Dutch veulen, German Low Germ...

FOAMS.d: Plural of FOAM: A substance composed of a large collection of bubbles or their solidified remains, especially
FOAMS.e: From Middle English fom, foom, from Old English fām, from Proto-West Germanic *faim, from Proto-Germanic *faimaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)poHy-m-os, from *(s)poH(y)- (“foam”). Cognate with German Feim (“foam”), Latin spūma (“foam”), Latin pūmex (“pumice”), Sanskrit फेन (phén...

FOCUS.d: The centre of attention; to concentrate.

FOILS.d: Plural of FOIL: An acronym for the algorithm for multiplying two binomials.
FOILS.e: Acronym of first outer inner last or similar.

FOLDS.d: Plural of FOLD: To bend (any thin material, such as paper) over so that it comes in contact with itself.
FOLDS.e:
The verb is from Middle English folden, from Old English fealdan, from Proto-West Germanic *falþan, from Proto-Germanic *falþaną (“to fold”), from Proto-Indo-European *pel- (“to fold”).
The noun is from Middle English folde, falde, itself derived from the verb.

FOLKS.d: Plural of FOLK: A people; a tribe or nation; the inhabitants of a region, especially the native inhabitants.
FOLKS.e:
From Middle English folk, from Old English folc, from Proto-West Germanic *folk, from Proto-Germanic *fulką, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁-gós, from *pleh₁- (“to fill”).
Cognate with German Volk, Dutch volk, Swedish folk and Danish folk. Doublet of volk.

FONDS.d: Plural of FOND: Having a liking or affection (for).
FONDS.e: From Middle English fond, fonned, past participle of fonnen (“to be foolish, be simple, dote”), equivalent to fon + -ed. More at fon.

FONTS.d: Plural of FONT: A receptacle in a church for holy water, especially one used in baptism.
FONTS.e: From Old English font, an early borrowing from Latin fōns, fontis (“fountain”).

FOODS.d: Plural of FOOD: Any solid substance that can be consumed by living organisms, especially by eating, in order to sustain life.
FOODS.e:
From Middle English fode, foode, from Old English fōda (“food”), from Proto-West Germanic *fōdō, from Proto-Germanic *fōdô (“food”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂- (“to guard, graze, feed”).
Cognate with Scots fuid (“food”), Low German föde, vöde (“food”), West Frisian fiedsel (...

FOOLS.d: Plural of FOOL: A person with poor judgment or little intelligence.
FOOLS.e: From Middle English fole (“fool”), from Old French fol (cf. modern French fou (“mad”)) from Latin follis. Doublet of fals and follis. Displaced native Old English dwæs.

FOOTS.d: Plural of FOOT: A biological structure found in many animals that is used for locomotion and that is frequently a separate organ at the terminal part of the leg.
FOOTS.e:
From Middle English fot, fote, foot, from Old English fōt, from Proto-West Germanic *fōt, from Proto-Germanic *fōts, from Proto-Indo-European *pṓds. Doublet of pes, pie (“Spanish unit of length”), and pous.
Cognates
*Scots fit (“foot”)
*Yola voote (“foot”)
*North Frisian fut, föt...

FORBS.d: Plural of FORB: Any non-woody flowering plant that is not a graminoid (a grass, sedge, or rush).
FORBS.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek φορβή (phorbḗ, “food”), from φέρβω (phérbō, “to feed”).

FORCE.e: From Old French force, from Latin fortis (strong).

FORDS.d: Plural of FORD: A location where a stream is shallow and the bottom has good footing, making it possible to cross from one side to the other with no bridge, by walking, riding, or driving through the water; a crossing.
FORDS.e:
