Proto-Indo-European *-tus
Proto-Indo-European *pértus
Proto-Germanic *furduz
Proto-West Germanic *furdu
Old English ford
English ford
Inherited from Middle English fōrd, from Old English ford, from Proto-West Germanic *furdu, from Proto-Ge...

FORES.d: Plural of FORE: Former; occurring earlier (in some order); previous.
FORES.e: A development of the prefix fore-.

FORKS.d: Plural of FORK: Any of several types of pronged (tined) tools (physical tools), as follows:
FORKS.e: From Middle English forke (“digging fork”), from Old English force, forca (“forked instrument used to torture”), from Proto-West Germanic *furkō (“fork”), from Latin furca (“pitchfork, forked stake; gallows, beam, stake, support post, yoke”), of uncertain origin. The Middle Engli...

FORMS.d: Plural of FORM: To do with shape.
FORMS.e:
From Middle English forme (“shape, figure, manner, bench, frame, seat, condition, agreement, etc.”), borrowed from Old French forme, from Latin fōrma (“shape, figure, image, outline, plan, mold, frame, case, etc., manner, sort, kind, etc.”).
In sense "division grouping school stu...

FORTH.d: Forward; out from a starting point.

FORTS.d: Plural of FORT: A fortified defensive structure stationed with troops.
FORTS.e: From Middle English fort, from Middle French fort (“strong”) (adjective use is from Old French). Doublet of fortis and forte.

FOULS.d: Plural of FOUL: Covered with, or containing unclean matter; dirty.
FOULS.e:
Inherited from Middle English foul, from Old English fūl (“foul, dirty, unclean, impure, vile, corrupt, rotten, stinking, guilty”), from Proto-West Germanic *fūl, from Proto-Germanic *fūlaz (“foul, rotten”), from Proto-Indo-European *puH- (“to rot”).
Cognate with Dutch vuil (“fou...

FOUND.d: Past tense of find; to establish.
FOUND.e: From Old English findan / Old French fonder.

FOURS.d: Plural of FOUR: A numerical value equal to 4; the number after three and before five; two plus two. This many dots (••••)
FOURS.e:
PIE word
 *kʷetwóres
From Middle English four, from Old English fēower, from Proto-West Germanic *feuwar, from Proto-Germanic *fedwōr, from previous pre-Grimm *petwṓr, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷetwṓr, the neuter form of *kʷetwóres. Doublet of cuatro and quatre.
Cognates include...

FOWLS.d: Plural of FOWL: A bird hunted or kept for food, grouped into landfowl (order Galliformes), also called gamefowl, and waterfowl (order Anseriformes: ducks, geese, swans, etc.), which together form the clade Galloanserae.
FOWLS.e: From Middle English foul, foghel, fowel, fowele, from Old English fugol (“bird”), from Proto-West Germanic *fugl, from Proto-Germanic *fuglaz, dissimilated variant of *fluglaz (compare Old English flugol ‘fleeing’, Mercian fluglas heofun ‘birds of the air’), from *fleuganą (“to f...

FOXED.d: Past tense of FOX: A small-to-medium-sized canine mammal, related to dogs and wolves, with a flattened skull, upright triangular ears, a pointed, slightly upturned snout, and a long bushy tail, of the following groups:
FOXED.e: From Middle English fox, from Old English fox (“fox”), from Proto-West Germanic *fuhs, from Proto-Germanic *fuhsaz (“fox”), from Proto-Indo-European *púḱsos (“the tailed one”), possibly from *puḱ- (“tail”).

FOXES.d: Plural of FOX: A small-to-medium-sized canine mammal, related to dogs and wolves, with a flattened skull, upright triangular ears, a pointed, slightly upturned snout, and a long bushy tail, of the following groups:
FOXES.e: From Middle English fox, from Old English fox (“fox”), from Proto-West Germanic *fuhs, from Proto-Germanic *fuhsaz (“fox”), from Proto-Indo-European *púḱsos (“the tailed one”), possibly from *puḱ- (“tail”).

FRAME.d: A border or structure; to construct.

FRAPS.d: Plural of FRAP: To draw together tightly; to secure by many turns of a lashing.
FRAPS.e: From Middle English frapen, from Old French fraper.

FRAYS.d: Plural of FRAY: To rub or wear away (something); to cause (something made of strands twisted or woven together, such as cloth or rope) to unravel through friction; also, to irritate (something) through chafing or rubbing; to chafe.
FRAYS.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English fraien (“to beat so as to cause bruising, to bruise; to crush; to rub; to wear, wear off”), borrowed from Old French fraier, freier, freiier (modern French frayer (“to clear, open up (a path, etc.); (figuratively) to find one’s way thr...

FREES.e:
From Middle English free, fre, freo, from Old English frēo (“free”), from Proto-West Germanic *frī, from Proto-Germanic *frijaz (“beloved, not in bondage”), from Proto-Indo-European *priHós (“pleased, loved”), from *preyH- (“to please, love”). Related to friend.

FRETS.d: Plural of FRET: Especially when describing animals: to consume, devour, or eat.
FRETS.e: From Middle English frēten (“to eat (at), corrode, destroy, annoy”), from Old English fretan (“to eat up, devour; to fret; to break, burst”), from Proto-West Germanic *fraetan, from Proto-Germanic *fraetaną (“to consume, devour, eat up”), from Proto-Germanic *fra- (“for-, prefix ...

FRIED.d: Past tense of FRY: A method of cooking food.
FRIED.e: From Middle English fryen, borrowed from Old French frire, from Latin frīgō (“to roast, fry”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer-. Cognate with Ancient Greek φρύγω (phrúgō, “I roast, bake”), Sanskrit भृज्जति (bhṛjjati, “to roast, grill, fry”), भृग् (bhṛg, “the crackling of fire”). R...

FRIER.d: Comparative form of FRY: A method of cooking food.
FRIER.e: From Middle English fryen, borrowed from Old French frire, from Latin frīgō (“to roast, fry”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer-. Cognate with Ancient Greek φρύγω (phrúgō, “I roast, bake”), Sanskrit भृज्जति (bhṛjjati, “to roast, grill, fry”), भृग् (bhṛg, “the crackling of fire”). R...

FRIES.d: Plural of FRY: A method of cooking food.
FRIES.e: From Middle English fryen, borrowed from Old French frire, from Latin frīgō (“to roast, fry”), from Proto-Indo-European *bʰer-. Cognate with Ancient Greek φρύγω (phrúgō, “I roast, bake”), Sanskrit भृज्जति (bhṛjjati, “to roast, grill, fry”), भृग् (bhṛg, “the crackling of fire”). R...

FRIGS.e: From Middle English friggen (“to quiver”), perhaps from Old English *frygian (“to rub, caress”), related to Old English frēogan, frīgan (“to love, release, embrace, caress”), frīge (pl., “love”). Compare also Faroese fríggj (“erotocism, sex, flirtation”), Old English ġefrīgian (“...

FRITS.d: Plural of FRIT: A fused mixture of materials used to make glass.
FRITS.e: Either from French fritte, from frit (“fried”), or else from Italian fritta f (“fried”).

FROGS.d: Plural of FROG: Any of a class of small tailless amphibians of the order Anura that typically hop.
FROGS.e:
From Middle English frogge, from Old English frocga, from Proto-West Germanic *froggō (“frog”). Cognate with Old Norse frauki, and Old English frox, frosc, whence Modern English frosh and frosk (“frog”).
Possibly related to Saterland Frisian Poage (“frog”), German Low German Pogg...

FRONT.e: From Old French front, from Latin frōns.

FROWS.d: Plural of FROW: A woman; a wife, especially a Dutch or German one.
FROWS.e:
From Middle Dutch vrouwe (“lady”), from Old Dutch *frōwa, from Proto-West Germanic *frauwjā, from Proto-Germanic *frawjǭ (“lady, mistress”), from Proto-Indo-European *prōw- (“right; judge, master”).
Cognate with Dutch vrouw (“woman, wife, lady, mistress”), Low German frouw, frauw...

FRUIT.d: The seed-bearing part of a plant.
FRUIT.e: From Old French fruit, from Latin frūctus.

FUCKS.d: Plural of FUCK: To have sexual intercourse; to copulate.
FUCKS.e: From Middle English *fukken, probably of Germanic origin: either from Old English *fuccian or Old Norse *fukka, both from Proto-Germanic *fukkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *pewǵ- (“to strike, punch, stab”). Compare windfucker and its debated etymology.

FUELS.d: Plural of FUEL: Substance consumed to provide energy through combustion, or through chemical or nuclear reaction.
FUELS.e: From Middle English fewell, from Old French fouaille, feuaille (“firewood, kindling”), from feu (“fire”), from Late Latin focus (“fire”), from Latin focus (“hearth”). Cognate with Spanish fuego (“fire”), and Portuguese fogo (“fire”). Doublet of focus.

FULLS.d: Plural of FULL: Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
FULLS.e:
From Middle English ful, from Old English full (“full”), from Proto-West Germanic *full, from Proto-Germanic *fullaz (“full”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós (“full”).
Germanic cognates include West Frisian fol, Low German vull, Dutch vol, German voll, Danish fuld, and Norweg...

FUMED.d: Past tense of FUME: A gas or vapour/vapor that is strong-smelling or dangerous to inhale.
FUMED.e: From Middle English fume, from Old French fum (“smoke, steam, vapour”), from Latin fūmus (“vapour, smoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰuh₂mós (“smoke”), from *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust”). Doublet of thymus and thymos. More at dun, dusk, dust.

FUMES.d: Plural of FUME: A gas or vapour/vapor that is strong-smelling or dangerous to inhale.
FUMES.e: From Middle English fume, from Old French fum (“smoke, steam, vapour”), from Latin fūmus (“vapour, smoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰuh₂mós (“smoke”), from *dʰewh₂- (“to smoke, raise dust”). Doublet of thymus and thymos. More at dun, dusk, dust.

FUNDS.d: Plural of FUND: A sum or source of money.
FUNDS.e:
PIE word
 *bʰudʰmḗn
Borrowed from Latin fundus. Doublet of fond and fundus.

FUNKS.d: Plural of FUNK: Foul or unpleasant smell, especially body odor.
FUNKS.e: 1620, from French dialectal (Norman) funquer, funquier (“to smoke, reek”), from Old Northern French fungier (“to smoke”), from Vulgar Latin fūmicāre, alteration of Latin fūmigāre (“to smoke, fumigate”). Related to French dialect funkière (“smoke”). More at fumigate.

FURLS.d: Plural of FURL: To lower, roll up and secure (something, such as a sail or flag)
FURLS.e: Perhaps from Old French ferlier, modern French ferler.

FUSED.d: Past tense of FUSE: A cord that, when lit, conveys the fire to some explosive device, such as a bomb.
FUSED.e: From Italian fuso and French fusée, from Latin fūsus (“spindle”).

FUSES.d: Plural of FUSE: A cord that, when lit, conveys the fire to some explosive device, such as a bomb.
FUSES.e: From Italian fuso and French fusée, from Latin fūsus (“spindle”).

GAFFS.d: Plural of GAFF: A tool consisting of a large metal hook with a handle or pole, especially the one used to pull large fish aboard a boat.
GAFFS.e:
From Middle English gaffe, from Old French gaffe, from Old Occitan gaf (“hook”), derivative of gafar (“to seize”), from 𐌲𐌹𐌱𐌰𐌽 (giban, “to give”). Doublet of gaffe.
Sense 5 apparently derives from the idea that the garment tricks or deceives others about the wearer's genitalia.

GAGED.d: Past tense of GAGE: To bind (someone) by pledge or security; to engage.
GAGED.e: From Middle English gage, from later Old French or early Middle French gager (verb), (also guagier in Old French) gage (noun), ultimately from Frankish *waddi, from Proto-Germanic *wadją (whence English wed). Doublet of wage, from the same origin through the Old Northern French v...

GAGES.d: Plural of GAGE: To bind (someone) by pledge or security; to engage.
GAGES.e: From Middle English gage, from later Old French or early Middle French gager (verb), (also guagier in Old French) gage (noun), ultimately from Frankish *waddi, from Proto-Germanic *wadją (whence English wed). Doublet of wage, from the same origin through the Old Northern French v...

GAINS.d: Plural of GAIN: To acquire possession of.
GAINS.e: From Middle English gayn, gain, gein (“profit, advantage”), from Old Norse gagn (“benefit, advantage, use”), from Proto-Germanic *gagną, *gaganą (“gain, profit", literally "return”), from Proto-Germanic *gagana (“back, against, in return”), a reduplication of Proto-Germanic *ga- ...

GAITS.d: Plural of GAIT: Manner of walking or stepping; bearing or carriage while moving on legs.
GAITS.e: From Middle English gate (“way”), from Old Norse gata (“road”), from Proto-Germanic *gatwǭ. Doublet of gate.

GALAS.e: From French gala, or directly from that word's etymon, which is either Italian gala, or Spanish gala, both meaning "festive occasion", and derived from Old French gale (“rejoicing”). (The French word likely kept the final -a to avoid homophony with gale (“scabies”).) Ultimately c...

GALES.d: Plural of GALE: To cry; groan; croak.
GALES.e: From Middle English galen, from Old English galan (“to sing, enchant, call, cry, scream; sing charms, practice incantation”), from Proto-Germanic *galaną (“to roop, sing, charm”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰel- (“to shout, scream, charm away”). Cognate with Danish gale (“to crow...

GALLS.d: Plural of GALL: Impudence or brazenness; temerity; chutzpah.
GALLS.e:
From Middle English galle, from Old English ġealla, galla, from Proto-West Germanic *gallā, from Proto-Germanic *gallǭ.
The figurative senses (e.g., impudence, brazenness, chutzpah) are related to the literal sense (i.e., bile) via the lasting linguocultural effects of humorism, ...

GAMED.d: Past tense of GAME: A playful or competitive activity.
GAMED.e: From Middle English game, gamen, gammen, from Old English gamen (“sport, joy, mirth, pastime, game, amusement, pleasure”), from Proto-West Germanic *gaman, from Proto-Germanic *gamaną (“amusement, pleasure, game", literally "participation, communion, people together”), from *ga- ...

GAMES.d: Plural of GAME: A playful or competitive activity.
GAMES.e: From Middle English game, gamen, gammen, from Old English gamen (“sport, joy, mirth, pastime, game, amusement, pleasure”), from Proto-West Germanic *gaman, from Proto-Germanic *gamaną (“amusement, pleasure, game", literally "participation, communion, people together”), from *ga- ...

GANGS.d: Plural of GANG: To go; walk; proceed.
GANGS.e:
From Middle English gangen, from Old English gangan (“to go, walk, turn out”), from Proto-West Germanic *gangan, from Proto-Germanic *ganganą (“to go, walk”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰengʰ- (“to step, walk”).
Cognate with Scots gang (“to go on foot, walk”), Swedish gånga (“to ...

GAOLS.d: Plural of GAOL: Dated spelling of jail.
GAOLS.e: From Middle English gayole, gaiol, gaylle, gaille, gayle, gaile, via Old French gaiole, gayolle, gaole, from Medieval Latin gabiola, for Late Latin caveola, a diminutive of Latin cavea (“cavity, coop, cage”). See also cage.

GAPED.d: Past tense of GAPE: To open the mouth wide, especially involuntarily, as in a yawn, anger, or surprise.
GAPED.e: From Middle English gapen, from Old Norse gapa (“to gape”) (compare Swedish gapa, Danish gabe), from Proto-Germanic *gapōną (descendants Middle English geapen, Dutch gapen, German gaffen), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰеh₂b-. Cognates include Russian зяпа (zjapa).

GAPES.d: Plural of GAPE: To open the mouth wide, especially involuntarily, as in a yawn, anger, or surprise.
GAPES.e: From Middle English gapen, from Old Norse gapa (“to gape”) (compare Swedish gapa, Danish gabe), from Proto-Germanic *gapōną (descendants Middle English geapen, Dutch gapen, German gaffen), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰеh₂b-. Cognates include Russian зяпа (zjapa).

GARBS.d: Plural of GARB: Fashion, style of dressing oneself up.
GARBS.e: From Middle French garbe ("graceful outline, silhouette"; > Modern French galbe), from Italian garbo (“grace, elegance”), from Germanic (compare Old High German garwi, garawi (“dress, equipment, preparation”), Middle High German gerwe (“outfitting, jewelry, clothing, robe, regali...

GASES.d: Plural of GAS: Matter in an intermediate state between liquid and plasma that can be contained only if it is fully surrounded by a solid (or in a bubble of liquid, or held together by gravitational pull); it can condense into a liquid, or can (rarely) become a solid directly by deposition.
GASES.e: Borrowed from Dutch gas, coined by chemist Jan Baptist van Helmont in Ortus Medicinae. Derived from Ancient Greek χάος (kháos, “chasm, void, empty space”); perhaps also inspired by geest (“breath, vapour, spirit”). Doublet of chaos. First attested in 1648.

GASPS.d: Plural of GASP: To draw in the breath suddenly, as if from a shock.
GASPS.e: From Middle English gaspen, gayspen (“to gape, outbreathe”), related to and likely derived from Old Norse geispa (“to yawn”) or its descendant Danish gispe, which may be related to gapa (“to gape”).

GATED.d: Past tense of GATE: A doorlike structure outside a house.
GATED.e:
From Middle English gate, gat, ȝate, ȝeat, from Old English ġeat (“gate”), from Proto-West Germanic *gat, from Proto-Germanic *gatą (“hole, opening”).
See also Old Norse gat, Swedish and Dutch gat, Low German Gaat, Gööt.

GATES.d: Plural of GATE: A doorlike structure outside a house.
GATES.e:
From Middle English gate, gat, ȝate, ȝeat, from Old English ġeat (“gate”), from Proto-West Germanic *gat, from Proto-Germanic *gatą (“hole, opening”).
See also Old Norse gat, Swedish and Dutch gat, Low German Gaat, Gööt.

GAURS.d: Plural of GAUR: An Asian species of wild bovine (Bos gaurus), of large size and an untamable disposition.
GAURS.e: Borrowed from Hindi गौर (gaur), from Sanskrit गौर (gaura). Attested in English since the early 19th century. Doublet of gayal.

GAWKS.d: Plural of GAWK: A cuckoo; (sometimes by extension) any gawky bird.
GAWKS.e:
From a variant of gowk, from Middle English gowke, goke, from Old Norse gaukr (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Germanic *gaukaz (“cuckoo”). Cognate with Danish gøg, Swedish gök, German Gauch, Old English ġēac.
Compare also French gauche, and English gawky and gallock.

GAZED.d: Past tense of GAZE: To stare intently or earnestly.
GAZED.e: From Middle English gasen; akin to Swedish dialectal gasa and Gothic 𐌿𐍃𐌲𐌰𐌹𐍃𐌾𐌰𐌽 (usgaisjan, “to terrify”).

GEARS.d: Plural of GEAR: Equipment or paraphernalia, especially that used for an athletic endeavor.
GEARS.e: From Middle English gere, a borrowing from Old Norse gervi, from Proto-Germanic *garwijaną (“to prepare”). See also adjective yare, yar from the same root via Old English.

GEEKS.d: Plural of GEEK: A carnival performer specializing in bizarre and unappetizing behavior.
GEEKS.e: Started as carnival slang, likely from the British dialectal term geck (“a fool, dupe, simpleton”) (1510s), apparently from Dutch gek or Low German geck, from an imitative verb found in North Sea Germanic and Scandinavian meaning "to croak, cackle," and also "to mock, cheat" (Dut...

GELDS.e: From Middle English geld and reinforced by Medieval Latin geldum, both from Old English geld, ġield (“payment, tribute”), from Proto-West Germanic *geld, from Proto-Germanic *geldą (“reward, gift, money”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰeldʰ- (“to pay”). Probably reinforced by gelt ...

GENES.d: Plural of GENE: A theoretical unit of heredity of living organisms which may take several values and (in principle) predetermines a precise trait of an organism's form (phenotype), such as hair color.
GENES.e: From German Gen, from Ancient Greek γενεά (geneá, “generation, descent”), from the aorist infinitive of γίγνομαι (gígnomai, “I come into being”). Coined by Danish botanist Wilhelm Ludwig Johannsen in 1909, in a German-language publication, from the last syllable of pangene.

GENUS.e:
PIE word
 *ǵónu
Borrowed from Latin genu (“knee”).

GERMS.d: Plural of GERM: The small mass of cells from which a new organism develops; a seed, bud, spore, or zygote.
GERMS.e: From Middle French germe, from Latin germen (“bud, seed, embryo”). Doublet of germen.

GEUMS.d: Plural of GEUM: Any of the genus Geum of perennial herbaceous plants.

GHATS.d: Plural of GHAT: A descending path or stairway to a river; a ford or landing-place.
GHATS.e: Borrowed from Hindi घाट (ghāṭ, “pier”), from Sanskrit घट्ट (ghaṭṭa, “a landing-place, steps on the side of a river leading to the waters”), from Dravidian. Compare Telugu గట్టు (gaṭṭu, “dam, embankment”), కట్ట (kaṭṭa, “dam, embankment”), derived from కట్టు (kaṭṭu, “to tie”).

GHEES.d: Plural of GHEE: A type of clarified butter used in South Asian cooking; usli ghee.
GHEES.e: Borrowed from Hindustani گھی (ghī) / घी (ghī), from Sanskrit घृत (ghṛta, “sprinkled”). First attested in the late 17th century.

GIBED.d: Past tense of GIBE: Alternative spelling of gybe.

GIBES.d: Plural of GIBE: Alternative spelling of gybe.

GIFTS.d: Plural of GIFT: Something given to another voluntarily, without charge.
GIFTS.e:
From Middle English gift (also yift, yifte, ȝift, ȝeft), partly from Old English ġift (“giving, consideration, dowry, wedding”) and Old Norse gipt (“gift, present, wedding”); both from Proto-Germanic *giftiz (“gift”). Equivalent to give + -t (etymologically yive + -t).
Cognate wi...

GILDS.d: Plural of GILD: To cover with a thin layer of gold; to cover with gold leaf.
GILDS.e: From Middle English gilden, gulden, from Old English gyldan (“to gild, to cover with a thin layer of gold”), from Proto-West Germanic *gulþijan, from Proto-Germanic *gulþijaną, from Proto-Germanic *gulþą (“gold”).

GILLS.d: Plural of GILL: A breathing organ of fish and other aquatic animals.
GILLS.e: From Middle English gille, gylle (“gill”), of North Germanic origin, akin to Danish gælle, Swedish gäl, Norwegian gjelle, and further to Old Norse gjǫlnar (“lips”), which also may have had the meaning of "gills" (based on Old Danish fiskegæln (“gills”)). The Old Norse word has be...

GILTS.d: Plural of GILT: Gold or other metal in a thin layer; gilding.
GILTS.e: Formed in English from the verb gild (“to cover in gold”). Compare gold and German Geld.

GIMPS.d: Plural of GIMP: A narrow ornamental fabric or braid of silk, wool, or cotton, often stiffened with metallic wire or coarse cord running through it, used as trimming for dresses, curtains, furniture, etc. Also guimpe.
GIMPS.e:
Attested since about 1660, perhaps from Dutch gimp or French guimpe, and likely from Old French guimpre, a variant of guipure, a kind of trimming.
The regional sense of "gumption" is attested since about 1905, and may have developed due to the reinforced nature of gimp cord, or p...

GIRDS.d: Plural of GIRD: To bind with a flexible rope or cord.
GIRDS.e: From Middle English girden, gerden, gürden, from Old English gyrdan (“to put a belt around, to put a girdle around”), from Proto-Germanic *gurdijaną (“to gird”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰerdʰ-. Cognate with West Frisian gurdzje, girdzje, Dutch gorden, German gürten, Swedish gj...

GIRLS.d: Plural of GIRL: A female child.
GIRLS.e: From Middle English gerle, girle, gyrle (“young person (boy or girl)”), perhaps from Old English *gyrele, from Proto-West Germanic *gurilā, from a zero-grade diminutive of *gaurā (“young child”) + *-ilā. Ultimately of unknown origin. Doublet of gal/gyal and gyaru.

GIROS.d: Plural of GIRO: A transfer of funds between different account holders, carried out by the bank according to payer's written instructions.
GIROS.e: Via German, from Italian giro (“circulation”), from Latin gyrus (“circle”), from Ancient Greek γῦρος (gûros, “circle”), from Proto-Indo-European *gew- (“to curve, to bend”).

GIRTS.d: Plural of GIRT: A horizontal structural member of post and beam architecture, typically attached to bridge two or more vertical members such as corner posts.

GISTS.d: Plural of GIST: The main idea or substance, or the most essential part, of a longer or more complicated matter; the crux, the heart, the pith.
GISTS.e: The noun is derived from Old French gist, a noun use of the third person singular indicative of gesir (“to lie down”) (modern French gésir; compare Anglo-Norman (cest) action gist (literally “(law) (this) action lies”)), from Latin iacēre, the present active infinitive of iaceō (...

GLADS.d: Plural of GLAD: Pleased; happy; gratified.
GLADS.e:
From Middle English glad, gled, from Old English glæd (“shining; bright; cheerful; glad”), from Proto-Germanic *gladaz (“shiny; gleaming; radiant; happy; glossy; smooth; flat”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰladʰ-, from *ǵʰelh₂- (“to shine”).
Cognate with Scots gled, glaid (“shinin...

GLEDS.d: Plural of GLED: Alternative form of glede.

GLEES.d: Plural of GLEE: Joy; happiness; great delight, especially from one's own good fortune or from another's misfortune.
GLEES.e:
From Middle English gle, from Old English glēo, glīġ, glēow, glīw (“glee, pleasure, mirth, play, sport; music; mockery”), from Proto-West Germanic *glīw, from Proto-Germanic *glīwą (“joy, mirth”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰlew- (“to joke, make fun, enjoy”).
Cognate with Scots g...

GLENS.d: Plural of GLEN: A secluded and narrow valley, especially one with a river running through it; a depression between hills; a dale.
GLENS.e: From Middle English glen, borrowed from Irish gleann and Scottish Gaelic gleann, Old and Middle Irish glend, glenn (“mountain valley”), from Proto-Celtic *glendos (“valley”), hypothetically from Proto-Indo-European *glend- (“shore”) but the word may have been borrowed from a non-...

GLEYS.d: Plural of GLEY: A type of hydric soil, sticky, greenish-blue-grey in colour and low in oxygen.
GLEYS.e: 1920s, from Ukrainian ґлей (glej, “clayey soil”), from Proto-Slavic *glьjь, from Proto-Indo-European *gl̥h₁y-ó-s, from Proto-Indo-European *gleh₁y-. Cognate of clay.

GLIMS.e: From Middle English glim, glimme (“radiance; shining brightness”), of uncertain further origin. Perhaps from Old English gleomu (“splendor”) and/or Old Norse *glim, *glima, both apparently from Proto-Germanic *glimō, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰley- (“to gleam, shimmer, glow”). C...

GLOBS.d: Plural of GLOB: A round, shapeless or amorphous lump, as of a semisolid substance.
GLOBS.e: Possibly a blend of blob + gob or a clipping of globule. An element of sound symbolism is clearly involved: compare such phonetically and semantically similar words as glop, gop, blob, clump and clod. (Still, globe, clump and clod may be related via the Proto-Indo-European root *...

GLOMS.e: From Scottish English glom, glaum (“to grab or snatch at”), a variant of clam, claum (“to clutch, seize, grasp, reach for”), from Middle English *clammen, from Old English clæmman (“to pinch, press, inclose”), from Proto-West Germanic *klammjan. Related to clamp.

GLOWS.d: Plural of GLOW: To emit light as if heated.
GLOWS.e:
From Middle English glowen, from Old English glōwan, from Proto-West Germanic *glōan, from Proto-Germanic *glōaną, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰleh₁-.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian gloie, glöie, gluuje, West Frisian gloeie, Dutch gloeien, German glühen, Danish and Norwegian glo, ...

GLUED.d: Past tense of GLUE: A hard gelatin made by boiling bones and hides, used in solution as an adhesive; or any sticky adhesive substance.
GLUED.e:
From Middle English glew, glue, from Old French glu (“glue, birdlime”), from Late Latin glūs (stem glūt-), from Latin glūten. Related to clay.
Partially displaced native Old English līm (“glue”) and ġelīman (“to glue”) (whence modern lime).

GLUES.d: Plural of GLUE: A hard gelatin made by boiling bones and hides, used in solution as an adhesive; or any sticky adhesive substance.
GLUES.e:
From Middle English glew, glue, from Old French glu (“glue, birdlime”), from Late Latin glūs (stem glūt-), from Latin glūten. Related to clay.
Partially displaced native Old English līm (“glue”) and ġelīman (“to glue”) (whence modern lime).

GLUTS.d: Plural of GLUT: An excess, too much.
GLUTS.e: Inherited from Middle English glotien /glotten, probably derived from Old French gloter /glotir /glotoiier (“to eat greedily”) [compare French engloutir (“to devour”), French glouton (“glutton”)], derived from Latin gluttiō, gluttīre (“to swallow”). Compare Russian глота́ть (glot...

GNATS.d: Plural of GNAT: Any small insect of the order Diptera, specifically within the suborder Nematocera.
GNATS.e: From Middle English gnat, from Old English gnætt (“gnat; midge; mosquito”), from Proto-West Germanic *gnatt, *gnattu, from Proto-Germanic *gnattaz, *gnattuz (“gnat”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰneHdʰn-, *gʰneHd- (“to gnaw; scratch”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰen- (“to gnaw; bi...

GNAWS.d: Plural of GNAW: To bite something persistently, especially something tough.
GNAWS.e:
From Middle English gnawen, gnaȝen, from Old English gnagan, from Proto-West Germanic *gnagan, from Proto-Germanic *gnaganą (“to gnaw”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *gʰnēgʰ- (“to gnaw, scratch”).
Cognate with Dutch knagen, German nagen, Danish gnave (“to gnaw”), Norwegian B...

GOADS.d: Plural of GOAD: A long, pointed stick used to prod animals.
GOADS.e: From Middle English gode, from Old English gād (“goad”), from Proto-Germanic *gaidō (compare Old Norse gedda (“pike (fish)”), Lombardic gaida (“spear”)), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰey- (compare Old Irish gath (“spear”), Sanskrit हिन्वति (hinvati), हिनोति (hinoti, “to urge on, th...

GOALS.d: Plural of GOAL: A result that one is attempting to achieve.
GOALS.e: From Middle English gol (“boundary, limit”), from Old English *gāl (“obstacle, barrier, marker”), suggested by its derivatives Old English gǣlan (“to hinder, delay, impede, keep in suspense, linger, hesitate, dupe”), and hyġegǣls (“hesitating, slow, sluggish”), hyġegǣlsa (“slow o...

GOATS.d: Plural of GOAT: Any hoofed mammal of the genus Capra.
GOATS.e:
From Middle English goot, got, gat, from Old English gāt, from Proto-West Germanic *gait, from Proto-Germanic *gaits, from a substrate language.
The sense of lecherous man derives from the slang expression "horny as a goat".

GOERS.d: Plural of GOER: One who, or that which, goes.
GOERS.e: From Middle English goere, equivalent to go + -er. Compare German Geher (“goer, walker”).

GOLDS.d: Plural of GOLD: A heavy yellow elemental metal of great value, with atomic number 79 and symbol Au.
GOLDS.e: From Middle English gold, from Old English gold (“gold”), from Proto-West Germanic *golþ, from Proto-Germanic *gulþą (“gold”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰl̥h₃tóm (“gold”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰelh₃- (“green, yellow”). Related to yellow; see there for more. Germanic cognat...

GOLFS.d: Plural of GOLF: A ball game played by individuals competing against one another in which the object is to hit a ball into each of a series of (usually 18 or nine) holes in the minimum number of strokes.
GOLFS.e: The word is first known in English from the 17th century as a borrowing from Middle Scots golf, gouff. Although the etymology is uncertain, the most likely origin is that it comes from the Middle Dutch colve, colf (“club”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *kulbaz (“club”), related...

GONGS.d: Plural of GONG: A percussion instrument consisting of a metal disk that emits a loud resonant sound when struck with a soft hammer.

GOODS.d: Plural of GOOD: Of a person or an animal:
GOODS.e:
Inherited from Middle English good, from Old English gōd, from Proto-West Germanic *gōd, from Proto-Germanic *gōdaz (“good”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰedʰ- (“to unite, be associated, suit, fit”).
Related to gather and together, but not to god/God.
Eclipsed non-native Middle En...

GOOFS.d: Plural of GOOF: A mistake or error.
GOOFS.e:
Perhaps from dialectal English goff (“foolish clown”), from earlier goffe, in which case further etymology is uncertain.
Perhaps from Middle English goffen (“to speak in a frivolous manner”), possibly from Old English gaf, ġegaf (“base; wanton; lewd”, adjective), ġegaf (“buffoone...

GOOKS.d: Plural of GOOK: A person of (South) East Asian descent (originally revolutionaries of the Katipunan then generally to any native of the Philippines, after the enemy and collaborators hid amongst them), but now especially:
GOOKS.e: First attested in the 1890s, US military slang in reference to Filipinos (in particular, it is defined in an 1893 citation in Slang and Its Analogues as referring to prostitutes who followed army camps; it is defined similarly in a 1914 work). The word was used for Nicaraguans du...

GOOPS.d: Plural of GOOP: A thick, slimy substance; goo.
GOOPS.e: 1930s, perhaps a variant of goo; compare gloop, and glob.

GORED.d: Past tense of GORE: Blood, especially that from a wound when thickened due to exposure to the air.
GORED.e:
From Middle English gore, gor, gorre (“mud, muck”), from Old English gor (“manure, dung, filth, muck, dirt”), from Proto-West Germanic *gor, from Proto-Germanic *gurą (“half-digested stomach contents; faeces; manure”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰer- (“hot; warm”).
Cognate to Ol...

GORES.d: Plural of GORE: Blood, especially that from a wound when thickened due to exposure to the air.
GORES.e:
From Middle English gore, gor, gorre (“mud, muck”), from Old English gor (“manure, dung, filth, muck, dirt”), from Proto-West Germanic *gor, from Proto-Germanic *gurą (“half-digested stomach contents; faeces; manure”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰer- (“hot; warm”).
Cognate to Ol...

GOTHS.d: Plural of GOTH: A punk-derived subculture of people who predominantly dress in black, associated with mournful music and attitudes.
GOTHS.e: From gothic rock, first used by John Stickney in reference to The Doors in 1967 and used by the late 1970s to describe the musical scene that gave rise to the goth subculture, both from a supposed aesthetic similarity to dark and moody 19th century gothic fiction and earlier goth...

GOUTS.d: Plural of GOUT: An extremely painful inflammation of joints, especially of the big toe, caused by a metabolic defect resulting in the accumulation of uric acid in the blood and the deposition of urates around the joints.
GOUTS.e:
From Middle English goute, from Old French gote, gute, from Latin gutta (“drop”). Compare Spanish gota (“drop, droplet”). Doublet of goutte, gutta, and gutter.
The sense shift derived from humorism and "the notion of the 'dropping' of a morbid material from the blood in and aroun...

GOWKS.e: From Middle English goke, gowke, from Old Norse gaukr (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Germanic *gaukaz (“cuckoo”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰegʰuǵʰ- (“cuckoo”).

GOWNS.d: Plural of GOWN: A loose, flowing upper garment.
GOWNS.e: From Middle English gowne, from Anglo-Norman goune, gune (“fur-trimmed coat, pelisse”), from Old French goune, from Late Latin gunna (“leather garment, a fur”). Cognate with Manx gooyn, Irish gúna.

GRABS.d: Plural of GRAB: To grip suddenly; to seize; to clutch.
GRABS.e: From Middle Dutch grabben or Middle Low German grabben (“to grasp, grab, seize, snatch”), from Old Saxon gravan, from Proto-West Germanic *grabbōn, a secondary form of Proto-Germanic *grabōną (“to gather, rake”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰrebʰ- (“to gather, rake, grab, seize”)....

GRACE.e: From Old French grace, from Latin grātia.

GRADE.d: A level of quality; a school year.

GRADS.d: Plural of GRAD: Clipping of graduate.

GRAIN.d: Seeds of cereal plants; a small amount.
GRAIN.e: From Old French grain, from Latin grānum.

GRAMS.d: Plural of GRAM: A unit of mass equal to one-thousandth of a kilogram. Symbol: g.
GRAMS.e: From French gramme, from Ancient Greek γράμμα (grámma, “a small weight, a scruple”). Doublet of gramma.

GRAND.e: From Old French grant, from Latin grandis.

GRAVE.e: From Old English græf / Old French grave.

GRAYS.d: Plural of GRAY: Of a colour between black and white, having neutral hue and intermediate brightness.
GRAYS.e:
From Middle English gray, from Old English grǣġ, grǣw (“grey”), from Proto-West Germanic *grāu, from Proto-Germanic *grēwaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰreh₁- (“to green, to grow”).
Cognate with West Frisian grau (“grey”), Dutch grauw (“grey”), German Low German grau, gr...

GREYS.d: Plural of GREY: Commonwealth standard spelling of gray.
GREYS.e: From Middle English grey, from Old English grǣġ, from Proto-Germanic *grēwaz (compare Dutch grauw, German grau, Old Norse grár), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰreh₁- (“to green, to grow”) (compare Latin rāvus (“grey”), Old Church Slavonic зьрѭ (zĭrjǫ, “to see, to glance”), Russian з...

GRIDS.d: Plural of GRID: A rectangular array of squares or rectangles of equal size, such as in a crossword puzzle.
GRIDS.e: Back-formation or clipping of griddle or gridiron.

GRIGS.e: The word is often used in the phrase "merry as a grig". The word is of uncertain origin, though various theories have been suggested, such as a corruption of "merry as a cricket" or "merry as a Greek", as in William Shakespeare's Troilus and Cressida: "Then she's a merry Greek in...

GRINS.d: Plural of GRIN: A smile in which the lips are parted to reveal the teeth.
GRINS.e: From Middle English grinnen, from Old English grennian, from Proto-West Germanic *grannjōn, from Proto-Germanic *granjōną. Related to groan. Compare to Middle High German grennen (“to mutter, complain”) and Danish grine (“to show one's teeth, to laugh”)

GRIPS.d: Plural of GRIP: To take hold (of), particularly with the hand.
GRIPS.e:
Verb from Middle English grippen, from Old English grippan, from a Proto-Germanic *gripjaną (compare Old High German gripfen); compare the related Old English grīpan, whence English gripe. See also grope, and the related Proto-Germanic *grīpaną.
Noun from Middle English grippe, g...

GRITS.d: Plural of GRIT: A collection of hard small materials, such as dirt, ground stone, debris from sandblasting or other such grinding, or swarf from metalworking.
GRITS.e: With early modern vowel shortening, from Middle English grete, griet, from Old English grēot, from Proto-West Germanic *greut, from Proto-Germanic *greutą. Compare grist.

GROGS.d: Plural of GROG: An alcoholic beverage made with rum and water, especially that once issued to sailors of the Royal Navy.
GROGS.e:
An allusion to Admiral Edward Vernon (nicknamed “Old Grog” after the grogram coat he habitually wore), who in 1740 ordered his sailors' rum to be watered down.
Alternatively, from Old Catalan grog or groch, modern groc, meaning "yellow" (ultimately from Latin crocum (“saffron”); ...

GROTS.e: From grotto, by shortening, or French grotte.

GROUP.d: A number of people or things together.
GROUP.e: From French groupe, from Italian gruppo.

GROWS.d: Plural of GROW: To become larger, to increase in magnitude.
GROWS.e:
From Middle English growen, from Old English grōwan (“to grow, increase, flourish, germinate”), from Proto-West Germanic *grōan, from Proto-Germanic *grōaną (“to grow, grow green”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰreh₁- (“to grow, become green”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots grow, gre...

GRUBS.d: Plural of GRUB: An insect, especially a beetle, at an immature stage of its life cycle.
GRUBS.e: From Middle English grubben, grobben, from Old English *grubbian, from Proto-West Germanic *grubb-, from Proto-Germanic *grubb- (compare Middle Dutch grobben (“to scrape, scramble, grab”), Old High German grubilōn (“to dig, search”), German grübeln (“to meditate, ponder”)), from ...

GUARD.d: A person who protects; to watch over.

GUFFS.d: Plural of GUFF: Nonsensical talk or thinking.

GUIDE.d: A person who shows the way; to direct.

GULFS.d: Plural of GULF: A hollow place in the earth; an abyss; a deep chasm or basin.
GULFS.e: From Middle English gulf, goulf, golf, from Old French golf, from Italian golfo, from Late Latin colfos, from Ancient Greek κόλπος (kólpos, “bosom, gulf”), of obscure origin, but possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kʷelp- (“to curve, arch”).

GULLS.d: Plural of GULL: A seabird of the genus Larus or of the subfamily Larinae.
GULLS.e:
Inherited from Middle English gulle, from a Brythonic language (compare Breton gouelan, Welsh gwylan, and Cornish golan), from Proto-Brythonic *gwuɨlann, from Proto-Celtic *weilannā (“seagull”).
Cognate with Old Irish foílenn, Scottish Gaelic faoileag. Compare French goéland, a b...

GULPS.d: Plural of GULP: The usual amount swallowed.
GULPS.e:
From Middle English gulpen, probably from West Flemish or Middle Dutch gulpen, golpen, of uncertain origin. Perhaps of imitative origin, or related to Dutch galpen (“to roar, squeal”), English galp, gaup (“to gape”).
Related to German Low German gulpen (“to gush out, belch, gulp”...

GUNKS.d: Plural of GUNK: Grime, dirt, slime; any vague, messy, or unknown substance.
GUNKS.e: Apparently from Gunk, trademark name for a liquid soap; perhaps taken as a blend of grime + funk.

GURUS.d: Plural of GURU: In Indian traditions: a spiritual teacher who transmits knowledge to a shishya.
GURUS.e: Borrowed from Hindi गुरु (guru) / Punjabi ਗੁਰੂ (gurū), from Sanskrit गुरु (guru, “venerable, respectable”), originally "heavy" and in this sense cognate to English grieve and, more distantly, brute. Doublet of grave. A traditional, though flawed etymology based on the Advayatarak...

GUSTS.d: Plural of GUST: A strong, abrupt rush of wind.
GUSTS.e: Apparently from an unrecorded Middle English *gust, from Old Norse gustr (“a gust, blast”), from Proto-Germanic *gustiz, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵʰew-. Cognate with Icelandic gustur (“gust of wind”). Related also to Old Norse gusa (“to gush forth”), Old High German gussa (“floo...

GUYED.d: Past tense of GUY: An effigy of a man burned on a bonfire on the anniversary of the Gunpowder Plot (5th November).
GUYED.e: Coined by semantic widening from the name of Guy Fawkes (1570–1606), an English Catholic executed for his role in the Gunpowder Plot, from Old French Gui, a form of Proto-Germanic *Wido, a short form of names beginning with the element witu "wood" from Proto-Germanic *widuz, such...

GYBED.d: Past tense of GYBE: To shift a fore-and-aft sail from one side of a sailing vessel to the other, while sailing before the wind.
GYBED.e:
Probably from Dutch gijben (obsolete), gijpen; cognate with Danish gibbe, German gieben, giepen, Swedish gipa, gippa.
The noun is derived from the verb; compare Dutch gijb (obsolete), gijp (“act of gybing; a boom”).

GYBES.d: Plural of GYBE: To shift a fore-and-aft sail from one side of a sailing vessel to the other, while sailing before the wind.
GYBES.e:
Probably from Dutch gijben (obsolete), gijpen; cognate with Danish gibbe, German gieben, giepen, Swedish gipa, gippa.
The noun is derived from the verb; compare Dutch gijb (obsolete), gijp (“act of gybing; a boom”).

GYRED.d: Past tense of GYRE: A swirling vortex.
GYRED.e: Borrowed from Latin gȳrus (“circle; circular motion”), from Ancient Greek γῦρος (gûros, “circle; ring”), from Proto-Indo-European *gew- (“to bend; to curve”). The English word is a doublet of gyro and gyrus.

GYRES.d: Plural of GYRE: A swirling vortex.
GYRES.e: Borrowed from Latin gȳrus (“circle; circular motion”), from Ancient Greek γῦρος (gûros, “circle; ring”), from Proto-Indo-European *gew- (“to bend; to curve”). The English word is a doublet of gyro and gyrus.

HAARS.d: Plural of HAAR: Thick, cold, wet fog along the northeastern coast of Northern England and Scotland.
HAARS.e:
Attested since the late 17th century, alongside Scots haar (“cold easterly wind; misty wind; cold fog or mist”).
Perhaps ultimately from Middle Dutch hare (“cold wind”) or a related Low German word; compare Dutch harig (“windy; foggy, misty”), Saterland Frisian harig (“misty”).

HACKS.e:
From Middle English hacken, hakken, from Old English *haccian (“to hack”), from Proto-West Germanic *hakkōn, from Proto-Germanic *hakkōną (“to chop; hoe; hew”), from Proto-Indo-European *keg-, *keng- (“to be sharp; peg; hook; handle”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian häkje (“to ha...

HAEMS.d: Plural of HAEM: Australia, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand, South Africa, and UK standard spelling of heme.

HAFTS.d: Plural of HAFT: The handle of a tool or weapon.
HAFTS.e: From Middle English haft, from Old English hæft, from Proto-West Germanic *haftī, from Proto-Germanic *haftiją.

HAILS.d: Plural of HAIL: Balls or pieces of ice falling as precipitation, often in connection with a thunderstorm.
HAILS.e: From Middle English hayle, haile, hail, hawel, haghil, haȝel, from Old English hæġl, hæġel, hagol (“hail”), from Proto-West Germanic *hagl, from Proto-Germanic *haglaz, of uncertain origin. Either from Proto-Indo-European *kagʰlos (“pebble”); or alternatively from *ḱoḱló-, a redu...

HAIRS.d: Plural of HAIR: A pigmented filament of keratin which grows from a follicle on the skin of humans and other mammals.
HAIRS.e:
From Middle English her, heer, hær, from Old English hǣr, from Proto-West Germanic *hār, from Proto-Germanic *hērą (“hair”), from Proto-Indo-European *kes- (“to scrape, comb”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Hier, Híer (“hair”), West Frisian hier (“hair”), Cimbrian haar, har (“ha...

HAKES.d: Plural of HAKE: A hook; a pot-hook.
HAKES.e:
From Middle English *hake, from Old English hæca, haca (“hook, bolt, door-fastening, bar”), from Proto-West Germanic *hakō, from Proto-Germanic *hakô (“hook”), from Proto-Indo-European *keg-, *keng- (“peg, hook”). Related to hook.
Cognates
Cognate with Dutch haak (“hook”), German...

HALED.d: Past tense of HALE: Sound, entire, healthy; robust, not impaired.
HALED.e: From Northern Middle English hal, hale, variants of hole (“healthy; safe; whole”) (whence whole), from Old English hāl, from Proto-West Germanic *hail, from Proto-Germanic *hailaz (“whole; entire; healthy”). See whole for more.

HALES.d: Plural of HALE: Sound, entire, healthy; robust, not impaired.
HALES.e: From Northern Middle English hal, hale, variants of hole (“healthy; safe; whole”) (whence whole), from Old English hāl, from Proto-West Germanic *hail, from Proto-Germanic *hailaz (“whole; entire; healthy”). See whole for more.

HALLS.d: Plural of HALL: A corridor; a hallway.
HALLS.e:
Inherited from Middle English halle, from Old English heall (“hall, dwelling, house; palace, temple; law-court”), from Proto-West Germanic *hallu, from Proto-Germanic *hallō (“hall”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱel- (“to hide, conceal”).
Cognate with Scots hall, haw (“hall”), Dutc...

HALOS.d: Plural of HALO: A circular band of coloured light, visible around the sun or moon etc., caused by reflection and refraction of light by ice crystals in the atmosphere.
HALOS.e: From Latin halōs, from Ancient Greek ἅλως (hálōs, “threshing floor; disk; disk of the sun or moon; ring of light around the sun or moon”), of unknown origin. The threshing floor's circular threshold or oxen walking on it in a circle gave rise to the other meanings. Used in Englis...

HALTS.d: Plural of HALT: To limp; move with a limping gait.
HALTS.e: From Middle English halten, from Old English healtian (“to be lame, walk with a limp”), from Proto-West Germanic *haltōn, related to *halt. English usage in the sense of 'make a halt' is from the noun. Cognate with North Frisian halte, Swedish halta.

HAMES.d: Plural of HAME: shroud, a covering, skin, membrane.
HAMES.e: From Middle English hame, home, from Old English hama, homa (“a cover, skin”), from Proto-Germanic *hamô (“clothes, skirt”). Cognate with Old Norse hamr and its descendants, such as Danish ham (“skin, bladder, figure”), Danish hams (“shell, sleeve”).

HANDS.d: Plural of HAND: The part of the forelimb below the forearm or wrist in a human, and the corresponding part in many other animals.
HANDS.e:
From Middle English hond, hand, from Old English hand, from Proto-West Germanic *handu, from Proto-Germanic *handuz.
See also Dutch and Swedish hand (“hand”), Danish hånd, German Hand, West Frisian hân). Perhaps compare Old Swedish hinna (“to gain”), Gothic 𐍆𐍂𐌰-𐌷𐌹𐌽𐌸𐌰𐌽 (fra-hinþan...

HANGS.d: Plural of HANG: To be or remain suspended.
HANGS.e: From Middle English hangen, hongen, from a fusion of Old English hōn (“to hang, be hanging”, transitive verb) and hangian (“to hang, cause to hang”, intransitive verb), from Proto-West Germanic *hą̄han and *hangēn; also probably influenced by Old Norse hengja (“to suspend”) and h...

HANKS.d: Plural of HANK: A diminutive of the male given name Henry.

HARDS.d: Plural of HARD: Solid and firm.
HARDS.e:
From Middle English hard, from Old English heard, from Proto-West Germanic *hard(ī), from Proto-Germanic *harduz, from Proto-Indo-European *kort-ús, from *kret- (“strong, powerful”).
Cognates
Cognate with Yola hard (“hard”), West Frisian hurd (“hard”), Alemannic German hert (“har...

HARED.d: Past tense of HARE: Any of several plant-eating mammals of the genus Lepus, similar to a rabbit, but larger and with longer ears.
HARED.e:
From Middle English hare, from Old English hara (“hare”), from Proto-West Germanic *hasō ~ *haʀ-, from Proto-Germanic *hasô, from *haswaz (“grey”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱh₂s-én-.
