HOSED.d: Past tense of HOSE: A flexible tube conveying water or other fluid.
HOSED.e:
From Middle English hose (“leggings, hose”), from Old English hose, hosa (“hose, leggings”), from Proto-West Germanic *hosā, from Proto-Germanic *husǭ (“coverings, leggings, trousers”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewH- (“to cover”).
Cognate with West Frisian hoas (“hose”), Dutc...

HOSES.d: Plural of HOSE: A flexible tube conveying water or other fluid.
HOSES.e:
From Middle English hose (“leggings, hose”), from Old English hose, hosa (“hose, leggings”), from Proto-West Germanic *hosā, from Proto-Germanic *husǭ (“coverings, leggings, trousers”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewH- (“to cover”).
Cognate with West Frisian hoas (“hose”), Dutc...

HOSTS.d: Plural of HOST: One which receives or entertains a guest, socially, commercially, or officially.
HOSTS.e: From Middle English hoste, from Old French oste (French: hôte), from Latin hospitem, accusative of hospes (“a host, also a sojourner, visitor, guest; hence, a foreigner, a stranger”), from *hostipotis, an old compound of hostis and the root of potis, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰó...

HOURS.d: Plural of HOUR: A unit of time of one twenty-fourth of a day (sixty minutes).
HOURS.e: From Middle English houre, hour, oure, from Old French houre, from Latin hōra (“hour”), from Ancient Greek ὥρα (hṓra, “any time or period, whether of the year, month, or day”), from Proto-Indo-European *yóh₁r̥ (“year, season”). Akin to Old English ġēar (“year”). Doublet of hora a...

HOWES.d: Plural of HOWE: An English topographic surname from Middle English for someone who lived by a small hill.

HOWLS.d: Plural of HOWL: The protracted, mournful cry of a dog, wolf or other canid; also of other animals.
HOWLS.e:
From Middle English howlen, houlen, from Old English *hūlian, from Proto-West Germanic *hūilōn, from Proto-Germanic *hūwilōną, *hiuwilōną (“to howl”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *kū-, *kew- (“to howl, scream”). Likely of imitative origin.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian huul...

HUFFS.d: Plural of HUFF: A heavy breath; a grunt or sigh.
HUFFS.e: Probably an altered spelling of earlier *hough, represented by Scots hech (“to breathe hard, pant”). Compare also German hauchen (“to breathe”).

HULAS.d: Plural of HULA: A form of chant and dance, which was developed in the Hawaiian Islands by the Polynesians who originally settled there.

HULKS.d: Plural of HULK: A large ship used for transportation; (more generally) a large ship that is difficult to manoeuvre.
HULKS.e:
From Middle English hulk, hulke, holke (“hut; shed for hogs; type of ship; husk, pod, shell; large, clumsy person; a giant”) (probably reinforced by
Middle Dutch hulk, huelc, and Middle Low German hulk, holk, hollek (“freighter, cargo ship, barge”)), from Old English hulc (“light...

HULLS.d: Plural of HULL: The outer covering of a fruit or seed.
HULLS.e:
From Middle English hul, hulle, holle (“seed covering, hull of a ship”), from Old English hulu (“seed covering”), from Proto-Germanic *hul-, perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *ḱel- (“to cover, hide”); or possibly from Proto-Indo-European *kal- (“hard”).
Compare Dutch hul (“hood”),...

HUMPS.d: Plural of HUMP: A mound of earth.
HUMPS.e: Probably borrowed from Dutch homp (“hump, lump”) or Middle Low German hump (“heap, hill, stump”), from Old Saxon *hump (“hill, heap, thick piece”), from Proto-Germanic *humpaz (“hip, height”), from Proto-Indo-European *kumb- (“curved”). Compare Proto-Germanic *huppōną (“to hop”),...

HUNKS.d: Plural of HUNK: A large or dense piece of something.
HUNKS.e: Probably borrowed from West Flemish hunke (“hunk; chunk”), of obscure origin. Probably from an earlier *humke, *humpke, a diminutive related to Dutch homp (“hunk; lump”), English hump, equivalent to hump + -kin. The sense of an attractive man is recorded in Australian slang in 19...

HUNTS.d: Plural of HUNT: To find or search for an animal in the wild with the intention of killing the animal for its meat or for sport.
HUNTS.e: From Middle English hunten, from Old English huntian (“to hunt”), from Proto-West Germanic *huntōn (“to hunt, capture”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *ḱent- (“to catch, seize”). Related to Old High German hunda (“booty”), Gothic 𐌷𐌿𐌽𐌸𐍃 (hunþs, “body of captives”), Old English...

HURLS.d: Plural of HURL: To throw (something) with force.
HURLS.e: Inherited from Middle English hurlen, of onomatopoeic origin; compare hurry, hurtle.

HURTS.d: Plural of HURT: To cause (a person or animal) physical pain and/or injury.
HURTS.e: From Middle English hurten, hirten, hertan (“to injure, scathe, knock together”), from Old Northern French hurter ("to ram into, strike, collide with"; > Modern French heurter), perhaps from Frankish *hūrt (“a battering ram”), cognate with Welsh hwrdd (“ram”) and Cornish hordh (“...

HUSKS.d: Plural of HUSK: The dry, leafy or stringy exterior of certain vegetables or fruits, which must be removed before eating the meat inside.
HUSKS.e: From Middle English huske, husk (“husk”). Perhaps from Old English *husuc, *hosuc (“little covering, sheath”), diminutive of hosu (“pod, shell, husk”), from Proto-West Germanic *hosā, from Proto-Germanic *husǭ (“covering, shell, leggings”), from Proto-Indo-European *kawəs- / kawe...

HYMNS.d: Plural of HYMN: A song of praise or worship, especially a religious one.
HYMNS.e: From Middle English ymne, from Old English ymen (reinforced by Old French ymne), from Latin hymnus, borrowed from Ancient Greek ὕμνος (húmnos).

HYPED.d: Past tense of HYPE: Promotion or propaganda, especially exaggerated claims.

HYPES.d: Plural of HYPE: Promotion or propaganda, especially exaggerated claims.

HYPOS.d: Plural of HYPO: Melancholy; a fit of hypochondria; a morbid depression.
HYPOS.e: Clipping of various terms beginning with hypo-, from Ancient Greek ὑπό (hupó, “under”).

IAMBS.d: Plural of IAMB: A metrical foot in verse consisting of an unstressed syllable followed by a stressed syllable.
IAMBS.e: From French iambe in the mid-1800s, from Latin ïambus, from Ancient Greek ἴαμβος (íambos). Displaced iambus which shares the same classical origin.

ICIER.d: Comparative form of ICY: Pertaining to, resembling, or abounding in ice; cold; frosty.
ICIER.e: From ice + -y; cf. Old English īsiġ.

ICING.d: Present participle of ICE: Water in frozen (solid) form.
ICING.e:
From Middle English is, from Old English īs (“ice”), from Proto-West Germanic *īs, from Proto-Germanic *īsą (“ice”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁eyH- (“ice, frost”).
Cognates
Cognate with North Frisian is (“ice”), Saterland Frisian Ies (“ice”), West Frisian iis (“ice”), Alemannic...

ICONS.d: Plural of ICON: An image, symbol, picture, portrait, or other representation usually as an object of religious devotion.
ICONS.e: From Latin īcōn, from Ancient Greek εἰκών (eikṓn, “likeness, image, portrait”). Eastern Orthodox Church sense is attested from 1833. Computing sense first recorded in 1982.

IDEAS.d: Plural of IDEA: An abstract archetype of a given thing, compared to which real-life examples are seen as imperfect approximations; pure essence, as opposed to actual examples.
IDEAS.e: Borrowed from Latin idea (“a (Platonic) idea; archetype”), from Ancient Greek ἰδέα (idéa, “notion, pattern”), from εἴδω (eídō, “I see”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *weyd- (“to know; see”). Cognate with French idée. Doublet of idée. Related to idol, idolum, and eidolon.

IDLED.d: Past tense of IDLE: Empty, vacant.
IDLED.e: From Middle English idel, ydel, from Old English īdel, from Proto-West Germanic *īdal, from Proto-Germanic *īdalaz. Cognate with Dutch ijdel (“vain, meaningless”), ijl (“rareified, skinny”), iel (“thin, slender”); German Low German iedel (“vain, idle”); German eitel (“vain, conce...

IDLES.e: From Middle English idel, ydel, from Old English īdel, from Proto-West Germanic *īdal, from Proto-Germanic *īdalaz. Cognate with Dutch ijdel (“vain, meaningless”), ijl (“rareified, skinny”), iel (“thin, slender”); German Low German iedel (“vain, idle”); German eitel (“vain, conce...

IDOLS.d: Plural of IDOL: A graven image or representation of anything that is revered, or believed to convey spiritual power.
IDOLS.e: From Middle English ydole, from Old French idole, from Latin idolum, from Ancient Greek εἴδωλον (eídōlon, “image, idol”), from εἶδος (eîdos, “form”), from Proto-Indo-European *wéydos (“seeing, image”), from *weyd- (“to see”). Doublet of aidoru, eidolon, and idolum and related to ...

IMAGE.e: From Old French image, from Latin imāgō.

IMAMS.d: Plural of IMAM: One who leads the salat prayers in a mosque.

IMPED.d: Past tense of IMP: To engraft or plant (a plant or part of one, a sapling, etc.).
IMPED.e: From Middle English impen, ympen (“to plant; (figuratively) to bury; to graft; to add to, insert, put into, set in; to mend (a falcon’s feather) by attaching a new feather on to the broken stump”), from Old English impian, ġeimpian (“to graft”), from Proto-West Germanic *impōn (“...

IMPIS.d: Plural of IMPI: A group of Zulu (or other Bantu) warriors; a detachment of armed men.

INCAS.d: Plural of INCA: A member of the group of Quechuan peoples of highland Peru who established an empire from northern Ecuador to central Chile before the Spanish conquest.
INCAS.e: Borrowed from Spanish inca, from Classical Quechua inka (“emperor”).

INKED.d: Past tense of INK: A pigment (or dye)-based fluid used for writing, printing etc.
INKED.e: From Middle English ynke, from Old French enque, from Latin encaustum (“purple ink used by Roman emperors to sign documents”), from Ancient Greek ἔγκαυστον (énkauston, “burned-in”), from ἐν (en, “in”) + καίω (kaíō, “burn”). In this sense, displaced native Old English blæc (“ink”,...

INPUT.d: What is put in; data entered.

IOTAS.d: Plural of IOTA: The ninth letter of the Greek alphabet (Ι, ι).
IOTAS.e:
From Ancient Greek ἰῶτα (iôta), ultimately from Proto-Semitic *yad- (“hand”). Doublet of jot and yodh.
Sense “jot, small quantity” in reference to a phrase in the New Testament: ”one iote or one title, shall in no wise passe from the law”, iota being the smallest letter of the Gr...

IRKED.d: Past tense of IRK: to irritate; annoy; bother
IRKED.e: Inherited from Middle English irken (“to tire, grow weary”), from Old Norse yrkja (“to work”), from Proto-Germanic *wurkijaną (“to work”), from Proto-Indo-European *werǵ- (“to work”). Cognate with Icelandic yrkja (“to compose”), Swedish yrka (“to urge, argue”), Old English wyrċan...

IRONS.d: Plural of IRON: A common, inexpensive metal, silvery grey when untarnished, that rusts, is attracted by magnets, and is used in making steel: a chemical element having atomic number 26 and symbol Fe.
IRONS.e:
From Middle English iren, from Old English īsern, īsærn, īren, īsen, from Proto-West Germanic *īsarn, from Proto-Germanic *īsarną (“iron”), from Proto-Celtic *īsarnom (“iron”), a derivation from Proto-Indo-European *h₁ésh₂r̥ (“blood”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots airn, ern (“iron...

ISLED.d: Past tense of ISLE: An island, usually very small. Compare with islet.
ISLED.e: From Middle English ile, yle (with s added, similar to English island), borrowed from Old French ille, idle, isle, from Latin insula. Not related to island. Doublet of insula.

ISLES.d: Plural of ISLE: An island, usually very small. Compare with islet.
ISLES.e: From Middle English ile, yle (with s added, similar to English island), borrowed from Old French ille, idle, isle, from Latin insula. Not related to island. Doublet of insula.

ISSUE.d: A topic; a problem; to distribute.
ISSUE.e: From Old French issue, from Latin exīre (to go out).

ITEMS.d: Plural of ITEM: A distinct physical object.
ITEMS.e: From Middle English item, from Latin item (“also; in the same manner”). The present English meaning derives from a usage in lists, where the first entry would begin in primis (“firstly”) or imprimis, and the other entries with item (“also, moreover”). Later, the members of lists ...

IVIED.d: Past tense of IVY: Any of several woody, climbing, or trailing evergreen plants of the genus Hedera.
IVIED.e: From Middle English ivi, from Old English īfiġ, from Proto-West Germanic *ibig, *ibag, *ibah, from Proto-Germanic *ibahs (compare West Flemish iefte, Low German Eiloov, Ieloof, German Efeu), from Proto-Indo-European *(h₁)ebʰ- (compare Welsh efwr (“black elder”), Ancient Greek ἴφυ...

IVIES.d: Plural of IVY: Any of several woody, climbing, or trailing evergreen plants of the genus Hedera.
IVIES.e: From Middle English ivi, from Old English īfiġ, from Proto-West Germanic *ibig, *ibag, *ibah, from Proto-Germanic *ibahs (compare West Flemish iefte, Low German Eiloov, Ieloof, German Efeu), from Proto-Indo-European *(h₁)ebʰ- (compare Welsh efwr (“black elder”), Ancient Greek ἴφυ...

IXIAS.d: Plural of IXIA: Any of the genus Ixia of cormous plants native to South Africa.

JACKS.d: Plural of JACK: A coarse medieval coat of defence, especially one made of leather.
JACKS.e: Inherited from Middle English jakke, from Anglo-Norman jacke, Middle French jaque, jacque, from jacques (“peasant”), from the proper name Jacques. Compare jacquerie.

JADED.d: Past tense of JADE: A semiprecious stone, either nephrite or jadeite, generally green or white in color, often used for carving figurines.
JADED.e: Borrowed from French le jade, rebracketing of earlier l'éjade (“jade”), from Spanish piedra de ijada (“flank stone”), via Vulgar Latin *iliata from Latin ilia (“flank”). (Jade was thought to cure pains in the side.)

JADES.d: Plural of JADE: A semiprecious stone, either nephrite or jadeite, generally green or white in color, often used for carving figurines.
JADES.e: Borrowed from French le jade, rebracketing of earlier l'éjade (“jade”), from Spanish piedra de ijada (“flank stone”), via Vulgar Latin *iliata from Latin ilia (“flank”). (Jade was thought to cure pains in the side.)

JAILS.d: Plural of JAIL: A place or institution for the confinement of persons held against their will in lawful custody or detention, especially (in US usage) a place where people are held for minor offenses or with reference to some future judicial proceeding.
JAILS.e: From Middle English gayole, gaylle, gaille, gayle, gaile, from Old French gaiole, gayolle, gaole, from Medieval Latin gabiola, from Late Latin caveola (“small cage, cell”), a diminutive of Latin cavea (“cavity, coop, cage”). Doublet of caveola and related to cage. More at cajole....

JAMBS.d: Plural of JAMB: Either of the vertical components that form the side of an opening in a wall, such as that of a door frame, window frame, or fireplace.
JAMBS.e: From Middle English jambe, jaumbe, from Old French jambe (“leg”), from Late Latin gamba (“hock, shank, leg, thigh”), from Ancient Greek καμπή (kampḗ, “turning post, bend or flexure”). Doublet of gam, gamb, gamba, and jambe.

JAPED.d: Past tense of JAPE: A joke or quip.
JAPED.e:
From Middle English japen (“to deceive, play tricks on; act foolishly, joke; have sex with”), of uncertain origin, but perhaps combining Old French japer (“to bark, howl, scream; chatter, gossip”) with gaber (“to mock, deride”).
See also gab, Old Occitan japar, jaupar (“to bark, ...

JAPES.d: Plural of JAPE: A joke or quip.
JAPES.e:
From Middle English japen (“to deceive, play tricks on; act foolishly, joke; have sex with”), of uncertain origin, but perhaps combining Old French japer (“to bark, howl, scream; chatter, gossip”) with gaber (“to mock, deride”).
See also gab, Old Occitan japar, jaupar (“to bark, ...

JARED.d: Past tense of JAR: An earthenware container, either with two or no handles, for holding oil, water, wine, etc., or used for burial.
JARED.e: Inherited from Middle English jarre (“jar”), from Medieval Latin jarra, or from Middle French jarre (“liquid measure”) (from Old French jare; modern French jarre (“earthenware jar”)), or from Spanish jarra, jarro (“jug, pitcher; mug, stein”), all from Arabic جَرَّة (jarra, “earth...

JARLS.d: Plural of JARL: A medieval Scandinavian nobleman, especially in Norway and Denmark.
JARLS.e: From Old Norse jarl, from Proto-Norse ᛖᚱᛁᛚᚨᛉ (erilaʀ). Cognates include Old English eorl. Doublet of earl and eorl.

JATOS.d: Plural of JATO: An auxiliary jet engine in a detachable unit that provides extra power for the takeoff of an aircraft

JAWED.d: Past tense of JAW: One of the bones, usually bearing teeth, which form the framework of the mouth.
JAWED.e:
From Middle English jawe/jowe (“jaw; sides of the lower face”, 14th century), the further origin of which is disputed. Either:
* From Anglo-Norman jowe, from Old French joe (“cheek; jaw”), from Vulgar Latin *ga(v)ota (“cheek”), of uncertain further origin.
** It has been objected...

JEANS.e: From the Middle English Gene (“Genoa”), from the Old French Jannes. Bleu de Gênes (“Genovese blue”) was a blue dye made in Genoa used to tint the denim cloth produced in Nîmes (de Nîmes). Doublet of Genoa and Geneva and distantly related to knee.

JEEPS.d: Plural of JEEP: A vehicle (of a particular brand) suitable for rough terrain.

JEERS.d: Plural of JEER: A mocking remark or reflection.
JEERS.e: From earlier gyr, probably from Dutch gieren (“to roar with laughter, laugh loudly”) (related to German gieren (“to gape, snap”)); or from Dutch gekscheren (“to jeer”, literally “to shear the fool”), from gek (“a fool”) (see geck) + scheren (“to shear”) (see shear (verb)). The OE...

JELLS.d: Plural of JELL: a jelly or gel
JELLS.e: A back-formation from jelly; reinforced by gel. Compare obsolete geal.

JERKS.d: Plural of JERK: A sudden, often uncontrolled movement, especially of the human body.
JERKS.e: Probably from Middle English yerk (“sudden motion”) and Middle English yerkid (“tightly pulled”), from Old English ġearc (“ready, active, quick”) and Old English ġearcian (“to prepare, make ready, procure, furnish, supply”). Cognate with Scots yerk (“to jerk”). Related also to En...

JESTS.d: Plural of JEST: An act performed for amusement; a joke.
JESTS.e: From Middle English geste (“idle tale”), from Old French geste (“acts, exploits”), from Latin gesta (“acts, deeds”). Doublet of gest.

JIBED.d: Past tense of JIBE: A facetious or insulting remark; a jeer, a taunt.
JIBED.e:
Uncertain; possibly from Old French giber (“to engage in horseplay; to play roughly in sport”). Compare English jib (“usually of a horse: to stop and refuse to go forward”), Old Norse geipa (“to talk nonsense”).
The noun is derived from the verb.

JIBES.d: Plural of JIBE: A facetious or insulting remark; a jeer, a taunt.
JIBES.e:
Uncertain; possibly from Old French giber (“to engage in horseplay; to play roughly in sport”). Compare English jib (“usually of a horse: to stop and refuse to go forward”), Old Norse geipa (“to talk nonsense”).
The noun is derived from the verb.

JIFFS.d: Plural of JIFF: A jiffy; a moment; a short time.

JILTS.d: Plural of JILT: A woman who readily casts aside her lover.
JILTS.e: Contraction of jillet (“a giddy girl, a jill-flirt”).

JINKS.d: Plural of JINK: A quick evasive turn.
JINKS.e: Origin uncertain. The Oxford English Dictionary suggests onomatopoeia for motion. Attested since the 18th century. Compare unnasalised dialectal jick (“to avoid with a sudden jerk of the body, elude”).

JINNS.d: Plural of JINN: A human-like spiritual or immaterial being, as opposed to al-ins (people), often invisible but able to manifest in form and also inhabit people or animals; origin of the genie of Western literature, film etc.
JINNS.e: Derived from Arabic جِنّ (jinn, collective noun) (singular جِنِّيّ (jinniyy)).

JIVED.d: Past tense of JIVE: To deceive; to be deceptive.
JIVED.e: Unknown. Slang attested in African-American and rural American culture. Frequently used to imply lying, verbal deception or trickery. Has a possible historical antecedent in gyve (“shackle”). Alternatively, of African origin, compare Wolof jev, jeu (“to talk about someone absent,...

JIVES.d: Plural of JIVE: To deceive; to be deceptive.
JIVES.e: Unknown. Slang attested in African-American and rural American culture. Frequently used to imply lying, verbal deception or trickery. Has a possible historical antecedent in gyve (“shackle”). Alternatively, of African origin, compare Wolof jev, jeu (“to talk about someone absent,...

JOCKS.d: Plural of JOCK: A common man.
JOCKS.e: From Jock, a Scottish hypocoristic form of John (compare Jack).

JOEYS.d: Plural of JOEY: The immature young of a marsupial, notably a junior kangaroo, but also a young wallaby, koala, etc.
JOEYS.e: Unknown. Older and more general sources state that joey comes from an Australian Aboriginal language (cited as joè), but newer sources that focus on Australian English and Aboriginal languages say the origin is unknown. The Australian National Dictionary includes a sense of “youn...

JOHNS.d: Plural of JOHN: A prostitute's client.
JOHNS.e: From the male given name John (q.v.), whose ubiquity led to extensive use of the name in generic contexts. Its use for toilets derives from John and Cousin John, which both probably relate to jacques and jakes, used in equivalent senses by the British and Irish.

JOINS.d: Plural of JOIN: To connect or combine into one; to put together.
JOINS.e: From Middle English joinen, joynen, joignen, from Old French joindre, juindre, jungre, from Latin iungō (“join, yoke”, verb), from Proto-Indo-European *yewg- (“to join, unite”). Cognate with Old English iucian, iugian, ġeocian, ġyċċan (“to join; yoke”). More at yoke.

JOKED.d: Past tense of JOKE: An amusing story.
JOKED.e: From Latin iocus (“joke, jest, pastime”), from Proto-Italic *jokos (“word, (playful?) saying”), from Proto-Indo-European *yokos (“word, utterance”), from ultimate root Proto-Indo-European *yek- (“to speak, utter”) (of which distant cognates include Proto-Celtic *yextis (“language...

JOKES.d: Plural of JOKE: An amusing story.
JOKES.e: From Latin iocus (“joke, jest, pastime”), from Proto-Italic *jokos (“word, (playful?) saying”), from Proto-Indo-European *yokos (“word, utterance”), from ultimate root Proto-Indo-European *yek- (“to speak, utter”) (of which distant cognates include Proto-Celtic *yextis (“language...

JOLTS.d: Plural of JOLT: To push or shake abruptly and roughly.
JOLTS.e: Perhaps from joll (“to knock, strike”) + -t (frequentative suffix).

JONES.e: From Welsh, meaning son of John.

JOWLS.d: Plural of JOWL: The jaw, jawbone; especially one of the lateral parts of the mandible.
JOWLS.e: From Middle English jawle, chawl, chavel (“jaw, jawbone”), from Old English ċeafl (“jaw, cheek”), from Proto-West Germanic *kafl (“jaw, cheek”). The modern form (for expected chavel, chawl; still found dialectally) is influenced by jaw, which it is a partial doublet of.

JOYED.d: Past tense of JOY: A feeling of extreme happiness or cheerfulness, especially related to the acquisition or expectation of something good.
JOYED.e: The noun is from Middle English joye, borrowed from Old French joie, from Late Latin gaudia, neuter plural (mistaken as feminine singular) of Latin gaudium (“joy”), from gaudēre (“to be glad, rejoice”). Doublet of jo and gaudy (“Oxford college reunion”). Displaced native Old Engl...

JUDGE.d: A person who presides over a court; to form an opinion.
JUDGE.e: From Old French juge, from Latin iūdex.

JUDOS.d: Plural of JUDO: A Japanese martial art and sport adapted from jujutsu.
JUDOS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 柔(じゅう)道(どう) (jūdō, literally “the soft way”).

JUICE.e: From Old French jus, from Latin iūs (broth).

JUMPS.d: Plural of JUMP: To propel oneself rapidly upward, downward and/or in any horizontal direction such that momentum causes the body to become airborne.
JUMPS.e: From Middle English jumpen (“to walk quickly, run, jump”), probably of Middle Low German or North Germanic origin, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *gumpōną ~ *gumbōną (“to hop, skip, bounce”), an iterative verb. The OED suggests an imitative origin. Related to jumble. In the sense...

JUNKS.d: Plural of JUNK: Miscellaneous items of little value, especially discarded or unwanted items.
JUNKS.e: From earlier meaning "old refuse from boats and ships", from Middle English junk, jounke, jonk, joynk (“an old cable or rope”, nautical term), sometimes cut into bits and used as caulking; of uncertain origin; perhaps related to join, joint, juncture. Often compared to Middle Eng...

JUSTS.d: Plural of JUST: Factually right, correct; factual.
JUSTS.e: From Middle English juste, from Old French juste, from Latin iūstus (“just, lawful, rightful, true, due, proper, moderate”), from Proto-Italic *jowestos, related to Latin iūs (“law, right”); ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *h₂yew-. Compare Scots juist (“just”), Saterland Fris...

JUTES.d: Plural of JUTE: The coarse, strong fibre of the East Indian plants, Corchorus olitorius and Corchorus capsularis, used to make mats, paper, gunny cloth etc.
JUTES.e: Borrowed from Bengali ঝুট (jhuṭ). Likely related to Ukrainian джгут (džhut) and Russian жгут (žgut).

KADIS.d: Plural of KADI: Alternative spelling of qadi, Islamic judge, particularly (historical) in Ottoman contexts where they initially oversaw local administration as well as Islamic law.
KADIS.e: From Ottoman Turkish قاضی (kadı), from Arabic قَاضِي (⁧qāḍī⁩), and from Arabic directly.

KAILS.d: Plural of KAIL: Alternative form of kale.

KAKAS.d: Plural of KAKA: Any of four taxa of birds in the genus Nestor in the parrot family confined to New Zealand and adjacent islands.

KALES.d: Plural of KALE: An edible plant, similar to cabbage, with curled leaves that do not form a dense head (Brassica oleracea var. acephala)
KALES.e: From Northern Middle English cale, cal (Southern col), from Old English cāl, cāul, cāwel, from Latin caulis. Compare Icelandic kál (“cabbage”), German Kohl (“cabbage”). Doublet of caulis, cole, and gobi.

KAMES.d: Plural of KAME: A round hill or short ridge of sand or gravel deposited by a melting glacier.
KAMES.e: From Scots, from Middle English cambe (“comb”).

KANAS.d: Plural of KANA: The hiragana and katakana syllabaries. These are made up of characters that represent individual syllables, which are used to write Japanese words and particles. Kana are derived from kanji.
KANAS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 仮名(かな) (kana, “phonetic character”, literally “borrowed character”, from the way that kana were originally Chinese characters "borrowed" for their phonetic values).

KAONS.d: Plural of KAON: any of four unstable subatomic particles, mesons, they are a combination of a strange quark or antiquark and either an up or down quark or antiquark

KARTS.e: Short for go-kart, an alteration of go-cart.

KAYOS.e: Respelling of the initial letters KO.

KECKS.d: Plural of KECK: To heave or retch as if to vomit.

KEEKS.d: Plural of KEEK: To peek; peep.
KEEKS.e:
From Middle English kyken, kiken, keken (“to look, peep”), probably from Middle Dutch kiken, kieken or Middle Low German kîken (“to look, peep”), from Old Saxon *kīkan (“to look”), from Proto-West Germanic *kīkan, from Proto-Germanic *kīkaną (“to look”).
Cognate with Dutch kijken...

KEELS.d: Plural of KEEL: A large beam along the underside of a ship’s hull from bow to stern.
KEELS.e: From Middle English kele, from Old Norse kjǫlr, itself from Proto-Germanic *keluz, of uncertain origin. Displaced Old English ċēol from a related root. Distantly related to kile.

KEENS.d: Plural of KEEN: Often with a prepositional phrase, or with to and an infinitive: showing a quick and ardent responsiveness or willingness; eager, enthusiastic, interested.
KEENS.e:
From Middle English kene (“bold, brave, sharp”), from Old English cēne (“keen, fierce, bold, brave, warlike, powerful; learned, clever, wise”), from Proto-Germanic *kōniz (“knowledgeable, skilful, experienced, clever, capable”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃- (“to know”).
Cogna...

KEEPS.d: Plural of KEEP: To continue in (a course or mode of action); to not intermit or fall from; to uphold or maintain.
KEEPS.e: From Middle English kepen (“to keep, guard, look after, watch”), from Old English cēpan (“to seize, hold, observe”), from Proto-West Germanic *kōpijan, from Proto-Germanic *kōpijaną (“to look, heed, watch, observe”) (compare West Frisian kypje (“to look”)), from Proto-Indo-Europe...

KELPS.d: Plural of KELP: Any of several large brown algae seaweeds (order Laminariales).
KELPS.e: From Middle English culp, culpe, of uncertain origin; possibly from Old English *colba, *colfa, from Proto-West Germanic *kolbō (“bulb, cob”), from Proto-Germanic *kulbaz (“round object, club”). Compare Middle High German kolbe (“clublike plant”), Old Norse kolfr (“bulb of a plan...

KELTS.d: Plural of KELT: Obsolete spelling of Celt.

KEMPS.d: Plural of KEMP: A coarse or bristly hair, whisker; (in the plural) knotty hairs that will not felt.
KEMPS.e: From Middle English kempe (“coarse hairs”), from Old English cenep (“moustache; bit (of a bridle, bristling with points)”), from Proto-West Germanic *kanip, from Proto-Germanic *kanipaz (“beard, moustache, whiskers”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵénus (“jaw”). Related to chin.

KENOS.d: Plural of KENO: A gambling game, a variety of lotto, played with balls or knobs, numbered, and cards also numbered.
KENOS.e: From French quine, with reference to a set of five winning lottery numbers.

KEPIS.d: Plural of KEPI: A cap with a flat circular top and a visor, particularly associated with French uniforms.
KEPIS.e: From French képi, from Switzerland German Käppi, diminutive of Kappe, from Middle High German kappe, from Old High German kappa, from Latin cappa. Akin to English cap.

KERBS.d: Plural of KERB: Alternative spelling of curb.
KERBS.e: From curb (“raised border or frame”) [from mid-17th c.]. Doublet of curve.

KERFS.d: Plural of KERF: The act of cutting or carving something; a stroke or slice.
KERFS.e: From Middle English kerf, kirf, kyrf, from Old English cyrf (“an act of cutting, a cutting off; a cutting instrument”), from Proto-West Germanic *kurbi, from Proto-Germanic *kurbiz (“a cut; notch; clipping”), from Proto-Indo-European *gerbʰ- (“to scratch”). Cognate with Saterland...

KERNS.d: Plural of KERN: A corn; grain; kernel.
KERNS.e: From Middle English curn, cooren, variant forms of Middle English corn, see English corn and also Dutch kern, Old High German kerno, cherno, Middle High German kerne, kern, German Kern (“core, kernel”), Old Norse kjarni, Icelandic kjarni, Danish kjerne, Swedish kärna (“core, kern...

KEYED.d: Past tense of KEY: An object designed to open and close a lock.
KEYED.e: From Middle English keye, kaye, keiȝe, from Old English cǣġ (“key, solution, experiment”) (whence also Scots key and kay (“key”)), of uncertain origin. The only sure cognates are Saterland Frisian Koai (“key”), West Frisian kaai (“key”), and North Frisian kai, koie (“key”). Possi...

KHANS.d: Plural of KHAN: A ruler over various Turkic and Mongol peoples in the Middle Ages.
KHANS.e: Via late Middle English can, chan from Old French chan, from Medieval Latin chanis, from Turkic *qan, contraction of *qaɣan. Cognate with Old Turkic 𐰴𐰍𐰣 (qaɣan), and Mongolian хаан (xaan), possibly from Rouran. Sense 1 (ruler in the Middle Ages) after Genghis Khan, from Middle Mo...

KIBES.d: Plural of KIBE: A chilblain (often ulcerated), especially on the heel of the foot (also afflictive to some animals); a cold sore or blister.
KIBES.e:
Origin unknown, but first attested in Middle English.
suggested origins and context
Attestations in Shakespeare's time seem to suggest it was intended as mildly vulgar (compare zit) and metaphorical; see more at this Open Literature article, which claims Welsh as most probable or...

KICKS.d: Plural of KICK: To strike or hit with the foot or other extremity of the leg.
KICKS.e: From Middle English kyken (“to strike out with the foot”), from Old Norse kikna (“to sink at the knees”) and keikja (“to bend backwards”) (compare Old Norse keikr (“bent backwards, the belly jutting forward”)), from Proto-Germanic *kaikaz (“bent backwards”), of uncertain origin. ...

KIERS.d: Plural of KIER: A bleaching vat.
KIERS.e: Borrowed from Old Norse ker (whence also Icelandic ker (“tub”)).

KILLS.d: Plural of KILL: To put to death; to extinguish the life of.
KILLS.e:
From Middle English killen, kyllen, cüllen (“to strike, beat, cut”), of obscure origin. Cognate with Scots kele, keil (“to kill”).
* Perhaps from unattested Old English *cyllan, from Proto-West Germanic *kwulljan, from Proto-Germanic *kwuljaną, from Proto-Indo-European *gʷelH- (“...

KILNS.d: Plural of KILN: An oven or furnace or a heated chamber, for the purpose of hardening, burning, calcining or drying anything; for example, firing ceramics, curing or preserving tobacco, or drying grain.
KILNS.e:
From Middle English kilne, from Old English cyln, cylen, cylin (“large oven, kiln”), from Latin culīna (“kitchen, kitchen stove”).
Middle English -ln(e) usually becomes modern -ll as in mill. The pronunciation /kɪln/ may be based on dialects in which this simplification did not t...

KILOS.d: Plural of KILO: Clipping of kilogram.

KILTS.d: Plural of KILT: To gather up (skirts) around the body.
KILTS.e: From Middle English kilten (“to tuck up, gird”), apparently from North Germanic, ultimately from Old Norse kelta, kjalta (“skirt; lap”). Perhaps from Proto-Germanic *kelt-, *kelþǭ, *kilþį̄ (“womb”), from Proto-Indo-European *gelt- (“round body; child”). Cognate with Danish kilte ...

KINDS.d: Plural of KIND: A type, race or category; a group of entities that have common characteristics such that they may be grouped together.
KINDS.e: From Middle English kynde, kinde, from Old English cynd, ġecynd (“inherent nature, disposition, kind, gender, generation, race”), from Proto-West Germanic *kundi, from Proto-Germanic *kinþiz, related to Proto-Germanic *kunją (“race, kin”) and Old English cennan (“to bear, give bi...

KINES.d: Plural of KINE: plural of cow
KINES.e: Inherited from Middle English kyn, kyne, equivalent to ky + -en (plural ending), a double plural.

KINGS.d: Plural of KING: A male monarch; a man who heads a monarchy; in an absolute monarchy, the supreme ruler of his nation.
KINGS.e:
From Middle English king, kyng, from Old English cyng, cyning (“king”), from Proto-West Germanic *kuning, from Proto-Germanic *kuningaz, *kunungaz (“king”), equivalent to kin + -ing. Doublet of cyning and knez.
Cognate with Scots keeng (“king”), North Frisian köning (“king”), Wes...

KINKS.d: Plural of KINK: To laugh loudly.
KINKS.e: From Middle English kinken, kynken, from Old English *cincian (attested in cincung), from Proto-West Germanic *kinkōn, from Proto-Germanic *kinkōną (“to laugh”), from Proto-Indo-European *gang- (“to mock, jeer, deride”), related to Old English canc (“jeering, scorn, derision”). C...

KINOS.d: Plural of KINO: A botanical gum produced by various trees and other plants, particularly bloodwood species of eucalypts (Angophora, Corymbia, Eucalyptus), Butea, and Pterocarpus, used in tanning and dyeing and as an astringent in medicine.
KINOS.e: 18th century. Perhaps borrowed from Mandingo cano, or from a language of the East Indies.

KIRKS.e: Inherited from Northern Middle English kyrke, from either Old Norse kirkja or Old English ċiriċe. Doublet of church.

KISTS.d: Plural of KIST: simple past and past participle of kiss.

KITED.d: Past tense of KITE: A bird of prey of the family Accipitridae.
KITED.e: The noun is from Middle English kyte, kīte, kete (“a kite endemic to Europe, especially the red kite (Milvus milvus)”), from Old English cȳta (“kite; bittern”), from Proto-West Germanic *kūtijō, diminutive of Proto-Germanic *kūts (“bird of prey”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewH-d...

KITES.d: Plural of KITE: A bird of prey of the family Accipitridae.
KITES.e: The noun is from Middle English kyte, kīte, kete (“a kite endemic to Europe, especially the red kite (Milvus milvus)”), from Old English cȳta (“kite; bittern”), from Proto-West Germanic *kūtijō, diminutive of Proto-Germanic *kūts (“bird of prey”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewH-d...

KITHS.d: Plural of KITH: Friends and acquaintances.
KITHS.e: From Middle English kith (“kinsmen, relations”), from Old English cȳþþ, cȳþþu (“kinship, kinsfolk, relations”), from Proto-Germanic *kunþiþō (“knowledge, acquaintance”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃- (“to know”). Cognate with Old High German kundida (“kith”), kundī (“knowledge...

KIWIS.d: Plural of KIWI: A flightless bird of the order Apterygiformes native to New Zealand.

KNAPS.d: Plural of KNAP: To break (something) into small pieces with a cracking sound; to fragment, to smash; also, to break (something) apart sharply; to snap.
KNAPS.e: The verb is derived from Late Middle English knappen (“to strike (something)”); further etymology uncertain, probably related to Middle Dutch knappen, cnappen (“to break (something) with a sharp sound, snap; to crack or crackle”) (modern Dutch knappen), probably ultimately onomat...

KNARS.d: Plural of KNAR: A knot or burl in a tree; a knurl, a gnarl.
KNARS.e:
From Middle English knarre (“a crag; twisted rock; knot in wood”), probably from Old English *cnearra, which could be related to cnotta.
Cognate with Dutch knar, knor (“gnarl, knot”), German Low German Knurre, Knur (“knot in wood”), German Knorren (“knot in wood”). Related also t...

KNEES.d: Plural of KNEE: In humans, the joint or the region of the joint in the middle part of the leg between the thigh and the shank.
KNEES.e:
From Middle English kne, from Old English cnēow, from Proto-West Germanic *kneu, from Proto-Germanic *knewą, from Proto-Indo-European *ǵnéw-o-m, a thematic derivative of *ǵónu.
See also West Frisian knibbel, Low German Knee, Knie, Dutch knie, German Knie, Danish knæ, Norwegian kn...

KNIFE.d: A cutting instrument with a blade.
KNIFE.e: From Old English cnīf, from Old Norse knífr.

KNITS.d: Plural of KNIT: To turn thread or yarn into a piece of fabric by forming loops that are pulled through each other. This can be done by hand with needles or by machine.
KNITS.e:
From Middle English knytten, from Old English cnyttan (“to fasten, tie, bind, knit; add, append”), from Proto-West Germanic *knuttijan, from Proto-Germanic *knutjaną, *knuttijaną (“to make knots, knit”).
Cognate with Low German knütten and Old Norse knýta (whence Danish knytte, N...

KNOBS.d: Plural of KNOB: A rounded protuberance, especially one arising from a flat surface; a fleshy lump or caruncle.
KNOBS.e: From Middle English knobbe, of unknown origin but probably from Scandinavian or German source. Compare Middle Dutch knobbe, cnoppe, Middle Low German knobbe (“knob; knot in wood”), knubbe, knop, Old Frisian knopp, knapp, Old High German knopf, German Knopf (“button”), Old Norse k...

KNOPS.d: Plural of KNOP: A knob, usually ornamental
KNOPS.e: From Middle English knop, from Middle Low German and Middle Dutch knoppe, from Proto-Germanic *knuppô, *knuppaz, *knappô, which is perhaps related to *knappō (“knob, boy”). Possible doublet of knave and knob.

KNOTS.d: Plural of KNOT: A looping of a piece of string or of any other long, flexible material that cannot be untangled without passing one or both ends of the material through its loops.
KNOTS.e:
From Middle English knotte, from Old English cnotta, from Proto-West Germanic *knottō, from Proto-Germanic *knuttô, *knudô (“knot”); probably ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *gnod- (“to bind”).
See also Old High German knoto (German Knoten, Dutch knot, Low German Knütte; also...

KNOWS.d: Plural of KNOW: To perceive the truth or factuality of; to be certain of; to be certain that.
KNOWS.e:
From Middle English knowen, from Old English cnāwan (“to know, perceive, recognise”), from Proto-West Germanic *knāan, from Proto-Germanic *knēaną (“to know”), from Proto-Indo-European *ǵneh₃- (“to know”).
Cognates
from Indo-European: Latin gnoscō, Latin cognoscō (Spanish conocer...

KOANS.d: Plural of KOAN: A story about a Zen master and his student, sometimes like a riddle, other times like a fable or parable, which has become an object of Zen study, and which, when meditated upon, may unlock mechanisms in the Zen student’s mind leading to satori.
KOANS.e: From Japanese 公案 (kōan), which was from Chinese 公案 (gōng'àn, “official business”).

KOELS.d: Plural of KOEL: A cuckoo of the genus Eudynamys, native to Asia, Australia and the Pacific.
KOELS.e: From Hindi कोयल (koyal), from Sanskrit कोकिल (kokila) which is of onomatopoeic origin.

KOLAS.d: Plural of KOLA: A tree, genus Cola, bearing large brown seeds ("nuts") that are the source of cola extract.
KOLAS.e: Presumably from a West African language. Compare Hausa gōr̃ò, Bambara goro, Temne kola, Mandinka kolo (“kola nut”).

KOTOS.d: Plural of KOTO: A Japanese stringed instrument having numerous strings, usually seven or thirteen, that are stretched over a convex wooden sounding board and are plucked with three plectra, worn on the thumb, index finger, and middle finger of one hand.

KUDUS.d: Plural of KUDU: A large, striped, African antelope of the species Tragelaphus imberbis (lesser kudu) or Tragelaphus strepsiceros (greater kudu).
KUDUS.e: Ultimately Khoekhoe kudu-b, through Afrikaans koedoe and French koudou.

LACED.d: Past tense of LACE: A light fabric containing patterns of holes, usually built up from a single thread.
LACED.e: From Middle English lace, laace, las, from Old French las, from Vulgar Latin *laceum, based on Latin laqueus. Doublet of lasso.

LACES.d: Plural of LACE: A light fabric containing patterns of holes, usually built up from a single thread.
LACES.e: From Middle English lace, laace, las, from Old French las, from Vulgar Latin *laceum, based on Latin laqueus. Doublet of lasso.

LACKS.d: Plural of LACK: A deficiency or need (of something desirable or necessary); an absence, want, dearth.
LACKS.e: From Middle English lack, lakke, lak, from Old English *læc (“deficiency, lack, want”), from Proto-West Germanic *lak, from Proto-Germanic *laką, *lakaz (“slackness”), from Proto-Germanic *lakaz (“limp, slack, loose, low”), related to *lak(k)ōną (“to blame, reproach”), from Proto...

LADED.d: Past tense of LADE: To fill or load (related to cargo or a shipment).
LADED.e: From Middle English laden, from Old English hladan and Old English hleadan, from Proto-West Germanic *hlaþan, from Proto-Germanic *hlaþaną (“to load”), from Proto-Indo-European *kleh₂- (“to put, lay out”).

LADES.d: Plural of LADE: To fill or load (related to cargo or a shipment).
LADES.e: From Middle English laden, from Old English hladan and Old English hleadan, from Proto-West Germanic *hlaþan, from Proto-Germanic *hlaþaną (“to load”), from Proto-Indo-European *kleh₂- (“to put, lay out”).

LAICS.d: Plural of LAIC: A layperson as opposed to a cleric, i.e. not a member of the clergy.
LAICS.e: From French laïque, from Latin lāicus (“common people”), from Ancient Greek λαός (laós). Doublet of lay.

LAIRS.d: Plural of LAIR: A place inhabited by a wild animal, often a cave or a hole in the ground.
LAIRS.e: From Middle English leir, leire, lair, lare, from Old English leġer (“couch, bed”), from Proto-Germanic *legrą, from Proto-Indo-European *legʰ-.

LAKED.d: Past tense of LAKE: A large, landlocked stretch of water or similar liquid.
LAKED.e:
Arose from a conflation of
* Middle English lake (“small stream of running water, pool, lake”), from Old English lacu (“stream, pool, pond, lake”), from Proto-West Germanic *laku, from Proto-Germanic *lakō (“stream, pool, body of water", originally "a place where water collects”)...

LAKES.d: Plural of LAKE: A large, landlocked stretch of water or similar liquid.
LAKES.e:
Arose from a conflation of
* Middle English lake (“small stream of running water, pool, lake”), from Old English lacu (“stream, pool, pond, lake”), from Proto-West Germanic *laku, from Proto-Germanic *lakō (“stream, pool, body of water", originally "a place where water collects”)...

LAMAS.d: Plural of LAMA: A master of Tibetan Buddhism.

LAMBS.d: Plural of LAMB: A young sheep.
LAMBS.e:
From Middle English lamb, from Old English lamb, from Proto-West Germanic *lamb, from Proto-Germanic *lambaz, probably from Proto-Indo-European *h₁l̥h₁onbʰos, enlargement of *h₁elh₁én, ultimately from *h₁el-.
See also Dutch lam, German Lamm, Bavarian Lamperl, Danish lam, Swedish ...

LAMED.d: Past tense of LAME: Unable to walk properly because of a problem with one's feet or legs.
LAMED.e: From Middle English lame, from Old English lama (“lame”), from Proto-West Germanic *lam, from Proto-Germanic *lamaz (“lame”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃lemH- (“to tire; to break”).

LAMES.d: Plural of LAME: Unable to walk properly because of a problem with one's feet or legs.
LAMES.e: From Middle English lame, from Old English lama (“lame”), from Proto-West Germanic *lam, from Proto-Germanic *lamaz (“lame”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃lemH- (“to tire; to break”).

LAMPS.d: Plural of LAMP: A device that generates heat, light or other radiation. Especially an electric light bulb.
LAMPS.e: From Middle English laumpe, lampe, from Old French lampe (“lamp, light”), from Latin lampas (“torch, lamp, light”), from Ancient Greek λαμπάς (lampás, “torch, lamp, beacon, light, meteor”), from Proto-Indo-European *leh₂p- (“to shine”). Cognate with Lithuanian lópė (“light”), Wel...

LANDS.d: Plural of LAND: The part of Earth which is not covered by oceans or other bodies of water.
LANDS.e: From Middle English lond, land, from Old English land, from Proto-West Germanic *land, from Proto-Germanic *landą (“land”), from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“land, heath”).

LANES.d: Plural of LANE: A road, street, or similar thoroughfare.
LANES.e:
From Middle English lane, lone, from Old English lanu (“a lane, alley, avenue”), from Proto-West Germanic *lanu, from Proto-Germanic *lanō (“lane, passageway”).
Cognate with Scots lone (“cattle-track, by-road”), West Frisian leane, loane (“a walkway, avenue”), Dutch laan (“alley,...

LARDS.d: Plural of LARD: Fat from the abdomen of a pig, especially as prepared for use in cooking or pharmacy.
LARDS.e: From Middle English lard, from Old French lard (“bacon”), from Latin lārdum, lāridum (“bacon fat”).

LARGE.e: From Old French large, from Latin largus.

LARKS.d: Plural of LARK: Any of various small, singing passerine birds of the family Alaudidae.
LARKS.e: From Middle English larke, laverke, from Old English lāwerce, lǣwerce, lāuricæ, from Proto-West Germanic *laiwarikā, from Proto-Germanic *laiwarikǭ, *laiwazikǭ (compare dialectal West Frisian larts, Dutch leeuwerik, German Lerche), from *laiwaz (borrowed into Finnish leivo, Eston...

LASED.d: Past tense of LASE: To use a laser beam on, as for cutting.
LASED.e: Back-formation from laser, as if removing -er. Compare mase.

LASTS.d: Plural of LAST: Final, ultimate, coming after all others of its kind.
LASTS.e: From Middle English laste, latst, syncopated variant of latest.

LATED.d: Past tense of LATE: Near the end of a period of time.
LATED.e:
From Middle English late, lat, from Old English læt (“slow; slack, lax, negligent; late”), from Proto-West Germanic *lat, from Proto-Germanic *lataz (“slow, lazy”). By surface analysis, deverbal from let.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola laate (“late”), North Frisian leed, leet, lääs (...

LATHS.d: Plural of LATH: A thin, narrow strip, fastened to the rafters, studs, or floor beams of a building, for the purpose of supporting a covering of tiles, plastering, etc.
LATHS.e: From Middle English laththe, laþþe, earlier lathe, laþe, altered from Old English lætt (“lath”), from Proto-West Germanic *lattu, from Proto-Germanic *lattō, *laþþō (compare Dutch lat, German Latte) from Proto-Indo-European *(s)lat- (compare Welsh llath (“rod, wand, yard”)).

LAUDS.d: Plural of LAUD: Glorification or praise.
LAUDS.e: From Middle English lauden, from Old French lauder, from Latin laudō, laudāre, from laus (“praise, glory, fame, renown”), from echoic Proto-Indo-European root *leh₁wdʰ- (“song, sound”). Cognate with Old English lēoþ (“song, poem”), German Lied (“song”). Doublet of leed.

LAVAS.d: Plural of LAVA: The molten rock ejected by a volcano from its crater or fissured sides; magma that has breached the surface of the earth.
LAVAS.e: From Italian, from Neapolitan and Sicilian lava (“lava”, but also “downpour overflowing the streets”). Likely in the sense of “landslide, torrent” from Latin labes (“fall”), compare labina (“avalanche, landslide”). A supposed relation with lavare (“to wash”) is now widely discred...

LAVED.d: Past tense of LAVE: To bathe or wash (someone or something).
LAVED.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English laven (“to bathe, wash; to bail or draw water, drain, exhaust; to dampen, wet; to pour; of water, etc.: to flow, stream”), and then partly:
* from Old French laver (“to be washed; to wash”) (modern French laver (“to wash (oneself)”)), from ...

LAVES.d: Plural of LAVE: To bathe or wash (someone or something).
LAVES.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English laven (“to bathe, wash; to bail or draw water, drain, exhaust; to dampen, wet; to pour; of water, etc.: to flow, stream”), and then partly:
* from Old French laver (“to be washed; to wash”) (modern French laver (“to wash (oneself)”)), from ...

LAWED.d: Past tense of LAW: The body of binding rules and regulations, customs, and standards established in a community by its legislative and judicial authorities.
LAWED.e: From Middle English lawe, laȝe, from Old English lagu (“law”), borrowed from Old Norse lǫg (“law”, literally “things laid down or firmly established”), originally the plural of lag (“layer, stratum, a laying in order, measure, stroke”), from Proto-Germanic *lagą (“that which is l...

LAWNS.d: Plural of LAWN: Ground (generally in front of or around a house) covered with grass kept closely mown.
LAWNS.e: Early Modern English laune (“turf, grassy area”), alteration of laund (“glade”), from Middle English launde, from Old French lande (“heath, moor”), of Germanic or Gaulish origin, from Proto-Germanic *landą (“land”) or Proto-Celtic *landā, both from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“l...

LAYED.d: Past tense of LAY: To place down in a position of rest, or in a horizontal position.
LAYED.e:
Inherited from Middle English leyen, leggen, from Old English leċġan (“to lay”), from Proto-West Germanic *laggjan, from Proto-Germanic *lagjaną (“to lay”), causative form of Proto-Germanic *ligjaną (“to lie, recline”), from Proto-Indo-European *legʰ- (“to lie, recline”).
Cognate...

LAYER.d: A sheet or thickness of material.

LAZED.d: Past tense of LAZE: To be lazy, waste time.

LEADS.d: Plural of LEAD: A heavy, pliable, inelastic metal element, having a bright, bluish color, but easily tarnished; both malleable and ductile, though with little tenacity. It is easily fusible, forms alloys with other metals, and is an ingredient of solder and type metal. Atomic number 82, symbol Pb (from Latin plumbum).
LEADS.e:
From Middle English led, leed, from Old English lēad (“lead”), from Proto-West Germanic *laud (“lead”), possibly borrowed from Proto-Celtic *ɸloudom, from Proto-Indo-European *plewd- (“to flow”).
Cognate with Scots leid, lede (“lead”), North Frisian lud, luad (“lead”), West Frisi...

LEAFS.d: Plural of LEAF: The usually green and flat organ that represents the most prominent feature of most vegetative plants.
LEAFS.e:
From Middle English leef, from Old English lēaf, from Proto-West Germanic *laub, from Proto-Germanic *laubą (“leaf”), from Proto-Indo-European *lowbʰ-o-m, from *lewbʰ- (“leaf, rind”)
See also West Frisian leaf, Low German Loov, Dutch loof, German Laub, Danish løv, Swedish löv, No...

LEAKS.d: Plural of LEAK: A crack, crevice, fissure, or hole which admits water or other fluid, or lets it escape.
LEAKS.e:
From Middle English leken (“to let water in or out”), from Old English *lecan (“to leak”), Middle Dutch leken (“to leak, drip”) or Old Norse leka (“to leak, drip”); all from Proto-Germanic *lekaną (“to leak, drain”), from Proto-Indo-European *leg-, *leǵ- (“to leak”).
Cognate with...

LEANS.d: Plural of LEAN: To incline, deviate, or bend, from a vertical position; to be in a position thus inclining or deviating.
LEANS.e:
From Middle English lenen (“to lean”), from Old English hleonian, hlinian (“to lean, recline, lie down, rest”), from Proto-West Germanic *hlinēn, from Proto-Germanic *hlināną (“to lean, incline”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱley-.
Cognate via Proto-Germanic with Middle Dutch leune...

LEAPS.e:
From Middle English lepen, from Old English hlēapan, from Proto-West Germanic *hlaupan, from Proto-Germanic *hlaupaną. Doublet of lope, lowp, elope, gallop, galop, interlope, and loop.
Cognate with North Frisian laap, luup, luupe (“to jog, run, walk”), Saterland Frisian lope, loo...

LEAVE.d: To go away from; to allow to remain.

LEEKS.d: Plural of LEEK: A vegetable of variety Allium ampeloprasum, having edible leaves and an onion-like bulb but with a milder flavour than the onion.
LEEKS.e:
From Middle English leke, leek, lek, from Old English lēac (“a garden herb, leek, onion, garlic”), from Proto-West Germanic *lauk, from Proto-Germanic *lauką *laukaz (“leek, onion”), from Proto-Indo-European *lewg- (“to bend”).
Cognate with Dutch look (“garlic, leek”), German Low...

LEERS.d: Plural of LEER: To look sideways or obliquely; now especially with sexual desire or malicious intent.
LEERS.e: Exact development uncertain, but apparently from a verb *leer (“to make a face, look sideways”), from leer (“cheek, face, profile”).

LEETS.d: Plural of LEET: A portion or list, especially a list of candidates for an office; also the candidates themselves.
LEETS.e: From Scots leet, leit, of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old French lite, litte, variant of liste (“list”); or from Old Norse leiti, hleyti (“a share, portion”) (compare Old English hlēt (“share, lot”)); or an aphaeretic shortening of French élite.

LEFTS.d: Plural of LEFT: Designating the side of the body toward the west when one is facing north; the side of the body on which the heart is located in most humans; the opposite of right. This arrow points to the reader's left: ←
LEFTS.e: From Middle English left, luft, leoft, lift, lyft, from Old English left, lyft (“weak, clumsy, foolish”), attested in Old English lyftādl (“palsy, paralysis”), from Proto-Germanic *luft-, from *lubjaną (“to castrate, lop off”) (compare dialectal English lib, West Frisian lobje, D...

LEHRS.d: Plural of LEHR: A long oven or kiln, often having a moving belt, used for annealing glass.

LENDS.d: Plural of LEND: To allow to be used by someone temporarily, on condition that it or its equivalent will be returned.
LENDS.e: From earlier len (with excrescent -d, as in sound, round, etc.), from Middle English lenen, lænen, from Old English lǣnan (“to lend; give, grant, lease”), from Proto-West Germanic *laihnijan, from Proto-Germanic *laihnijaną (“to loan”), from Proto-Germanic *laihną (“loan”), from ...

LENOS.d: Plural of LENO: A type of weave used to make light, open cotton fabric used for window curtains.
LENOS.e: From French linon (“lawn (linen fabric)”), from lin (“linen; flax”) + -on.

LEVEL.e: From Old French livel, from Latin libella.

LIARS.d: Plural of LIAR: A person who frequently lies; someone who tells a lie.
LIARS.e: From Middle English lier, liere, lyere, liȝer, lieȝer, legher, from Old English lēgere, lēogere (“liar, false witness, hypocrite”), from Proto-West Germanic *leugārī, from Proto-Germanic *leugārijaz (“liar”), from *leuganą (“to lie”) + *-ārijaz, equivalent to lie + -ar. More at l...

LICKS.d: Plural of LICK: To stroke with the tongue.
LICKS.e:
From Middle English likken, from Old English liccian, from Proto-West Germanic *likkōn, from Proto-Germanic *likkōną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyǵʰ- (“to lick”). Sense evolution towards violence unclear; not paralleled in any other Germanic language.
See also Saterland Frisian ...

LIDOS.d: Plural of LIDO: Part of the sea by a beach sectioned off for swimming and other aquatic activities.
LIDOS.e: After Lido (Lido di Venezia), an island with a long beach in Venice, Italy, site of Europe’s first modern beach resort (1857), from Italian lido (“beach, shore”), from Latin litus (“shore”) (hence also English littoral (“of the shore”)). The name is aspirational, evoking glamorou...

LIENS.e: Borrowed from Middle French lien, from Latin ligāmen (“a bond”), from ligō (“tie, bind”).

LIEUS.d: Plural of LIEU: A place or stead.
LIEUS.e: Borrowed from French lieu, from Latin locum, accusative of locus (“place”).

LIFTS.d: Plural of LIFT: To raise or rise.
LIFTS.e: From Middle English liften, lyften, from Old Norse lypta (“to lift, air”, literally “to raise in the air”), from Proto-Germanic *luftijaną (“to raise in the air”), related to *luftuz (“roof, air”), perhaps from Proto-Indo-European *lewp- (“to peel, break off, damage”) or from a r...

LIKED.d: Past tense of LIKE: To enjoy, be pleased by; favor; be in favor of.
LIKED.e:
Verb from Middle English liken, from Old English līcian (“to like, to please”), from Proto-West Germanic *līkēn, from Proto-Germanic *līkāną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyg- (“image; likeness; similarity”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian liekje (“to be similar, resemble”), West F...

LIKES.d: Plural of LIKE: To enjoy, be pleased by; favor; be in favor of.
LIKES.e:
Verb from Middle English liken, from Old English līcian (“to like, to please”), from Proto-West Germanic *līkēn, from Proto-Germanic *līkāną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyg- (“image; likeness; similarity”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian liekje (“to be similar, resemble”), West F...

LILTS.d: Plural of LILT: To do something rhythmically, with animation and quickness, usually of music.

LIMBS.d: Plural of LIMB: A major appendage of human or animal, used for locomotion (such as an arm, leg or wing).
LIMBS.e:
From Middle English lyme, lim, from Old English lim (“limb, branch”), from Proto-West Germanic *limu, from Proto-Germanic *limuz (“branch, limb”). Cognate with Old Norse limr (“limb”).
The spelling with the silent unetymological -b first arose in the late 1500s. Compare crumb.

LIMED.d: Past tense of LIME: Any inorganic material containing calcium, usually calcium oxide (quicklime) or calcium hydroxide (slaked lime).
LIMED.e:
From Middle English lyme, lym, lime, from Old English līm, from Proto-West Germanic *līm, from Proto-Germanic *līmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂leyH- (“to smear”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Liem (“glue”), Dutch lijm, German Leim (“glue”), Danish lim (from Old Norse lím), L...

LIMES.d: Plural of LIME: Any inorganic material containing calcium, usually calcium oxide (quicklime) or calcium hydroxide (slaked lime).
LIMES.e:
From Middle English lyme, lym, lime, from Old English līm, from Proto-West Germanic *līm, from Proto-Germanic *līmaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂leyH- (“to smear”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Liem (“glue”), Dutch lijm, German Leim (“glue”), Danish lim (from Old Norse lím), L...

LIMNS.d: Plural of LIMN: To draw or paint; to delineate.
LIMNS.e: From Middle English limnen, limyne, lymm, lymn, lymne (“to illuminate (a manuscript)”), a variant of luminen (“to illuminate (a manuscript)”), short form of enluminen (“to shed light on, illuminate; to enlighten; to make bright or clear; to give colour to; to illuminate (a manusc...

LIMOS.d: Plural of LIMO: Clipping of limousine.

LIMPS.d: Plural of LIMP: To walk lamely, as if favoring one leg.
LIMPS.e:
From Middle English limpen (“to fall short”), from Old English limpan, from Proto-West Germanic *limpan, from Proto-Germanic *limpaną (“to hang down”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)lemb-, *(s)lembʰ- (“to hang loosely, hang limply”).
Cognate with Low German lumpen (“to limp”), Mid...

LINED.d: Past tense of LINE: A path through two or more points (compare ‘segment’); a continuous mark, including as made by a pen; any path, curved or straight.
LINED.e: From Middle English line, lyne, from Old English līne (“line, cable, rope, hawser, series, row, rule, direction”), from Proto-West Germanic *līnā, from Proto-Germanic *līnǭ (“line, rope, flaxen cord, thread”), from Proto-Germanic *līną (“flax, linen”), from Proto-Indo-European *l...

LINES.d: Plural of LINE: A path through two or more points (compare ‘segment’); a continuous mark, including as made by a pen; any path, curved or straight.
LINES.e: From Middle English line, lyne, from Old English līne (“line, cable, rope, hawser, series, row, rule, direction”), from Proto-West Germanic *līnā, from Proto-Germanic *līnǭ (“line, rope, flaxen cord, thread”), from Proto-Germanic *līną (“flax, linen”), from Proto-Indo-European *l...

LINGS.d: Plural of LING: Any of various marine food fish, of the genus Molva, resembling the cod.
LINGS.e: From Middle English lenge, lienge, from Middle French leynge (compare French lingue), from Middle Dutch *lenge (modern Dutch leng). Cognate with Old Norse langa. Probably related to long.

LINKS.d: Plural of LINK: A connection between places, people, events, things, or ideas.
LINKS.e: From Middle English linke, lenke, from a merger of Old English hlenċe, hlenċa (“ring; chainlink”) and Old Norse *hlenkr, hlekkr (“ring; chain”); both from Proto-Germanic *hlankiz (“ring; bond; fettle; fetter”). Used in English since the 14th century. Related to lank.

LINNS.d: Plural of LINN: A waterfall or cataract (torrent of water running over a rocky bed), or a ravine down which such a waterfall rushes.
LINNS.e: From Middle English *linne, from Old English hlynn (“torrent”).

LINOS.d: Plural of LINO: Clipping of linoleum.
LINOS.e: Clipping of linoleum, probably influenced by -o (“diminutive suffix”).

LINTS.d: Plural of LINT: Clinging fuzzy fluff that clings to fabric or accumulates in one's pockets or navel etc.
LINTS.e: From Middle English lynet, linet, from Old French linette (“grain of flax”), diminutive of lin (“flax”); or, from Medieval Latin linteum, from Latin līnum (“flax”).

LIONS.d: Plural of LION: A big cat, Panthera leo, native to Africa, India and formerly much of Europe.
LIONS.e: From Middle English lyoun, lion, leon, borrowed from Old French lion, from Latin leō, (accusative: leōnem), from Ancient Greek λέων (léōn), of unclear origin. Doublet of Leo, leu, lev, and Lyon. Displaced Old English lēo, from the same Latin source.

LIRAS.d: Plural of LIRA: The basic unit of currency in Turkey.
LIRAS.e: From Italian lira, from Latin lībra (partly via Turkish lira, Arabic لِيرَة (līra), Maltese lira, Greek λίρα (líra), and Hebrew לִירָה (“lirá”), all of which are originally from the Italian). Doublet of arratel, libbra, Libra, libra, litra, litre, livre, and rottol.

LISPS.d: Plural of LISP: The act or a habit of lisping.
LISPS.e: From Middle English lispen, lipsen, wlispen, from Old English *wlispian (attested in āwlyspian (“to lisp”)), from Old English wlisp, wlips (“stammering, lisping”, adjective), from Proto-Germanic *wlispaz (“lisping”), from Proto-Indo-European *wlis-, *wleys- (“rod”), from *wel- (“...

LISTS.d: Plural of LIST: A strip of fabric, especially from the edge of a piece of cloth.
LISTS.e: From Middle English lī̆st, lī̆ste (“band, stripe; hem, selvage; border, edge, rim; list, specification; barriers enclosing area for jousting, etc.”), from Old English līste (“hem, edge, strip”), or Old French liste, listre (“border; band; strip of paper; list”), or Medieval Latin...

LOADS.d: Plural of LOAD: A burden; a weight to be carried.
LOADS.e: The sense of “burden” first arose in the 13th century as a secondary meaning of Middle English lode, loade, which had the main significance of “way, course, journey”, from Old English lād (“course, journey; way, street, waterway; leading, carrying; maintenance, support”) (ultimat...

Proto-West Germanic *hlaib
Old English hlāf

English loaf
* From Middle English lof, laf, from Old English hlāf (“bread, loaf of bread”), from Proto-West Germanic *hlaib, from Proto-Germanic *hlaibaz (“bread, loaf”), of unc...

LOAMS.d: Plural of LOAM: A type of soil; an earthy mixture of sand, silt and clay, with organic matter to which its fertility is chiefly due.
LOAMS.e: From Middle English lome, lame, lam, from Old English lām (“clay, mud, mire, earth”), from Proto-West Germanic *laim, from Proto-Germanic *laimaz, *laimô (“clay”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂leyH- (“to smear”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Leem (“loam”), West Frisian liem (“lo...

LOANS.d: Plural of LOAN: An act or instance of lending, an act or instance of granting something for temporary use.
LOANS.e:
From Middle English lone, lane, from Old Norse lán, from Proto-Germanic *laihną, from Proto-Indo-European *leykʷ- (“to leave (over)”).
Cognate with Icelandic lán, Swedish lån, Danish lån, German Lehen (“fief”), Dutch leen (“fief”), West Frisian lien, North Frisian leen (“fief; lo...

LOBED.d: Past tense of LOBE: Any projection or division, especially one of a somewhat rounded form.
LOBED.e: From Middle French lobe in early 16th century, from New Latin lobus (“a lobe”), from Ancient Greek λοβός (lobós, “the lobe of the ear or of the liver, the pod of a leguminous plant”).

LOBES.d: Plural of LOBE: Any projection or division, especially one of a somewhat rounded form.
LOBES.e: From Middle French lobe in early 16th century, from New Latin lobus (“a lobe”), from Ancient Greek λοβός (lobós, “the lobe of the ear or of the liver, the pod of a leguminous plant”).

LOCHS.e: From Middle English lough, borrowed from Scottish Gaelic loch. Doublet of lay, Looe, and lough.

LOCKS.d: Plural of LOCK: Something used for fastening, which can only be opened with a key or combination.
LOCKS.e:
From Middle English lok, from Old English loc, from Proto-West Germanic *lok, from Proto-Germanic *luką from Proto-Indo-European *lewg- (“to bend; turn”).
Cognate with Cimbrian loch, lòch (“hole”), Dutch lok (“hole”), German Loch (“hole”), German Low German Lock (“hole”), Luxembo...

LOCOS.d: Plural of LOCO: A direction in written or printed music to be returning to the proper pitch after having played an octave higher or lower.

LODES.d: Plural of LODE: A way or path; a road.
LODES.e: Doublet of load, which has however become semantically restricted. The now-archaic lode continues the old sense of Old English lād (“way, course, journey”) but by the 19th century survived only dialectally in the sense of “watercourse”, as a technical term in mining, and in the c...

LOFTS.d: Plural of LOFT: air, the air; the sky, the heavens.
LOFTS.e:
From Middle English lofte (“air, sky, upper region, loft”), from Old English loft, (doublet of native Old English lyft) of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse lopt (“upper chamber, attic, region of sky, air”), from Proto-Germanic *luftuz (“air, sky”).
Akin to Scots lift (“air; ...

LOGES.d: Plural of LOGE: A booth or stall.
LOGES.e: From French loge (“arbor, covered walk-way”) from Frankish *laubijā (“shelter”). Akin to Old High German loub (“porch, gallery”) (German Laube (“bower, arbor”)), Old High German loub (“leaf, foliage”), Old English lēaf (“leaf, foliage”). Doublet of lobby, loggia, and lodge. More ...

LOGOS.d: Plural of LOGO: A visual symbol or emblem that acts as a trademark or a means of identification of a company or organization.

LOINS.d: Plural of LOIN: The part of the body (of humans and quadrupeds) at each side of the backbone, between the ribs and hips.
LOINS.e: From Middle English loyne, from Old French loigne, from Vulgar Latin *lumbea, from Latin lumbus, of uncertain origin, possibly from Oscan-Umbrian *londwo- or Proto-Germanic *lundwuz, both ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“kidney, waist”). Cognate with Modern English l...

LOLLS.d: Plural of LOLL: To act lazily or indolently while reclining; to lean; to lie at ease.
LOLLS.e: From Middle English lollen, lullen (“to lounge idly, hang loosely”), of uncertain origin; the Middle English Dictionary suggests a derivation from Middle Dutch lollen, lullen (“to doze; to mumble, talk nonsense”), though the words could merely be cognate. Compare modern Dutch lol...

LONGS.d: Plural of LONG: Having much distance in space from one end to the other.
LONGS.e:
From Middle English long, lang, from Old English long, lang (“long, tall, lasting”), from Proto-West Germanic *lang, from Proto-Germanic *langaz (“long”), from Proto-Indo-European *dlongʰos (“long”).
Cognate with Scots lang (“long”), North Frisian lung, lüng (“long”), Saterland F...

LOOED.d: Past tense of LOO: A lavatory: a room used for urination and defecation.
LOOED.e: Uncertain, although usually derived in some way from Waterloo, the site of Wellington's 1815 victory over Napoleon, likely via a pun based on water closet. Other suggested derivations include corruptions of French l'eau (“water”), lieu (“place”), lieux d'aisances (“'places of con...

LOOKS.d: Plural of LOOK: To try to see, to pay attention to with one’s eyes.
LOOKS.e: From Middle English loken, lokien, from Old English lōcian, from Proto-West Germanic *lōkōn. Further origin unknown, no certain cognates outside Germanic. Cognate with Scots luke, luik, leuk (“to look, see”), West Frisian lôkje, loaitsje (“to look”), Dutch loeken (“to look”), Ger...

LOOMS.d: Plural of LOOM: A utensil; tool; a weapon; (usually in compound) an article in general.
LOOMS.e: From Middle English lome, from Old English *lōma, ġelōma (“tool, utensil, implement, article of furniture, household effect”) (also as andlōma, andġelōma, andlama (“utensil, instrument, implement, tool, vessel”), from Proto-West Germanic *lōmō, *lamō (“tool, utensil”), of uncerta...

LOONS.d: Plural of LOON: A crazy or deranged person; a lunatic.
LOONS.e: From Middle English louen, lowen (“rascal; rogue”), probably of Middle Dutch or Middle Low German origin. Compare Dutch loen (“simpleton”). Or, related to etymology 2, due to the bird's loud cry. Folk etymology associates it slang-wise with lunatic, though the latter may have inf...

LOOPS.d: Plural of LOOP: A length of thread, line or rope that is doubled over to make an opening.
LOOPS.e: From Middle English loupe (“noose, loop”), earlier lowp-knot (“loop-knot”), of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse hlaup (“a run”), used in the sense of a "running knot", from hlaupa (“to leap”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *hlaupaną (“to leap, run”). Compare Swedish löp-knu...

LOOTS.d: Plural of LOOT: Synonym of booty, goods seized from an enemy by violence, particularly (historical) during the sacking of a town in war or (video games) after successful combat.
LOOTS.e: Borrowed from Hindi लूट (lūṭ, “booty”), either from Sanskrit लोप्त्र (loptra, “booty, stolen property”) or लुण्ट् (luṇṭ, “to rob, plunder”). The figurative meaning developed in American English in the 1920s, resulting in a generalized meaning by the 1950s.

LOPED.d: Past tense of LOPE: To travel an easy pace with long strides.
LOPED.e: From Middle English lopen, from Old Norse hlaupa (“to leap, jump”). See leap. Cognate with German laufen (“walk, run”), Danish løbe (“run”), Dutch lopen (“walk, run”), Norwegian løpe (“run”). Doublet of leap.

LOPES.d: Plural of LOPE: To travel an easy pace with long strides.
LOPES.e: From Middle English lopen, from Old Norse hlaupa (“to leap, jump”). See leap. Cognate with German laufen (“walk, run”), Danish løbe (“run”), Dutch lopen (“walk, run”), Norwegian løpe (“run”). Doublet of leap.

LORDS.d: Plural of LORD: The master of the servants of a household; (historical) the master of a feudal manor
LORDS.e: From Middle English lord and lorde (attested from the 15th century), from earlier (14th century) lourde and other variants which dropped the intervocalic consonant of earlier lowerd, louerd, loverd, laford, and lhoaverd; from Old English hlāford < hlāfweard, a compound of hlāf (“...

LORED.d: Past tense of LORE: All the facts and traditions about a particular subject that have been accumulated over time through education or experience.
LORED.e: From Middle English lore, from Old English lār, from Proto-West Germanic *laiʀu, from Proto-Germanic *laizō, from *laizijaną (“to teach”). Cognate with Dutch leer, German Lehre, Swedish lära and Danish lære. See also learn.

LORES.d: Plural of LORE: All the facts and traditions about a particular subject that have been accumulated over time through education or experience.
LORES.e: From Middle English lore, from Old English lār, from Proto-West Germanic *laiʀu, from Proto-Germanic *laizō, from *laizijaną (“to teach”). Cognate with Dutch leer, German Lehre, Swedish lära and Danish lære. See also learn.

LOSES.d: Plural of LOSE: To cease to have (something) in one's possession or capability.
LOSES.e: From Middle English losen, from Old English losian, from Proto-West Germanic *losōn, from Proto-Germanic *lusōną, *luzōną, from Proto-Germanic *lusą. The modern pronunciation with /uː/ (instead of the /oʊ~əʊ/ that would be expected from Early Modern /ɔː/) is due to conflation wit...

LOURS.d: Plural of LOUR: To frown; to look sullen.
LOURS.e:
The verb is derived from Middle English louren, lour, loure (“to frown or scowl; to be dark or overcast; to droop, fade, wither; to lurk, skulk”), probably from Old English *lūran, *lūrian, from Proto-Germanic *lūraną (“to lie in wait, lurk”).
The English word is cognate with Dan...

LOUTS.d: Plural of LOUT: A troublemaker, often violent; a rude violent person; a yob.
LOUTS.e:
Of dialectal origin, likely derived from Middle English louten (“to bow, bend low, stoop over”), from Old English lūtan (“to bow, bend forward, stoop”), from Proto-West Germanic *lūtan, from Proto-Germanic *lūtaną (“to bow down, lout”).
Alternatively, derived from Middle English ...

LOVED.d: Past tense of LOVE: A deep caring for the existence of another.
LOVED.e:
From Middle English love, luve, from Old English lufu, from Proto-West Germanic *lubu, from Proto-Germanic *lubō, from Proto-Indo-European *lewbʰ- (“love, care, desire”).
The close of a letter sense is presumably a truncation of With love or the like.
The verb is from Middle Engl...

LUAUS.d: Plural of LUAU: An elaborate Hawaiian feast featuring traditional foods and entertainment.
LUAUS.e: From Hawaiian lūʻau. Replaced earlier paina (from pāʻina) and ahaaina (from ʻahaʻaina).

LUCKS.d: Plural of LUCK: Something that happens to someone by chance, a chance occurrence.
LUCKS.e: From Middle English luk, lukke, related to Old Frisian luk (“luck”), West Frisian gelok (“luck”), Saterland Frisian Gluk (“luck”), Dutch geluk (“luck, happiness”), Low German luk (“luck”), German Glück (“luck, good fortune, happiness”), Danish lykke (“luck”), Swedish lycka (“luck...

LUFFS.d: Plural of LUFF: The vertical edge of a sail that is closest to the direction of the wind.
LUFFS.e: From Old French lof. Collins English Dictionary states that this word is ultimately derived from Middle Dutch loef. Ellert Ekwall's Shakspere's Vocabulary: its etymological elements (1903) related this verb and loof instead to the East Frisian verb lofen, lufen, which would make ...

LUGES.d: Plural of LUGE: A racing sled for one or two people that is ridden with the rider or riders lying on their back.
LUGES.e: The noun is borrowed from Swiss French or Franco-Provençal luge, from Medieval Latin scludia, from Late Latin sclodia, of Celtic origin, from Gaulish *stludio, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *sleydʰ- (“to slide, slip; to be slick or slippery”). If so, it is related to sled and...

LULLS.d: Plural of LULL: A period of rest or soothing.
LULLS.e:
From Middle English lullen, lollen. Originally, perhaps expressive in origin from la-la-la or lu-lu-lu sounds made in calming a child. Compare Finnish laulaa (“to sing”) and Hiligaynon lala (“to sing a lullaby”).
Cognate with Scots lul, lule, loll (“to lull, put to sleep, howl, c...

LULUS.d: Plural of LULU: A remarkable person, object, or idea.
LULUS.e: Probably from American stage magician Lulu Hurst (1869–1950).

LUMPS.d: Plural of LUMP: Something that protrudes, sticks out, or sticks together; a cluster or blob; a mound or mass of no particular shape.
LUMPS.e: From Middle English lumpe, from a Germanic base akin to Proto-Germanic *limpaną (“to glide, go, hang loosely”). Compare Dutch lomp (“rag”), German Low German Lump (“rag”), German Lumpen (“rag”) and Lump (“ragamuffin”).

LUNES.d: Plural of LUNE: A fit of lunacy or madness; a period of frenzy; a crazy or unreasonable freak.

LUNGS.d: Plural of LUNG: A biological organ of vertebrates that controls breathing and oxygenates the blood.
LUNGS.e: From Middle English lunge, longe, from Old English lungen, from Proto-Germanic *lunganjō, an enlargement of *lungô (“the light organ, lung”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁lengʷʰ-, whence ultimately also light. Cognate with West Frisian long, Dutch long, German Lunge, Danish lunge,...

LURED.d: Past tense of LURE: Something that tempts or attracts, especially one with a promise of reward or pleasure.
LURED.e: From Anglo-Norman lure, from Old French loirre (Modern French leurre), from Frankish *lōþr, from Proto-Germanic *lōþr-, perhaps ultimately related to *laþō (“invitation, calling”), or from Proto-Indo-European *leh₂- (“to hide”). Compare English allure, also from Old French. Proba...

LURES.d: Plural of LURE: Something that tempts or attracts, especially one with a promise of reward or pleasure.
LURES.e: From Anglo-Norman lure, from Old French loirre (Modern French leurre), from Frankish *lōþr, from Proto-Germanic *lōþr-, perhaps ultimately related to *laþō (“invitation, calling”), or from Proto-Indo-European *leh₂- (“to hide”). Compare English allure, also from Old French. Proba...

LURKS.d: Plural of LURK: To remain concealed in order to ambush.
LURKS.e:
From Middle English lurken, from Old Norse *lúrka, possibly from Proto-Germanic *lūrukōną (“to be lying in wait, lurk”), equivalent to lour + -k (frequentative suffix).
Cognate with Norwegian Nynorsk lurka (“to sneak away, go slowly”), dialectal Swedish lurka (“to dawdle, be slow...

LUSTS.d: Plural of LUST: A feeling of strong desire, especially such a feeling driven by sexual arousal.
LUSTS.e:
From Middle English lust, from Old English lust (“lust, pleasure, longing”), from Proto-West Germanic *lustu, from Proto-Germanic *lustuz.
Akin to Old Saxon, Dutch lust, Old Frisian, Old High German, German Lust, Swedish lust, Danish lyst, Icelandic lyst, Old Norse losti, Gothic ...

LUTED.d: Past tense of LUTE: A fretted stringed instrument, similar to the guitar, having a bowl-shaped body or soundbox; any of a wide variety of chordophones with a pear-shaped body and a neck whose upper surface is in the same plane as the soundboard, with strings along the neck and parallel to the soundboard.
LUTED.e: From Middle French lut (modern luth), from Old French leüt, probably from Old Occitan laüt, from Arabic اَلْعُود (al-ʕūd, “wood”) (probably representing an Andalusian Arabic or North African pronunciation). Doublet of oud, lavta, and laouto.

LUTES.d: Plural of LUTE: A fretted stringed instrument, similar to the guitar, having a bowl-shaped body or soundbox; any of a wide variety of chordophones with a pear-shaped body and a neck whose upper surface is in the same plane as the soundboard, with strings along the neck and parallel to the soundboard.
LUTES.e: From Middle French lut (modern luth), from Old French leüt, probably from Old Occitan laüt, from Arabic اَلْعُود (al-ʕūd, “wood”) (probably representing an Andalusian Arabic or North African pronunciation). Doublet of oud, lavta, and laouto.

LUXES.d: Plural of LUX: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of illuminance or illumination; one lumen per square metre. Symbol: lx
LUXES.e: Borrowed from Latin lūx (“light”), from Proto-Indo-European *lewk- (“white; light; bright”). Cognates include Ancient Greek λευκός (leukós, “white, blank, light, bright, clear”), Ancient Greek λύκη (lúkē, “light, morning twilight”), Sanskrit रोचते (rocate), Middle Persian 𐭩𐭥𐭬 (rō...

LYRES.d: Plural of LYRE: An ancient stringed musical instrument (a yoke lute chordophone) of Greek origin, consisting of two arms extending from a body to a crossbar (a yoke), and strings, parallel to the soundboard, connecting the body to the yoke.
