LYRES.e: From Ancient Greek λύρᾱ (lúrā, “lyre, a stringed instrument with a sounding-board formed of the shell of a tortoise”). Doublet of lira, Lyra, and lyra.

MACED.d: Past tense of MACE: A heavy fighting club.
MACED.e: From Middle English mace, borrowed from Old French mace, mache, from Vulgar Latin *mattia, *mattea, matia, (compare Italian mazza, Spanish maza), probably from Proto-West Germanic *mattjō (“cutting tool, hoe”).

MACES.d: Plural of MACE: A heavy fighting club.
MACES.e: From Middle English mace, borrowed from Old French mace, mache, from Vulgar Latin *mattia, *mattea, matia, (compare Italian mazza, Spanish maza), probably from Proto-West Germanic *mattjō (“cutting tool, hoe”).

MACKS.d: Plural of MACK: Synonym of guy, term of address for a man or person.
MACKS.e: (In sense one) From either the male name Mack or mack, itself from mackerel, which comes from Old French maquerel, from Dutch makelaar. Compare French mec.

MAGES.d: Plural of MAGE: A magician, wizard, sorcerer, witch, warlock or mystic.
MAGES.e: From Middle English mages (plurale tantum), from Latin magus, from Ancient Greek Μάγος (Mágos), from the hapax Old Persian 𐎶𐎦𐎢𐏁 (m-gu-u-š /⁠maguš⁠/). Doublet of magus.

MAGIC.d: The power of apparently influencing events by supernatural means.
MAGIC.e: From Old French magique, from Latin magicus.

MAIDS.d: Plural of MAID: A girl or an unmarried young woman; maiden.
MAIDS.e: From Middle English mayde, maide, abbreviation of Middle English maiden from Old English mæġden (Old English mǣden). Ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *magaþ, from Proto-Germanic *magaþs (“girl, virgin”).

MAILS.d: Plural of MAIL: A bag or wallet.
MAILS.e: From Middle English male, from Anglo-Norman male, Old French male (“bag, wallet”), from Frankish *malha (“bag”), from Proto-Germanic *malhō (“bag, pouch”), from Proto-Indo-European *molko- (“leather pouch”). Compare Dutch maal.

MAIMS.d: Plural of MAIM: To wound seriously; to cause permanent loss of function of a limb or part of the body.
MAIMS.e: From Middle English maymen, mahaymen, from Anglo-Norman maheimer, mahaigner, of Germanic origin; see mayhem.

MAINS.d: Plural of MAIN: Of chief or leading importance; prime, principal.
MAINS.e:
From Middle English mayn, main, maine, mæin, meyn, from main (noun) (see further at etymology 2); compare Old English mæġen (“strong, main, principal”) (used in combination) and Old Norse megn, megenn (“strong, main”).
The word is cognate with Old High German megīn (“strong, migh...

MAKER.d: A person or thing that makes.

MAKES.e:
From Middle English maken, from Old English macian (“to make, build, work”), from Proto-West Germanic *makōn (“to make, build, work”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂ǵ- (“to knead, mix, make”).
Related to match.
Cognates
* Scots mak (“to make”)
* Saterland Frisian moakje (“to make...

MAKOS.d: Plural of MAKO: Ellipsis of mako shark
MAKOS.e: Borrowed from Maori makō (“shark”), a Southern Maori dialect form of the more standard mangō (“shark”).

MALES.d: Plural of MALE: Belonging to the sex which typically produces sperm, or to the gender which is typically associated with it.
MALES.e: From Middle English male, borrowed from Old French malle, masle (Modern French mâle), from Latin masculus (“masculine, a male”), diminutive of mās (“male, masculine”). Doublet of macho. Displaced native Old English wǣpned (“male”, literally “penised”), derived from the noun wǣpn ...

MALLS.d: Plural of MALL: A pedestrianised street, especially a shopping precinct.
MALLS.e: Probably from The Mall, a major street in London, England, which was originally a pall mall alley.

MALTS.d: Plural of MALT: Malted grain (sprouted grain) (usually barley), used in brewing and otherwise.
MALTS.e:
From Middle English malt, from Old English mealt, from Proto-West Germanic *malt, from Proto-Germanic *maltą (“malt”), from *maltaz (“soft; nesh; weak; squashy; melting”), from Proto-Indo-European *meld-, *mled- (“to crush; grind; make weak”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Moalt...

MAMAS.d: Plural of MAMA: Mother, female parent.
MAMAS.e: Originally from baby talk. Possibly influenced by Middle English mome (“mother, aunt”), from Old English *mōme, from Proto-West Germanic *mōmā, from Proto-Germanic *mōmǭ (“mother, aunt”), from Proto-Indo-European *méh₂-méh₂, reduplication of *méh₂- (“mother”), related to German M...

MANED.d: Past tense of MANE: Longer hair growth on back of neck of an animal, especially a horse or lion.
MANED.e:
From Middle English mane, mayne, from Old English manu (“mane”), from Proto-West Germanic *manu, from Proto-Germanic *manō (“mane”), from Proto-Indo-European *mony-, *mon- (“neck”).
Cognate with Dutch maan, manen (“mane”), German Mähne (“mane”), Danish man (“horse's mane”), Swedi...

MANES.d: Plural of MANE: Longer hair growth on back of neck of an animal, especially a horse or lion.
MANES.e:
From Middle English mane, mayne, from Old English manu (“mane”), from Proto-West Germanic *manu, from Proto-Germanic *manō (“mane”), from Proto-Indo-European *mony-, *mon- (“neck”).
Cognate with Dutch maan, manen (“mane”), German Mähne (“mane”), Danish man (“horse's mane”), Swedi...

MARAS.d: Plural of MARA: A nightmare; a spectre or wraith-like creature in Germanic and particularly Scandinavian folklore; a female demon who torments people in sleep by crouching on their chests or stomachs, or by causing terrifying visions.
MARAS.e: Borrowed from Old Norse mara, from Proto-Germanic *marǭ, cognate with Old English mare or mære. Doublet of mare. See nightmare.

MARCH.d: To walk in a military manner; the third month.
MARCH.e: From Old French marchier / Latin Mārtius.

MARCS.d: Plural of MARC: The refuse matter that remains after fruit, particularly grapes, has been pressed.
MARCS.e: From Middle French marc, from Old French marcher (“to trample”).

MARES.d: Plural of MARE: An adult female horse.
MARES.e:
From Middle English mare, mere, from Old English mīere (“female horse, mare”), from Proto-West Germanic *marhijā, from Proto-Germanic *marhijō (“female horse”), from *marhaz (“horse”).
Cognates
See also Scots mere, meir, mear (“mare”), North Frisian mar (“mare, horse”), West Fris...

MARKS.d: Plural of MARK: Boundary, land within a boundary.
MARKS.e: From Middle English mark, merk, merke, from Old English mearc (“mark, sign, line of division; standard; boundary, limit, term, border; defined area, district, province”), from Proto-West Germanic *marku, from Proto-Germanic *markō (“boundary; boundary marker”), from Proto-Indo-Eu...

MARLS.d: Plural of MARL: A mixed earthy substance, consisting of carbonate of lime, clay, and possibly sand, in very variable proportions, and accordingly designated as calcareous, clayey, or sandy.
MARLS.e: From Middle English marle, from Old French marle, from Late Latin margila, diminutive of marga (“marl”). Doublet of marla.

MARTS.d: Plural of MART: A shop, a store, a market.
MARTS.e: From Middle Dutch mart, markt (“market”) (Modern Dutch markt), from Old Dutch *markat, from Late Latin marcātus, an alternative form of Classical Latin mercātus. See market.

MASKS.d: Plural of MASK: A cover, or partial cover, for the face, used for disguise or protection.
MASKS.e: Borrowed from Middle French masque (“a covering to hide or protect the face”), from Italian maschera (“mask, disguise”), from (a byform of, see it for more) Medieval Latin masca, mascha, a borrowing of Proto-West Germanic *maskā, from which English mesh and mask (“mesh”) (below a...

MASTS.d: Plural of MAST: A tall, slim post or tower, usually tapering upward, used to support, for example, sails or observation platforms on a ship, the main rotor of a helicopter, flags, floodlights, meteorological instruments, or communications equipment, such as an aerial, usually supported by guy-wires (except in the case of a helicopter).
MASTS.e:
From Middle English mast, from Old English mæst (“mast”), from Proto-West Germanic *mast, from Proto-Germanic *mastaz (“mast, sail-pole”), from Proto-Indo-European *mazdos (“pole, mast”).
Cognate with Dutch mast, German Mast, and via Indo-European with Latin mālus, Russian мост (...

MATED.d: Past tense of MATE: A fellow, comrade, colleague, partner or someone with whom something is shared, e.g. shipmate, classmate.
MATED.e: From Middle English mate, a borrowing from Middle Low German mate (“messmate”) (replacing Middle English mette (“table companion, mate, partner”), from Old English ġemetta (“sharer of food, table-guest”)), derived from Proto-Germanic *gamatjô, itself from *ga- (“together”) (relat...

MATES.d: Plural of MATE: A fellow, comrade, colleague, partner or someone with whom something is shared, e.g. shipmate, classmate.
MATES.e: From Middle English mate, a borrowing from Middle Low German mate (“messmate”) (replacing Middle English mette (“table companion, mate, partner”), from Old English ġemetta (“sharer of food, table-guest”)), derived from Proto-Germanic *gamatjô, itself from *ga- (“together”) (relat...

MATTS.d: Plural of MATT: Alternative spelling of matte.

MAULS.d: Plural of MAUL: A heavy long-handled hammer, used for splitting logs by driving a wedge into them, or in combat.
MAULS.e: From Middle English malle (“mace, maul”), from Anglo-Norman mail, from Old French mail, from Latin malleus (“hammer”). Doublet of malleus.

MAWED.d: Past tense of MAW: The stomach, especially of an animal.
MAWED.e:
From Middle English mawe, maghe, maȝe, from Old English maga (“stomach; maw”), from Proto-West Germanic *magō, from Proto-Germanic *magô (“belly; stomach”), from Proto-Indo-European *mak-, *maks- (“bag, bellows, belly”).
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian mage, Dutch maag (“stoma...

MAXIS.d: Plural of MAXI: Having a hemline at ankle length.
MAXIS.e: Back-formation from maximum on the analogy of minimum and mini.

MAYED.d: Past tense of MAY: To be strong; to have power (over).
MAYED.e:
From Middle English mowen, mayen, moȝen, maȝen, from Old English magan, from Proto-West Germanic *magan, from Proto-Germanic *maganą, from Proto-Indo-European *megʰ-.
Cognate with Dutch mag (“may”, first- and third-person singular of mogen (“to be able to, be allowed to, may”)), ...

MAYOR.d: The head of a city government.
MAYOR.e: From Old French maire, from Latin māior.

MAZED.d: Past tense of MAZE: A labyrinth; a puzzle consisting of a complicated network of paths or passages, the aim of which is to find one's way through.
MAZED.e: From Middle English mase, from Middle English masen (“to perplex, bewilder”); or perhaps from Old English *mæs (“delusion, bewilderment”); akin to Old English āmasian (“to perplex, confound”), Icelandic masa (“to chatter”). More at amaze.

MAZES.d: Plural of MAZE: A labyrinth; a puzzle consisting of a complicated network of paths or passages, the aim of which is to find one's way through.
MAZES.e: From Middle English mase, from Middle English masen (“to perplex, bewilder”); or perhaps from Old English *mæs (“delusion, bewilderment”); akin to Old English āmasian (“to perplex, confound”), Icelandic masa (“to chatter”). More at amaze.

MEADS.d: Plural of MEAD: An alcoholic drink fermented from honey and water.
MEADS.e:
From Middle English mede, from Old English medu, from Proto-West Germanic *medu, from Proto-Germanic *meduz, from Proto-Indo-European *médʰu (“honey; honey wine”).
Cognate with Ancient Greek μέθυ (méthu) (whence English methyl), Lithuanian medùs, Old Church Slavonic медъ (medŭ, “...

MEALS.d: Plural of MEAL: Food that is prepared and eaten, usually at a specific time, and usually in a comparatively large quantity (as opposed to a snack).
MEALS.e:
From Middle English mel, from Old English mǣl (“measure, time, occasion, set time, time for eating, meal”), from Proto-West Germanic *māl, from Proto-Germanic *mēlą, from Proto-Indo-European *meh₁- (“to measure”).
Cognate with West Frisian miel, Dutch maal (“meal, time, occurrenc...

MEANS.e: From Middle English menen (“to intend; remember; lament; comfort”), from Old English mǣnan (“to mean, complain”), Proto-West Germanic *mainijan, from Proto-Germanic *mainijaną (“to mean, think; complain”), from Proto-Indo-European *meyn- (“to think”), or perhaps from Proto-Indo-E...

MEATS.d: Plural of MEAT: The flesh (muscle tissue) of an animal used as food, or a food designed to replicate its taste and texture (like plant-based meat).
MEATS.e: From Middle English mete, from Old English mete (“food”), from Proto-West Germanic *mati, from Proto-Germanic *matiz (“food”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to drip, ooze; grease, fat”). Cognate with West Frisian mete, Old Saxon meti, Old High German maz (“food”), Icelandic ...

MEEDS.d: Plural of MEED: A payment or recompense made for services rendered or in recognition of some achievement; reward; award.
MEEDS.e:
From Middle English meede, mede, from Old English mēd, meord, meard, meorþ (“meed, reward, pay, price, compensation, bribe”), from Proto-West Germanic *miʀdu, from Proto-Germanic *mizdō (“meed”), from Proto-Indo-European *misdʰéh₂, from Proto-Indo-European *mey- (“to exchange”).
...

MEEKS.d: Plural of MEEK: Humble, non-boastful, modest, meager, or self-effacing.
MEEKS.e: From Middle English meek, meke, meoc, unknown origin, likely related to Old English smēag (“subtle, stealthy, etc.”) and smūgan and possibly a borrowing from Old Norse mjúkr (“soft; meek”), from Proto-Germanic *meukaz, *mūkaz (“soft; supple”), from Proto-Indo-European *mewg-, *me...

MEETS.d: Plural of MEET: To make contact (with someone) while in proximity.
MEETS.e:
From Middle English meten, from Old English mētan (“to meet, find, encounter”), from Proto-West Germanic *mōtijan (“to meet”), from Proto-Germanic *mōtijaną (“to meet”), from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to come, meet”).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots met, mete, meit (“to meet”), N...

MELDS.d: Plural of MELD: To combine (multiple things) together; to blend, to fuse.
MELDS.e:
The verb is probably derived:
* from a blend of melt + weld; or
* from melled (“blended; mingled”), the past participle of mell.
The noun is derived from the verb.
Compare also melting pot.

MELTS.d: Plural of MELT: To change (or to be changed) from a solid state to a liquid state, usually by a gradual heat.
MELTS.e: From Middle English melten, from a merger of Old English meltan (intransitive) and mieltan (transitive), both meaning “to melt, digest,” from Proto-West Germanic *meltan and *maltijan, from Proto-Germanic *meltaną and *maltijaną, both from Proto-Indo-European *(s)meld- (“melt”). ...

MEMOS.d: Plural of MEMO: A short note; a memorandum.

MENDS.d: Plural of MEND: To physically repair (something that is broken, defaced, decayed, torn, or otherwise damaged).
MENDS.e: From Middle English menden (“to cure; to do good to, benefit; to do or make better, improve; to get better, recover; to keep in a good state; to put right, amend; to reform, repent”), the aphetic form of amenden (“to alter, change (especially for the better); to atone; to chastis...

MENUS.d: Plural of MENU: The details of the food to be served at a banquet; a bill of fare.
MENUS.e: Borrowed from French menu. Doublet of menudo and minute.

MEOWS.d: Plural of MEOW: Used to indicate the cry of a cat.
MEOWS.e:
Alteration of earlier mew, from Middle English mewen, mouwen (“to mew, meow”), of onomatopoeic origin.
Compare Saterland Frisian mauje, miauje (“to meow”), West Frisian miaukje (“to meow”), Dutch miauwen (“to meow”), Middle Low German mauwen, mawen, mouwen (“to meow”) (whence mod...

MERED.d: Past tense of MERE: Just, only; no more than, pure and simple, neither more nor better than might be expected.
MERED.e:
From Middle English mere, mer, from Anglo-Norman meer, from Old French mier, from Latin merus (“pure, unmixed, undiluted”), from Proto-Indo-European *mer- (“to sparkle, gleam”).
Cognate with Old English āmerian, āmyrian (“to purify, examine, revise”). The Middle English word was ...

MERES.d: Plural of MERE: Just, only; no more than, pure and simple, neither more nor better than might be expected.
MERES.e:
From Middle English mere, mer, from Anglo-Norman meer, from Old French mier, from Latin merus (“pure, unmixed, undiluted”), from Proto-Indo-European *mer- (“to sparkle, gleam”).
Cognate with Old English āmerian, āmyrian (“to purify, examine, revise”). The Middle English word was ...

MESAS.d: Plural of MESA: Flat area of land or plateau higher than other land, with one or more clifflike edges.
MESAS.e: First attested 1759, from Spanish mesa (“table”), from Latin mēnsa. Doublet of mensa.

METAL.d: A solid material that conducts heat and electricity.
METAL.e: From Old French metal, from Latin metallum.

METED.d: Past tense of METE: To dispense, measure in order to dispense, allot (especially punishment, reward etc.).
METED.e:
From Middle English meten, from Old English metan (“to measure, mete out, mark off, compare, estimate; pass over, traverse”), from Proto-West Germanic *metan, from Proto-Germanic *metaną (“to measure”), from Proto-Indo-European *med- (“to measure, consider”).
Cognate with Scots m...

METES.d: Plural of METE: To dispense, measure in order to dispense, allot (especially punishment, reward etc.).
METES.e:
From Middle English meten, from Old English metan (“to measure, mete out, mark off, compare, estimate; pass over, traverse”), from Proto-West Germanic *metan, from Proto-Germanic *metaną (“to measure”), from Proto-Indo-European *med- (“to measure, consider”).
Cognate with Scots m...

METHS.d: Plural of METH: Methamphetamine, especially in the form of the crystalline hydrochloride.

MEWED.d: Past tense of MEW: A gull, seagull.
MEWED.e: From Middle English mewe, mowe, meau, from Old English mǣw (“seagull”), from Proto-West Germanic *maiwī, from Proto-Germanic *mai(h)waz (“seagull”). See also West Frisian meau, miuw, Dutch meeuw, German Möwe (whence Polish mewa); akin to Latvian maût (“to roar”), Old Church Slavo...

MEWLS.d: Plural of MEWL: To cry weakly with a soft, high-pitched sound; to whimper; to whine.
MEWLS.e: From 1599 or earlier (1530 in a Scottish document), apparently from Shakespeare with this spelling. Perhaps from Middle English mewen (“to whimper”) + -le (frequentative suffix).

MICAS.d: Plural of MICA: Any of a group of hydrous aluminosilicate minerals characterized by highly perfect cleavage, so that they readily separate into very thin leaves, more or less elastic.

MICKS.e: From a common Irish name Michael.

MIDIS.d: Plural of MIDI: Abbreviation of Musical Instrument Digital Interface.

MIENS.d: Plural of MIEN: Demeanor; facial expression or attitude, especially one which is intended by its bearer.
MIENS.e: From French mine (“appearance”) (whence also Danish mine and German Miene), perhaps from Breton min (“face of an animal”), or from Latin minio (“to redden”).

MIFFS.d: Plural of MIFF: A small argument; a quarrel.
MIFFS.e: Compare German muffeln (“grouse, grumble”) and similar German words with similar meanings such as Muff, mupf, Muffel and Dutch moppen (“growl, grouse”). Probably related to mop (“grimace”).

MIKED.d: Past tense of MIKE: A microphone.
MIKED.e: Alteration of mic, clipping of microphone. Attested since 1927.

MIKES.e: Alteration of mic, clipping of microphone. Attested since 1927.

MILES.d: Plural of MILE: The international mile: a unit of length precisely equal to 1.609344 kilometers established by treaty among Anglophone nations in 1959, divided into 5,280 feet or 1,760 yards.
MILES.e: From Middle English myle, mile, from Old English mīl, from Proto-West Germanic *mīliju, a borrowing of Latin mīlia, mīllia, plural of mīle, mīlle (“mile”) (literally ‘thousand’ but used as a short form of mīlle passūs (“a thousand paces”)).

MILKS.d: Plural of MILK: A white liquid produced by the mammary glands of female mammals to nourish their young. From certain animals, especially cows, it is also called dairy milk and is a common food for humans as a beverage or used to produce various dairy products such as butter, cheese, and yogurt.
MILKS.e:
From Middle English milk, mylk, melk, mulc, from Old English meolc, meoluc (“milk”), from Proto-West Germanic *meluk, from Proto-Germanic *meluks, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂melǵ-.
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian molke, Dutch melk, Dutch Low Saxon melk, German Milch, German L...

MILLS.d: Plural of MILL: A grinding apparatus for substances such as grains, seeds, etc.
MILLS.e: From Middle English mylne, mille, from Old English mylen, from Proto-West Germanic *mulīnu (“mill”), from Late Latin molīna, molīnum, molīnus (“mill”), from Latin molō (“grind, mill”, verb), closely allied to Proto-Germanic *muljaną (“to crush, grind”) (see English millstone). Pe...

MILTS.d: Plural of MILT: The spleen, especially of an animal bred for food.
MILTS.e: From Middle English milte, from Old English milte, milt (“milt, spleen”), from Proto-West Germanic *miltijā, *meltā, from Proto-Germanic *meltǭ (“spleen”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)meld- (“to beat, grind, crush, weaken”). Cognate with German Milz, Dutch milt, Danish milt, Nor...

MIMED.d: Past tense of MIME: A form of acting without words; pantomime.
MIMED.e: Possibly from Middle English *mime, from Old English mīma (“a buffoon, jester, mime”), from Latin mimus, from Ancient Greek μῖμος (mîmos, “imitator, actor”), but more likely re-borrowed in modern times from French mime (“mimic actor”), from the same source.

MIMES.d: Plural of MIME: A form of acting without words; pantomime.
MIMES.e: Possibly from Middle English *mime, from Old English mīma (“a buffoon, jester, mime”), from Latin mimus, from Ancient Greek μῖμος (mîmos, “imitator, actor”), but more likely re-borrowed in modern times from French mime (“mimic actor”), from the same source.

MINDS.d: Plural of MIND: The capability for rational thought.
MINDS.e: From Middle English minde, munde, imynde, imunde, ȝemynde, ȝemunde, from Old English mynd, ġemynd (“mind, memory”), from Proto-West Germanic *mundi, *gamundi, from Proto-Germanic *mundiz, *gamundiz (“memory, remembrance”), from Proto-Indo-European *méntis (“thought”) (compare als...

MINED.d: Past tense of MINE: That or those belonging to me.
MINED.e:
From Middle English min, myn, from Old English mīn, from Proto-West Germanic *mīn, from Proto-Germanic *mīnaz, from Proto-Indo-European *méynos.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian mien, West Frisian myn, Dutch mijn, Low German mien, German mein, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian min, Ice...

MINES.d: Plural of MINE: That or those belonging to me.
MINES.e:
From Middle English min, myn, from Old English mīn, from Proto-West Germanic *mīn, from Proto-Germanic *mīnaz, from Proto-Indo-European *méynos.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian mien, West Frisian myn, Dutch mijn, Low German mien, German mein, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian min, Ice...

MINIS.d: Plural of MINI: Miniature, tiny, small.

MINKS.d: Plural of MINK: Any semi-aquatic, carnivorous mammal in the Mustelinae subfamily, similar to weasels, with dark fur, native to Europe and America, of which two species in different genera are extant: the American mink (Neogale vison) and the European mink (Mustela lutreola).
MINKS.e: From Late Middle English mynk (“fur of the European mink”), apparently from Swedish mink, mänk, menk (“stinking animal in Finland, mink”). Compare Danish mink (“mink”), Icelandic minkur (“mink”).

MINOR.d: Lesser in importance; a person under legal age.

MINTS.d: Plural of MINT: A building or institution where money (originally, only coins) is produced under government licence.
MINTS.e: From Middle English mynt, münet (“money, coin”), from Old English mynet (“coin”), from late Proto-West Germanic *munit, from Latin monēta (“place for making coins, coined money”), from the temple of Juno Moneta (named for Monēta mother of the Muses), where coins were made. Double...

MIRED.d: Past tense of MIRE: Deep mud; moist, spongy earth.
MIRED.e: From Middle English mire, a borrowing from Old Norse mýrr, from Proto-Germanic *miuzijō, whence also Swedish myr, Norwegian myr, Icelandic mýri, Dutch *mier (in placenames, for example Mierlo). Related to Proto-Germanic *meusą, whence Old English mēos, and Proto-Germanic *musą, w...

MIRES.d: Plural of MIRE: Deep mud; moist, spongy earth.
MIRES.e: From Middle English mire, a borrowing from Old Norse mýrr, from Proto-Germanic *miuzijō, whence also Swedish myr, Norwegian myr, Icelandic mýri, Dutch *mier (in placenames, for example Mierlo). Related to Proto-Germanic *meusą, whence Old English mēos, and Proto-Germanic *musą, w...

MIRKS.d: Plural of MIRK: Archaic spelling of murk.

MISTS.d: Plural of MIST: Water or other liquid finely suspended in air. (Compare fog, haze.)
MISTS.e: The noun is from Middle English mist, from Old English mist (“mist; darkness; dimness (of eyesight)”), from Proto-Germanic *mihstaz (“mist, fog”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃migʰstos, from the root *h₃meygʰ- (“cloud, fog, drizzle”). Cognate with Scots mist (“mist, fog”), West Fr...

MITES.d: Plural of MITE: Any of many minute arachnids which, along with the ticks, comprise subclass Acarina (aka Acari).
MITES.e: From Middle English mite, from Old English mīte (“mite, tiny insect”), from Proto-West Germanic *mītā, from Proto-Germanic *mītǭ (“biting insect”, literally “cutter”), from *maitaną (“to cut”), from Proto-Indo-European *mey- (“small”) or *meh₂y- (“to cut”). Akin to Old High Germa...

MIXES.d: Plural of MIX: To stir together.
MIXES.e:
From Middle English mixen (attested in past tense as mixed, myxyd), from Old English *mixian, miscian, from Proto-West Germanic *miskijan, from Proto-Germanic *miskijaną, from Proto-Indo-European *miḱ-sḱé-ti, from *meyǵ-, *meyḱ- (“to mix”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian miskje (...

MOANS.d: Plural of MOAN: A low, mournful cry of pain, sorrow or pleasure.
MOANS.e:
From Middle English mone, mane, mān, (also as mene), from Old English *mān, *mǣn (“complaint; lamentation”), from Proto-West Germanic *mainu, from Proto-Germanic *mainō (“opinion; mind”).
Cognate with Old Frisian mēne (“opinion”), Old High German meina (“opinion”). Old English *m...

MOATS.d: Plural of MOAT: A deep, wide defensive ditch, normally filled with water, surrounding a fortified habitation.
MOATS.e: From Middle English mote, from Old French mote (“mound, embankment”); compare also Old French motte (“hillock, lump, clod, turf”), from Medieval Latin mota (“a mound, hill”), of Germanic origin, perhaps via Frankish *mot, *motta (“mud, peat, bog, turf”), from Proto-Germanic *mutô...

MOBED.d: Past tense of MOB: A large or disorderly group of people; especially one bent on riotous or destructive action.
MOBED.e: From Middle English mob, short for mobile, from Latin mōbile (vulgus) (“fickle (crowd)”). The video-gaming sense originates from English mobile, used by Richard Bartle for objects capable of movement in an early MUD.

MOCKS.d: Plural of MOCK: An imitation, usually of lesser quality.
MOCKS.e: From Middle English mokken, from Old French mocquer, moquier (“to deride, jeer”), from Middle Dutch mocken (“to mumble”) or Middle Low German mucken (“to grumble, talk with the mouth half-opened”), both from Proto-West Germanic *mokkijan, *mukkijan (“to low, bellow; mumble”), fro...

MODEL.d: A representation; a person who poses.
MODEL.e: From Italian modello, from Latin modulus.

MODES.d: Plural of MODE: One of several common scales in modern Western music, one of which corresponds to the modern major scale and one to the natural minor scale.
MODES.e: From Old French mode (masculine), from Latin modus (“measure, due measure, rhythm, melody”). Doublet of modus.

MOILS.d: Plural of MOIL: To toil, to work hard.
MOILS.e: From Middle English mollen (“to soften by wetting”), borrowed from Old French moillier with the same meaning, from Vulgar Latin *molliō, *molliare, from mollis (“soft”).

MOKES.e: Unknown. In the sense of a variety performer, comes from "The Lively Moke" (or "Musical Moke"), an 1860s blackface song, dance and multi-instrumental routine popularized by Johnny Thompson, William J. "Billy" Ashcroft and others.

MOLES.d: Plural of MOLE: A naevus, a pigmented, slightly raised, and sometimes hairy spot on the skin.
MOLES.e:
From Middle English mole, mool, from Old English māl (“a mole, spot, mark, blemish”), from Proto-West Germanic *mail, from Proto-Germanic *mailą (“spot, wrinkle”), from Proto-Indo-European *mel-, *melw- (“dark, dirty”), from Proto-Indo-European *mey-, *my- (“to soil, sully”).
Cog...

MOLLS.d: Plural of MOLL: A female companion of a gangster, especially a former or current prostitute.
MOLLS.e: From Moll, an archaic nickname for Mary (see also Molly).

MONEY.e: From Old French moneie, from Latin monēta.

MONKS.d: Plural of MONK: A male member of a monastic order who has devoted his life for religious service.
MONKS.e: From Middle English monk, from Old English munuc, from Proto-West Germanic *munik, from Late Latin monicus, variant of monachus, from Ancient Greek μοναχός (monakhós, “single, solitary”), from μόνος (mónos, “alone”).

MONOS.d: Plural of MONO: A bicycle or motorcycle trick where the front wheel is lifted off the ground while riding.
MONOS.e: Shortenings, ultimately from the prefix mono- (“one, single”).

MONTH.e: From Old English mōnaþ, related to moon.

MOODS.d: Plural of MOOD: A mental or emotional state, composure.
MOODS.e: From Middle English mood, mode, mod, from Old English mōd (“mind,” in poetry also “heart, spirit, courage”), from Proto-West Germanic *mōd, from Proto-Germanic *mōdaz (“sense, courage, zeal, anger”), from Proto-Indo-European *moh₁-, *meh₁- (“endeavour, will, temper”). Cognate wit...

MOOED.d: Past tense of MOO: The characteristic lowing sound made by cattle.

MOONS.d: Plural of MOON: Alternative letter-case form of Moon (“the Earth's only permanent natural satellite”).
MOONS.e:
From Middle English mone, from Old English mōna (“moon”), from Proto-West Germanic *mānō, from Proto-Germanic *mēnô (“moon”), from Proto-Indo-European *mḗh₁n̥s (“moon, month”), probably from *meh₁- (“to measure”).
cognates and doublets
Cognate with Scots mone, mune, muin (“moon”)...

MOORS.d: Plural of MOOR: An extensive waste covered with patches of heath, and having a poor, light (and usually acidic) soil, but sometimes marshy, and abounding in peat; a heath. (Compare bog, peatland, marsh, swamp, fen.)
MOORS.e: From Middle English mor, from Old English mōr, from Proto-West Germanic *mōr, from Proto-Germanic *mōraz, from Proto-Indo-European *móri. Cognates include Welsh môr, Old Irish muir (from Proto-Celtic *mori); Scots muir, Dutch moer, Old Saxon mōr, Old Saxon mūr, German Moor and pe...

MOOTS.d: Plural of MOOT: Subject to discussion (originally at a moot); arguable, debatable, unsolved or impossible to solve.
MOOTS.e: From Middle English mōt, ȝemōt, from Old English *mōt, ġemōt (“meeting”), from Proto-Germanic *mōtą, from Proto-Indo-European *meh₂d- (“to encounter, come”). Cognate with Scots mut, mote (“meeting, assembly”), Low German Mööt (“meeting”), Moot (“meeting”), archaic Dutch (ge)moet ...

MOPED.d: Past tense of MOPE: To carry oneself in a depressed, lackadaisical manner; to give oneself up to low spirits; to pout, sulk.
MOPED.e:
Late Middle English (as a noun meaning "simpleton, fool"), probably related to mop (“young of an animal, moppet”).
Alternatively, of North Germanic origin, related to Swedish mopa (“to sulk”), Danish måbe, themselves borrowed from Low German mopen (“to make faces, gape”), of unce...

MOPES.d: Plural of MOPE: To carry oneself in a depressed, lackadaisical manner; to give oneself up to low spirits; to pout, sulk.
MOPES.e:
Late Middle English (as a noun meaning "simpleton, fool"), probably related to mop (“young of an animal, moppet”).
Alternatively, of North Germanic origin, related to Swedish mopa (“to sulk”), Danish måbe, themselves borrowed from Low German mopen (“to make faces, gape”), of unce...

MORES.d: Plural of MORE: comparative degree of many: in greater number. (Used for a discrete quantity.)
MORES.e:
From Middle English more, from Old English māra (“more”), from Proto-West Germanic *maiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *maizô (“more”), from Proto-Indo-European *mē- (“many”).
Cognate with Scots mair (“more”), Saterland Frisian moor (“more”), West Frisian mear (“more”), Dutch meer (“more...

MORNS.e:
From Middle English morn, morwen, from Old English morgen, from Proto-West Germanic *morgan, *morgin, from Proto-Germanic *murganaz, *murginaz, from Proto-Indo-European *mr̥kéno, *mr̥kóno, from Proto-Indo-European *mr̥Hko, from *mer- (“to shimmer, glisten”).
See also West Frisian...

MOSES.d: Plural of MOS: Alternative letter-case form of MOS (“manual of style”).

MOSTS.d: Plural of MOST: superlative degree of much.
MOSTS.e: From Middle English most, moste, from Old English mǣst, māst, from Proto-Germanic *maistaz, *maist. Cognate with Scots mast, maist (“most”), Saterland Frisian maast (“most”), West Frisian meast (“most”), Dutch meest (“most”), German meist (“most”), Danish and Swedish mest (“most”...

MOTED.d: Past tense of MOTE: A small particle; a speck.
MOTED.e:
From Middle English mot, from Old English mot (“grain of sand; mote; atom”), from Proto-West Germanic *mot (“grain of dirt or sand, speck”). Perhaps linked to and English mud.
Compare West Frisian mot (“peat dust”), Dutch mot (“dust from turf; sawdust; grit”), Low German mut (“pe...

MOTES.d: Plural of MOTE: A small particle; a speck.
MOTES.e:
From Middle English mot, from Old English mot (“grain of sand; mote; atom”), from Proto-West Germanic *mot (“grain of dirt or sand, speck”). Perhaps linked to and English mud.
Compare West Frisian mot (“peat dust”), Dutch mot (“dust from turf; sawdust; grit”), Low German mut (“pe...

MOTHS.d: Plural of MOTH: Any flying insect of the order Lepidoptera not in the superfamily Papilionoidea, most species of which are nocturnal and can be distinguished from butterflies by feather-like antennae.
MOTHS.e: From Middle English moth, moththe, motthe, moght, mohþe, mouȝte, from Old English moþþe, mohþe, mohþa (“any destructive insect larva”), from Proto-West Germanic *moþþō, *mottō, from Proto-Germanic *muþþô, *muttô (“moth, worm”), from Proto-Indo-European *mutn-, *mut- (“worm”). Cog...

MOUES.d: Plural of MOUE: A pout, especially as expressing mock-annoyance or flirtatiousness.
MOUES.e: Borrowed from French moue, from Old French moe (“grimace”), from Frankish *mauwa (“pout, protruding lip”). Doublet of mow ("grimace").

MOUNT.e: From Old French mont, from Latin mōns.

MOUSE.d: A small rodent; a computer input device.

MOUTH.d: The opening in the face for eating and speaking.

MOVES.d: Plural of MOVE: To change place or posture; to go, in any manner, from one place or position to another.
MOVES.e: From Middle English moven, moeven, meven, borrowed from Old Northern French mover, moveir and Old French mouver, moveir (“to move”) (compare modern French mouvoir from Old French movoir), from Latin movēre (“move; change, exchange, go in or out, quit”), from Proto-Indo-European *...

MUCKS.d: Plural of MUCK: Slimy mud, sludge.
MUCKS.e: From Middle English mok, muk, from Old Norse myki, mykr (“dung”) or less likely Old English *moc, *moce (in hlōsmoc (“pigsty dung”) and lustmoce (“lady's smock (Cardamine pratensis)”)) (compare Icelandic mykja and Danish møg ("dung")), from Proto-Germanic *mukį̄ (“dung; manure”),...

MUFFS.d: Plural of MUFF: A piece of fur or cloth, usually with open ends, used for keeping the hands warm.

MULED.d: Past tense of MULE: The generally sterile male or female hybrid offspring of a male donkey and a female horse.
MULED.e: From Middle English mule, from Anglo-Norman mule and Old English mūl, both from Latin mūlus, from Proto-Indo-European *mukslós. Compare Late Latin muscellus (“young he-mule”), Old East Slavic мъшкъ (mŭškŭ, “mule”), Ancient Greek (Phocian) μυχλός (mukhlós, “he-ass”), and German Ma...

MULES.d: Plural of MULE: The generally sterile male or female hybrid offspring of a male donkey and a female horse.
MULES.e: From Middle English mule, from Anglo-Norman mule and Old English mūl, both from Latin mūlus, from Proto-Indo-European *mukslós. Compare Late Latin muscellus (“young he-mule”), Old East Slavic мъшкъ (mŭškŭ, “mule”), Ancient Greek (Phocian) μυχλός (mukhlós, “he-ass”), and German Ma...

MULLS.d: Plural of MULL: To work (over) mentally; to cogitate; to ruminate.
MULLS.e: Inherited from Middle English molle, mulle (“dust, rubbish”), possibly from Old English myl (“dust, mould”), from Proto-West Germanic *muli, a deverbal formation from *mulljan and thus cognate with Dutch mul (“dust, mould”), German Müll (“rubbish”), Swedish moln (“cloud”) and rel...

MUONS.d: Plural of MUON: An unstable elementary particle in the lepton family, having similar properties to the electron but with a mass 207 times greater.
MUONS.e: Contraction of the earlier term mu-meson; the particle has now been recategorised as a lepton. Coined by Italian physicist Enrico Fermi in 1951 in his book Elementary Particles.

MURKS.e: From Middle English merke, mirke, from Old English mirce, myrce (“dark, gloomy, evil”) and Old Norse myrkr (“dark, murky”), both from Proto-Germanic *merkuz (“dark”), from Proto-Indo-European *mergʷ- (“to flicker; to darken; to be dark”). Cognate Danish mørk (“dark”), Norwegian m...

MUSED.d: Past tense of MUSE: Of a person: a source of inspiration.
MUSED.e: From Middle French muse, from Latin Mūsa, from Ancient Greek Μοῦσα (Moûsa).

MUSES.d: Plural of MUS: plural of mu

MUSIC.d: Vocal or instrumental sounds combined pleasingly.
MUSIC.e: From Old French musique, from Latin mūsica, from Greek mousikḗ.

MUSKS.d: Plural of MUSK: A greasy secretion with a powerful odour, produced in a glandular sac of the male musk deer and used in the manufacture of perfumes.
MUSKS.e: From Middle English muske, borrowed from Old French musc, from Late Latin muscus, from Ancient Greek μόσχος (móskhos), from Middle Persian [script needed] (mwšk' /⁠muʃk⁠/) whence Persian مشک (mošk). Ultimately from Sanskrit मुष्क (muṣka, “testicle”), the shape of the gland of ani...

MUSTS.d: Plural of MUST: To do as a requirement; indicates that the sentence subject is required as an imperative or directive to execute the sentence predicate, with failure to do so resulting in a failure or negative consequence.
MUSTS.e: From Middle English moste ("must", literally, "had to", the past tense of Middle English moten (“to have to”)), from Old English mōste (“had to”), 1st & 3rd person singular past tense of mōtan (“to be allowed, be able to, have the opportunity to, be compelled to, must, may”), fro...

MUTED.d: Past tense of MUTE: Not having the power of speech; dumb.
MUTED.e: From Middle English muet, from Anglo-Norman muet, moet, Middle French muet, from mu (“dumb, mute”) + -et, remodelled after Latin mūtus.

MUTES.d: Plural of MUTE: Not having the power of speech; dumb.
MUTES.e: From Middle English muet, from Anglo-Norman muet, moet, Middle French muet, from mu (“dumb, mute”) + -et, remodelled after Latin mūtus.

MUTTS.d: Plural of MUTT: A mongrel dog (or sometimes cat); an animal of mixed breed or uncertain origin.

MYNAS.d: Plural of MYNA: One of the South and East Asian birds of the starling family Sturnidae.
MYNAS.e: Borrowed from Hindi मैना (mainā) / Urdu مینا (mainā), from Sanskrit मदन (madana).

MYTHS.d: Plural of MYTH: A traditional story which embodies a belief regarding some fact or phenomenon of experience, and in which often the forces of nature and of the soul are personified; a sacred narrative regarding a god, a hero, the origin of the world or of a people, etc.
MYTHS.e: From Ancient Greek μῦθος (mûthos, “word, humour, companion, speech, account, rumour, fable”). Attested in English since 1830. Doublet of mythos.

NAIFS.d: Plural of NAIF: Alternative spelling of naïf.

NAILS.d: Plural of NAIL: The thin, horny plate at the ends of fingers and toes on humans and some other animals.
NAILS.e:
From Middle English nail, nayl, Old English næġl, from Proto-West Germanic *nagl, from Proto-Germanic *naglaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃nogʰ- (“nail”).
Cognates
Compare North Frisian Nail (“nail”), Saterland Frisian Nail (“nail”), West Frisian neil, Low German Nagel, Dutch nag...

NAMED.d: Past tense of NAME: Any nounal word or phrase which indicates a particular person, place, class, or thing.
NAMED.e:
PIE word
 *h₁nómn̥
From Middle English name, nome, from Old English nama, noma, from Proto-West Germanic *namō, from Proto-Germanic *namô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁nómn̥.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola naame, name, naume (“name”), North Frisian Noom, noome, nööm (“name”), Saterlan...

NAMES.d: Plural of NAME: Any nounal word or phrase which indicates a particular person, place, class, or thing.
NAMES.e:
PIE word
 *h₁nómn̥
From Middle English name, nome, from Old English nama, noma, from Proto-West Germanic *namō, from Proto-Germanic *namô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁nómn̥.
Cognates
Cognate with Yola naame, name, naume (“name”), North Frisian Noom, noome, nööm (“name”), Saterlan...

NAPES.d: Plural of NAPE: The back part of the neck.
NAPES.e: From Middle English nape, naape, of uncertain origin. Possibly from Old French hanap (“goblet”), from Frankish *hnapp, from Proto-Germanic *hnappaz ( > Old English hnæpp, hnæp (“cup, bowl, goblet”)), as there is a hollow at the base of the skull. More at nap.

NARDS.d: Plural of NARD: A flowering plant of species Nardostachys jatamansi, in the valerian family, that grows in the Himalayas and is used as a perfume, an incense, a sedative, and an herbal medicine.
NARDS.e: From Middle English narde, from Old French narde, Latin nardus, from Ancient Greek νάρδος (nárdos), from Phoenician [Term?], Sanskrit नलद (nálada, “Indian narde”). Doublet of nardus.

NARKS.d: Plural of NARK: A police spy or informer.
NARKS.e: Uncertain. Perhaps from Angloromani nok (“nose”), from Romani nakh, from Sauraseni Prakrit 𑀡𑀓𑁆𑀓 (ṇakka), ultimately a doublet of nose.

NEAPS.d: Plural of NEAP: The tongue or pole of a cart or other vehicle drawn by two animals.
NEAPS.e: Perhaps of Scandinavian origin: compare dialectal Norwegian neip (“forked pole”).

NEARS.e: From Middle English nere, ner, from Old English nēar (“nearer”, comparative of nēah (“nigh”), the superlative would become next), influenced by Old Norse nær (“near”), both originating from Proto-Germanic *nēhwiz (“nearer”), comparative of the adverb *nēhw (“near”), from the adje...

NEATS.d: Plural of NEAT: Clean, tidy; free from dirt or impurities.
NEATS.e: From Middle English nete, net, nette, from Anglo-Norman neit (“good, desirable, clean”), a variant of Old French net, nette (“clean, clear, pure”), from Latin nitidus (“gleaming”), derived from nitēre (“to shine”). Doublet of net and nitid. Cognate with German nett (“nice, kind”)...

NECKS.d: Plural of NECK: The part of the body connecting the head and the trunk found in humans and some animals.
NECKS.e: From Middle English nekke, nakke, from Old English hnecca, *hnæcca (“neck, nape”), from Proto-Germanic *hnakkô (“nape, neck”), from Proto-Indo-European *knog-, *kneg- (“back of the head, nape, neck”). Cognate with Scots nek (“neck”), North Frisian neek, neeke, Nak (“neck”), Sater...

NEEDS.d: Plural of NEED: A requirement for something; something needed.
NEEDS.e:
From Middle English need, nede, a merger of two terms:
* Old English nīed (West Saxon), nēd (Mercian), nēad (“necessity, compulsion, want”), from Proto-West Germanic *naudi, from Proto-Germanic *naudiz, from Proto-Indo-European *neh₂w- (“death”).
* Old English nēod (“desire, long...

NEEPS.d: Plural of NEEP: The swede (rutabaga); turnip.
NEEPS.e:
From Middle English neep, from Old English nǣp (“turnip, rape”), borrowed from Latin nāpus. Compare Icelandic næpa (“turnip”).
Cognate with English turnip.

NENES.d: Plural of NENE: The Hawaiian goose, Branta sandvicensis, which was designated the state bird of Hawaii in 1957.
NENES.e: Borrowed from Hawaiian nēnē, which is imitative of the bird’s call.

NEONS.d: Plural of NEON: The chemical element (symbol Ne) with an atomic number of 10. The second of the noble gases, it is a colourless, odorless inert gas.
NEONS.e: Learned borrowing from Ancient Greek νέον (néon), neuter of νέος (néos, “new”), from earlier *νέϝος (*néwos), from Proto-Hellenic *newos, from Proto-Indo-European *néwos. By surface analysis, neo- + -on (suffix used in all noble gases).

NERDS.d: Plural of NERD: A person who is intellectual but generally introverted.
NERDS.e:
Unknown. Attested since 1951 as US student slang.
* Perhaps an alteration of nerts (“nuts", "crazy”); see references below.
* The word, capitalized, appeared in 1950 in Dr. Seuss’s If I Ran the Zoo as the name of an imaginary animal:
*: And then, just to show them, I’ll sail to K...

NESTS.d: Plural of NEST: A structure built by a bird as a place to incubate eggs and rear young.
NESTS.e: From Middle English nest, nist, nyst, from Old English nest, from Proto-West Germanic *nest, from Proto-Germanic *nestą, from Proto-Indo-European *nisdós (“nest”), literally "where [the bird] sits down", a compound of *ni (“down”) (whence also English nether) + the zero-grade of ...

NETTS.d: Plural of NETT: Alternative spelling of net (remaining after expenses or deductions).

NEWTS.d: Plural of NEWT: A small lizard-like amphibian in the subfamily Pleurodelinae that lives in the water as an adult.
NEWTS.e: From Middle English newte, newete, from rebracketing of Middle English an ewte as a newte (for similar misdivisions compare adder, nickname, apron, umpire, etc.). Middle English evete, eute, euete, ewte (“newt”), derives from Old English efete (“lizard; newt”). Doublet of eft.

NICKS.d: Plural of NICK: A small cut in a surface.
NICKS.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English nik (“notch, tally; nock of an arrow”). Its further etymology is unknown; a connection with nock (“notch in a bow to hold the bowstring; notch at the rear of an arrow that fits the bowstring; cleft in the buttocks”) has not been clearl...

NINES.d: Plural of NINE: A numerical value equal to 9; the number following eight and preceding ten.
NINES.e:
PIE word
 *h₁néwn̥
From Middle English nyne, nine, from Old English nigon (“nine”), from Proto-West Germanic *neun, from Proto-Germanic *newun (“nine”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁néwn̥ (“nine”). Cognate with Scots neen, nine (“nine”), Saterland Frisian njúgen (“nine”), West Fri...

NIPAS.d: Plural of NIPA: Initialism of National Income and Product Accounts.

NIXES.e: From German nix, colloquial form of nichts (“nothing”). Compare also Dutch niks (“nothing”), informal for niets (“nothing”). More at naught.

NOCKS.d: Plural of NOCK: Either of the two grooves in a bow that hold the bowstring.
NOCKS.e: From Middle English nokke, attested since the 14th century, probably from a Scandinavian/North Germanic language (compare Swedish nock (“notch”), but compare Dutch nok, from Middle Dutch nocke (“tip, point”). Both could be related to nook (“corner, recess”).

NODED.d: Past tense of NODE: A knot, knob, protuberance or swelling.
NODED.e: From Middle English node, borrowed from Latin nōdus. Doublet of knot, knout, and nodus.

NODES.d: Plural of NODE: A knot, knob, protuberance or swelling.
NODES.e: From Middle English node, borrowed from Latin nōdus. Doublet of knot, knout, and nodus.

NOILS.d: Plural of NOIL: A short fibre left over from combing wool or spinning silk during the preparation of textile yarns. Sometimes it is referred to as 'Raw Silk', although this is somewhat of a misnomer.
NOILS.e: Inherited from Middle English *noyel, from Old French noiel, variant of noel, from either Early Medieval Latin nōdellus (“buckle”, diminutive of nōdus "knot") or Late Latin nucālis (“nut-like”, derivative of nux "nut"). Doublet of newel and noyau.

NONES.d: Plural of NONE: Not any of a given number or group.
NONES.e: From Middle English none, noon, non (“not one”), from Old English nān (“not one, not any, none”), from Proto-West Germanic *nain, from Proto-Germanic *nainaz (“none, nought, nothing”), equivalent to ne (“not”) + one. (Regarding the different phonological development of only and o...

NOOKS.d: Plural of NOOK: A small corner formed by two walls; an alcove.
NOOKS.e: From Middle English noke, nok (“nook, corner, angle”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old English hnoc, hnocc (“hook, angle”), from Proto-Germanic *hnukkaz, *hnukkô (“a bend”), from Proto-Indo-European *knewg- (“to turn, press”), from Proto-Indo-European *ken- (“to pinch, pres...

NOONS.d: Plural of NOON: The time of day when the Sun seems to reach its highest point in the sky; solar noon.
NOONS.e: From Middle English noen, none, non, from Old English nōn (“the ninth hour”), from a Germanic borrowing of classical Latin nōna (“ninth hour”) (short for nōna hōra), feminine of nōnus (“ninth”). Cognate with Dutch noen, obsolete German Non, Norwegian non.

NORMS.d: Plural of NORM: That which is normal or typical.
NORMS.e: From Latin norma (“a carpenter's square, a rule, a pattern, a precept”). Doublet of norma.

NORTH.d: The direction to the left when facing east.

NOSED.d: Past tense of NOSE: A protuberance on the face housing the nostrils, which are used to breathe or smell.
NOSED.e:
From Middle English nose, from Old English nosu, from Proto-West Germanic *nosu, variant of *nasō, old dual from Proto-Indo-European *néh₂s- ~ *nh₂es- (“nose, nostril”).
See also Saterland Frisian Noose, West Frisian noas, Dutch neus, Swedish nos, Norwegian nos (“snout”), Low Ger...

NOTES.d: Plural of NOTE: A symbol or annotation.
NOTES.e: From Middle English note, from Old English not, nōt (“note, mark, sign”) and Old French note (“letter, note”), both from Latin nota (“mark, sign, remark, note”).

NOUNS.d: Plural of NOUN: A word that functions as the name of a specific object or set of objects, such as person, animal, place, word, thing, phenomenon, substance, quality, or idea: one of the basic parts of speech in many languages, including English.
NOUNS.e: From Middle English noun, from Anglo-Norman noun, non, nom, from Latin nōmen (“name; noun”). The grammatical sense in Latin was a semantic loan from Koine Greek ὄνομα (ónoma). Doublet of name and nomen.

NOVAS.d: Plural of NOVA: Any sudden brightening of a previously inconspicuous star.
NOVAS.e: Feminine nominative singular of Latin novus (“new”). The feminine is used since stella (“star”) is feminine; thus nova is a shortening of nova stella (“new star”), first used in this sense in 1573 by Tycho Brahe.

NOVEL.d: A long fictional story; new and original.

NUDES.d: Plural of NUDE: Without clothing or other covering of the skin; without clothing on the genitals or female nipples.
NUDES.e: Entered English 1493 as a legal term, meaning "unsupported, not formally attested," from Middle English nud, from Latin nūdus (“naked, bare”).

NUKES.d: Plural of NUKE: A nuclear weapon.
NUKES.e: Clipping of nuclear weapon. The verb is derived from the noun.

NULLS.d: Plural of NULL: A non-existent or empty value or set of values.
NULLS.e: Borrowed from Middle French nul, from Latin nūllus.

NUMBS.d: Plural of NUMB: Physically unable to feel, not having the power of sensation.
NUMBS.e: From the past participle of nim (“to take”). Compare German benommen (“dazed, numb”) and Old Norse numinn. The final ⟨b⟩ is a later addition; it was never pronounced, and did not appear in the original word.

NUMPS.d: Plural of NUMP: Alternative form of numps.

OARED.d: Past tense of OAR: A type of lever used to propel a boat, having a flat blade at one end and a handle at the other, and pivoted in a rowlock atop the gunwale, whereby a rower seated in the boat and pulling the handle can pass the blade through the water by repeated strokes against the water's resistance, thus moving the boat.
OARED.e: From Middle English ore (“oar”), from Old English ār, from Proto-West Germanic *airu, from Proto-Germanic *airō (“oar”). Cognate with Old Norse ár.

OATHS.d: Plural of OATH: A solemn pledge or promise that invokes a deity, a ruler, or another entity (not necessarily present) to attest the truth of a statement or sincerity of one's desire to fulfill a contract or promise.
OATHS.e: From Middle English ooth, oth, ath, from Old English āþ (“oath”), from Proto-West Germanic *aiþ (“oath”), from Proto-Germanic *aiþaz (“oath”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁óytos (“oath”). Cognate with Scots aith, athe (“oath”), North Frisian ith, iss (“oath”), Saterland Frisian Ee...

OAVES.d: Plural of OAF: A person, especially a large male, who is clumsy or a simpleton.
OAVES.e: Variant of awf, auf, aufe,, probably from Old Norse álfr (“elf”) (whence Norwegian Bokmål alv). Doublet of alf and elf.

OBEYS.d: Plural of OBEY: To do as ordered by (a person, institution etc), to act according to the bidding of.
OBEYS.e: From Middle English obeyen, from Anglo-Norman obeir, obeier et al., Old French obeir, from Latin oboediō (also obēdiō (“to listen to, harken, usually in extended sense, obey, be subject to, serve”)), from ob- (“before, near”) + audiō (“to hear”). Compare audient. In Latin, ob + a...

OBITS.d: Plural of OBIT: The death of a person.
OBITS.e: From Anglo-Norman obit, Middle French obit, and their source, Latin obitus (“going down; death”), from obīre (“to go down, to die”).

OBOES.d: Plural of OBOE: A soprano and melody wind instrument in the modern orchestra and wind ensemble. It is a smaller instrument and generally made of grenadilla wood. It is a member of the double reed family.
OBOES.e: An earlier form in English is hautboy, but the spelling oboe was adopted into English ca. 1770 from the Italian oboè, a transliteration in that language's orthography of the 17th-century pronunciation of the French word hautbois, a compound word made of haut (“high, loud, high-pi...

OBOLS.d: Plural of OBOL: A silver coin of Ancient Greece.
OBOLS.e: Borrowed from Ancient Greek ὀβολός (obolós) (literally “spit” or “iron rod”). Doublet of obole and pul.

OCCUR.e: From Latin occurrere (to run to meet).

OCEAN.d: A vast body of salt water.
OCEAN.e: From Latin ōceanus, from Greek Ōkeanós.

OFFER.d: To present for acceptance; a proposal.
OFFER.e: From Old English offrian, from Latin offerre.

OGLED.d: Past tense of OGLE: To stare at (someone or something), especially impertinently, amorously, or covetously.
OGLED.e: 17th century. Probably from Low German ögeln (“to ogle, to flirt with one's eyes”), from Middle Low German ö̂gelen, frequentative of Middle Low German ö̂gen, from Old Saxon ōgian, from Proto-West Germanic *augijan (“to show”). Alternatively from an equivalent Dutch *ogelen, but t...

OGLES.d: Plural of OGLE: To stare at (someone or something), especially impertinently, amorously, or covetously.
OGLES.e: 17th century. Probably from Low German ögeln (“to ogle, to flirt with one's eyes”), from Middle Low German ö̂gelen, frequentative of Middle Low German ö̂gen, from Old Saxon ōgian, from Proto-West Germanic *augijan (“to show”). Alternatively from an equivalent Dutch *ogelen, but t...

OGRES.d: Plural of OGRE: A type of brutish giant from folk tales that eats human flesh.
OGRES.e: First attested in the 18th century, borrowed from French ogre, from Latin Orcus (“god of the underworld”), from Ancient Greek Ὅρκος (Hórkos), the personified demon of oaths (ὅρκος (hórkos, “oath”)) who inflicts punishment upon oath-breakers. Doublet of orc and Orcus.

OILED.d: Past tense of OIL: Liquid fat.
OILED.e: From Middle English oyle, oile (“olive oil”), borrowed from Anglo-Norman olie, from Latin oleum (“oil, olive oil”), from Ancient Greek ἔλαιον (élaion, “olive oil”), from ἐλαία (elaía, “olive”). Compare Proto-Slavic *lojь. More at olive. Doublet of oleum. Supplanted Middle English...

OINKS.d: Plural of OINK: Representing the grunting sound made by a pig.

OKAYS.d: Plural of OKAY: Alternative spelling of OK.

OKRAS.d: Plural of OKRA: The edible immature mucilaginous seed pod (properly, capsule) of the Abelmoschus esculentus.
OKRAS.e: From an unknown West African language, probably Igbo ọ́kụ̀rụ̀ but cf. Akan ŋkrũmã and ŋkrakra (“broth”).

OMENS.d: Plural of OMEN: Something which portends or is perceived to portend either a good or evil event or circumstance in the future, or which causes a foreboding; a portent or augury.

OMITS.d: Plural of OMIT: To leave out or exclude.
OMITS.e: At least by 1422, from late Middle English omitten, borrowed from Latin omittō (“to let go”), from ob- + mittō (“to send”), but also had the connotations “to fail to perform” and “to neglect”.

ONCES.d: Plural of ONCE: One and only one time.
ONCES.e: From Middle English ones, from Old English ānes, a remodelling (after ān (“one”)) of ǣnes, itself an extension of ǣne (“once”) with the genitive suffix -es. Compare Old Saxon ēnes (“once”), Old High German eines, einēst (“once”), modern German einst (“once”). More at one (includi...

OOHED.d: Past tense of OOH: An expression of surprise.

OOZED.d: Past tense of OOZE: Tanning liquor, an aqueous extract of vegetable matter (tanbark, sumac, etc.) in a tanning vat used to tan leather.
OOZED.e:
* (Noun) Middle English wose (“sap”), from Old English wōs (“sap, froth”), from Proto-Germanic *wōsą (cf. Middle Low German wose (“scum”), Old High German wasal (“rain”), Old Swedish os, oos), from Proto-Indo-European *wóseh₂ (“sap”) (cf. Sanskrit वसा (vásā, “fat”)).
* (Verb) Mid...

OOZES.d: Plural of OOZE: Tanning liquor, an aqueous extract of vegetable matter (tanbark, sumac, etc.) in a tanning vat used to tan leather.
OOZES.e:
* (Noun) Middle English wose (“sap”), from Old English wōs (“sap, froth”), from Proto-Germanic *wōsą (cf. Middle Low German wose (“scum”), Old High German wasal (“rain”), Old Swedish os, oos), from Proto-Indo-European *wóseh₂ (“sap”) (cf. Sanskrit वसा (vásā, “fat”)).
* (Verb) Mid...

OPAHS.d: Plural of OPAH: Any of various large, colourful, deep-bodied pelagic fish of the family Lamprididae.
OPAHS.e: From Igbo uba. Earliest attestation in English is the Royal Society’s 1752 Philosophical Transactions, 1749–50 (vol. 46, p. 519): “The black Prince, and his Cousin, from Anamaboe on the Coast of Guinea, and Mr. Creighton, formerly Governor of Capo Corso Castle, upon seeing this F...

OPALS.d: Plural of OPAL: A mineral consisting, like quartz, of silica, but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific gravity, of the chemical formula SiO₂·nH₂O.
OPALS.e: In Florio’s A World of Words 1598 as opale, from French opale, from Latin opalus, from Byzantine Greek ὀπάλλιος (opállios), from Sanskrit उपल (upala, “gem, stone”), from उपरि (upári, “the upper millstone”). Distantly related to over.

OPENS.d: Plural of OPEN: Physically unobstructed, uncovered, etc.
OPENS.e:
Adjective from Middle English open, from Old English open (“open”), from Proto-West Germanic *opan, from Proto-Germanic *upanaz (“open”), from Proto-Indo-European *upo (“up from under, over”).
Cognates
* Scots apen (“open”)
* Saterland Frisian eepen (“open”)
* West Frisian iepen ...

OPING.d: Present participle of OPE: An exclamation of surprise; oops.
OPING.e: Representing oh pronounced with the mouth snapped closed at the end (IPA⁽ᵏᵉʸ⁾: /oʊp/, [oʊp̚]) (excrescent /p/). Compare yep, yup, nope, and welp.

OPTED.d: Past tense of OPT: To choose; select.
OPTED.e: First attested in 1853; borrowed from French opter, from Latin optō (“to choose; to select”). Doublet of optate.

ORALS.d: Plural of ORAL: Relating to the mouth.
ORALS.e:
PIE word
 *h₁óh₃s
Early 17th century borrowing from Late Latin ōrālis, from ōs (“the mouth”) + -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix).

ORBED.d: Past tense of ORB: A spherical body; a sphere, especially one of the celestial spheres; a sun, planet, or star
ORBED.e: From Middle English orbe, from Old French orbe, from Latin orbis (“circle, orb”). Compare orbit.

ORCAS.d: Plural of ORCA: A sea mammal (Orcinus orca) related to dolphins and porpoises, commonly called the killer whale.
ORCAS.e: Learned borrowing from Latin orca (“tun, cask; whale”), see there for more. Although the origin is obscure, the sometimes-cited association with orcus (“underworld”) is folk-etymology. Doublet of orc.

ORDER.e: From Old French ordre, from Latin ōrdō.

ORLES.d: Plural of ORLE: A bordure that runs around the outline of a shield without touching the edge.
ORLES.e: From Old French (also modern) orle, from orler (“to hem”), or from Vulgar Latin *orula, a diminutive of Latin ora (“edge”), probably from os, oris (“mouth”).

OUGHT.d: Used to indicate duty or correctness.

OUSTS.d: Plural of OUST: To expel; to remove.
OUSTS.e: From Anglo-Norman ouster, oustier, from Old French oster (modern French ôter), from post-classical Latin obstare (“to remove”), classical obstāre (“to obstruct, stand in the way of”). Not related to out.

OUTED.d: Past tense of OUT: Away from the inside or centre.
OUTED.e: From Middle English out, oute, from a combination of Old English ūt (“out”, preposition & adverb), from Proto-West Germanic *ūt, from Proto-Germanic *ūt (“out”); and Old English ūte (“outside; without”, adverb), from Proto-Germanic *ūtai (“out; outside”); both from Proto-Indo-Eur...

OUZOS.d: Plural of OUZO: An anise-flavoured aperitif, originating in Greece.
OUZOS.e: From Greek ούζο (oúzo), either from Turkish üzüm (“grape”) or from the Italian uso in Marsiglia (“for use in Marseille”) stamped on selected silkworm cocoons exported from Tyrnavos in the 19th century, standing for “superior quality”. Other: from the ancient Greek word ὄζω (ózō, ...

OVALS.d: Plural of OVAL: An elongated round shape resembling an egg or ellipse.
OVALS.e: From Late Latin ovalis, from ovum; cognate with French and Italian ovale, Dutch ovaal. From 1570.

OVENS.d: Plural of OVEN: A chamber used for baking or heating.
OVENS.e: From Middle English oven, from Old English ofn, from Proto-West Germanic *ofn, from Proto-Germanic *uhnaz, *uhwnaz (compare Dutch oven, Low German Aven, West Frisian ûne, German Ofen, Danish ovn, Norwegian Bokmål ovn, Norwegian Nynorsk omn, Swedish ugn, Icelandic ofn, Finnish uun...

OVERS.d: Plural of OVER: Finished; ended; concluded.
OVERS.e:
From Middle English over, from Old English ofer, from Proto-West Germanic *obar, from Proto-Germanic *uber (“over”), from Proto-Indo-European *upér, related to *upó.
Akin to Scots ower (“over”), Yola oer, ower, owr (“over”), Saterland Frisian uur (“over”), West Frisian oer (“over...

OWING.d: Present participle of OWE: To be under an obligation to give something back to someone or to perform some action for someone.
OWING.e:
From Middle English owen, from Old English āgan, from Proto-West Germanic *aigan (“to own”), from Proto-Germanic *aiganą, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eh₂óyḱe (“to possess, own”), reduplicated stative of *h₂eyḱ- (“to own”). See also own, ought.
Cognate with Sanskrit ईष्टे (īṣṭe, “...

OWNED.d: Past tense of OWN: Belonging to; possessed; acquired; proper to; property of; titled to; held in one's name; under/using the name of. Often marks a possessive determiner as reflexive, referring back to the subject of the clause or sentence.
OWNED.e:
From Middle English owen, aȝen, from Old English āgen (“own, proper, peculiar”), originally the past participle of āgan; from Proto-West Germanic *aigan (“own”), from Proto-Germanic *aiganaz (“own”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂eyḱ- (“to have, possess”).
Cognates
Cognate with Sco...

PACAS.d: Plural of PACA: Any of the large rodents of the genus Cuniculus (but see also its synonyms), native to Central America and South America, which have dark brown or black fur, a white or yellowish underbelly and rows of white spots along the sides.
PACAS.e: Via Spanish paca and Portuguese paca, from Guaraní paka.

PACED.d: Past tense of PACE: A step.
PACED.e: From Middle English pase, from Anglo-Norman pas, Old French pas, and their source, Latin passus. Doublet of pas and fathom; compare also pass. Cognate with Spanish pasear.

PACES.e: From Middle English pase, from Anglo-Norman pas, Old French pas, and their source, Latin passus. Doublet of pas and fathom; compare also pass. Cognate with Spanish pasear.

PACKS.d: Plural of PACK: A bundle made up and prepared to be carried; especially, a bundle to be carried on the back, but also a load for an animal, a bale.
PACKS.e:
From Middle English pak, pakke, from Old English *pæcca and/or Middle Dutch pak, packe; both ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *pakkō, from Proto-Germanic *pakkô (“bundle, pack”).
Cognate with Dutch pak (“pack”), Low German Pack (“pack”), German Pack (“pack”), Swedish packe (“p...

PACTS.d: Plural of PACT: An agreement; a compact; a covenant.
PACTS.e: From Middle English pact, from Middle French pacte, from Old French, and its etymon Latin pactum (“something agreed upon”), from pacīscī (“to agree”). Probably a doublet of patio.

PAGED.d: Past tense of PAGE: One of the many pieces of paper bound together within a book or similar document.
PAGED.e: Borrowed from Middle French page, from Latin pāgina, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ǵ-. Doublet of pagina.

PAGES.d: Plural of PAGE: One of the many pieces of paper bound together within a book or similar document.
PAGES.e: Borrowed from Middle French page, from Latin pāgina, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ǵ-. Doublet of pagina.

PAILS.d: Plural of PAIL: A vessel of wood, tin, plastic, etc., usually cylindrical and having a handle -- used especially for carrying liquids, for example water or milk; a bucket (sometimes with a cover).
PAILS.e:
From Middle English payle (“bucket, pail, milking pail”), of uncertain origin.
Likely from Old English pæġel (“wine vessel, container for liquids, pail; a liquid measure”), from Proto-West Germanic *pagil, from Proto-Indo-European *bak- (“peg, club”), equivalent to peg + -le. Com...

PAINS.d: Plural of PAIN: An ache or bodily suffering, or an instance of this; an unpleasant sensation, resulting from a derangement of functions, disease, or injury by violence; hurt.
PAINS.e: From Middle English peyne, payne, from Old French and Anglo-Norman peine, paine, from Latin poena (“punishment, pain”), from Ancient Greek ποινή (poinḗ, “bloodmoney, weregild, fine, price paid, penalty”), from Proto-Hellenic *kʷoinā́, from Proto-Indo-European *kʷoynéh₂ (“payment”...

PAINT.d: A coloured substance; to apply paint.
PAINT.e: From Old French peint, from Latin pingere.

PAIRS.d: Plural of PAIR: Two similar or identical things taken together; often followed by of.
PAIRS.e: From Middle English paire, from Old French paire, from Latin paria (“equals”), neuter plural of par (“pair”). Related to pār (“equal”, adjective). Compare Saterland Frisian Poor (“pair”), West Frisian pear (“pair”), Dutch paar (“pair”), German Paar (“pair”), Italian paio (“pair”)

PALED.d: Past tense of PALE: Light in color.
PALED.e: From Middle English pale, from Old French pale, from Latin pallidus (“pale, pallid”), from palleō (“I am pale; I grow pale; I fade”), from Proto-Indo-European *pelito-, from *pelH- (“gray”). Doublet of pallid. Displaced native Old English blāc.

PALES.d: Plural of PALE: Light in color.
PALES.e: From Middle English pale, from Old French pale, from Latin pallidus (“pale, pallid”), from palleō (“I am pale; I grow pale; I fade”), from Proto-Indo-European *pelito-, from *pelH- (“gray”). Doublet of pallid. Displaced native Old English blāc.

PALLS.d: Plural of PALL: Senses relating to cloth.
PALLS.e: From Middle English pal, palle, from Old English pæl, pæll, from Old French paile and Latin pallium (“cloak; covering”) (and thus a doublet of pallium), probably from palla (“piece of cloth worn as apparel”) (possibly from Proto-Indo-European *pel- (“to cover, wrap; hide, skin; c...

PALMS.d: Plural of PALM: Any of various evergreen trees from the family Palmae or Arecaceae, which are mainly found in the tropics.
PALMS.e: From Middle English palme, from Old English palm, palma (“palm-tree, palm-branch”), from Latin palma (“palm-tree, palm-branch, palm of the hand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₂meh₂, *pl̥h₂emeh₂ (“palm of the hand”), from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₂- (“flat”). Cognate with Dutch ...

PALPS.d: Plural of PALP: Synonym of pedipalp.
PALPS.e:
* (verb): From French palper.
* (noun): From New Latin palpus (“a feeler”).
* Both ultimately from Latin palpō (“to stroke, touch softly, feel”).

PANED.d: Past tense of PANE: An individual sheet of glass in a window, door, etc.
PANED.e: From Middle English pane, pan, from Old French pan, from Latin pannus, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂n- (“fabric”). Doublet of pagne, pan, and pannus.

PANEL.d: A flat section; a group of experts.
PANEL.e: From Old French panel, from Latin pannus (cloth).

PANES.d: Plural of PANE: An individual sheet of glass in a window, door, etc.
PANES.e: From Middle English pane, pan, from Old French pan, from Latin pannus, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂n- (“fabric”). Doublet of pagne, pan, and pannus.

PANGS.d: Plural of PANG: A paroxysm of extreme physical pain or anguish; a feeling of sudden and transitory agony; a throe.
PANGS.e: The origin of the noun is uncertain; it is possibly derived from Middle English *pange, perhaps an altered form of prange, prōnge (“affliction, agony, pain; pointed instrument”) as in prongys of deth (“pangs of death, death throes”), from Anglo-Latin pronga, of unknown origin. Pe...

PANTS.d: Plural of PANT: A quick breathing; a catching of the breath; a gasp: the panting of animals such as a dog with their tong hung out- as a form of thermoregulation.
PANTS.e:
From Middle English panten, whence also English dialectal pank.
Possibly from Old French pantoyer, a byform or of Old French pantoisier (“to be breathless”) (compare modern French panteler (“to gasp for breath”)), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Vulgar Latin *pantasiō (“strugg...

PAPAS.d: Plural of PAPA: Dad, daddy, father; a familiar or old-fashioned term of address to one’s father.
PAPAS.e: From French papa, from Middle French papa, from Old French papa, from Latin papa, probably originally a reduplicated imitation of a child's early efforts at vocalising Latin pater (“father”). Compare Ancient Greek πάππας (páppas, “papa, daddy”).

PAPER.e: From Anglo-Norman papir, from Latin papȳrus.

PARAS.d: Plural of PARA: A former subunit of currency in several countries in the Ottoman/Turkish and Yugoslav regions.
PARAS.e: Borrowed from Serbo-Croatian pàra /па̀ра, from Ottoman Turkish پاره (pare, para), from Persian پاره (pâre).

PARED.d: Past tense of PARE: To remove the outer covering or skin of something with a cutting device, typically a knife.
PARED.e: From Middle English paren, from Old French parer (“to arrange, prepare, trim”), from Latin parō (“I prepare, arrange; I provide, furnish; I resolve, purpose”) (related to pariō (“I bear, I give birth to; I spawn, produce, beget; I procure, acquire”)), from a Proto-Indo-European *...

PARES.d: Plural of PARE: To remove the outer covering or skin of something with a cutting device, typically a knife.
PARES.e: From Middle English paren, from Old French parer (“to arrange, prepare, trim”), from Latin parō (“I prepare, arrange; I provide, furnish; I resolve, purpose”) (related to pariō (“I bear, I give birth to; I spawn, produce, beget; I procure, acquire”)), from a Proto-Indo-European *...

PARKS.d: Plural of PARK: An area of land set aside for environment preservation or recreation.
PARKS.e: From Middle English park, from Old French parc (“livestock pen”), from Medieval Latin parcus, parricus, from Frankish *parrik (“enclosure, pen, fence”). Cognate with Dutch perk (“enclosure; flowerbed”), Old High German pfarrih, pferrih (“enclosure, pen”), Old English pearroc (“en...

PARTS.d: Plural of PART: A portion; a component.
PARTS.e: From Middle English part, from Old English part (“part”) and Old French part (“part”); both from Latin partem, accusative of pars (“piece, portion, share, side, party, faction, role, character, lot, fate, task, lesson, part, member”), from Proto-Indo-European *par-, *per- (“to se...

PARTY.d: A social gathering; a political group.

PASES.d: Plural of PAS: The right of going foremost; precedence.

PASTS.d: Plural of PAST: The period of time that has already happened, in contrast to the present and the future.
PASTS.e: From Middle English passed, past participle of passen (“to pass, to go by”), whence Modern English pass.

PATED.d: Past tense of PATE: The head, particularly the top or crown.
PATED.e: From Middle English pate, of uncertain origin. Perhaps a shortened form of Old French patene or Medieval Latin patena, both from Latin patina (“pan, dish”). Alternatively, perhaps akin to Old Frisian pote (“skull”).

PATES.d: Plural of PATE: The head, particularly the top or crown.
PATES.e: From Middle English pate, of uncertain origin. Perhaps a shortened form of Old French patene or Medieval Latin patena, both from Latin patina (“pan, dish”). Alternatively, perhaps akin to Old Frisian pote (“skull”).

PATHS.d: Plural of PATH: A trail for the use of, or worn by, pedestrians.
PATHS.e: From Middle English path, peth, from Old English pæþ (“path, track”), from Proto-West Germanic *paþ, from Proto-Germanic *paþaz (“path”). The Proto-Germanic term is possibly borrowed from Iranian, from Proto-Iranian *pántaHh, from Proto-Indo-Iranian *pántaHs, from Proto-Indo-Euro...

PAVED.d: Past tense of PAVE: To cover something with paving slabs.
PAVED.e: From Old French paver (“to pave, to cover”), from Vulgar Latin *pavāre (“to beat down, to smash”), from Latin pavīre (“to beat, strike, ram, tread down”).

PAVES.d: Plural of PAVE: To cover something with paving slabs.
PAVES.e: From Old French paver (“to pave, to cover”), from Vulgar Latin *pavāre (“to beat down, to smash”), from Latin pavīre (“to beat, strike, ram, tread down”).

PAWED.d: Past tense of PAW: The soft foot of a mammal or other animal, generally a quadruped, that has claws or nails; comparable to a human hand or foot.
PAWED.e: From Middle English pawe, from Old French poue, poe, from Frankish *pōta (compare Dutch poot, Low German Pote, German Pfote), from Frankish *pōtōn (“to put, stick, plant”) (compare Dutch poten (“to plant”)), from Proto-Germanic *putōną (compare Old English potian (“to push”), pȳt...

PAWLS.d: Plural of PAWL: A pivoted catch designed to fall into a notch on a ratchet wheel so as to allow movement in only one direction (e.g. on a windlass or in a clock mechanism), or alternatively to move the wheel in one direction.
PAWLS.e: 17th c., perhaps from Low German or Dutch pal (“catch (mechanism)”), or from either French pal (“stake”) or épaule (“shoulder”).

PAWNS.d: Plural of PAWN: The state of being held as security for a loan, or as a pledge.
PAWNS.e: From Middle English paun, pawyn, pawnd, from Old French pan, pant (“pledge for a payment”), from a Germanic language, perhaps Frankish *pand (“deposit, security, pledge”), further origin uncertain. Cognate with Saterland Frisian Pound (“deposit, pledge, pawn”), West Frisian pân (...

PAYED.d: Past tense of PAY: To give money or other compensation to in exchange for goods or services.
PAYED.e: From Middle English payen, from Old French paiier (“pay”), from Medieval Latin pācāre (“to settle, satisfy”) from Latin pācāre (“to pacify”). In this sense, displaced native Old English ġield (“pay”) and ġieldan (“to pay”), whence Modern English yield.

PEACE.e: From Anglo-Norman pes, from Latin pāx.

PEAKS.d: Plural of PEAK: A point; the sharp end or top of anything that terminates in a point; as, the peak, or front, of a cap.
PEAKS.e:
From earlier peake, peek, peke, from Middle English pek (in place names), itself an alteration of pike, pyke, pyk (“a sharp point, pike”), from Old English pīc, piic (“a pike, needle, pin, peak, pinnacle”), from Proto-West Germanic *pīk, from Proto-Germanic *pīkaz (“peak”).
Cogna...

PEALS.d: Plural of PEAL: A loud sound, or a succession of loud sounds, as of bells, thunder, cannon, shouts, laughter, of a multitude, etc.
PEALS.e: From Middle English pele, peil, probably an apheretic variant of Middle English apel, appel, from Old French apel (“an appeal; pealing of bells”). Compare appeal.

PEANS.d: Plural of PEAN: A heraldic fur of gold spots on a black field.
PEANS.e: Derived from Middle French penne (“feather”), from penna (“feather”); doublet of pen and penna.

PEARS.d: Plural of PEAR: An edible fruit produced by the pear tree, similar to an apple but typically elongated towards the stem.
PEARS.e:
From Middle English pere, from Old English pere, from Proto-West Germanic *peru, from Vulgar Latin pira, originally the plural of Latin pirum but reconstrued as a feminine singular, ultimately a loanword from an unknown Mediterranean substrate source.
Cognate with Scots peer (“pe...

PEATS.d: Plural of PEAT: Soil formed of dead but not fully decayed plants found in bog areas, often burned as fuel.
PEATS.e: Inherited from Northern Middle English pete (recorded in Latin text as peta), of uncertain origin; perhaps from a Celtic language such as an unattested Pictish or Brythonic source, in turn possibly from Proto-Brythonic *peθ (“portion, segment, piece”); if so, it would be a double...

PECKS.d: Plural of PECK: To strike or pierce with the beak or bill (of a bird).
PECKS.e: From Middle English pecken, pekken, variant of Middle English piken, picken, pikken (“to pick, use a pointed implement”). More at pick.

PEEKS.d: Plural of PEEK: To look slyly, or with the eyes half closed, or through a crevice; to peep.
PEEKS.e: From Middle English *peken, piken, pyken (“to peep”), probably a fusion of Middle English pepen (“to peep”) and keken, kiken (“to keek, look, spy”), equivalent to a blend of peep + keek. Perhaps also possibly a metathetic alteration of Middle English kepen, kipen, kypen (“to keep...

PEELS.d: Plural of PEEL: To remove the skin or outer covering of.
PEELS.e: From Middle English pelen, from Old English pilian and Old French peler, pellier; both from Latin pilō, pilāre (“to remove hair from, depilate”), from pilus (“hair”). Doublet of pill.

PEENS.d: Plural of PEEN: The (often spherical) end of the head of a hammer opposite the main hammering end.
PEENS.e: Probably from a North Germanic source, compare dialectal Norwegian penn (“peen”), Danish pind (“peg”), German Pinne (“the peen of a hammer”), Old Swedish pæna (“to pound iron with a hammer”).

PEEPS.d: Plural of PEEP: A short, soft, high-pitched sound, as made by a baby bird.
PEEPS.e: From Middle English pepen. Compare Dutch piepen (“peep”), German Low German piepen (“to peep”), German piepen and pfeifen, all probably onomatopoeic.

PEERS.d: Plural of PEER: To look with difficulty, or as if searching for something.
PEERS.e: From Middle English peren, pyren, piren (“to peer, gaze”), perhaps from Old English *pȳran (“to look, peer”), from Proto-West Germanic *pūrijan (“to look”), related to Saterland Frisian pierje (“to look”), Dutch Low Saxon piren (“to look”), West Flemish pieren (“to look with narr...

PEKES.d: Plural of PEKE: A Pekingese dog.

PELES.d: Plural of PELE: The Hawaiian goddess of fire and volcanos.

PELFS.d: Plural of PELF: Money, riches; gain, especially when dishonestly acquired; lucre, mammon.
PELFS.e: From Late Middle English pelf, pelfe (“stolen goods, booty, spoil; forfeited property; money, riches; property; valuable object”), possibly from Anglo-Norman pelf (a variant of pelfre (“booty, loot”)) and Old French peufre (“frippery; rubbish”); further etymology uncertain, possi...

PELTS.d: Plural of PELT: The skin of an animal with the hair or wool on; either a raw or undressed hide, or a skin preserved with the hair or wool on it (sometimes worn as a garment with minimal modification).
PELTS.e:
The noun is inherited from Middle English pelt (“skin of a sheep, especially without the wool”); further etymology uncertain, possibly:
* from Middle English pellet (“skin of an animal, especially a sheep”), from Anglo-Norman pelette, pellet, and Old French pelete, pelette (“thin...

PENDS.d: Plural of PEND: To hang down; to cause something to hang down
PENDS.e: Borrowed from Middle French pendre (“to hang”), from Late Latin pendĕre, from Latin pendēre.
