PEONS.d: Plural of PEON: A lowly person; a peasant or serf; a labourer who is obliged to do menial work.
PEONS.e: From a combination of Middle French pion, peon and Spanish peón, both from Late Latin pedōnem (“pedestrian”). Doublet of pawn.

PEPOS.d: Plural of PEPO: A fruit of plants of the gourd family Cucurbitaceae, possessing a hard rind and producing many seeds in a single, central, pulpy chamber.
PEPOS.e: Borrowed from Latin pepō, from Ancient Greek πέπων (pépōn, “large melon”), from πέπων (pépōn, “ripe”), from πέπτω (péptō, “ripen”). Doublet of pumpion; compare pumpkin.

PERIS.d: Plural of PERI: A sprite or supernatural being.
PERIS.e: Borrowed from Ottoman Turkish پری (peri), from Persian پری (pari).

PERMS.d: Plural of PERM: Clipping of permanent wave (“hairstyle”).

PESOS.d: Plural of PESO: A former unit of currency in Spain and Spain's colonies, worth 8 reales; the Spanish dollar.

PESTS.d: Plural of PEST: A pestilence, i.e. a deadly epidemic, a deadly plague.
PESTS.e: In the 16th century in the sense of "pestilence" and specifically bubonic plague from Middle French peste (“pestilence”) (whence French peste). The other meanings are recorded soon after. Ultimately from Latin pestis.

PHONS.d: Plural of PHON: A unit of apparent loudness, equal in number to the intensity in decibels of a 1,000-hertz tone judged to be as loud as the sound being measured.

PICAS.d: Plural of PICA: A disorder characterized by appetite and craving for non-edible substances, such as chalk, clay, dirt, ice, or sand.
PICAS.e:
Borrowed from Latin pīca (“jay; magpie”). Doublet of pie (“magpie”).
* (pathology): From the idea that magpies will eat almost anything.

PICKS.d: Plural of PICK: A tool used for digging; a pickaxe.
PICKS.e: From Middle English piken, picken, pikken, from Old English *piccian, *pīcian (attested in pīcung (“a pricking”)), and pīcan, pȳcan (“to pick, prick, pluck”), both from Proto-West Germanic *pikkōn, from Proto-Germanic *pikkōną (“to pick, peck, prick, knock”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

PIING.d: Present participle of PIE: A type of pastry that consists of an outer crust and a filling. (Savory pies are more popular in the UK and sweet pies are more popular in the US, so "pie" without qualification has different connotations in these dialects.)
PIING.e: From Middle English pye, pie, pey, perhaps from Old English *pīe (“pastry”) (compare Old English pīe, pēo (“insect, bug”)), attested in early Middle English piehus (“bakery”, literally “pie-house”) c. 1199. Relation to Medieval Latin pica, pia (“pie, pastry”) is unclear, as there...

PIKED.d: Past tense of PIKE: A very long spear used two-handed by infantry soldiers for thrusting (not throwing), both for attacks on enemy foot soldiers and as a countermeasure against cavalry assaults.
PIKED.e: From Middle English pyke, pyk, pik, pike (“pike; sharp point, iron tip of a staff or spear, pointed toe of an item of footwear; sharp tool; mountain, peak”), from Old English pīc (“pointed object, pick axe”), and Middle French pique (“long thrusting weapon”), from Old French pic ...

PIKES.d: Plural of PIKE: A very long spear used two-handed by infantry soldiers for thrusting (not throwing), both for attacks on enemy foot soldiers and as a countermeasure against cavalry assaults.
PIKES.e: From Middle English pyke, pyk, pik, pike (“pike; sharp point, iron tip of a staff or spear, pointed toe of an item of footwear; sharp tool; mountain, peak”), from Old English pīc (“pointed object, pick axe”), and Middle French pique (“long thrusting weapon”), from Old French pic ...

PILED.d: Past tense of PILE: A mass of things heaped together; a heap.
PILED.e: From Middle English pyle, from Old French pile, from Latin pīla (“pillar, pier”).

PILES.d: Plural of PILE: A mass of things heaped together; a heap.
PILES.e: From Middle English pyle, from Old French pile, from Latin pīla (“pillar, pier”).

PILLS.d: Plural of PILL: A small, usually round or cylindrical object designed for easy swallowing, usually containing some sort of medication.
PILLS.e:
* From Middle English pille (also pillem), a borrowing from Middle Low German pille or Middle Dutch pille (whence Dutch pil), probably from Latin pila, pilula.
* (persuade or convince): Generalized from red pill.

PILOT.d: A person who operates an aircraft.
PILOT.e: From French pilote, from Italian pilota.

PIMPS.d: Plural of PIMP: Someone who solicits customers for prostitution and acts as manager for a group of prostitutes; a pander.
PIMPS.e: Origin unknown. Perhaps from French pimpant (“smart, sparkish”) or German Pimpf (“boy, youth, young squirt”). The Old English near-synonym was rendered by Old English forspennend (literally “solicitor”).

PINAS.d: Plural of PINA: Alternative form of piña.

PINED.d: Past tense of PINE: Any coniferous tree of the genus Pinus.
PINED.e: From Middle English pyne, from Old English *pīne, from Proto-West Germanic *pīnā, from Latin pīnus, see there for more. Doublet of pinus. Possibly related to fat.

PINES.d: Plural of PINE: Any coniferous tree of the genus Pinus.
PINES.e: From Middle English pyne, from Old English *pīne, from Proto-West Germanic *pīnā, from Latin pīnus, see there for more. Doublet of pinus. Possibly related to fat.

PINGS.d: Plural of PING: A high-pitched, short and somewhat sharp sound.
PINGS.e: Partly onomatopoeic, and partly continuing Middle English pingen (“to push, shove, pierce, stab, prod, goad, urge, feel remorse, incite”), from Old English pyngan (“to prick”), in turn likely from pungere. Compare English pang.

PINKS.d: Plural of PINK: A color reminiscent of pinks, the flowers.
PINKS.e: Origin uncertain; perhaps from Dutch pinken (“blink”) or the English verb pink from the same source. Perhaps from the notion of the petals being pinked.

PINTS.d: Plural of PINT: A unit of volume, equivalent to:
PINTS.e: From Middle English pinte, from Old French pinte, assumed from Vulgar Latin *pincta (“a mark used to indicate a level of quantity against a larger measure”), from Latin picta (“painted”), from Latin pingō (“paint”, verb). Doublet of pinto and Pinto.

PIONS.d: Plural of PION: Any of three semistable mesons, having positive, negative or neutral charge, composed of up and down quarks/antiquarks.
PIONS.e: From pi + -on, as alteration of pi-meson.

PIPED.d: Past tense of PIPE: Meanings relating to a wind instrument.
PIPED.e: From Middle English pīpe, pype (“hollow cylinder or tube used as a conduit or container; duct or vessel of the body; musical instrument; financial records maintained by the English Exchequer, pipe roll”), from Old English pīpe (“pipe (musical instrument); the channel of a small s...

PIPES.d: Plural of PIPE: Meanings relating to a wind instrument.
PIPES.e: From Middle English pīpe, pype (“hollow cylinder or tube used as a conduit or container; duct or vessel of the body; musical instrument; financial records maintained by the English Exchequer, pipe roll”), from Old English pīpe (“pipe (musical instrument); the channel of a small s...

PITCH.d: The degree of highness of sound; to throw.

PITHS.d: Plural of PITH: The soft, spongy substance inside plant parts; specifically, the parenchyma in the centre of the roots and stems of many plants and trees.
PITHS.e: The noun is derived from Middle English pith, pithe (“central tissue of a plant’s stem or a tree’s trunk and branches; other spongy inner tissue in a plant; flesh of a fruit, pulp; inner tissue in a body; inner part of an object; essential part, essence, quintessence; importance,...

PIXES.d: Plural of PIX: plural of pic (“picture”)
PIXES.e: Abbreviation of pictures, first used in Variety in 1916, along with other similar words that the magazine calls slanguage.

PLACE.e: From Old French place, from Latin platea.

PLAIN.d: Simple; a flat area of land.
PLAIN.e: From Old French plain, from Latin plānus.

PLANS.d: Plural of PLAN: A drawing showing technical details of a building, machine, etc., with unwanted details omitted, and often using symbols rather than detailed drawing to represent doors, valves, etc.
PLANS.e: From French plan (“flat surface, ground plot, map”), from Latin plānus. Some sources also argue for influence or alteration of French plant, from plantar, from Latin plantāre (“set, fix in place”). Compare plane, plain.

PLATE.d: A flat dish; a flat piece of metal.

PLATS.d: Plural of PLAT: A plot of land; a lot.
PLATS.e: The noun is derived from Middle English plat, platte (“flat part of a sword; flat piece of ground, plot of ground”), probably a variant of Middle English plot, (modern English plot) and influenced by Middle English plat, plate (modern English plate) and Anglo-Norman, Middle Frenc...

PLAYS.d: Plural of PLAY: To act in a manner such that one has fun; to engage in activities expressly for the purpose of recreation or entertainment.
PLAYS.e: From Middle English pleyen, playen, pleȝen, plæien, also Middle English plaȝen, plawen (compare English plaw), from Old English pleġan, pleoġan, plæġan, and Old English plegian, pleagian, plagian (“to play, exercise, etc.”), from Proto-West Germanic *plehan (“to care about, be co...

PLAZA.e: From Spanish plaza, from Latin platea.

PLEAS.d: Plural of PLEA: An appeal, petition, urgent prayer or entreaty.
PLEAS.e: From Middle English ple, from Old French plait, plaid, from Medieval Latin placitum (“a decree, sentence, suit, plea, etc., Latin an opinion, determination, prescription, order; literally, that which is pleasing, pleasure”), neuter of placitus, past participle of placere (“to ple...

PLEBS.d: Plural of PLEB: A commoner; a member of the lower class of a society.
PLEBS.e: A clipping of plebeian and plebe, sometimes also understood as a back-formation from plebs.

PLIED.d: Past tense of PLY: A layer of material.
PLIED.e: From Middle English pleit, plit, plite (“a fold, pleat, wrinkle; braid, strand in a braided cord, ply”), from Anglo-Norman pli, plei, pleit, and Middle French pli, ploy, ply (“a fold, pleat; joint in armour; situation, state”) (modern French pli (“a fold, pleat”)), from plier, pl...

PLIER.d: Comparative form of PLY: A layer of material.
PLIER.e: From Middle English pleit, plit, plite (“a fold, pleat, wrinkle; braid, strand in a braided cord, ply”), from Anglo-Norman pli, plei, pleit, and Middle French pli, ploy, ply (“a fold, pleat; joint in armour; situation, state”) (modern French pli (“a fold, pleat”)), from plier, pl...

PLIES.d: Plural of PLY: A layer of material.
PLIES.e: From Middle English pleit, plit, plite (“a fold, pleat, wrinkle; braid, strand in a braided cord, ply”), from Anglo-Norman pli, plei, pleit, and Middle French pli, ploy, ply (“a fold, pleat; joint in armour; situation, state”) (modern French pli (“a fold, pleat”)), from plier, pl...

PLODS.d: Plural of PLOD: A slow or labored walk or other motion or activity.
PLODS.e: From Middle English *plodden (found only in derivative plodder), probably originally a splash through water and mud, from plodde, pludde (“a puddle”) (whence modern plud). Compare Scots plod, plodge, plodder, dialectal Dutch plodden, plodderen, dialectal German ploddern, Danish p...

PLOPS.d: Plural of PLOP: A sound or action like liquid hitting a hard surface, or an object falling into a body of water.
PLOPS.e: Imitative of the sound, or perhaps a variant of plap.

PLOTS.d: Plural of PLOT: The course of a story, comprising a series of incidents which are gradually unfolded, sometimes by unexpected means.
PLOTS.e: From Middle English plot, plotte, from Old English plot (“a plot of ground”), from Proto-Germanic *plataz, *platjaz (“a patch”), of uncertain origin. Cognate with Middle Low German plet (“patch, strip of cloth, rags”), German Bletz (“rags, bits, strip of land”), and possibly Goth...

PLOYS.d: Plural of PLOY: A tactic, strategy, or scheme.
PLOYS.e: Possibly from a shortened form of employ or deploy. Or from earlier ploye, from Middle English, borrowed from Middle French ployer (compare modern plier), from Latin plicāre.

PLUGS.d: Plural of PLUG: A pronged connecting device which fits into a mating socket, especially an electrical one.
PLUGS.e: From Dutch plug, from Middle Dutch plugge (“peg, plug”), from Old Dutch *pluggi, from Proto-West Germanic *plugi. Further origin unknown. Possibly from Proto-Germanic *plugjaz, but the word seems originally restricted to northern continental West Germanic. Perhaps ultimately from...

PLUMS.d: Plural of PLUM: The fruit and its tree.
PLUMS.e: From Middle English plomme, ploume, from Old English plūme, from Proto-West Germanic *plūmā, borrowed from Latin prūnum. Doublet of prune.

POCKS.d: Plural of POCK: A pus-filled swelling on the surface on the skin caused by an eruptive disease.
POCKS.e: From Middle English pok, from Old English poc, pocc (“pock; pustule; ulcer”), from Proto-West Germanic *pokk, from Proto-Germanic *pukkaz, *pukkǭ (“pock; swelling”), from Proto-Indo-European *bew-, *bʰew- (“to grow; swell”). Cognate with Dutch pok (“pock”), Low German Pocke (“poc...

POEMS.d: Plural of POEM: A literary piece written in verse.
POEMS.e: From Middle French poème, from Latin poēma, from Ancient Greek ποίημα (poíēma), from ποιέω (poiéō, “I make”). Displaced native Old English lēoþ.

POETS.d: Plural of POET: A person who writes poems.
POETS.e: From Middle English poete, from Old French poete, from Latin poēta (“poet, author”), from Ancient Greek ποιητής (poiētḗs, “creator, maker, author, poet”), from ποιέω (poiéō, “to make, compose”). Displaced native Old English sċop. Doublet of piyyut.

POINT.d: A sharp end; a location; to indicate.
POINT.e: From Old French point, from Latin pūnctum.

POKED.d: Past tense of POKE: To prod or jab with an object such as a finger or a stick.
POKED.e: From Middle English poken, perhaps from Middle Dutch poken or Middle Low German poken, both from Proto-West Germanic *pukōn or similar, which is itself of uncertain origin, but may be from an imitative Proto-Germanic root *puk-. Doublet of poach.

POKES.d: Plural of POKE: To prod or jab with an object such as a finger or a stick.
POKES.e: From Middle English poken, perhaps from Middle Dutch poken or Middle Low German poken, both from Proto-West Germanic *pukōn or similar, which is itself of uncertain origin, but may be from an imitative Proto-Germanic root *puk-. Doublet of poach.

POLED.d: Past tense of POLE: Originally, a stick; now specifically, a long and slender piece of metal or (especially) wood, used for various construction or support purposes.
POLED.e: From Middle English pole, pal, from Old English pāl (“a pole, stake, post; a kind of hoe or spade”), from Proto-West Germanic *pāl (“pole”), from Latin pālus (“stake, pale, prop, stay”), perhaps from Old Latin *paxlos, from Proto-Italic *pākslos, ultimately from Proto-Indo-Europe...

POLES.d: Plural of POLE: Originally, a stick; now specifically, a long and slender piece of metal or (especially) wood, used for various construction or support purposes.
POLES.e: From Middle English pole, pal, from Old English pāl (“a pole, stake, post; a kind of hoe or spade”), from Proto-West Germanic *pāl (“pole”), from Latin pālus (“stake, pale, prop, stay”), perhaps from Old Latin *paxlos, from Proto-Italic *pākslos, ultimately from Proto-Indo-Europe...

POLLS.d: Plural of POLL: A survey of people, usually statistically analyzed to gauge wider public opinion.
POLLS.e: From Middle English pol, polle ("scalp, pate"), from or cognate with Middle Dutch pol, pōle, polle (“top, summit; head”), from Proto-West Germanic *poll, from Proto-Germanic *pullaz (“round object, head, top”), from Proto-Indo-European *bolno-, *bōwl- (“orb, round object, bubble”...

POLOS.d: Plural of POLO: A ball game where two teams of players on horseback use long-handled mallets to propel the ball along the ground and into their opponent's goal.
POLOS.e: From Balti پولو (polo, “ball”). Cognate with Tibetan པོ་ལོ (po lo), ཕོ་ལོང (pho long), སྤོ་ལོ (spo lo, “ball”).

POMPS.d: Plural of POMP: Show of magnificence; parade; display; power.
POMPS.e:
The noun is derived from Middle English pomp, pompe, from Old French pompe, from Latin pompa (“pomp”), from Ancient Greek πομπή (pompḗ, “a sending, a solemn procession, pomp”), from πέμπω (pémpō, “I send”).
The verb is derived from Middle English pompen, from pomp, pompe (see abo...

PONDS.d: Plural of POND: An inland body of standing water, either natural or man-made, that is smaller than a lake.
PONDS.e: From Middle English pond, ponde (“pond, pool”), probably from Old English *pond, *pand (attested in placenames), a variant of *pund (“enclosure”). Doublet of pound.

PONES.d: Plural of PONE: A writ in law used by the superior courts to remove cases from inferior courts.
PONES.e: Inherited from Middle English pone, from Anglo-Norman pone, from Late Latin pone, from Latin pōne, imperative of pōnere (“to place”).

POOHS.d: Plural of POOH: Short for Winnie the Pooh.

POOLS.d: Plural of POOL: A small and rather deep area of (usually) fresh water, as one supplied by a spring, or occurring in the course of a stream or river; a reservoir for water.
POOLS.e:
From Middle English pool, pole, pol, from Old English pōl (“pool”), from Proto-West Germanic pōl, from Proto-Germanic *pōlaz (“pool, pond”), from Proto-Indo-European *bōlos (“bog, marsh”).
Cognate with Scots puil (“pool”), Saterland Frisian Pol (“pool”), West Frisian poel (“pool”...

POONS.d: Plural of POON: Any of several East Indian trees of the genus Calophyllum, yielding a light, hard wood used for masts, spars, etc.
POONS.e: Compare Tamil புன்னை (puṉṉai), Malayalam പുന്ന (punna), names for Calophyllum inophyllum. Doublet of punnai.

POOPS.d: Plural of POOP: To make a short blast on a horn.
POOPS.e: Uncertain, possibly from Middle English poupen (“to make a gulping sound while drinking, blow on a horn, toot”). Compare Dutch poepen (“to defecate”), German Low German pupen (“to fart; break wind”). Also representing poo pronounced with the mouth snapped closed at the end.

POPES.d: Plural of POPE: An honorary title of the Roman Catholic bishop of Rome as father and head of his church, a sovereign of the Vatican city state.
POPES.e: From Middle English pope, popa, from Old English pāpa, from Vulgar Latin papa (title for priests and bishops, esp. and by 8th c. only the bishop of Rome), from early Byzantine Greek παπᾶς (papâs, title for priests and bishops, especially by 3rd c. the bishop of Alexandria), from ...

PORED.d: Past tense of PORE: A tiny opening in the skin.
PORED.e: From Middle English pore, from Old French pore, from Latin porus, from Ancient Greek πόρος (póros, “passage”). Displaced native English sweat hole from Middle English swet hole, which might have been a reformation of Old English swātþȳrel (literally “sweat hole”), which competed ...

PORES.d: Plural of PORE: A tiny opening in the skin.
PORES.e: From Middle English pore, from Old French pore, from Latin porus, from Ancient Greek πόρος (póros, “passage”). Displaced native English sweat hole from Middle English swet hole, which might have been a reformation of Old English swātþȳrel (literally “sweat hole”), which competed ...

PORKS.d: Plural of PORK: The meat of a pig.
PORKS.e:
From Middle English pork, porc, via Anglo-Norman, from Old French porc (“swine, hog, pig; pork”), from Latin porcus (“domestic hog, pig”).
Cognate with Old English fearh (“piglet”). Doublet of farrow. Compare also other West Germanic words for pigs: Ferkel, Ferke, and varken.

PORNS.e: Clipping of pornography. Attested from mid-20th century.

PORTS.d: Plural of PORT: A place on the coast at which ships can shelter, or dock to load and unload cargo or passengers.
PORTS.e: From Old English port, borrowed from Latin portus (“port, harbour”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *pértus (“crossing”) (and thus a distant doublet of ford). The directional sense, attested since at least the 1500s, derives from ancient vessels with the steering oar on the ...

POSED.d: Past tense of POSE: Common cold, head cold; catarrh.
POSED.e: From Middle English pose, from Old English ġeposu pl (“cold in the head; catarrh”, literally “(the) sneezes; (the) snorts”), from Old English pos, ġepos (“sneeze, snort”), from Proto-West Germanic *pos, from Proto-Germanic *pusą (“sneeze, snort”), from Proto-Germanic *pusōną, *pu...

POSTS.d: Plural of POST: A long dowel or plank protruding from the ground; a fencepost; a lightpost.
POSTS.e: Inherited from Old English post (“pillar, door-post”) and Latin postis (“a post, a door-post”) through Old French. .

POUND.d: A unit of weight; British currency.
POUND.e: From Old English pund, from Latin pondō.

POURS.d: Plural of POUR: To cause (liquid, or liquid-like substance) to flow in a stream, either out of a container or into it.
POURS.e:
From Middle English pouren (“to pour”), of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Old Northern French purer (“to sift (grain), pour out (water)”), from Latin pūrō (“to purify”), from pūrus (“pure”). Compare Middle Dutch afpuren (“to pour off, drain”).
To pour displaced several Middle Eng...

POUTS.d: Plural of POUT: To push out one's lips.
POUTS.e: From Middle English pouten, probably from Scandinavian (compare Norwegian pute (“pillow, cushion”), dial. Swedish puta (“to be puffed out”), Danish pude (“pillow, cushion”)), from Proto-Germanic *pūto (“swollen”) (compare English eelpout, Dutch puit, Low German puddig (“inflated”...

POWER.d: The ability to do something; strength.

POXED.d: Past tense of POX: A disease characterized by purulent skin eruptions that may leave pockmarks.
POXED.e: From the plural of Middle English pocke. See also pock.

POXES.d: Plural of POX: A disease characterized by purulent skin eruptions that may leave pockmarks.
POXES.e: From the plural of Middle English pocke. See also pock.

PRAMS.d: Plural of PRAM: A small vehicle, usually covered, in which a newborn baby is pushed around in a lying position.

PRATS.d: Plural of PRAT: A cunning or mischievous trick; a prank, a joke.
PRATS.e: From Middle English prat, from Old English præt, prætt (“trick, prank, craft, art, wile”), from Proto-West Germanic *prattu, from Proto-Germanic *prattuz (“boastful talk, deceit”), from Proto-Indo-European *brodno- (“to wander about”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian prat, Dutch p...

PRAYS.d: Plural of PRAY: To direct words, thoughts, or one's attention to a deity or any higher being, for the sake of adoration, thanks, petition for help, etc.
PRAYS.e:
From Middle English preien, from Anglo-Norman preier, from Old French preier, proier (French prier), from Latin precārī, from prex, precis (“a prayer, a request”), from Proto-Italic *preks, from Proto-Indo-European *preḱ- (“to ask, woo”). Displaced native Old English gebiddan.
Co...

PREED.d: Past tense of PRE: Before (something significant).
PREED.e: From Latin prae (“in front of”); see pre-.

PRESS.e: From Old French presser, from Latin pressāre.

PREYS.d: Plural of PREY: That which is or may be seized by animals to be devoured.
PREYS.e: From Middle English preye, prei, preyȝe, borrowed from Anglo-Norman and Old French preie, one of the variants of proie, from Latin praeda. Compare predator. Doublet of prede.

PRICE.e: From Old French pris, from Latin pretium.

PRIED.e: The verb is inherited from Middle English prien, pryen (“to look closely, peer into, pry, spy”) [and other forms], from Old English *prīwan, *prēowian (“to look narrowly, to squint at”), attested by Old English beprīwan, beprēwan (“to wink”); further etymology unknown, but probab...

PRIER.d: Comparative form of PRY: To peer closely and curiously, especially at something closed or not public.
PRIER.e: The verb is inherited from Middle English prien, pryen (“to look closely, peer into, pry, spy”) [and other forms], from Old English *prīwan, *prēowian (“to look narrowly, to squint at”), attested by Old English beprīwan, beprēwan (“to wink”); further etymology unknown, but probab...

PRIES.d: Plural of PRY: To peer closely and curiously, especially at something closed or not public.
PRIES.e: The verb is inherited from Middle English prien, pryen (“to look closely, peer into, pry, spy”) [and other forms], from Old English *prīwan, *prēowian (“to look narrowly, to squint at”), attested by Old English beprīwan, beprēwan (“to wink”); further etymology unknown, but probab...

PRIGS.d: Plural of PRIG: A deliberately superior person; a person who demonstrates an exaggerated conformity or propriety, especially in an irritatingly arrogant or smug manner.
PRIGS.e: UK 16th century. Of unknown origin. Earlier noun senses ("tinker" and "thief"), as hyponyms of "undesirable person", may have informed later senses ("conceited person").

PRIME.d: Of first importance; the best time.

PRIMS.d: Plural of PRIM: Of a person, their manner or appearance: Formal and precise; stiffly decorous.
PRIMS.e:
Of uncertain origin.
In the verb sense, first appeared in Thomas D'Urfey's A Fool's Preferment in the year 1688.
In the noun sense, first appeared in A New Dictionary of the Terms Ancient and Modern of the Canting Crew in the year 1699, meaning "prig." Now obsolete.
In the adject...

PRINT.d: To produce text by pressing; printed matter.

PROAS.d: Plural of PROA: A sailing vessel found in the waters of Micronesia and Indonesia; it has a single, large outrigger and a triangular sail.
PROAS.e: From Malay perau, a variant of perahu. In some forms via Portuguese parão or Dutch prauw; in some forms assimilated to prow.

PRODS.d: Plural of PROD: To poke, to push, to touch.
PRODS.e: Alteration of earlier brod (perhaps through influence of poke; compare prog), from Middle English brodden (“to goad, incite, urge; to sprout”), from brod (“goad, nail; shoot, sprout”), from Old Norse broddr (“shaft, spike, thorn”), from Proto-Germanic *bruzdaz. Cognate with Icela...

PROFS.d: Plural of PROF: Clipping of professor.

PROGS.d: Plural of PROG: Abbreviation of progressive.

PROMS.d: Plural of PROM: A promenade concert.

PROPS.d: Plural of PROP: An object placed against or under another, to support it; anything that supports.
PROPS.e: From Middle English proppe (“a prop, support, support for a vine or plant”), from Middle Dutch proppe (“support, support for a vine, stopper for a bottle”). Compare Middle Low German proppe (“plug, stopper”), German Pfropfen (“plug”), Danish prop (“plug, stopper”).

PROSS.d: Plural of PROS: plural of pro

PROVE.e: From Old French prover, from Latin probāre.

PROWS.d: Plural of PROW: The front part of a vessel.
PROWS.e: From Middle French proue, proe, from Ligurian prua, proa, from Latin prōra, from Ancient Greek πρῷρα (prōîra).

PUCES.d: Plural of PUCE: A brownish-purple color, sometimes more or less deep red or grayish.
PUCES.e: From French couleur puce, from Latin pūlex (“flea”).

PUCKS.d: Plural of PUCK: A mischievous or hostile spirit.
PUCKS.e:
From Middle English pouke, from Old English pūca (“goblin, demon”), from Proto-West Germanic *pūkō, from Proto-Germanic *pūkô (“a goblin, spook”), of uncertain origin.
Cognate with Old Norse púki (“devil”) (dialectal Swedish puke). Doublet of pooka.

PUFFS.d: Plural of PUFF: A sharp exhalation of a small amount of breath through the mouth.
PUFFS.e: From Middle English puff, puf, from Old English pyf (“a blast of wind, puff”), imitative. Cognate with Middle Low German puf, pof.

PUKED.e: Probably imitative; or, alternatively from Proto-Germanic *pukaną (“to spit, puff”), from Proto-Indo-European *bew- (“to blow, swell”). If so, then cognate with German pfauchen, fauchen (“to hiss, spit”). Compare also Dutch spugen (“to spit, spit up”), German spucken (“to spit, p...

PULED.d: Past tense of PULE: A plaintive melancholy whine.
PULED.e: From French piauler, a variant of French piailler (“to chirp, cheep”). Compare Italian pigolare (“to cheep as a chicken”).

PULES.d: Plural of PULE: A plaintive melancholy whine.
PULES.e: From French piauler, a variant of French piailler (“to chirp, cheep”). Compare Italian pigolare (“to cheep as a chicken”).

PULLS.d: Plural of PULL: To apply a force to (an object) so that it comes toward the person or thing applying the force.
PULLS.e: Verb from Middle English pullen, from Old English pullian (“to pull, draw, tug, pluck off”), of uncertain ultimate origin. Related to West Frisian pûlje (“to shell, husk”), Middle Dutch pullen (“to drink”), Middle Dutch polen (“to peel, strip”), Low German pulen (“to pick, pluck,...

PULPS.d: Plural of PULP: A soft, moist, shapeless mass or matter.
PULPS.e: From Middle English pulpe, from Latin pulpa.

PUMAS.d: Plural of PUMA: A mountain lion or cougar (Puma concolor).
PUMAS.e: Borrowed from Spanish puma, from Quechua puma.

PUMPS.d: Plural of PUMP: A device for moving or compressing a liquid or gas.
PUMPS.e:
From Middle English pumpe, possibly from Middle Dutch pompe (“pipe, water conduit”) or Middle Low German pumpe (“pump”), probably ultimately imitative.
Compare Dutch pompen, German pumpen, and Danish pompe; also Spanish bomba (“pump”).

PUNAS.d: Plural of PUNA: An alpine biological community in the central portion of the Andes in which short, coarse grass supports a Native American population.
PUNAS.e: From Spanish puna, from Quechua puna.

PUNKS.d: Plural of PUNK: One who engages in sexual intercourse
PUNKS.e: Uncertain. Possibly from punk (“rotten wood dust used as tinder”), attested since 1678, to anything worthless (attested since 1869) and then to any undesirable person (since 1908). The relatively tame 21st century usage of punk (“prank”, verb) was popularized by the American tele...

PUNTS.d: Plural of PUNT: A pontoon; a narrow shallow boat propelled by a pole.
PUNTS.e: From Old English [Term?], from Latin pontō (“Gaulish flat-bottomed boat, pontoon”), from pons (“bridge”); readopted from Middle Low German punte (“ferry boat”) or Middle Dutch ponte (“ferry boat”) of the same origin.

PUPAS.d: Plural of PUPA: An insect in the development stage between larva and adult.
PUPAS.e: Borrowed from New Latin, from a special use of Latin pūpa (“little girl; doll, puppet”). Doublet of pupe; compare also puppet, puppy.

PURED.d: Past tense of PURE: Free of flaws or imperfections; unsullied.
PURED.e: From Middle English pure, pur, from Old French pur, from Latin pūrus (“clean, free from dirt or filth, unmixed, plain”), from Proto-Indo-European *pewH- (“to cleanse, purify”). Displaced native Middle English lutter (“pure, clear, sincere”) (from Old English hlūtor, hluttor), Mid...

PURIS.d: Plural of PURI: A type of unleavened bread from India and Pakistan, usually deep-fried.
PURIS.e: From Hindi पूरी (pūrī), a kind of fried flatbread.

PURLS.d: Plural of PURL: A particular stitch in knitting in which the working yarn is pulled through an existing stitch from front to back.
PURLS.e: Unknown; apparently related to Scots and dialect pirl (“twist, ripple, whirl, spin”), and possibly to Older Scots pyrl ("thrust or poke at"). Compare Venetan pirlo, an embellishment where the woven threads are twisted together. May be unrelated to purfle, though the meanings are ...

PURRS.d: Plural of PURR: To make a vibrating sound in its throat when contented or in certain other conditions.

PUSES.d: Plural of PUS: A whitish-yellow or yellow substance composed primarily of dead white blood cells and dead pyogenic bacteria, normally found in regions of bacterial infection.

PUTTS.d: Plural of PUTT: The act of tapping a golf ball lightly on a putting green.
PUTTS.e: Borrowed from Scots putt (“to put”). Compare Middle Dutch putten (“to dig a pit”). The Old English putian (“to push; thrust; put; place”) derivation is commonly assumed, although no longer valid. In Dutch, the word is instanced in a description of golf in an early seventeenth-cen...

PYRES.d: Plural of PYRE: A funeral pile; a combustible heap on which corpses are burned.
PYRES.e: Learned borrowing from Latin pyra (“pyre, funeral pile”), from Ancient Greek πυρά (purá), from πῦρ (pûr, “fire”). Doublet of fire.

PYXES.d: Plural of PYX: A small, usually round container used to hold the host (“consecrated bread or wafer of the Eucharist”), especially when bringing communion to the sick or others unable to attend Mass.
PYXES.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English pix, pixe (“vessel for holding a host, pyx; hip bone socket, pyxis”) [and other forms], from Late Latin pyxis (“vessel for holding a host”), Latin pyxis (“small box for medicines or toiletries; box holding sample coins for testing; hip...

QUADS.d: Plural of QUAD: Clipping of quadrat.
QUADS.e:
Shortened, via clipping or abbreviation, from various English terms. Ultimately related to Latin quattuor (“4”); compare quadri-, quadruple.
The typography senses are from the abbreviation quad. for obsolete quadrat; the keyboard command comes from the verb sense.

QUAYS.d: Plural of QUAY: A stone or concrete structure on navigable water used for loading and unloading vessels; a wharf.
QUAYS.e: The current spelling replaced the spelling key in the 1690s to emulate the spelling but (at least originally) not the pronunciation of the equivalent modern French quai. From Middle English kay, key, kaye, keye, from Old French kay, cail, from Gaulish *kagyum, cagiíun (“enclosure...

QUIDS.d: Plural of QUID: The inherent nature of something.
QUIDS.e: Borrowed from Latin quid (“what, something”), neuter singular of quis (“who”).

QUIPS.d: Plural of QUIP: A smart, sarcastic turn or jest; a taunt; a severe retort or comeback; a gibe.
QUIPS.e: From a shortening of earlier quippy, perhaps from Latin quippe (“indeed”), ultimately quid (“what”).

QUITS.d: Plural of QUIT: Released from obligation, penalty, etc; free, clear, or rid.
QUITS.e:
From Middle English quiten, quyten, from Anglo-Norman quitter, Old French quitter, from quitte (“acquitted, quit”), ultimately from Latin quietus, which itself derives from Proto-Indo-European *kʷyéh₁-ti-s, from *kʷyeh₁- (“to rest”). Doublet of coy, quite, quiet, and quietus.

QUODS.d: Plural of QUOD: A quadrangle or court, as of a prison; a prison.
QUODS.e: Abbreviation of quadrangle; originally (17th century) referring to the quadrangles of Newgate Prison, London.

QUOTE.d: To repeat someone's words; a quotation.

RACED.e: From Middle English race, partially from Old English rǣs (“a race, swift or violent running, rush, onset”), from Proto-West Germanic *rās; and partially from Old Norse rás (“a running, race”); both from Proto-Germanic *rēsō (“a course”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reh₁s- (“to fl...

RACKS.d: Plural of RACK: A series of one or more shelves, stacked one above the other.
RACKS.e: From Middle English rakke, rekke, from Middle Dutch rac, recke, rec (Dutch rek), see rekken.

RADIO.d: The transmission of programs by electromagnetic waves.

RAFFS.d: Plural of RAFF: A disorderly heap; a jumble; a large quantity; lumber; refuse.
RAFFS.e: From Middle English raf, from Old French raffer, of Germanic origin; compare German raffen, akin to rap (“to snatch”). Compare riffraff, rip (“to tear”).

RAFTS.d: Plural of RAFT: A flat-bottomed craft able to float and drift on water, used for transport or as a waterborne platform.
RAFTS.e: Late Middle English, of North Germanic origin, from West Old Norse raptr, from Proto-Germanic *raf-tra-, from Proto-Indo-European *rap-tro-, from *rep- (“stake, beam”). See also Norwegian raft (“beam, rafter”), Danish raft (“thin pole”). Compare also Albanian trap (“raft, ferry”)...

RAGAS.d: Plural of RAGA: Any of various melodic forms used in Indian classical music, or a piece of music composed in such a form.

RAGED.d: Past tense of RAGE: Violent uncontrolled anger.
RAGED.e:
From Middle English rage, from Anglo-Norman rage, from Late Latin rabia, from Classical Latin rabiēs (“anger, fury”). Doublet of rabies.
Displaced native Middle English wode, from Old English wōd ("madness, fury, rage"; compare Modern dialectal English wood (“mad, insane, furious...

RAGES.d: Plural of RAGE: Violent uncontrolled anger.
RAGES.e:
From Middle English rage, from Anglo-Norman rage, from Late Latin rabia, from Classical Latin rabiēs (“anger, fury”). Doublet of rabies.
Displaced native Middle English wode, from Old English wōd ("madness, fury, rage"; compare Modern dialectal English wood (“mad, insane, furious...

RAIDS.d: Plural of RAID: A quick hostile or predatory incursion or invasion in a battle.
RAIDS.e: From Scots raid, from Northern Middle English rade, from Old English rād (“a riding, an expedition on horseback, road”), whence also the inherited English road (“way, street”). The earlier senses of “a riding, expedition, raid” fell into disuse in Early Modern English, but were r...

RAILS.d: Plural of RAIL: A horizontal bar extending between supports and used for support or as a barrier; a railing.
RAILS.e: From Middle English rail, rayl, *reȝel, *reȝol (found in reȝolsticke (“a ruler”)), partly from Old English regol (“a ruler, straight bar”) and partly from Old French reille; both from Latin regula (“rule, bar”), from regō (“to rule, to guide, to govern”); see regular. Doublet of ...

RAINS.d: Plural of RAIN: Condensed water falling from a cloud.
RAINS.e:
From Middle English reyn, rein, from Old English reġn, from Proto-West Germanic *regn, from Proto-Germanic *regną, of uncertain origin. Possibly from pre-Germanic *Hréǵ-no-, from Proto-Indo-European *Hreǵ- (“to flow”), although the consonant reflexes don't match.

RAKED.e:
From Middle English rake [and other forms], from Old English raca, racu, ræce (“tool with a row of pointed teeth, rake”), from Proto-Germanic *rakō, *rekô (“tool with a row of pointed teeth, rake”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃reǵ- (“to straighten, right oneself”).

RALES.d: Plural of RALE: An abnormal clicking, rattling or crackling sound, made by one or both lungs and heard with a stethoscope, caused by the popping open of airways collapsed by fluid or exudate, or sometimes by pulmonary edema.

RAMPS.d: Plural of RAMP: An inclined surface that connects two levels; an incline.
RAMPS.e: From French rampe, from Middle French rampe, deverbal of ramper, from Old French ramper (“to crawl, climb, scale up”), from Frankish *hrampōn (“to contract oneself, wrinkle, rumple, crumple, curve”), from Proto-Germanic *hrimpaną (“to shrivel, shrink”). Cognate with German Rampf ...

RANDS.d: Plural of RAND: The border of an area of land, now especially marshland.
RANDS.e: From Middle English rand, from Old English rand (“edge, border, margin, rim, shore”), from Proto-West Germanic *rand, from Proto-Germanic *randaz, *randō (“edge, rim, crust”), from Proto-Indo-European *rem- (“to rest, prop or support oneself”). Cognate with Dutch rand (“edge, bor...

RANIS.d: Plural of RANI: The wife of a rajah.
RANIS.e: From Hindustani رانی (rānī) / रानी (rānī), from Sanskrit राज्ञी (rā́jñī, “queen, princess”). Doublet of Regina.

RANKS.e: From Middle English rank (“strong, proud”), from Old English ranc (“proud, haughty, arrogant, insolent, forward, overbearing, showy, ostentatious, splendid, bold, valiant, noble, brave, strong, full-grown, mature”), from Proto-West Germanic *rank, from Proto-Germanic *rankaz (“st...

RAPES.d: Plural of RAPE: The act of forcing sex upon another person without their consent or against their will; originally coitus forced by a man on a woman, but now generally any sex act forced by any person upon another person, regardless of gender; by extension, any non-consensual sex act forced on, perpetrated by, or forced to penetrate any being.
RAPES.e: From Middle English rapen, rappen (“to abduct; ravish; seduce; rape; seize; snatch; carry off; transport”), probably from Latin rapiō (verb), possibly through or influenced by Anglo-Norman rap, rape (noun) (compare also ravish). But compare Swedish rappa (“to snatch, seize, carry...

RAPID.e: From Latin rapidus, from rapere (to seize).

RASED.e: From Late Middle English rasen, rasyn (“to rage; to enrage (?)”), probably from Middle Dutch râsen, râzen (“to be extremely angry, rage; to be mad, rave; to talk nonsense; of a dog: to be rabid”), from Old Dutch *rāson (modern Dutch razen), from Proto-West Germanic *rāsōn (“to ru...

RASPS.d: Plural of RASP: A coarse file or filelike tool, on which the cutting prominences are distinct points raised by the oblique stroke of a sharp punch, instead of lines raised by a chisel, as on the true file.
RASPS.e:
From Middle English raspen, from Old French rasper, from Frankish *hraspōn, from Proto-Germanic *hraspōną, related to Proto-Germanic *hrespaną (“to tear”). Compare Old High German raspōn (“to gather, rake”), Old English ġehrespan (“to tear”).
The noun is from Middle French raspe.

RATED.d: Past tense of RATE: The worth of something; value.
RATED.e: From Middle English rate, from Old French rate, from Medieval Latin rata, from Latin prō ratā parte (“according to a fixed part”), from ratus (“fixed”), from rērī (“think, deem, judge, estimate", originally "reckon, calculate”).

RATES.d: Plural of RATE: The worth of something; value.
RATES.e: From Middle English rate, from Old French rate, from Medieval Latin rata, from Latin prō ratā parte (“according to a fixed part”), from ratus (“fixed”), from rērī (“think, deem, judge, estimate", originally "reckon, calculate”).

RATIO.d: A quantitative relation between two amounts.

RAVED.d: Past tense of RAVE: An enthusiastic review (such as of a play).
RAVED.e: From Middle English raven (“to rave; talk like a madman”), from Old French raver, variant of resver, of uncertain origin. Compare rave below, and rove.

RAYED.d: Past tense of RAY: A beam of light or radiation.
RAYED.e: Via Middle English, borrowed from Old French rai, from Latin radius (“staff, stake, spoke”). Doublet of radius.

RAZED.e: The verb is derived from Middle English rasen, racen, rase (“to scrape; to shave; to erase; to pull; to strip off; to pluck or tear out; to root out (a tree, etc.); to pull away, snatch; to pull down; to knock down; to rend, tear apart; to pick clean, strip; to cleave, slice; to ...

RAZES.d: Plural of RAZE: To level or tear down (a building, a town, etc.) to the ground; to demolish.
RAZES.e: The verb is derived from Middle English rasen, racen, rase (“to scrape; to shave; to erase; to pull; to strip off; to pluck or tear out; to root out (a tree, etc.); to pull away, snatch; to pull down; to knock down; to rend, tear apart; to pick clean, strip; to cleave, slice; to ...

REACH.d: To stretch out; to arrive at.

READS.d: Plural of READ: To look at and interpret letters or other information that is written.
READS.e:
From Middle English reden, from Old English rǣdan (“to counsel, advise, consult; interpret, read”), from Proto-West Germanic *rādan, from Proto-Germanic *rēdaną (“advise, counsel”), from Proto-Indo-European *Hreh₁dʰ- (“to arrange”).
Cognate with Scots rede, red (“to advise, couns...

REALM.d: A kingdom; a field of activity.

REALS.d: Plural of REAL: True, genuine, not merely nominal or apparent.
REALS.e: From Middle English real, from Old French reel, from Late Latin reālis (“actual”), from Latin rēs (“matter, thing”), from Proto-Indo-European *reh₁ís (“wealth, goods”). Doublet of realis.

REAMS.d: Plural of REAM: Cream; also, the creamlike froth on ale or other liquor; froth or foam in general.
REAMS.e:
From Middle English reme, rem, from Old English rēam (“cream”), from Proto-West Germanic *raum, from Proto-Germanic *raumaz (“cream”), from Proto-Indo-European *réwgʰmn̥ (“to sour [milk]”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Room (“cream”), West Frisian rjemme (“cream”), Dutch room (...

REAPS.d: Plural of REAP: To cut (for example a grain) with a sickle, scythe, or reaping machine
REAPS.e: From Middle English repen, from Old English rēopan, rēpan, variants of Old English rīpan (“to reap”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīpan, from Proto-Germanic *rīpaną (compare West Frisian repe, Norwegian ripa (“to score, scratch”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyb- (“to snatch”).

REARS.d: Plural of REAR: To bring up to maturity, as offspring; to educate; to instruct; to foster.
REARS.e: From Middle English reren (“to raise”), from Old English rǣran (“to raise, set upright, promote, exalt, begin, create, give rise to, excite, rouse, arouse, stir up”), from Proto-West Germanic *raiʀijan, from Proto-Germanic *raizijaną, *raisijaną (“to cause to rise, raise”), from ...

RECKS.d: Plural of RECK: To take account of (someone or something); to care for; to consider, to heed, to regard.
RECKS.e: From Middle English recken, rekken, reken, from Old Norse rœkja (compare Old English rēċċan, rēċan (“to care, reck, take care of, be interested in, care for, desire”); whence English retch), from Proto-Germanic *rōkijaną (“to care, take care”), from Proto-Indo-European *rēǵ-, *rē...

REDOS.d: Plural of REDO: To do again.

REEDS.d: Plural of REED: Any of various types of tall stiff perennial grass-like plants growing together in groups near water.
REEDS.e:
From Middle English red, reed, from Old English hrēod, from Proto-West Germanic *hreud, of uncertain origin.
Akin to Saterland Frisian Rait (“reed”), West Frisian reid (“reed”), Dutch riet (“reed”), German Ried (“reed”). No cognates in North Germanic languages, but the existence ...

REEFS.d: Plural of REEF: A chain or range of rocks, sand, or coral lying at or near the surface of the water.
REEFS.e: From earlier riff, from Middle English rif, from Old Norse rif (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Germanic *ribją (“rib, reef”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rebʰ- (“arch, ceiling, cover”). Dutch rif (“reef”), Low German riff, reff (“reef”), German Riff (“reef, ledge”) are also borrowed fr...

REEKS.d: Plural of REEK: A strong unpleasant smell.
REEKS.e:
From Middle English rek, reke (“smoke”), from Old English rēc, from Proto-West Germanic *rauki, from Proto-Germanic *raukiz, from Proto-Indo-European *rowgi-.
See also West Frisian reek, riik, Dutch rook, Low German Röök, German Rauch, Danish røg, Norwegian Bokmål røyk; also Lith...

REELS.d: Plural of REEL: A shaky or unsteady gait.
REELS.e: From Middle English reel, reele, from Old English rēol, hrēol, from Proto-West Germanic *hrehul, from Proto-Germanic *hrehulaz, *hrahilaz, from Proto-Indo-European *krek- (“to weave, beat”). Cognate with Icelandic ræl, hræll.

REFED.d: Past tense of REF: Clipping of referee.

REINS.d: Plural of REIN: A strap or rope attached to a bridle or bit, used to control a horse, animal or young child.
REINS.e:
From Middle English rein, reyne, from Anglo-Norman reyne, resne, from Early Medieval Latin retina, ultimately from Classical Latin retineō (“hold back”), from re- + teneō (“keep, hold”). Compare modern French rêne.
Displaced native Old English brīdel (“bridle, rein”), Old English...

RENDS.d: Plural of REND: To separate into parts with force or sudden violence; to split; to burst.
RENDS.e: From Middle English renden, from Old English rendan (“to rend, tear, cut, lacerate, cut down”), from Proto-West Germanic *(h)randijan (“to tear”), of uncertain origin. Believed by some to be the causative of Proto-Germanic *hrindaną (“to push”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱret-, *...

RENTS.d: Plural of RENT: A payment made by a tenant at intervals in order to lease a property.
RENTS.e: From Middle English rent, rente, from Old French rente, from Early Medieval Latin rendita, from Late Latin rendere, from Latin reddere.

RESTS.d: Plural of REST: Relief from work or activity by sleeping; sleep.
RESTS.e: From Middle English rest, reste, from Old English ræst, from Proto-West Germanic *rastu, from Proto-Germanic *rastō, from Proto-Indo-European *ros-, *res-, *erH- (“rest”). Cognate with West Frisian rêst (“rest”), Dutch rust (“rest”), German Rast (“rest”), Swedish rast (“rest”), N...

RHEAS.d: Plural of RHEA: A large flightless bird of the order Rheiformes, native to South America.
RHEAS.e: Learned borrowing from taxonomic name Rhea, from Ancient Greek Ῥέα (Rhéa, “the mother of Zeus in Greek mythology”).

RIALS.d: Plural of RIAL: The official currencies of Iran, Oman, and Yemen.
RIALS.e: Borrowed from Persian ریال (riyâl) (in the case of Iran) and a variant transliteration of Arabic رِيَال (riyāl) (in the case of Oman and Yemen), from Spanish real. Doublet of real, royal, and regal.

RICED.d: Past tense of RICE: Cereal plants, Oryza sativa of the grass family whose seeds are used as food.
RICED.e: From Middle English rys, from Old French ris, from Old Italian riso, risi, from Byzantine Greek ὄρυζα (óruza), from an Eastern Iranian language related to Middle Persian blnc (*brinǰ), Northern Kurdish riz (beyond Euphrates) and Zazaki riz. Theorized to come to Iranian languages ...

RICES.d: Plural of RICE: Cereal plants, Oryza sativa of the grass family whose seeds are used as food.
RICES.e: From Middle English rys, from Old French ris, from Old Italian riso, risi, from Byzantine Greek ὄρυζα (óruza), from an Eastern Iranian language related to Middle Persian blnc (*brinǰ), Northern Kurdish riz (beyond Euphrates) and Zazaki riz. Theorized to come to Iranian languages ...

RICKS.d: Plural of RICK: Straw, hay etc. stored in a stack for winter fodder, commonly protected with thatch.
RICKS.e: From Middle English *rykke, from Old English hrycce (“rick, heap, pile”), cognate with Scots ruk (“rick”), Norwegian ruka (“rick, haystack”). Related also to Old English hrēac (“rick, stack”), from Proto-Germanic *hraukaz (“heap”). Further relations: Dutch rook, Icelandic hraukur...

RIDES.d: Plural of RIDE: To transport oneself by sitting on and directing a horse, later also a bicycle etc.
RIDES.e:
From Middle English riden, from Old English rīdan, from Proto-West Germanic *rīdan, from Proto-Germanic *rīdaną, from Proto-Indo-European *Hreydʰ-, from Proto-Indo-European *h₃reyH-.
Cognates
From Proto-Germanic: North Frisian ride (“to ride”), Saterland Frisian riede (“to ride”)...

RIFFS.d: Plural of RIFF: A repeated melody line in a song, usually instrumental but sometimes vocal.
RIFFS.e: Uncertain. Perhaps a clipping of riffle, or an alteration of refrain.

RIFTS.d: Plural of RIFT: A chasm or fissure.
RIFTS.e: From Middle English rift, of North Germanic origin; akin to Danish rift, Norwegian Bokmål rift (“breach”), Old Norse rífa (“to tear”). More at rive.

RILED.d: Past tense of RILE: To stir or move from a state of calm or order.
RILED.e: From a dialectal pronunciation of roil.

RILES.d: Plural of RILE: To stir or move from a state of calm or order.
RILES.e: From a dialectal pronunciation of roil.

RILLS.d: Plural of RILL: A very small brook; a streamlet; a creek, rivulet.
RILLS.e: From or akin to West Frisian ril (“rill; a narrow channel”), Dutch ril (“rill; gully; trench; watercourse”), German Low German Rille, Rill (“a small channel; brook; furrow”), German Rille (“a groove; furrow”).

RIMED.d: Past tense of RIME: Archaic in the form rimes: originally, any frozen dew forming a white deposit on exposed surfaces; hoar frost (sense 1).
RIMED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English rim, rime, rym, ryme (“hoar frost; rime”), from Old English hrīm (“frost”), from Proto-West Germanic *hrīm (“rime; hoar frost”), from Proto-Germanic *hrīmą (North Germanic), *hrīmaz, *hrīmô (“rime; hoar frost”), probably from Proto-Indo-Eur...

RIMES.d: Plural of RIME: Archaic in the form rimes: originally, any frozen dew forming a white deposit on exposed surfaces; hoar frost (sense 1).
RIMES.e: The noun is derived from Middle English rim, rime, rym, ryme (“hoar frost; rime”), from Old English hrīm (“frost”), from Proto-West Germanic *hrīm (“rime; hoar frost”), from Proto-Germanic *hrīmą (North Germanic), *hrīmaz, *hrīmô (“rime; hoar frost”), probably from Proto-Indo-Eur...

RINDS.e: From Middle English rind, rinde, from Old English rind and rinde (“treebark, crust”), from Proto-West Germanic *rindā, from Proto-Germanic *rindō, *rindǭ (“crust, rind”), from Proto-Indo-European *rem- (“to come to rest, support or prop oneself”). Cognate with German Rinde (“bark...

RINGS.d: Plural of RING: A solid object in the shape of a circle.
RINGS.e: From Middle English ryng, from Old English hring (“ring, circle”), from Proto-West Germanic *hring, from Proto-Germanic *hringaz (“ring”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)krengʰ-, extended nasalized form of *(s)ker- (“to turn, bend”). Doublet of rank and rink, as well as indirectly ...

RINKS.d: Plural of RINK: A man, especially a warrior or hero.
RINKS.e:
From Middle English rink, renk, from Old English rinc (“man, warrior, hero”), from Proto-Germanic *rankiz (“upright man”), from *rankaz (“straight, upright”), from Proto-Indo-European *reǵ- (“straight, direct”).
Cognate with Scots rink, renk (“man, warrior, hero”), Old Saxon rink...

RIOTS.d: Plural of RIOT: A tumultuous disturbance of the public peace by a large group of people, often involving violence or damage to property.
RIOTS.e:
From Middle English riot (“debauched living, dissipation”), from Old French riote (“debate”), from rioter (“to quarrel”), perhaps related to riboter or from Latin rugio (“I roar”).
Compare French riotte and Occitan riòta.

RIPED.d: Past tense of RIPE: Ready for reaping or gathering; having attained perfection; mature.
RIPED.e: From Middle English ripe, rype, from Old English rīpe (“ripe, mature”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīpī, from Proto-Germanic *rīpijaz, *rīpiz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyb- (“to snatch”). Cognate with West Frisian ryp (“ripe”), Dutch rijp (“ripe”), German reif (“ripe”). Relate...

RIPES.d: Plural of RIPE: Ready for reaping or gathering; having attained perfection; mature.
RIPES.e: From Middle English ripe, rype, from Old English rīpe (“ripe, mature”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīpī, from Proto-Germanic *rīpijaz, *rīpiz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyb- (“to snatch”). Cognate with West Frisian ryp (“ripe”), Dutch rijp (“ripe”), German reif (“ripe”). Relate...

RISES.d: Plural of RISE: To move, or appear to move, physically upwards relative to the ground.
RISES.e:
From Middle English risen, from Old English rīsan, from Proto-West Germanic *rīsan, from Proto-Germanic *rīsaną, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁rey- (“to rise, arise”). According to Kroonen (2013), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃er- (“to stir, rise”). See also raise.

Cognate w...

RISKS.d: Plural of RISK: The probability of a negative outcome to a decision or event.
RISKS.e:
From earlier risque, from Middle French risque, from Old Italian risco (“risk”) (modern Italian rischio) and rischiare (“to run into danger”). Displaced native Old English pleoh (“risk”) and plēon (“to risk”).
speculation on earlier roots

RITES.d: Plural of RITE: A religious custom.
RITES.e: Via Middle English and Old French, from Latin ritus.

RIVED.d: Past tense of RIVE: To tear apart by force; to rend; to split; to cleave.
RIVED.e:
From Middle English riven (“to rive”), of North Germanic origin, from Old Norse rífa (“to rend, tear apart”), from Proto-Germanic *rīfaną (“to tear, scratch”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyp- (“to crumble, tear”).
Cognate with Danish rive (“to tear”), Old Frisian rīva (“to tear...

RIVER.d: A large natural stream of water.

RIVES.d: Plural of RIFE: Widespread, common, prevalent, current (mainly of unpleasant or harmful things).
RIVES.e: From Middle English rife, from Old English rīfe, rȳfe (“rife, abundant, frequent”), from Proto-West Germanic *rīb, from Proto-Germanic *rībaz (“generous”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁reyp- (“to tear (off), rip”). Cognate with West Frisian rju (“rife, much”), Dutch rijf (“abundan...

ROADS.d: Plural of ROAD: A way used for travelling between places, originally one wide enough to allow foot passengers and horses to travel, now (US) usually one surfaced with asphalt or concrete and designed to accommodate many vehicles travelling in both directions. In the UK both senses are heard: a country road is the same as a country lane.
ROADS.e: From Middle English rode, rade (“ride, journey”), from Old English rād (“riding, hostile incursion”), from Proto-West Germanic *raidu, from Proto-Germanic *raidō (“a ride”), from Proto-Indo-European *reydʰ- (“to ride”). Doublet of raid, acquired from Scots. Cognates include West ...

ROAMS.d: Plural of ROAM: To wander or travel freely and with no specific destination.
ROAMS.e: From Middle English romen, from Old English rāmian, from Proto-Germanic *raimōną (“to wander”), from *raim- (“to move, raise”), from *h₃reyH- (“to move, lift, flow”). Akin to Old English ārǣman (“to arise, stand up, lift up”), Old High German rāmēn (“to aim”) ( > archaic German r...

ROARS.d: Plural of ROAR: To make a loud, deep cry, especially from pain, anger, or other strong emotion.
ROARS.e:
From Middle English roren, raren, from Old English rārian (“to roar; wail; lament”), from Proto-West Germanic *rairōn, from Proto-Germanic *rairōną (“to bellow; roar”), from Proto-Indo-European *rey- (“to shout; bellow; yell; bark”), perhaps of imitative origin.
Cognate with Sate...

ROBED.d: Past tense of ROBE: A long loose outer garment, often signifying honorary stature.
ROBED.e: From Middle English robe, roobe, from Old French robe, robbe, reube (“booty, spoils of war, robe, garment”), from Frankish *rouba, *rauba (“booty, spoils, stolen clothes”, literally “things taken”), from Proto-Germanic *raubō, *raubaz, *raubą (“booty, that which is stripped or ca...

ROBES.d: Plural of ROBE: A long loose outer garment, often signifying honorary stature.
ROBES.e: From Middle English robe, roobe, from Old French robe, robbe, reube (“booty, spoils of war, robe, garment”), from Frankish *rouba, *rauba (“booty, spoils, stolen clothes”, literally “things taken”), from Proto-Germanic *raubō, *raubaz, *raubą (“booty, that which is stripped or ca...

ROBOT.d: A machine capable of carrying out actions automatically.

ROILS.d: Plural of ROIL: To render turbid by stirring up the dregs or sediment of.
ROILS.e: Origin uncertain. Possibly from French or Middle French rouiller (“to rust, make muddy”), from Old French rouil (“mud, rust”), from Vulgar Latin *robicula, from Latin robigo (“rust, blight”)

ROLES.d: Plural of ROLE: A character or part played by a performer or actor.
ROLES.e: From French rôle, from Middle French rolle, from Old French role, from Medieval Latin rotulus. Doublet of roll and rotulus.

ROLLS.d: Plural of ROLL: To revolve by turning over and over; to move by turning on a horizontal axis; to impel forward with a revolving motion on a supporting surface.
ROLLS.e: From Middle English rollen, partly from Old French roller, roler, röeler, röoler, from Medieval Latin rotulāre (“to roll; to revolve”), from Latin rotula (“a little wheel”), diminutive of rota (“a wheel”); partly from Anglo-Latin rollāre, from the same ultimate source.

ROMPS.d: Plural of ROMP: To play about roughly, energetically or boisterously.

ROODS.d: Plural of ROOD: A crucifix, cross, especially in a church.
ROODS.e:
From Middle English rode, rood (“cross”), from Old English rōd (“cross”), from Proto-Germanic *rōdō, *rōdǭ (“rod, pole”), from Proto-Indo-European *rōt-, *reh₁t- (“bar, beam, stem”).
Cognate with German Rute (“rod, cane, pole”), Norwegian roda (“rod”). Largely displaced by cross....

ROOFS.d: Plural of ROOF: The external covering at the top of a building.
ROOFS.e: From Middle English rof, from Old English hrōf (“roof, ceiling; top, summit; heaven, sky”), from Proto-Germanic *hrōfą (“roof”).

ROOKS.d: Plural of ROOK: A European bird, Corvus frugilegus, of the crow family.
ROOKS.e: * Inherited from Middle English rok, roke, from Old English hrōc, from Proto-West Germanic *hrōk, from Proto-Germanic *hrōkaz (compare Old Norse hrókr, Saterland Frisian Rouk, Dutch roek, obsolete German Ruch), from Proto-Indo-European *kerk- (“crow, raven”) (compare Old Irish ce...

ROOMS.d: Plural of ROOM: An opportunity or scope (to do something).
ROOMS.e: From Middle English roum, from Old English rūm (“room, space”), from Proto-West Germanic *rūm (“room”), from Proto-Germanic *rūmą (“room”), from Proto-Indo-European *(H)rewH-.

ROOTS.d: Plural of ROOT: The part of a plant, generally underground, that anchors and supports the plant body, absorbs and stores water and nutrients, and in some plants is able to perform vegetative reproduction.
ROOTS.e:
PIE word
 *wréh₂ds
From Middle English rote, root, roote (“the underground part of a plant”), from late Old English rōt, from Old Norse rót (Icelandic rót), from Proto-Germanic *wrōts, from Proto-Indo-European *wréh₂ds (“root”); Doublet of wort, radish, and radix.

ROPED.d: Past tense of ROPE: Thick strings, yarn, monofilaments, metal wires, or strands of other cordage that are twisted together to form a stronger line.
ROPED.e: From Middle English rop, rope, from Old English rāp (“rope, cord, cable”), from Proto-West Germanic *raip, from Proto-Germanic *raipaz, *raipą (“rope, cord, band, ringlet”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁roypnós (“strap, band, rope”), from *h₁reyp- (“to peel off, tear; border, edge...

ROPES.d: Plural of ROPE: Thick strings, yarn, monofilaments, metal wires, or strands of other cordage that are twisted together to form a stronger line.
ROPES.e: From Middle English rop, rope, from Old English rāp (“rope, cord, cable”), from Proto-West Germanic *raip, from Proto-Germanic *raipaz, *raipą (“rope, cord, band, ringlet”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁roypnós (“strap, band, rope”), from *h₁reyp- (“to peel off, tear; border, edge...

ROSED.d: Past tense of ROSE: A shrub of the genus Rosa, with red, pink, white or yellow flowers.
ROSED.e:
From Middle English rose, roose, from Old English rōse, but with its vowel influenced by Old French rose, both from Latin rosa.
cognates and more remote and uncertain etymology
The Latin is of uncertain origin, but likely via Oscan from Ancient Greek ῥόδον (rhódon, “rose”) (Aeoli...

ROTAS.d: Plural of ROTA: A schedule that allocates some task, responsibility or (rarely) privilege between a set of people according to a (possibly periodic) calendar.
ROTAS.e: Borrowed from Latin rota (“wheel”). Doublet of rotor and ruote.

ROTES.d: Plural of ROTE: Mechanical routine; a fixed, habitual, repetitive, or mechanical course of procedure.
ROTES.e: From Middle English rote (“custom, habit, wont, condition, state”), further origin unknown. Found in the Middle English phrase bi rote (“by heart, according to form, expertly”), c. 1300. Some have proposed a relationship either with Old French rote/rute (“route”), or Latin rota (...

ROUND.d: Shaped like a circle; a series.
ROUND.e: From Old French roond, from Latin rotundus.

ROUTE.e: From Old French rute, from Latin rupta via (broken way).

ROUTS.d: Plural of ROUT: A group of people; a crowd, a throng, a troop; in particular (archaic), a group of people accompanying or travelling with someone.
ROUTS.e: The noun is derived from Middle English rout, route (“group of people associated with one another, company; entourage, retinue; army; group of soldiers; group of pirates; large number of people, crowd; throng; group of disreputable people, mob; riot; group of animals; group of ob...

ROVED.d: Past tense of ROVE: To shoot with arrows (at).
ROVED.e: Probably from Middle English *roven, a Midlands variant of Northern Middle English raven (“to wander”), from Old Norse ráfa (“to rove; stray about”). Cognate with Icelandic ráfa (“to wander”), Scots rave (“to wander; stray; roam”).

ROVES.d: Plural of ROVE: To shoot with arrows (at).
ROVES.e: Probably from Middle English *roven, a Midlands variant of Northern Middle English raven (“to wander”), from Old Norse ráfa (“to rove; stray about”). Cognate with Icelandic ráfa (“to wander”), Scots rave (“to wander; stray; roam”).

ROWED.d: Past tense of ROW: A line of objects, often regularly spaced, such as seats in a theatre, vegetable plants in a garden, etc.
ROWED.e:
From Middle English rewe, rowe, rawe, from Old English rǣw, rāw, probably from Proto-Germanic *raiwō, *raigwō, *raih- (“row, streak, line”), from Proto-Indo-European *reyk- (“to carve, scratch, etch”).
Cognate with Scots raw (“row”), dialectal Norwegian rå (“boundary line”), Sate...

ROYAL.d: Relating to a king or queen.
ROYAL.e: From Old French roial, from Latin rēgālis.

RUCKS.d: Plural of RUCK: A throng or crowd of people or things; a mass, a pack.
RUCKS.e: From Middle English ruke, from or related to Old Norse hraukr, which is from Proto-Germanic *hraukaz (“haystack, heap”). Compare Icelandic hrúka, Swedish ruka.

RUFFS.d: Plural of RUFF: A circular frill or ruffle on a garment, especially a starched, fluted frill at the neck in Elizabethan and Jacobean England (1560s–1620s).
RUFFS.e: Clipping of ruffle, or possibly from rough.

RUING.d: Present participle of RUE: Sorrow; repentance; regret.
RUING.e:
From Middle English rewe, reowe, from Old English hrēow (“sorrow, regret, penitence, repentance, penance”), from Proto-West Germanic *hreuwu (“pain, sadness, regret, repentance”). Cognates include German reuen (“to regret, to repent”) and Dutch berouwen (“to regret, to repent”).

RUINS.d: Plural of RUIN: The remains of a destroyed or dilapidated construction, such as a house or castle.

SAFES.d: Plural of SAFE: Not in danger; out of harm's reach.

From Middle English sauf, safe, saf, saaf, from Old French sauf, saulf, salf (“safe”), from Latin salvus (“whole, safe”), from Proto-Italic *salwos, from Proto-Indo-European *solh₂- (“whole, every”).

SAGOS.e: From Malay sagu, via Portuguese sagu or Dutch sago.

SAIDS.d: Plural of SAID: simple past and past participle of say
SAIDS.e: From Middle English seide (preterite) and seid, iseid (past participle), from Old English sǣde, sæġde (preterite) and ġesæġd (past participle), equivalent to say + -ed.

SALES.d: Plural of SALE: An exchange of goods or services for currency or credit.
SALES.e: From Middle English sale, from Old English sala (“act of selling, sale”), from Old Norse sala (“sale”), from Proto-Germanic *salō (“delivery”), from Proto-Indo-European *selh₁- (“to grab”).

SALTS.d: Plural of SALT: A common substance, chemically consisting mainly of sodium chloride (NaCl), used extensively as a food ingredient, seasoning, condiment, and preservative.

PIE word

SANDS.d: Plural of SAND: Rock that is ground more finely than gravel, but is not as fine as silt (more formally, see grain sizes chart), forming beaches and deserts and also used in construction.
SANDS.e:
From Middle English sond, sand, from Old English sand, from Proto-West Germanic *samd, from Proto-Germanic *samdaz, from Proto-Indo-European *sámh₂dʰos, from *sem- (“to pour”).

SANED.d: Past tense of SANE: Being in a healthy condition; not deranged; thinking rationally.
SANED.e: Learned borrowing from Latin sānus (“healthy; sane”). Doublet of sound.

SANES.d: Plural of SANE: Being in a healthy condition; not deranged; thinking rationally.
SANES.e: Learned borrowing from Latin sānus (“healthy; sane”). Doublet of sound.
