SHOED.d: Past tense of SHOE: A protective covering for the foot, with a bottom part composed of thick leather or plastic sole and often a thicker heel, and a softer upper part made of leather or synthetic material. Shoes generally do not extend above the ankle, as opposed to boots, which do.
SHOED.e: From Middle English scho, sho, from Old English sċōh (“shoe”), from Proto-West Germanic *skōh, from Proto-Germanic *skōhaz (“shoe”), of unclear etymology; possibly a derivation from *skehaną (“to move quickly”), from Proto-Indo-European *skek- (“to move quickly, jump”). Eclipsed ...

SHOES.d: Plural of SHOE: A protective covering for the foot, with a bottom part composed of thick leather or plastic sole and often a thicker heel, and a softer upper part made of leather or synthetic material. Shoes generally do not extend above the ankle, as opposed to boots, which do.
SHOES.e: From Middle English scho, sho, from Old English sċōh (“shoe”), from Proto-West Germanic *skōh, from Proto-Germanic *skōhaz (“shoe”), of unclear etymology; possibly a derivation from *skehaną (“to move quickly”), from Proto-Indo-European *skek- (“to move quickly, jump”). Eclipsed ...

SHOOS.d: Plural of SHOO: To induce someone or something to leave.
SHOOS.e: From Middle English schew, schowe, show, showe, scou (“shoo!”, interjection). Compare Middle High German schū, schuo (“shoo!”, interjection) (modern German scheu! (“shoo!”)), Dutch schuwen (“to shun”), German scheuchen (“to scare, drive away”).

SHOOT.d: To fire a weapon; to photograph.

SHOPS.d: Plural of SHOP: An establishment that sells goods or services to the public; originally only a physical location, but now a virtual establishment as well.
SHOPS.e: From Middle English shoppe, schoppe, from Old English sċoppa (“shed; booth; stall; shop”), from Proto-Germanic *skupp-, *skup- (“barn, shed”), from Proto-Indo-European *skub-, *skup- (“to bend, bow, curve, vault”). Cognate with Dutch schop (“spade, kick”), German Schuppen (“shed”...

SHORE.d: The land along the edge of water.

SHOWS.d: Plural of SHOW: To display, to have somebody see (something).
SHOWS.e: From Middle English schewen, from Old English scēawian (“to look, look at, exhibit, display”), from Proto-West Germanic *skauwōn, from Proto-Germanic *skawwōną (“to look, see”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewh₁- (“to heed, look, feel, take note of”); see haw, gaum, caveat, caut...

SHUNS.d: Plural of SHUN: To avoid, especially persistently; ostracize.
SHUNS.e: From Middle English schonen (“to decline to do, avoid, fear”), from Old English sċunian (“to shun, fear, avoid”), of uncertain origin, though probably ultimately connected to the Proto-Indo-European root *(s)kewH- (“to cover, conceal”) via Proto-Germanic [Term?]; see that entry f...

SHUTS.d: Plural of SHUT: To close, in various senses.
SHUTS.e: From Middle English shutten, shetten, from Old English scyttan (“to cause rapid movement, shoot a bolt, shut, bolt”), from Proto-Germanic *skutjaną, *skuttijaną (“to bar, bolt”), from Proto-Germanic *skuttą, *skuttjō (“bar, bolt, shed”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kewd- (“to dr...

SICES.d: Plural of SICE: Alternative spelling of sais.

SICKS.d: Plural of SICK: In poor health; ill.
SICKS.e:
From Middle English sik, sike, seek, seke, seok, from Old English sēoc (“sick, ill”), from Proto-West Germanic *seuk, from Proto-Germanic *seukaz, from Proto-Indo-European *sewg- (“to be troubled or grieved”).
See also West Frisian siik, Dutch ziek, German siech, Norwegian Bokmål...

SIDED.d: Past tense of SIDE: A bounding straight edge of a two-dimensional shape.
SIDED.e: From Middle English side, from Old English sīde (“side, flank”), from Proto-Germanic *sīdǭ (“side, flank, edge, shore”), from Proto-Indo-European *sēy- (“to send, throw, drop, sow, deposit”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Siede (“side”), West Frisian side (“side”), Dutch zijde, ...

SIDES.d: Plural of SIDE: A bounding straight edge of a two-dimensional shape.
SIDES.e: From Middle English side, from Old English sīde (“side, flank”), from Proto-Germanic *sīdǭ (“side, flank, edge, shore”), from Proto-Indo-European *sēy- (“to send, throw, drop, sow, deposit”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian Siede (“side”), West Frisian side (“side”), Dutch zijde, ...

SIFTS.d: Plural of SIFT: To sieve or strain (something).
SIFTS.e: From Middle English syften, from Old English siftan, from Proto-West Germanic *siftijan.

SIGHS.d: Plural of SIGH: To inhale a larger quantity of air than usual, and immediately expel it; to make a deep single audible respiration, especially as the result or involuntary expression of fatigue, exhaustion, grief, sorrow, frustration, or the like.
SIGHS.e: From Middle English sighen (“to sigh”), back-formation from sighte, past tense form of siken, from Old English sīcan, from Proto-West Germanic *sīkan, perhaps ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *seykʷ- (“to pour out”).

SIGHT.d: The faculty of seeing; a view.

SIGNS.d: Plural of SIGN: A visible fact that shows that something exists or may happen.
SIGNS.e: From Middle English signe, sygne, syng, seine, sine, syne, from Old English seġn (“sign; mark; token”) and Old French signe, seing (“sign; mark; signature”); both from Latin signum (“a mark; sign; token”); root uncertain. Doublet of signum. Partially displaced native token.

SILKS.d: Plural of SILK: A fine fiber excreted by the silkworm or other arthropod (such as a spider).
SILKS.e: From Middle English silk, sylk, selk, selc, from Old English sioloc, seoloc, seolc (“silk”). The immediate source is uncertain; it probably reached English via the Baltic trade routes (cognates in Old Norse silki (> Danish silke, Swedish silke (“silk”)), Russian шёлк (šolk), obso...

SILLS.d: Plural of SILL: A breast wall; window breast; horizontal brink which forms the base of a window.
SILLS.e:
From Middle English sille, selle, sülle, from Old English syll, syl (“sill, threshold, foundation, base, basis”), from Proto-Germanic *sulī (“bar, sill”), from Proto-Indo-European *sel-, *swel- (“beam, board, frame, threshold”).
Cognate with Scots sil, sill (“balk, beam, floor, s...

SILOS.d: Plural of SILO: A vertical building, usually cylindrical, used for the production of silage.
SILOS.e: From Spanish silo, of unclear origin. See Spanish silo for more.

SILTS.d: Plural of SILT: Mud or fine earth deposited from running or standing water.
SILTS.e:
PIE word
 *séh₂ls
From Middle English silte, cilte, cylte, perhaps from Middle English silen ("to filter; strain"; equivalent to sile + -t), or cognate with Norwegian and Danish sylt (“salt marsh”), Middle Low German sulte (“salt-marsh”), German Sülze (“meat in aspic”), ultimatel...

SINCE.d: From a past time until now.

SINES.d: Plural of SINE: In a right triangle, the ratio of the length of the side opposite an angle to the length of the hypotenuse.
SINES.e: Borrowed from Latin sinus (“curve, bend; bosom”), a translation of Arabic جَيْب (jayb, “bosom”), a misidentification of the notation جيب (j-y-b), written without vowel diacritics, standing for Arabic جِيبَ (jība, “sine”), in turn from Sanskrit ज्या (jyā, “sine, chord, bowstring”)...

SINGS.d: Plural of SING: To produce musical or harmonious sounds with one’s voice.
SINGS.e: From Middle English singen, from Old English singan (“to sing”), from Proto-West Germanic *singwan, from Proto-Germanic *singwaną (“to sing”), from Proto-Indo-European *sengʷʰ- (“to recite, sing”). Cognate with Saterland Frisian sjunge (“to sing”), West Frisian sjonge (“to sing”)...

SINHS.d: Plural of SINH: A traditional tube skirt worn by Lao and Thai women, particularly northern Thai and northeastern Thai women.
SINHS.e: Borrowed from Lao ສິ້ນ (sin) or Thai ซิ่น (sîn).

SINKS.d: Plural of SINK: To move or be moved into something.
SINKS.e:
From Middle English synken, from Old English sincan, from Proto-West Germanic *sinkwan, from Proto-Germanic *sinkwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *sengʷ- (“to fall, sink”).
Compare West Frisian sinke, Low German sinken, Dutch zinken, German sinken, Danish and Norwegian Bokmål synke...

SIPED.d: Past tense of SIPE: Slit in a tire to drain away surface water and improve traction.
SIPED.e:
From Old English sipian, related to seep.
* around 888 AD, K Aelfred, translation of Boethius, Chapter 33, para.5 ,
: "Seo eorþe hit helt & be sumum dæle swilgþ, & for þam sype heo biþ geleht."

SIPES.d: Plural of SIPE: Slit in a tire to drain away surface water and improve traction.
SIPES.e:
From Old English sipian, related to seep.
* around 888 AD, K Aelfred, translation of Boethius, Chapter 33, para.5 ,
: "Seo eorþe hit helt & be sumum dæle swilgþ, & for þam sype heo biþ geleht."

SIRED.d: Past tense of SIRE: A lord, master, or other person in authority, most commonly used vocatively: formerly in speaking to elders and superiors, later only when addressing a sovereign.
SIRED.e: From Middle English sire, from Old French sire, the nominative singular of seignor; from Latin senior, from senex. Doublet of seigneur, seignior, senhor, senior, señor, senyor, signore, and sir. Cognate with French monsieur.

SIRES.d: Plural of SIRE: A lord, master, or other person in authority, most commonly used vocatively: formerly in speaking to elders and superiors, later only when addressing a sovereign.
SIRES.e: From Middle English sire, from Old French sire, the nominative singular of seignor; from Latin senior, from senex. Doublet of seigneur, seignior, senhor, senior, señor, senyor, signore, and sir. Cognate with French monsieur.

SISES.d: Plural of SIS: Initialism of Secret Intelligence Service.

SITED.d: Past tense of SITE: The place where anything is fixed; situation; local position
SITED.e: From Middle English site, from Anglo-Norman site, from Latin situs (“position, place, site”), from sinere (“to put, lay, set down, usually let, suffer, permit”). Doublet of sitio and situs.

SITES.d: Plural of SITE: The place where anything is fixed; situation; local position
SITES.e: From Middle English site, from Anglo-Norman site, from Latin situs (“position, place, site”), from sinere (“to put, lay, set down, usually let, suffer, permit”). Doublet of sitio and situs.

SITUS.d: Plural of SITU: Only used in in situ.

SIXES.d: Plural of SIX: A numerical value equal to 6; the number following five and preceding seven. This number of dots: (••••••).
SIXES.e:
PIE word
 *swéḱs
From Middle English six, from Old English six, from Proto-West Germanic *sehs, from Proto-Germanic *sehs, from Proto-Indo-European *swéḱs. Compare West Frisian seis, Dutch zes, Low German söss, sess, German sechs, Norwegian and Danish seks, also Latin sex, Ancien...

SIZES.d: Plural of SIZE: The dimensions or magnitude of a thing; how big something is.
SIZES.e: Attested since the 14th century, originally meant a “law or regulation that determines the amount to be paid”, from Middle English syse, sise (“regulation, control, limit”), from Old French cise, sise, aphetism of assise (“assize”), from the verb asseoir (“to sit down”), from Lat...

SKEPS.e: Late Old English sceppe, from Old Norse skeppa (“basket”). Cognate with Danish skæppe (“an old Danish unit of measure equalling 17.4 l”).

SKEWS.d: Plural of SKEW: To form or shape in an oblique way; to cause to take an oblique position.
SKEWS.e: The verb is derived from Middle English skeuen, skewe, skewen (“to run at an angle or obliquely; to escape”), from Old Northern French escuer [and other forms], variants of Old French eschuer, eschever, eschiver (“to escape, flee; to avoid”) (modern French esquiver (“to dodge (a ...

SKIDS.d: Plural of SKID: An out-of-control sliding motion as would result from applying the brakes too hard in a car or other vehicle.
SKIDS.e: From Middle English *skid, from Old Norse skíð (“a billet of wood, a beam or plank on which something rests”), from Proto-Germanic *skīdą (“log, clapboard”), from Proto-Indo-European *skey-t-, *skey- (“to split, divide, separate”). Cognate with English shide, from Middle English ...

SKIED.d: Past tense of SKY: The atmosphere above a given point, especially as visible from the surface of the Earth as the place where the sun, moon, stars, and clouds are seen.
SKIED.e: The noun is derived from Middle English sky (“sky; cloud; mist”), also spelled ski, skie, [and other forms], from Old Norse ský (“cloud”), from Proto-Germanic *skiwją (“cloud; sky”), from *skiwô (“cloud; cloud cover, haze; sky”) (whence Old English sċēo (“cloud”) and Middle Engli...

SKIER.d: Comparative form of SKY: The atmosphere above a given point, especially as visible from the surface of the Earth as the place where the sun, moon, stars, and clouds are seen.
SKIER.e: The noun is derived from Middle English sky (“sky; cloud; mist”), also spelled ski, skie, [and other forms], from Old Norse ský (“cloud”), from Proto-Germanic *skiwją (“cloud; sky”), from *skiwô (“cloud; cloud cover, haze; sky”) (whence Old English sċēo (“cloud”) and Middle Engli...

SKIES.d: Plural of SKY: The atmosphere above a given point, especially as visible from the surface of the Earth as the place where the sun, moon, stars, and clouds are seen.
SKIES.e: The noun is derived from Middle English sky (“sky; cloud; mist”), also spelled ski, skie, [and other forms], from Old Norse ský (“cloud”), from Proto-Germanic *skiwją (“cloud; sky”), from *skiwô (“cloud; cloud cover, haze; sky”) (whence Old English sċēo (“cloud”) and Middle Engli...

SKILL.d: The ability to do something well.

SKIMS.d: Plural of SKIM: To pass lightly; to glide along in an even, smooth course; to glide along near the surface.
SKIMS.e: From Middle English skemen, skymen, variants of scumen, from Old French escumer (“to remove scum”), from escume (“froth, foam”), from Frankish *skūm (“froth, foam”), from Proto-Germanic *skūmaz (“foam”), from Proto-Indo-European *skew- (“to cover, conceal”). See scum.

SKINS.d: Plural of SKIN: The outer protective layer of the body of any animal, including of a human.
SKINS.e: From Middle English skyn, skinn, from Old English scinn, from Old Norse skinn (“animal hide”), from Proto-Germanic *skinþą, from Proto-Indo-European *sken- (“to split off”), nasal variant of *skeh₁i-d- (“to cut”). Partially displaced native Old English hȳd (“skin, hide”), from wh...

SKIPS.d: Plural of SKIP: To move by hopping on alternate feet.
SKIPS.e:
From Middle English skippen, skyppen, of North Germanic origin, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *skupjaną, perhaps related to *skeubaną (“to drive, push”), iterative *skuppōną (“to push/move repeatedly, skip”), from Proto-Indo-European *skewbʰ- (“to push, throw, shake”).
Related t...

SKITS.d: Plural of SKIT: A short comic performance done by amateurs.
SKITS.e: Origin uncertain. Perhaps from Old Norse skjúta (“to shoot, dart, move quickly”), variant of skjóta. Compare flytja (“to move”). Alternately, perhaps a back-formation from skittish, which in turn may derive from Old Norse or another North Germanic language.

SKUAS.d: Plural of SKUA: Any of various predatory seabirds of the genus Stercorarius that often chase other seabirds to steal their catches.
SKUAS.e: From Faroese skúgvur (“Great Skua”), from Old Norse skúfr, of unknown origin.

SLABS.d: Plural of SLAB: A large, flat piece of solid material; a solid object that is large and flat.
SLABS.e: From Middle English sclabbe, slabbe, of uncertain origin; possibly from *slap, related to dialectal slappel (“portion, piece”), along with slape (“slippery”), sleip (“smooth piece of timber”), borrowed through Old Norse sleipr from Proto-Germanic *slaipaz, from Proto-Indo-Europea...

SLAGS.d: Plural of SLAG: Waste material from a mine.
SLAGS.e: Borrowed from Middle Low German slagge, slaggen (“slag, dross”), from Old Saxon *slaggo, from Proto-West Germanic *slaggō, from Proto-Germanic *slaggô, from Proto-Germanic *slagōną (“to strike”) + *-gô (diminutive suffix). Compare Middle Low German slāgen (“to strike”), since ori...

SLAMS.d: Plural of SLAM: To shut with sudden force so as to produce a shock and noise.
SLAMS.e: From Middle English *slammen (not recorded), apparently from a Scandinavian source ultimately from Old Norse slæma, slœma (“to slam, swing a weapon, strike an object out of reach”), related to Old Norse slamra, slambra (“to slam”). Cognate with Norwegian Bokmål slamre (“to slam”)...

SLAPS.d: Plural of SLAP: A blow, especially one given with the open hand, or with something broad and flat.
SLAPS.e: From Middle English slappen, of uncertain origin, possibly imitative. Compare Low German Slappe (“slap”), whence also German Schlappe (“defeat”). Compare also Italian sleppa (“slap”).

SLATS.d: Plural of SLAT: A thin, narrow strip or bar of wood (lath), metal, or plastic.
SLATS.e: From Middle English slatte, sklatte, sklat, sclat, from Old French esclat (“piece broken or split off, shiver, splinter”), from Old French esclater (“to split, burst”), from Frankish *slaitijan (“to split, break”), from Proto-Germanic *slītaną (“to rend, split”). Doublet of slate...

SLAYS.d: Plural of SLAY: To kill; to murder.
SLAYS.e:
From Middle English sleen, slayn, from Old English slēan (“to strike, beat, smite, stamp, forge, sting, slay, kill, impact”), from Proto-West Germanic *slahan, from Proto-Germanic *slahaną (“to fight, strike, kill”), from Proto-Indo-European *slak- (“to hit, strike, throw”).
Cogn...

SLEDS.d: Plural of SLED: A small, light vehicle with runners, used recreationally, mostly by children, for sliding down snow-covered hills; no draft animal pulls it.
SLEDS.e: From Middle English sledde, from Middle Dutch sledde or Middle Low German sledde (compare Dutch slee, slede, Low German Sleden), from Proto-Germanic *slidô (compare Saterland Frisian sliede, German Schlitten, Norwegian slede). Doublet of sleigh; also related to slide.

SLEEP.d: A state of rest with reduced consciousness.

SLEWS.d: Plural of SLEW: The act, or process of slewing.
SLEWS.e: In all senses, a mostly British spelling of slue.

SLEYS.d: Plural of SLEY: Reed (of a loom).
SLEYS.e: From Middle English slay, from Old English slege.

SLIDE.d: To move smoothly along a surface.

SLIMS.e: Borrowing from Low German or Dutch slim (“bad, sly, clever”), from Middle Dutch slim (“bad, crooked”), from Old Dutch *slimb, from Proto-West Germanic *slimb, from Proto-Germanic *slimbaz (“oblique, crooked”). The sense development would have been "slanting, cunning" (Dutch) > "i...

SLIPS.d: Plural of SLIP: To lose one’s traction on a slippery surface; to slide due to a lack of friction.
SLIPS.e: From Middle English slippen, probably from Middle Low German slippen, from Old Saxon *slippian, from Proto-West Germanic *slippjan, from Proto-Germanic *slipjaną (“to glide”), an iterative form of *slīpaną (“to slip, slide”), from Proto-Indo-European *sleyb- (“slimy; to slide”). ...

SLITS.d: Plural of SLIT: A narrow cut or opening; a slot.
SLITS.e: From Old English slītan, from Proto-Germanic *slītaną (“to tear apart”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)leyd- (“to tear, rend (cut apart), split apart”). Possibly cognate with Latin laed- (“to strike, hurt, injure”). Doublet of slite; also related to slice through French borrowing....

SLOBS.d: Plural of SLOB: A lazy and slovenly or obese person.
SLOBS.e: From Irish slaba. Compare slobber, which is of Germanic origin.

SLOES.d: Plural of SLOE: The small, astringent, wild fruit of the blackthorn (Prunus spinosa).
SLOES.e: From Middle English slo, sla, sloo, from Old English slā, slāh, from Proto-West Germanic *slaihā, from Proto-Germanic *slaihǭ, *slaihwō, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)leh₃y- (“bluish”). Doublet of Sliwa.

SLOGS.d: Plural of SLOG: A long, tedious walk or march.
SLOGS.e:
Probably a variation of slug (“to hit very hard”) or slough.
Possibly related to slag, seen in the North Germanic languages, in association with the third verb and second noun definition.

SLOPE.e: From Old English āslūpan (to slip away).

SLOPS.d: Plural of SLOP: A loose outer garment; a jacket or overall.
SLOPS.e: From Middle English slop, sloppe, slope, from Old English *slop (found in oferslop (“an outergarment, surplice”)). Cognate with Icelandic sloppur (“a long, loose gown”).

SLOTS.d: Plural of SLOT: A narrow depression, perforation, or aperture; especially, one for the reception of a piece fitting or sliding into it.
SLOTS.e: From Middle English slot, from Old French esclot, likely from Old Norse slóð (“track”). As a gambling machine, via clipping of slot machine. Compare sleuth. The scheduling (calendar) sense is by a metaphor whereby the time span is equated with the segment of a page or part of a d...

SLOWS.d: Plural of SLOW: Taking a long time to move or go a short distance, or to perform an action; not quick in motion; proceeding at a low speed.
SLOWS.e:
From Middle English slow, slaw, from Old English slāw (“sluggish, inert, slothful, late, tardy, torpid, slow”), from Proto-West Germanic *slaiw, from Proto-Germanic *slaiwaz (“blunt, dull, faint, weak, slack”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *sleyH-u- (“bad”).
Cognate with Sco...

SLUBS.d: Plural of SLUB: A small thickened portion or knot found in yarn, caused by defects or intentionally leaving sections of the yarn unspun.

SLUED.d: Past tense of SLUE: To rotate something on an axis.
SLUED.e: Unknown. Attested from the late 18th century.

SLUES.d: Plural of SLUE: To rotate something on an axis.
SLUES.e: Unknown. Attested from the late 18th century.

SLUGS.d: Plural of SLUG: Any of many gastropod mollusks, having no (or only a rudimentary) shell.
SLUGS.e: Originally referred to a slow, lazy person, from Middle English slugge (“lazy person", also "sloth, slothfulness”), probably of either Old English or Old Norse origin; compare Norn slug (“lazy, slothful, sluggish”), dialectal Norwegian slugg (“a large, heavy body”), sluggje (“hea...

SLUMS.d: Plural of SLUM: A dilapidated neighborhood where many people live in a state of poverty.
SLUMS.e: First attested in 1812. originally slang, in the sense "room", especially "backroom", of unknown origin.

SLURS.d: Plural of SLUR: An insult or slight, especially one that is muttered incoherently under one's breath.
SLURS.e: From Middle English sloor (“thin or fluid mud”). Cognate with Middle Low German sluren (“to trail in mud”). Also related to dialectal Norwegian sløra (“to be careless, to scamp, dawdle”), Danish sløre (“to wobble, be loose”) (especially for wheels); compare Old Norse slóðra (“to ...

SLUTS.d: Plural of SLUT: A sexually promiscuous woman.
SLUTS.e: From Middle English slutt, slutte, slute (“a dirty or slovenly person, usually a woman, scullery maid; messy animal to prepare as food; slush, mud”), probably from Old English *slȳte (“sleet”), from Proto-West Germanic *slautijā, from Proto-Germanic *slautijǭ (“sleet, hail”), rel...

SMART.e: From Old English smeortan (to cause pain).

SMEWS.d: Plural of SMEW: A small compact diving duck, Mergellus albellus, that breeds in the northern taiga of Europe and Asia and winters on sheltered coasts or inland lakes.
SMEWS.e: Origin unknown. In use since the 17th century.

SMOGS.d: Plural of SMOG: A noxious mixture of particulates and gases that is the result of urban air pollution.

SNAGS.d: Plural of SNAG: A stump or base of a branch that has been lopped off; a short branch, or a sharp or rough branch.
SNAGS.e: From earlier snag (“stump or branch of a tree”), from Middle English *snagge, *snage, from Old Norse snagi (“clothes peg”) (compare Old Norse snag-hyrndr (“snag-horned, having jagged corners”)), perhaps ultimately from a derivative of Proto-Germanic *snakk-, *snēgg, variations of...

SNAPS.d: Plural of SNAP: A quick breaking or cracking sound or the action of producing such a sound.
SNAPS.e: From Dutch snappen (“to bite; seize”) or Low German snappen (“to bite; seize”), ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *snappōn, from Proto-Germanic *snappōną (“to snap; snatch; chatter”), intensive form of *snapāną (”to snap; grab”, whence Old Norse snapa (“to get; scrounge”)), fro...

SNIBS.d: Plural of SNIB: A latch or fastening for a door, window etc.

SNIPS.d: Plural of SNIP: To cut with short sharp actions, as with scissors.
SNIPS.e: From Dutch snippen (“to snip; shred”) or Low German snippen (“to snip; shred”), of imitative origin. Compare snap.

SNOBS.d: Plural of SNOB: A person who wishes to be seen as a member of the upper classes and who looks down on those perceived to have inferior or unrefined tastes.
SNOBS.e: Late 18th century dialectal English snob (“cobbler”), of unknown origin. Early senses of the word carried the meaning of "lower status"; it was then used to describe those seeking to imitate those of higher wealth or status. Folk etymology derives it from the Latin phrase sine no...

SNOTS.d: Plural of SNOT: Mucus, especially mucus from the nose.
SNOTS.e:
From Middle English snot, snotte, from Old English ġesnot, *snott, from Proto-West Germanic *snott, *snutt, from Proto-Germanic *snuttuz (“nasal mucus”), from the same base as snout. Related also to snite.
Cognate with North Frisian snot (“snot”), Saterland Frisian Snotte (“snot”...

SNOWS.d: Plural of SNOW: The partly frozen, crystalline state of water that falls from the atmosphere as precipitation in flakes; also, the falling of such flakes; and the accumulation of them on the ground or on objects as a white layer.
SNOWS.e: The noun is derived from Middle English snaw, snou, snow (“snow; accumulation of snow; snowfall; snowstorm; whiteness”), from Old English snāw (“snow”), from Proto-West Germanic *snaiw (“snow”), from Proto-Germanic *snaiwaz (“snow”), from Proto-Indo-European *snóygʷʰos (“snow”), ...

SNUBS.e: From Middle English snubben (also snibben), from Old Norse snubba (“to curse, chide, snub, scold, reprove”), which, like the source of English snip, is probably imitative in some manner. Cognate with Danish snibbe, dialectal Swedish snebba.

SNUGS.d: Plural of SNUG: Warm and comfortable; cosy.
SNUGS.e: From dialectal English snug (“tight, handsome”), perhaps from Old Norse snøggr, from Proto-Germanic *snawwuz (“short, quick, fast”). Compare Icelandic snöggur (“smooth”), Danish snög (“neat”), Swedish snygg (“handsome, nice-looking”).

SOAKS.d: Plural of SOAK: To be saturated with liquid by being immersed in it.
SOAKS.e: From Middle English soken, from Old English socian (“to soak, steep”, literally “to cause to suck (up)”), from Proto-Germanic *sukōną (“to soak”), causative of Proto-Germanic *sūkaną (“to suck”). Cognate with Middle Dutch soken (“to cause to suck”). More at suck.

SOAPS.d: Plural of SOAP: A metallic salt derived from a fatty acid, commonly used in cleaning products.
SOAPS.e:
From Middle English sope, sape, from Old English sāpe (“soap, salve”), from Proto-West Germanic *saipā, from Proto-Germanic *saipǭ, from Proto-Indo-European *seyb-, *seyp- (“to pour out, drip, trickle, strain”).
Cognate with Scots saip, sape (“soap”), Saterland Frisian Seepe (“so...

SOARS.d: Plural of SOAR: To fly high with little effort, like a bird.
SOARS.e: From Middle English soren, from Old French essorer (“to fly up, soar”), from Vulgar Latin *exaurare (“to rise into the air”), from Latin ex (“out”) + aura (“the air, a breeze”), from Ancient Greek αὔρα (aúra, “breath”). Compare aura, and exhale.

SOCKS.d: Plural of SOCK: A knitted or woven covering for the foot.
SOCKS.e: From Middle English socke, sokke, sok, from Old English socc (“sock, light shoe, slipper”), a West Germanic borrowing from Latin soccus (“a light shoe or slipper, buskin”), from Ancient Greek σύκχος (súkkhos, “a kind of shoe”), probably from Phrygian or from an Anatolian language...

SODAS.e: From Italian soda. Sense 4 is an ellipsis of soda water.

SOFAS.d: Plural of SOFA: A raised area of a building's floor, usually covered with carpeting, used for sitting.
SOFAS.e: Borrowed from French sofa, ultimately from Arabic صُفَّة (ṣuffa, “a long seat made of stone or brick, covered with rich carpets and cushions and used for sitting”). Cognate with Aramaic צפא/Classical Syriac ܨܦܬܐ (ṣipā’, ṣeppəṯā, “mat, matting”). The word may have entered European...

SOFTS.d: Plural of SOFT: Easily giving way under pressure.
SOFTS.e: From Middle English softe, from Old English sōfte, alteration of earlier sēfte (“soft”), from Proto-West Germanic *samft(ī) (“level, even, smooth, soft, gentle”) (compare *sōmiz (“agreeable, fitting”)), from Proto-Indo-European *semptio-, *semtio-, from *sem- (“one, whole”). Cogn...

SOILS.d: Plural of SOIL: A mixture of mineral particles and organic material, used to support plant growth.
SOILS.e: From Middle English soile, soyle, sule (“ground, earth”), partly from Anglo-Norman soyl (“bottom, ground, pavement”), from Latin solium (“seat, chair; throne”), mistaken for Latin solum (“ground, foundation, earth, sole of the foot”); and partly from Old English sol (“mud, mire, ...

SOKES.d: Plural of SOKE: A soc (a medieval right to hold a court or to receive fines).
SOKES.e: From Middle English soke, from Medieval Latin (Anglo-Latin) sōca "right of jurisdiction", from Old English sōcn (“jurisdiction, prosecution”, literally “act of seeking”), from Proto-West Germanic *sōkni, from Proto-Germanic *sōkniz (“seeking, inquiry”), from Proto-Indo-European *...

SOLID.e: From Old French solide, from Latin solidus.

SOLOS.d: Plural of SOLO: A piece of music for one performer.
SOLOS.e: Borrowed from Italian solo, from Latin sōlus, probably related to se (“himself”).

SOMAS.d: Plural of SOMA: The whole axial portion of an animal, including the head, neck, trunk, and tail.
SOMAS.e: From New Latin, from Ancient Greek σῶμα (sôma, “body”).

SONES.d: Plural of SONE: a subjective unit of loudness for an average listener equal to the loudness of a 1000-hertz sound that has an intensity 40 decibels above the listener's own threshold of hearing

SONGS.d: Plural of SONG: A musical composition with lyrics for voice or voices, performed by singing.
SONGS.e: From Middle English song, sang, from Old English sang, from Proto-West Germanic *sangu, from Proto-Germanic *sangwaz (“singing, song”), from Proto-Indo-European *sengʷʰ- (“to sing”). Cognate with Scots sang, song (“singing, song”), Saterland Frisian Song (“song”), West Frisian sa...

SOOTS.d: Plural of SOOT: Fine black or dull brown particles of amorphous carbon and tar, produced by the incomplete combustion of coal, oil etc.
SOOTS.e: Inherited from Middle English soot, soote, sote, sot, from Old English sōt, from Proto-Germanic *sōtą (“soot”), from Proto-Indo-European *sed- (“to sit”). Cognate with dated Dutch zoet (“soot”), German Low German Soot (“soot”), Danish sod (“soot”), Swedish sot (“soot”), Icelandic...

SOPHS.d: Plural of SOPH: Clipping of sophomore.

SORAS.d: Plural of SORA: A rail (Porzana carolina) bird of North, Central, and northern South America.
SORAS.e: Early 19th-century sources observe that this term was in use in Virginia; presumably it is from an Indigenous American language of that area.

SORBS.d: Plural of SORB: The service tree, Sorbus domestica.
SORBS.e: Borrowed from Middle French sorbier (the tree), sorbe (the fruit), from Latin sorbus (the tree), sorbum (the fruit). See service tree.

SORES.d: Plural of SORE: Causing pain or discomfort; painfully sensitive.
SORES.e:
From Middle English sor, from Old English sār (“ache, wound”, noun) and sār (“painful, grievous”, adjective), from Proto-West Germanic *sair, from Proto-Germanic *sairaz (adjective) from Proto-Indo-European *sh₂eyro-, enlargement of *sh₂ey- (“to be fierce, afflict”).
See also Dut...

SORTS.d: Plural of SORT: A general type.
SORTS.e: From Middle English sort, soort, sorte (cognate Dutch soort, German Sorte, Danish sort, Swedish sort), borrowed from Old French sorte (“class, kind”), from Latin sortem, accusative form of sors (“lot, fate, share, rank, category”).

SOULS.d: Plural of SOUL: The spirit or essence of a person usually thought to consist of one's thoughts and personality, often believed to live on after the person's death.
SOULS.e:
From Middle English soule, sowle, saule, sawle, from Old English sāwol (“soul, life, spirit, being”), from Proto-West Germanic *saiwalu, from Proto-Germanic *saiwalō (“soul”), of uncertain ultimate origin (see there for further information).
Cognates
Cognate with Scots saul, sowe...

SOUND.d: Vibrations heard by the ear; healthy.
SOUND.e: From Old French son / Old English gesund.

SOUPS.d: Plural of SOUP: Any of various dishes commonly made by combining liquids, such as water or stock, with other ingredients, such as meat and vegetables, that contribute the food value, flavor, and texture.
SOUPS.e:
The noun is from Middle English soupe, sowpe, from Old French soupe, souppe, sope, from Late Latin suppa (“sopped bread”), from Proto-Germanic *supô (compare Middle Dutch sope (“broth”)). Doublet of sop and zuppa. See also sup and supper.
The verb is from the noun.

SOURS.d: Plural of SOUR: Tasting of acidity.
SOURS.e:
From Middle English sour, from Old English sūr (“sour”), from Proto-West Germanic *sūr, from Proto-Germanic *sūraz (“sour”), from Proto-Indo-European *súHros (“sour”).
Cognate with West Frisian soer, Dutch zuur (“sour”), Low German suur, German sauer (“sour”), Danish, Swedish and...

SOWED.d: Past tense of SOW: A female pig.
SOWED.e:
From Middle English sowe, from Old English sugu, from Proto-West Germanic *sugu, from Proto-Germanic *sugō, probably from Proto-Indo-European *su(H)kéh₂, from *suH- (“pig”).
See also West Frisian sûch, Dutch zeug, Low German Söög, German Sau, Swedish sugga, Norwegian sugge; also ...

SOYAS.d: Plural of SOYA: Alternative form of soy.
SOYAS.e: Borrowed from Dutch soja; from the Satsuma dialectal Japanese そや (soya), which is the topicalized form of 醤油 (そい, soi) (cognate to standard Japanese 醤油 (しょうゆ, shōyu)), from Late Middle Japanese 醤油 (しやうゆ, shiyauyu), orthographic borrowing from Middle Chinese 醬油 (tsjàng-yuw), from ...

SPACE.d: A continuous area; the universe beyond Earth.
SPACE.e: From Old French espace, from Latin spatium.

SPAED.d: Past tense of SPAE: To divine; foretell.

SPAES.d: Plural of SPAE: To divine; foretell.

SPANS.d: Plural of SPAN: The full width of an open hand from the end of the thumb to the end of the little finger used as an informal unit of length.
SPANS.e:
From Middle English spanne, from Old English spann, from Proto-Germanic *spannō (“span, handbreadth”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)pend- (“to stretch”).
Cognate with Dutch span, spanne, German Spanne. The sense “pair of horses” is probably from Old English ġespan, ġespann (“a jo...

SPARS.d: Plural of SPAR: A rafter of a roof.
SPARS.e: From Middle English sparre (“spar, rafter, beam”) (noun), sparren (“to close, bar”) (verb), from Middle Dutch sparre or Middle Low German Sparre, all ultimately from Proto-Germanic *sparrô (“stake, beam”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)par- (“beam, log”). Compare Dutch spar (“balk...

SPASS.d: Plural of SPAS: plural of spa

SPATS.d: Plural of SPAT: simple past and past participle of spit

SPAYS.d: Plural of SPAY: To destroy or remove the ovaries or uterus (of a female animal) to prevent pregnancy.
SPAYS.e: From Middle English spayen, spaien, from the Anglo-Norman espeier, equivalent to the Old French espeer (“to cut with a sword”), from espee (“sword”), whence the Modern French épée.

SPECS.d: Plural of SPEC: Clipping of specification.

SPEND.d: To pay out money; to use time.

SPEWS.d: Plural of SPEW: To eject forcibly and in a stream,
SPEWS.e:
From Middle English spewen, from Old English spīwan, from Proto-West Germanic *spīwan, from Proto-Germanic *spīwaną, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ptyēw- (“to spit, vomit”).
Germanic cognates include English spit, West Frisian spije, Dutch spuwen, Low German speen, spiien, German ...

SPICS.d: Plural of SPIC: A Latino; a person of Latin American descent.
SPICS.e: Possibly imitative of a Hispanic pronunciation of speak. Usually considered a contraction of the earlier used spiggoty.

SPIED.d: Past tense of SPY: A person who secretly watches and examines the actions of other individuals or organizations and gathers information on them (usually to gain an advantage).
SPIED.e: From Middle English spien, aphetic variant of earlier espien (“to espy”), from Old French espier (“to spy”), from Frankish *spehōn (“to spy”), from Proto-Germanic *spehōną (“to see, look”), from Proto-Indo-European *speḱ- (“to look”). Akin to German spähen (“to spy”), Dutch spied...

SPIER.d: Comparative form of SPY: A person who secretly watches and examines the actions of other individuals or organizations and gathers information on them (usually to gain an advantage).
SPIER.e: From Middle English spien, aphetic variant of earlier espien (“to espy”), from Old French espier (“to spy”), from Frankish *spehōn (“to spy”), from Proto-Germanic *spehōną (“to see, look”), from Proto-Indo-European *speḱ- (“to look”). Akin to German spähen (“to spy”), Dutch spied...

SPIES.d: Plural of SPY: A person who secretly watches and examines the actions of other individuals or organizations and gathers information on them (usually to gain an advantage).
SPIES.e: From Middle English spien, aphetic variant of earlier espien (“to espy”), from Old French espier (“to spy”), from Frankish *spehōn (“to spy”), from Proto-Germanic *spehōną (“to see, look”), from Proto-Indo-European *speḱ- (“to look”). Akin to German spähen (“to spy”), Dutch spied...

SPINS.d: Plural of SPIN: To rotate, revolve, gyrate (usually quickly); to partially or completely rotate to face another direction.
SPINS.e:
From Middle English spinnen, from Old English spinnan, from Proto-Germanic *spinnaną, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)penh₁-.
Cognates
Cognate with Dutch, German spinnen (“to spin”), Luxembourgish spannen (“to spin”), Yiddish שפּינען (shpinen, “spin”), Danish spinde (“to spin”), Far...

SPITS.d: Plural of SPIT: A thin metal or wooden rod on which meat is skewered for cooking, often over a fire.
SPITS.e: The noun is from Middle English spit, spite, spete, spette, spyte, spytte (“rod on which meat is cooked; rod used as a torture instrument; short spear; point of a spear; spine in the fin of a fish; pointed object; dagger symbol; land projecting into the sea”), from Old English sp...

SPIVS.d: Plural of SPIV: A smartly dressed person who trades in illicit, black-market or stolen goods, especially during World War II.
SPIVS.e: Unknown. Perhaps from spiff, spiffy. Spiv was the nickname of Henry Bagster, a Londoner arrested a number of times in 1904-6 for activities as described below, and may have been the archetype. Also possibly from Romani spiv (“sparrow”), as active and opportunistic.

SPOKE.d: Past tense of speak; a rod.

SPOTS.d: Plural of SPOT: A round or irregular patch on the surface of a thing having a different color, texture etc. and generally round in shape.
SPOTS.e: From Middle English spot, spotte, partially from Middle Dutch spotte (“spot, speck”), and partially merging with Middle English splot, from Old English splott (“spot, plot of land”), from Proto-West Germanic *splott, from Proto-Germanic *spluttaz (“segment”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

SPUDS.e: From Middle English spudde (“small knife”). Origin unknown; probably related to Danish spyd, Old Norse spjót (“spear”), German Spieß (“spear; spike; skewer”). Compare English spit (“sharp, pointed rod”). The use of the term for a potato perhaps first appeared in New Zealand and A...

SPURS.d: Plural of SPUR: A rigid implement, often roughly y-shaped, that is fixed to one's heel for the purpose of prodding a horse. Often worn by, and emblematic of, the cowboy or the knight.
SPURS.e: From Middle English spure, spore, from Old English spora, spura, from Proto-West Germanic *spurō, from Proto-Germanic *spurô, from Proto-Indo-European *sperH- (“to kick”).

STABS.d: Plural of STAB: An act of stabbing or thrusting with an object.
STABS.e: First attested in Scottish English (compare Scots stob, stobbe, stabb (“a pointed stick or stake; a thrust with a pointed weapon”)), from Middle English stabbe (“a stab”), probably a variant of Middle English stob, stub, stubbe (“pointed stick, stake, thorn, stub, stump”), from O...

STAGS.d: Plural of STAG: An adult male deer, especially a red deer and especially one in high adulthood versus a young adult.
STAGS.e: From Middle English stagge, steg, from Old English stagga, stacga (“a stag”) and Old Norse steggi, steggr (“a male animal”), both from Proto-Germanic *staggijô, *staggijaz (“male, male deer, porcupine”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *stegʰ-, *stengʰ- (“to sting; rod, blade; ...

STARS.d: Plural of STAR: Any small, natural and bright dot in the sky, most visible in the night or twilight sky. This sense includes the planets, but it is now sometimes used in exclusion of them due to influence from the technical astronomical sense.
STARS.e:
From Middle English sterre, from Old English steorra (“star”), from Proto-West Germanic *sterrō, variant of *sternō, from Proto-Germanic *sternô, *sternǭ (“star”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₂stḗr (“star”). Doublet of aster, stella, étoile, and estoile.
Cognates
Cognate with Scot...

STAYS.d: Plural of STAY: To remain in a particular place, especially for a definite or short period of time; sojourn; abide.
STAYS.e: From Middle English steyen, staien, from Old French estayer, estaier (“to fix, prop up, support, stay”), from estaye, estaie (“a prop, stay”), from Middle Dutch staeye (“a prop, stay”), a contracted form of staede, stade (“a prop, stay, help, aid”) (compare Middle Dutch staeyen, ...

STEMS.d: Plural of STEM: The stock of a family; a race or generation of progenitors.
STEMS.e: From Middle English stem, stemme, stempne, stevin, from Old English stemn, from Proto-West Germanic *stamni, from Proto-Germanic *stamniz, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *steh₂- (“to stand, stay”).

STEPS.d: Plural of STEP: An advance or movement made from one foot to the other; a pace.
STEPS.e:
From Middle English steppen, from Old English steppan (“to step, go, proceed, advance”), stepe (“step”), from Proto-West Germanic *stappjan, from Proto-Germanic *stapjaną (“to step”), *stapiz (“step”), from Proto-Indo-European *stebʰ- (“to support, stomp, curse, be amazed”).
Cogn...

STETS.d: Plural of STET: A symbol used by proofreaders and typesetters to indicate that a word or phrase that was crossed out should still remain.
STETS.e: Borrowed from Latin stet (“let it stand”), an inflection of stō (“I stand”).

STEWS.d: Plural of STEW: A cooking-dish used for boiling; a cauldron.
STEWS.e: From Middle English stewe, stue, from Anglo-Norman estouve, Old French estuve (“bath, bathhouse”) (modern French étuve), from Medieval Latin stupha, of uncertain origin. Perhaps from Vulgar Latin *extufāre, from ex- + Ancient Greek τῦφος (tûphos, “smoke, steam”), from τύφω (túphō...

STICK.d: A thin piece of wood; to adhere.

STIED.d: Past tense of STY: A pen or enclosure for swine.
STIED.e:
From Middle English sty, from Old English stī, stiġ (“sty, pen, a wooden enclosure; hall”, chiefly in compounds).
Cognate with German Stiege (“wooden crate”), dialectal German Steige (“hen-coop”), Danish sti (“sty, enclosure for swine, sheep, hens, etc.”), Swedish stia (“sty for ...

STIES.d: Plural of STY: A pen or enclosure for swine.
STIES.e:
From Middle English sty, from Old English stī, stiġ (“sty, pen, a wooden enclosure; hall”, chiefly in compounds).
Cognate with German Stiege (“wooden crate”), dialectal German Steige (“hen-coop”), Danish sti (“sty, enclosure for swine, sheep, hens, etc.”), Swedish stia (“sty for ...

STIRS.d: Plural of STIR: To disturb the relative position of the particles (of a liquid or similar) by passing an object through it.
STIRS.e: From Middle English stiren, sturien, steren, from Old English styrian (“to be in motion, move, agitate, stir, disturb, trouble”), from Proto-Germanic *sturiz (“turmoil, noise, confusion”), related to Proto-West Germanic *staurijan (“to destroy, disturb”). Cognate with Old Norse s...

STOPS.d: Plural of STOP: To cease moving.
STOPS.e: From Middle English stoppen, stoppien, from Old English stoppian (“to stop, close”), from Proto-West Germanic *stoppōn, from Proto-Germanic *stuppōną (“to stop, close”), *stuppijaną (“to push, pierce, prick”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tewp-, *(s)tewb- (“to push; stick”), from...

STORE.d: A shop; to keep for future use.

STORY.d: An account of events; a floor of a building.
STORY.e: From Anglo-Norman estorie / Old French estoree.

STOWS.d: Plural of STOW: A place, stead.
STOWS.e: From Middle English stowe, from Old English stōw (“place, location”), from Proto-West Germanic *stōu, from Proto-Germanic *stōō (“a place, stowage”), from Proto-Indo-European *steh₂- (“to stand, place, put”). Cognate with Old Frisian stō (“place”), Icelandic stó (“fireplace”), Du...

STRIP.d: A long narrow piece; to remove.

STUBS.d: Plural of STUB: Something blunted, stunted, or cut short, such as stubble or a stump.
STUBS.e: From Middle English stubbe (“tree stump”), from Old English stybb, stubb (“tree stump”), from Proto-West Germanic *stubb, from Proto-Germanic *stubbaz (compare Middle Dutch stubbe, Old Norse stubbr, Faroese stubbi (“stub”)), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)tew-; compare steep (“shar...

STUCK.d: Past tense of stick; unable to move.

STUDS.d: Plural of STUD: A male animal, especially a stud horse (stallion), kept for breeding.
STUDS.e: From Middle English stood, stod, from Old English stōd, from Proto-West Germanic *stōd, from Proto-Germanic *stōdą. Cognate with Middle Low German stōt, German Stute, Dutch stoet and Old Norse stóð.

STUDY.e: From Old French estudie, from Latin studium.

STUMS.d: Plural of STUM: Unfermented grape juice; must.
STUMS.e: From Dutch stom (“unfermented”, literally “mute; dull”). Compare French vin muet, German stummer Wein. Doublet of shtum.

STUNS.d: Plural of STUN: To incapacitate; especially by inducing disorientation or unconsciousness.
STUNS.e: Inherited from Middle English stonen, stone (“to astonish, stun, numb”, also stoneyen), probably either directly or indirectly from Anglo-Norman estoner (“to stun, astonish”), from Late Latin *stunāre, from Frankish *stunōn (“to thunder, crash”) or perhaps from an unattested Lati...

STYLE.d: A manner of doing something; fashion.

SUCKS.d: Plural of SUCK: An instance of drawing something into one's mouth by inhaling.
SUCKS.e: From Middle English souken, suken, from Old English sūcan (“to suck”), from Proto-West Germanic *sūkan, from Proto-Germanic *sūkaną (“to suck, suckle”), from Proto-Indo-European *sewg-, *sewk- (“to suck”). Cognate with Scots souke (“to suck”), obsolete Dutch zuiken (“to suck”), L...

SUETS.d: Plural of SUET: The fatty tissue that surrounds and protects the kidneys; that of sheep and cattle is used in cooking and in making tallow.
SUETS.e: From Middle English suet, sewet, borrowed from Anglo-Norman suet, siuet, from Old French seu, from Latin sebum.

SUGAR.e: From Old French sucre, from Arabic sukkar.

SUING.d: Present participle of SUE: To file a legal action against someone, generally a non-criminal (civil) action.
SUING.e: From Middle English seuen, sewen, siwen, borrowed from Anglo-Norman suer, siwer et al. and Old French sivre (“to follow after”) (modern French suivre), from Vulgar Latin *sequere (“to follow”), from Latin sequi. Cognate with Italian seguire and Spanish seguir. Doublet of segue. R...

SUITE.d: A set of rooms; a set of pieces.

SUITS.d: Plural of SUIT: A set of clothes to be worn together, now especially a man's matching jacket and trousers (also business suit or lounge suit), or a similar outfit for a woman.
SUITS.e: From Middle English sute, borrowed from Anglo-Norman suite and Old French sieute, siute (modern suite), originally a participle adjective from Vulgar Latin *sequita (for secūta), from Latin sequi (“to follow”), because the component garments "follow each other", i.e. are worn tog...

SULKS.d: Plural of SULK: To express ill humor or offence by remaining sullenly silent or withdrawn.
SULKS.e: Back-formation from sulky, of uncertain origin. Probably from Middle English *sulke, *solke (attested in solcenesse (“idleness; laziness”), from Old English āsolcennys (“idleness; slothfulness; sluggishness; laziness”), from āsolcen (“sulky, languid”), from past participle of Old...

SUMOS.d: Plural of SUMO: A stylised Japanese form of wrestling in which a wrestler loses if he is forced from the ring, or if any part of his body except the soles of his feet touches the ground.
SUMOS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 相(す)撲(もう) (sumō).

SUMPS.d: Plural of SUMP: A hollow or pit into which liquid drains, such as a cesspool, cesspit or sink.
SUMPS.e: From Middle English sompe, either from Middle Dutch somp, sump or Middle Low German sump from Old Saxon *sump, from Proto-West Germanic *sump, ultimately from Proto-Germanic *sumpaz. Doublet of swamp.

SURAS.d: Plural of SURA: Any of the 114 chapters of the Quran.
SURAS.e: From Arabic سُورَة (sūra, “chapter of the Qur'an”).

SURDS.d: Plural of SURD: An irrational number, especially one expressed using the √ symbol.
SURDS.e: First attested in the mid 16th century from Latin surdus (“deaf, mute”), used in mathematics for “irrational,” reflecting ἄλογος (álogos, “irrational, speechless”) as found in Euclid, apparently transmitted via Arabic جِذْر أَصَمّ (jiḏr ʔaṣamm, “deaf root”). The phonetic sense, “...

SURED.d: Past tense of SURE: Physically secure and certain, non-failing, reliable.
SURED.e: From Middle English sure, seur, sur, from Middle French sur or Old French seür, from Latin sēcūrus (“secure”, literally “carefree”), from sē- (“apart”) + cūra (“care”) (compare Old English orsorg (“carefree”), from or- (“without”) + sorg (“care”)). See cure. Doublet of secure and...

SURES.d: Plural of SURE: Physically secure and certain, non-failing, reliable.
SURES.e: From Middle English sure, seur, sur, from Middle French sur or Old French seür, from Latin sēcūrus (“secure”, literally “carefree”), from sē- (“apart”) + cūra (“care”) (compare Old English orsorg (“carefree”), from or- (“without”) + sorg (“care”)). See cure. Doublet of secure and...

SURFS.d: Plural of SURF: Waves that break on an ocean shoreline.
SURFS.e: Probably from earlier suff, suffe (“the inrush of the sea towards the shore”), possibly from Middle English suffe. Compare sough, surf (“a gutter, drain, sewer, trench”) and sough (“a soothing, gentle, murmuring sound of wind or water”). Alternatively, possibly of Indo-Aryan orig...

SWABS.d: Plural of SWAB: A small piece of soft, absorbent material, such as gauze, used to clean wounds, apply medicine, or take samples of body fluids. Often attached to a stick or wire to aid access.
SWABS.e: Mid 17th century (in the sense 'mop for cleaning the decks'): back-formation from Middle English swabber (“sailor detailed to swab decks”), from Middle Dutch zwabber, from a Germanic base meaning 'splash' or 'sway', also found as nautical German Schwabber and Volga German Schwabb...

SWAGS.d: Plural of SWAG: To (cause to) sway.
SWAGS.e: From Middle English *swaggen, swagen, swoggen, probably from Old Norse sveggja (“to swing, sway”). Compare dialectal Norwegian svaga (“to sway, swing, stagger”).

SWANS.d: Plural of SWAN: Any of various species of large, long-necked waterfowl, of genus Cygnus (bird family: Anatidae), most of which have white plumage.
SWANS.e:
From Middle English swan, from Old English swan, from Proto-West Germanic *swan, from Proto-Germanic *swanaz (“swan”, literally “the singing bird”), from Proto-Indo-European *swonh₂-/*swenh₂- (“to sing, make sound”).

SWATS.d: Plural of SWAT: Acronym of special weapons and tactics, the area of expertise of police officers trained and equipped to neutralize armed or entrenched criminals.

SWIGS.e: Unknown, mid 16th c. Perhaps connected with Old English swelgan (“to swallow”).

SWOTS.d: Plural of SWOT: To study with effort or determination.
SWOTS.e: From a dialectal English word, from Middle English swot, swat, from Old English swāt (“perspiration; sweat”), from Proto-Germanic *swaitą (“sweat”). More at sweat.

SYNCS.d: Plural of SYNC: Clipping of synchronization or synchrony.

TACOS.e: Borrowed from Mexican Spanish taco, of uncertain origin; see the Spanish entry for more.

TALCS.d: Plural of TALC: Originally a large range of transparent or glistening foliated minerals. TALCS.e: From Middle French talc, from Arabic طَلْق (ṭalq), from Persian تلک (talk), from Middle Persian [Term?] (“medicament”).

TAMPS.e: Probably a back-formation from tampin (misinterpreted as tamping), a variant of tampion.

TANGS.e: From Middle English tange, variant of tonge (“tongs, fang”), from Old Norse tangi (“pointed metal tool”), perhaps related to Old Norse tunga (“tongue”). But see also Middle Dutch tanger (“sharp, tart, pinching”).

TAXED.d: Past tense of TAX: Money or goods collected by a government (or an entity to whom the government has delegated this power, e.g. in tax farming) to fund itself and its services, for example by levying a charge on income, purchases (sales), property or harvest, other than that money which is collected by the government in exchange for specific goods (e.g. the purchase of surplus vehicles).
TAXED.e: From Middle English taxe, from Middle French taxe, from Medieval Latin taxa, from Latin taxō (“to appraise, value, estimate; (medieval) to tax”). Doublet of task. Displaced native Old English gafol, which was also the word for “tribute” and “rent”.

TIRED.e: From Middle English tiren, tirien, teorien, from Old English tȳrian, tēorian (“to fail, cease, become weary, be tired, exhausted; tire, weary, exhaust”), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Proto-West Germanic *teuʀōn (“to cease”), which is possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dews-...

TIRES.d: Plural of TIRE: To become sleepy or weary.
TIRES.e: From Middle English tiren, tirien, teorien, from Old English tȳrian, tēorian (“to fail, cease, become weary, be tired, exhausted; tire, weary, exhaust”), of uncertain origin. Possibly from Proto-West Germanic *teuʀōn (“to cease”), which is possibly from Proto-Indo-European *dews-...

TIROS.d: Plural of TIRO: Alternative spelling of tyro; a newly recruited soldier.

TITIS.d: Plural of TITI: Any New World monkey of the subfamily Callicebinae, native to South America, distinguished by their long soft fur.

TITLE.d: A name; a right to property.
TITLE.e: From Old French title, from Latin titulus.

TOADS.d: Plural of TOAD: An amphibian, a kind of frog (order Anura) with shorter hindlegs and a drier, wartier skin, many in family Bufonidae.
TOADS.e:
From Middle English tode, toode, tadde, tade, from Old English *tāde, a shortened variant of Old English tādie, tādiġe (“toad”).
Cognate with Scots tade, taid, taed, ted (“toad”). Compare also Danish tudse (“toad”), possibly originally from the same prehistoric root; also Swedish...

TOFFS.d: Plural of TOFF: An elegantly dressed person.
TOFFS.e: Probably an alteration of tuft, referring to the gold tassel on the cap worn by titled undergraduates at English universities.

TOFUS.d: Plural of TOFU: A protein-rich food made from curdled soy milk.
TOFUS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 豆(とう)腐(ふ) (tōfu), from Middle Chinese 豆腐 (duwᴴ bju^X, “curdled bean”). Doublet of dubu and doufu.

TOGAS.d: Plural of TOGA: A loose outer garment worn by the citizens of Ancient Rome.
TOGAS.e:
Borrowed directly from Latin toga, from tegō (“I clothe”). Doublet of toge.
The Philippine (and Indonesian) senses are due to the resemblance of the white ceremonial gowns worn by graduates of institutions to the loose outer garment worn by the citizens of Ancient Rome.

TOGED.d: Past tense of TOG: A cloak.
TOGED.e: Shortened from earlier togemans, togeman (“cloak, loose coat”), from Middle English tog, toge, togue, from Old French togue, from Latin toga (“cloak, mantle”) (compare the doublets toga and toge). Togeman(s) was an old thieves' and vegabonds' cant for "cloak; coat". By the 1700s ...

TOILS.d: Plural of TOIL: Labour, work, especially of a grueling nature.
TOILS.e: From Middle English toilen, toylen, apparently a conflation of Anglo-Norman toiller (“to agitate, stir up, entangle”) (compare Old Northern French tooillier, tooullier (“to agitate, stir”); of unknown origin), and Middle English tilyen, telien, teolien, tolen, tolien, tulien (“to...

TOKED.d: Past tense of TOKE: A gratuity.

TOLLS.d: Plural of TOLL: A fee paid for some liberty or privilege, particularly for the privilege of passing over a bridge or on a highway, or for that of vending goods in a fair, market, etc.
TOLLS.e:
From Middle English toll, tol, tolle, from Old English toll m or n and toln f (“toll, duty, custom”), from Proto-West Germanic *toll, *tolnu, from Proto-Germanic *tullaz, *tullō (“that which is counted or told, reckoning”), from Proto-Indo-European *del- (“calculation, fraud”).
C...

TOMBS.d: Plural of TOMB: A small building, or a room within one, for the remains of the dead, with walls, a roof, and (if it is to be used for more than one corpse) a door. It may be partly or wholly in the ground (except for its entrance) in a cemetery, or it may be inside a church proper or in its crypt. Single tombs may be permanently sealed; those for families (or other groups) have doors for access whenever needed.
TOMBS.e:
From Middle English tombe, toumbe, borrowed from Old French tombe, from Latin tumba from Ancient Greek τύμβος (túmbos, “a sepulchral mound, tomb, grave”), probably from Proto-Indo-European *tewh₂- (“to swell”).
The verb is from Middle English tomben.

TOMES.d: Plural of TOME: One in a series of volumes.
TOMES.e: From Middle French tome, from Latin tomus (“section of larger work”), from Ancient Greek τόμος (tómos, “section, roll of papyrus, volume”), from τέμνω (témnō, “I cut, separate”).

TONED.d: Past tense of TONE: A specific pitch.
TONED.e: From Middle English ton, tone, from Latin tonus (“sound, tone”) (possibly through Old French ton), from Ancient Greek τόνος (tónos, “strain, tension, pitch”), from τείνω (teínō, “I stretch”). Doublet of tune, ton, tonos, and tonus.

TONES.d: Plural of TONE: A specific pitch.
TONES.e: From Middle English ton, tone, from Latin tonus (“sound, tone”) (possibly through Old French ton), from Ancient Greek τόνος (tónos, “strain, tension, pitch”), from τείνω (teínō, “I stretch”). Doublet of tune, ton, tonos, and tonus.

TONGS.d: Plural of TONG: An instrument or tool used for manipulating things in a fire without touching them with the hands.
TONGS.e: From Middle English tonge (“tongs, fang”), tange, from Old English tange, from Proto-West Germanic *tangu, from Proto-Germanic *tangō, from Proto-Indo-European *denḱ- (“to bite”). Cognate with Old Norse tǫng (modern Icelandic töng), Old High German zanga (modern German Zange). Ot...

TOOLS.d: Plural of TOOL: Any physical device meant to ease or do a task.
TOOLS.e: From Middle English tool, tol, from Old English tōl (“tool, implement, instrument”, literally “that with which one prepares something”), perhaps borrowed from Old Norse tól, but at any rate ultimately from Proto-Germanic *tōlą (“that which is used in preparation, tool”), from Pro...

TOONS.d: Plural of TOON: A cartoon, especially an animated television show.

TOOTS.d: Plural of TOOT: The noise of a horn or whistle.
TOOTS.e:
Probably onomatopoeic in origin. Compare Dutch toeteren (“to blow a horn”), German tuten, Swedish tuta, Danish tude.
Noun sense 7 ("Mastodon post") and verb sense 10 ("to post on Mastodon") are influenced by tweet (“Twitter post”).

TOPED.d: Past tense of TOPE: To drink excessively; to get drunk.
TOPED.e: Alteration of obsolete top (“to drink”), as in top (off).

TOPES.d: Plural of TOPE: To drink excessively; to get drunk.
TOPES.e: Alteration of obsolete top (“to drink”), as in top (off).

TOPIC.e: From Latin topica, from Greek topikós.

TORED.d: Past tense of TORE: Hard, difficult; wearisome, tedious.
TORED.e: From Middle English tor, tore, toor, from Old Norse tor- (“hard, difficult, wrong, bad”, prefix), from Proto-Germanic *tuz- (“hard, difficult, wrong, bad”), from Proto-Indo-European *dus- (“bad, ill, difficult”). Cognate with Old High German zur- (“mis-”, prefix), Gothic 𐍄𐌿𐌶- (tu...

TORES.d: Plural of TORE: Hard, difficult; wearisome, tedious.
TORES.e: From Middle English tor, tore, toor, from Old Norse tor- (“hard, difficult, wrong, bad”, prefix), from Proto-Germanic *tuz- (“hard, difficult, wrong, bad”), from Proto-Indo-European *dus- (“bad, ill, difficult”). Cognate with Old High German zur- (“mis-”, prefix), Gothic 𐍄𐌿𐌶- (tu...

TORTS.d: Plural of TORT: A wrongful act, whether intentional or negligent, regarded as non-criminal and unrelated to a contract, which causes an injury and can be remedied in civil court, usually through the awarding of damages.
TORTS.e: From Middle English tort (“(uncountable) wrong; (countable) an injury, a wrong”), from Old French tort (“misdeed, wrong”) (modern French tort (“an error, wrong; a fault”)), from Medieval Latin tortum (“injustice, wrong”), a noun use of a neuter singular participle form of Latin t...

TOTED.d: Past tense of TOTE: A tote bag.
TOTED.e: Possibly from Middle Low German tûte, tǖte (“horn, conical paper bag”), whence also German Tute (“horn, bugle”) and German Tüte (“bag, paper bag”). Compare also Scots tout (“a drinking vessel”), Saterland Frisian Tüütje (“paper bag”), West Frisian tút (“spout, toot, kiss”), Dutch...

TOTES.d: Plural of TOTE: A tote bag.
TOTES.e: Possibly from Middle Low German tûte, tǖte (“horn, conical paper bag”), whence also German Tute (“horn, bugle”) and German Tüte (“bag, paper bag”). Compare also Scots tout (“a drinking vessel”), Saterland Frisian Tüütje (“paper bag”), West Frisian tút (“spout, toot, kiss”), Dutch...

TOURS.d: Plural of TOUR: A journey through a particular building, estate, country, etc.
TOURS.e: From Old French tour, tourn, from the verb torner, tourner.

TOUTS.d: Plural of TOUT: Someone advertising for customers in an aggressive way.
TOUTS.e: From Middle English touten (“to jut out, protrude, gaze upon, observe, peer”), from Old English *tūtian (“to be sticking out, protrude”), related to Old English tȳtan (“to stand out, be conspicuous, shine”), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *tut(t)- (“to stick out, project”). Compa...

TOWED.d: Past tense of TOW: To pull something behind one, such as by using a line, chain, or tongue.
TOWED.e:
From Middle English towen, from Old English togian, from Proto-West Germanic *togōn, from Proto-Germanic *tugōną, from Proto-Indo-European *dewk-.
See also Middle High German zogen, German ziehen, Dutch tijgen, Old Norse toga.

TOWER.e: From Old French tur, from Latin turris.

TOWNS.d: Plural of TOWN: A settlement; an area with residential districts, shops and amenities, and its own local government; especially one larger than a village and smaller than a city, historically enclosed by a fence or walls, with total populations ranging from several hundred to more than a hundred thousand (as of the early 21st century)
TOWNS.e:
From Middle English toun, from Old English tūn (“enclosure, garden”), from Proto-West Germanic *tūn, from Proto-Germanic *tūną (“fence, enclosure”), of Celtic origin, from Proto-Celtic *dūnom, from Proto-Indo-European *dewh₂- (“to finish, come full circle”).
Cognate with Saterlan...

TOYED.d: Past tense of TOY: Something to play with, especially as intended for use by a child.
TOYED.e: Inherited from Middle English toye (“amorous play, piece of fun or entertainment”), probably from Middle Dutch toy, tuyg (“tools, apparatus, utensil, ornament”) as in Dutch speel-tuig (“play-thing, toy”), from Old Dutch *tiug, from Proto-West Germanic *tiugī̆, *teug, from Proto-G...

TRADE.d: The buying and selling of goods.

TRAIN.d: A connected line of vehicles; to teach.

TRAMS.d: Plural of TRAM: A passenger vehicle for public use that runs on tracks in the road (called a streetcar or trolley in North America).
TRAMS.e: Early 16th century, borrowed from Scots, probably from Low German traam (“tram, shaft of a barrow”), from Middle Low German and Middle Dutch trame (“narrow shaft, beam”), said to be ultimately from a lost West Germanic (Ingvaeonic) word, probably from Proto-Germanic *drum (“splin...

TRAPS.d: Plural of TRAP: A machine or other device designed to catch (and sometimes kill) animals, either by holding them in a container, or by catching hold of part of the body.
TRAPS.e: From Middle English trappe, from Old English træppe, treppe (“trap, snare”) (also in betræppan (“to trap”)) from Proto-West Germanic *trappjā (“trap, snare”), from Proto-West Germanic *trappjan (“to step”), from Proto-Germanic *trapjaną (“to tread, stamp”), from Proto-Indo-Europe...

TRAYS.d: Plural of TRAY: A small, typically rectangular or round, flat, and rigid object upon which things are carried.
TRAYS.e: From Middle English trey, from Old English trēġ, trīġ (“wooden board, tray”), from Proto-West Germanic *trauwi, from Proto-Germanic *trawją (“wooden vessel”), from Proto-Indo-European *drewo-, *dóru (“tree; wood”). Cognate with Old Norse treyja (“carrier”), Old Swedish trø (“wood...

TREAT.d: To behave towards; a special pleasure.

TREES.d: Plural of TREE: A perennial woody plant taller and larger than a shrub with a wooden trunk and, at some distance from the ground, having leaves and branches.
TREES.e: From Middle English tre, tree, treo, treou, trew, trow, from Old English trēo, trēow (“tree, wood, timber, beam, log, stake, stick, grove, cross, rood”), from Proto-West Germanic *treu, from Proto-Germanic *trewą (“tree, wood”), from pre-Germanic *dréwom, thematic e-grade derivat...

TREKS.d: Plural of TREK: A journey by ox wagon.
TREKS.e: From Afrikaans trek, from Dutch trekken, from Middle Dutch trekken (weak verb) and trēken (“to trek, place, bring, move”, strong verb), from Old Dutch *trekkan, *trekan, from Proto-West Germanic *trekan, from Proto-Germanic *trekaną, *trakjaną (“to drag, haul, scrape, pull”), fro...

TREYS.d: Plural of TREY: A nickname for someone who is the third person in the family sharing his father's name.

TRIER.d: Comparative form of TRY: To attempt; to endeavour. Followed by infinitive.
TRIER.e: From Middle English trien (“to separate out, sift, choose, select, evaluate, try a legal case”), from Anglo-Norman trier, triher, triere (“to divide, separate, choose, select, prove, determine, try a case”), Old French trier (“to choose, pick out or separate from others, sift, cu...

TRIES.d: Plural of TRY: To attempt; to endeavour. Followed by infinitive.
TRIES.e: From Middle English trien (“to separate out, sift, choose, select, evaluate, try a legal case”), from Anglo-Norman trier, triher, triere (“to divide, separate, choose, select, prove, determine, try a case”), Old French trier (“to choose, pick out or separate from others, sift, cu...

TRIGS.d: Plural of TRIG: True; trusty; trustworthy; faithful.
TRIGS.e: From Middle English trig, tryg, from Old Norse tryggr (“loyal, faithful, true”), from Proto-Germanic *triwwiz (“loyal, faithful, true”). Cognate with Old English trīewe (“faithful, loyal, true”). More at true.

TRIMS.d: Plural of TRIM: To reduce slightly; to cut; especially, to remove excess.
TRIMS.e: From Middle English trimen, trymen, trümen, from Old English trymman (“to make firm; strengthen”), from Proto-West Germanic *trummjan, from Proto-Germanic *trumjaną (“to make fast; strengthen”), from Proto-Germanic *trumaz (“firm; strong; sound”).

TRIOS.d: Plural of TRIO: A group of three people or things.
TRIOS.e:
PIE word
 *tréyes
1715-25; borrowing from Italian trio.

TRIPS.d: Plural of TRIP: A journey; an excursion or jaunt.
TRIPS.e: From Middle English trippen (“tread or step lightly and nimbly, skip, dance”), perhaps from Old French triper (“to hop or dance around, strike with the feet”), from a Frankish source; or alternatively from Middle Dutch trippen (“to skip, trip, hop, stamp, trample”) (> Modern Dutc...

TROTS.d: Plural of TROT: A gait of a person or animal faster than a walk but slower than a run.
TROTS.e: From Middle English trotten, from Old French trotter, troter (“to go, trot”), from Medieval Latin *trottō, *trotō (“to go”), from Frankish *trottōn (“to go, run”), from Proto-Germanic *trudōną, *trudaną, *tradjaną (“to go, step, tread”), from Proto-Indo-European *dreh₂- (“to run,...

TRUED.d: Past tense of TRUE: Conforming to the actual state of reality or fact; factually correct.
TRUED.e: From Middle English trewe, from Old English trīewe, (Mercian) trēowe (“trusty, faithful”), from Proto-Germanic *triwwiz (compare Saterland Frisian trjou (“honest”), Dutch getrouw and trouw, German treu, Norwegian and Swedish trygg (“safe, secure’”)), from pre-Germanic *drewh₂yos,...

TRUES.d: Plural of TRUE: Conforming to the actual state of reality or fact; factually correct.
TRUES.e: From Middle English trewe, from Old English trīewe, (Mercian) trēowe (“trusty, faithful”), from Proto-Germanic *triwwiz (compare Saterland Frisian trjou (“honest”), Dutch getrouw and trouw, German treu, Norwegian and Swedish trygg (“safe, secure’”)), from pre-Germanic *drewh₂yos,...

TSARS.d: Plural of TSAR: An emperor of Russia (1547 to 1917) and of some South Slavic states.
TSARS.e: Borrowed from Russian царь (carʹ), from Old East Slavic цьсарь (cĭsarĭ), from Proto-Slavic *cěsařь, from a Germanic language, from Proto-Germanic *kaisaraz, from Latin Caesar. Doublet of Caesar and Kaiser. The spelling tsar began to replace the older czar in the nineteenth centur...

TUBAS.d: Plural of TUBA: A large brass musical instrument, usually in the bass range, played through a vibration of the lips upon the mouthpiece and fingering of the keys.
TUBAS.e: Borrowed in the 19th century from French tuba (“tuba”), German Tuba (“tuba”), originally Baß-Tuba (literally “bass tuba”), or Italian tuba (“tuba”), from Latin tuba (“tube, trumpet, military trumpet”). The Latin term is of obscure ultimate origin, but is possibly connected to tīb...

TUBED.d: Past tense of TUBE: Anything that is hollow and cylindrical in shape.
TUBED.e: From Middle French tube, from Latin tubus (“tube, pipe”), related to tuba (“long trumpet; war-trumpet”), of obscure ultimate origin, but possibly connected to tībia (“shinbone, reed-pipe”); see there. Doublet of tubus.

TUBES.d: Plural of TUBE: Anything that is hollow and cylindrical in shape.
TUBES.e: From Middle French tube, from Latin tubus (“tube, pipe”), related to tuba (“long trumpet; war-trumpet”), of obscure ultimate origin, but possibly connected to tībia (“shinbone, reed-pipe”); see there. Doublet of tubus.

TUCKS.d: Plural of TUCK: To pull or gather up (an item of fabric).
TUCKS.e: From Middle English tuken, touken (“to torment, to stretch (cloth)”), from Old English tūcian (“to torment, vex”) and Middle Dutch tucken (“to tuck”), both from Proto-Germanic *teuh-, *teug- (“to draw, pull”) (compare also *tukkōną), from Proto-Indo-European *dewk- (“to pull”). A...

TUFTS.d: Plural of TUFT: A bunch of feathers, grass or hair, etc., held together at the base.
TUFTS.e: From Middle English tuft, toft, tofte, an alteration of earlier *tuffe (> Modern English tuff), from Old French touffe, tuffe, toffe, tofe (“tuft”) (modern French touffe), from Late Latin tufa (“helmet crest”) (near Vegezio). Compare Old English þūf (“tuft”), Old Norse þúfa (“mou...

TUNAS.d: Plural of TUNA: Any of several species of fish of the genus Thunnus in the family Scombridae.
TUNAS.e: From American Spanish alteration of the Spanish atún, from Arabic اَلتُّنّ (at-tunn, “tuna”) from Latin thunnus, itself from Ancient Greek θύννος (thúnnos). Possibly in the sense of "darter" from thynein "to dart along". Doublet of tonno.

TUNED.d: Past tense of TUNE: A melody.
TUNED.e: From Middle English tune, an unexplained variant of tone, from Old French ton, from Latin tonus, from Ancient Greek τόνος (tónos, “a tone”). Doublet of tone, ton, and tonus.

TUNES.e: From Middle English tune, an unexplained variant of tone, from Old French ton, from Latin tonus, from Ancient Greek τόνος (tónos, “a tone”). Doublet of tone, ton, and tonus.

TURDS.d: Plural of TURD: A piece of solid feces.
TURDS.e: From Middle English toord, tord, from Old English tord (“piece of dung, excrement, filth”), from Proto-West Germanic *tord, from Proto-Germanic *turdą (“manure, mud”), from Proto-Indo-European *der- (“to split, flay”). Cognate with Old English tyrdel (“dropping, small piece of ex...

TURFS.d: Plural of TURF: A layer of earth covered with grass; sod.
TURFS.e:
From Middle English turf, torf, from Old English turf (“turf, sod, soil, piece of grass covered earth, greensward”), from Proto-West Germanic *turb, from Proto-Germanic *turbz (“turf, lawn”), from Proto-Indo-European *derbʰ- (“tuft, grass”).
Cognate with Dutch turf (“turf”), Midd...

TURNS.e: From Middle English turnen, from Old English turnian, tyrnan (“to turn, rotate, revolve”), from From Proto-West Germanic *turnēn (“to turn, lathe”) (also the source of German turnen and its derivatives) and Old French torner (“to turn”), both from Latin tornāre (“to round off, tu...

TUSHS.e: From Middle English tusshe, tusche, tussch, tossche, tosch, from Old English tūsc, from Proto-Germanic *tunþskaz. Doublet of tusk.

TUSKS.d: Plural of TUSK: One of a pair of elongated pointed teeth that extend outside the mouth of an animal such as walrus, elephant or wild boar, and which continue to grow throughout the animal's life.
TUSKS.e: From Middle English tusk (also tux, tusch), from Old English tūx, tūsc (“canine tooth, tusk, molar”), from Proto-West Germanic *tų̄sk, *tunsk, from Proto-Germanic *tunþskaz (“canine tooth”), extended form of *tanþs (“tooth”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃dónts (“tooth”). Cognate w...

TUTUS.d: Plural of TUTU: A ballet skirt made of layered stiff but light netting.
TUTUS.e: Borrowed from French tutu, from cucu (“bum, bottom”), playful reduplication of cul (“arse”).

TWATS.d: Plural of TWAT: The vagina or vulva.
TWATS.e: Unknown origin. Possibly cognate with Old Norse þveit (“cut, slit, forest clearing”), and if so a doublet of thwaite. May however simply be onomatopoeic or sound-symbolic.

TWIGS.d: Plural of TWIG: A small thin branch of a tree or bush.
TWIGS.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English twig, twyg, twigge, twygge, from Old English twigg, twicg, from Proto-West Germanic *twiggu (“small twig, shoot”), apparently a diminutive of Proto-West Germanic *twig (“branch, twig”) (whence also Old English twiġ and twiġa), from Proto-Germa...

TWINS.d: Plural of TWIN: Either of two people (or, less commonly, animals) who shared the same uterus at the same time; one who was born at the same birth as a sibling.
TWINS.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English twinne, twynne, from Old English ġetwin, ġetwinn (“twin, multiple”, noun) and twinn (“twin, two-fold, double, two by two”, adjective), from Proto-Germanic *twinjaz, *twinahz (“two each”), from Proto-Indo-European *dwino- (“twin”), from *dwóh₁ ...

TWITS.d: Plural of TWIT: To blame or reproach (someone), especially in a good-natured or teasing manner; also, to ridicule or tease (someone).
TWITS.e:
PIE word
 *h₂éd
The verb is an apheretic form of atwite (“(obsolete) to blame, reproach”), from Middle English atwiten (“to attribute (something) to someone; to blame (something) on someone; to accuse or charge (someone) with something; to speak ill of; to taunt”), from Old Engli...

TYKES.d: Plural of TYKE: A mongrel dog.
TYKES.e:
From Middle English tike, tyke, from Old Norse tík (“female dog”), from Proto-Germanic *tīkō. Compare Icelandic tík, Faroese tík, and Swedish tik, all meaning “bitch”.
Sense 5 (“Roman Catholic”) is an alteration of taig, and was first used in writing in the early 20ᵗʰ century.

TYPED.d: Past tense of TYPE: A grouping based on shared characteristics; a class.
TYPED.e: From Middle English type (“symbol, figure, emblem”), from Latin typus, from Ancient Greek τύπος (túpos, “mark, impression, type”), from τύπτω (túptō, “I strike, beat”).

TYPES.d: Plural of TYPE: A grouping based on shared characteristics; a class.
TYPES.e: From Middle English type (“symbol, figure, emblem”), from Latin typus, from Ancient Greek τύπος (túpos, “mark, impression, type”), from τύπτω (túptō, “I strike, beat”).

TYPOS.d: Plural of TYPO: A typographical error.
