TYRED.e: The Oxford English Dictionary suggests that the word derives from attire, while other sources suggest a connection with the verb to tie. George Sturt in The Wheelwright's Shop (1923) makes a case for the latter derivation in that the metal tyre ('tyer') pulled the wooden wagon wh...

TYRES.d: Plural of TYRE: The ring-shaped protective covering around a wheel which is usually made of rubber or plastic composite and is either pneumatic or solid.
TYRES.e: The Oxford English Dictionary suggests that the word derives from attire, while other sources suggest a connection with the verb to tie. George Sturt in The Wheelwright's Shop (1923) makes a case for the latter derivation in that the metal tyre ('tyer') pulled the wooden wagon wh...

TYROS.d: Plural of TYRO: A beginner; a novice.
TYROS.e: From Latin tīrō (“young soldier, recruit”). In Medieval Latin the term was often spelt as tyro whence the English spelling is derived.

TZARS.d: Plural of TZAR: Alternative spelling of tsar.

ULNAS.d: Plural of ULNA: The bone of the forearm that extends from the elbow to the wrist on the side opposite to the thumb, corresponding to the fibula of the hind limb. Also, the corresponding bone in the forelimb of any vertebrate.
ULNAS.e: From Latin ulna (“elbow”). Doublet of ell.

UMBOS.d: Plural of UMBO: The boss of a shield, at or near the middle and usually projecting, sometimes in a sharp spike.
UMBOS.e: Borrowed from Latin umbō (“a shield boss”). Doublet of umbone.

UNCLE.e: From Old French oncle, from Latin avunculus.

UNCOS.e: From Scots unco, shortening of uncouth.

UNION.d: The act of joining; an organization.
UNION.e: From Old French union, from Latin ūniō.

UNITS.d: Plural of UNIT: Oneness, singularity, seen as a component of a whole number; a magnitude of one.
UNITS.e: Formerly unite, a later form of unity; see unity.

UREAS.d: Plural of UREA: A water-soluble organic compound, CO(NH₂)₂, formed by the metabolism of proteins and excreted in the urine.
UREAS.e: From New Latin, from French urée, from Ancient Greek οὖρον (oûron, “urine”).

URGED.d: Past tense of URGE: A strong desire; an itch to do something.

URGES.d: Plural of URGE: A strong desire; an itch to do something.

USERS.d: Plural of USER: One who uses or makes use of something, a consumer or client or an express or implied licensee (free user) or a trespasser.
USERS.e: From Middle English usere, equivalent to use + -er. Cognate with Scots usar, uiser (“user”).

USING.d: Present participle of USE: The act of using.
USING.e: Noun from Middle English use, from Old French us, from Latin ūsus (“use, custom, skill, habit”), from past participle stem of ūtor (“use”). Displaced native Middle English note (“use”) (see note) from Old English notu, Middle English nutte (“use”) from Old English nytt, Old Engli...

VAILS.d: Plural of VAIL: Profit; return; proceeds.
VAILS.e: From Middle English vayle, from Old French vail, from valoir (“to be worth”), from Latin valeō (“I am worth”).

VALES.e: From Middle English vale, from Old French val (“valley”), from Latin vallis, valles.

VAMPS.d: Plural of VAMP: The top part of a boot or shoe, above the sole and welt and in front of the ankle seam, that covers the instep and toes; the front part of an upper; the analogous part of a stocking.
VAMPS.e: From Middle English vaumpe, vaum-pei, vampe (“covering for the foot, perhaps a slipper or understocking; upper of a boot or shoe”), or from Anglo-Norman vampe, *vaumpé (“part of a stocking covering the top of the foot”), from Old French avantpied, avantpiet, variants of avantpié,...

VANED.d: Past tense of VANE: A weather vane.
VANED.e:
From Middle English vane, Southern Middle English variant of fane, from Old English fana (“cloth, banner, flag”), from Proto-West Germanic *fanō, from Proto-Germanic *fanô, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂n- (“something woven; weave; tissue; fabric; cloth”).
Cognate with Saterland ...

VANES.d: Plural of VANE: A weather vane.
VANES.e:
From Middle English vane, Southern Middle English variant of fane, from Old English fana (“cloth, banner, flag”), from Proto-West Germanic *fanō, from Proto-Germanic *fanô, from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂n- (“something woven; weave; tissue; fabric; cloth”).
Cognate with Saterland ...

VASTS.d: Plural of VAST: Very large or wide (literally or figuratively).
VASTS.e: From Middle French vaste, from Latin vastus (“void, immense”). Related to waste and German Wüste.

VEALS.d: Plural of VEAL: The flesh of a calf (i.e. a young bovine) used for food.
VEALS.e: From Middle English veel, from Anglo-Norman veel, from Latin vitellus, diminutive of vitulus (“calf”). Doublet of vitellus.

VEERS.d: Plural of VEER: To let out (a sail-line), to allow (a sheet) to run out.
VEERS.e: Borrowed from Middle Dutch vieren (“to slacken”).

VEILS.d: Plural of VEIL: Something hung up or spread out to hide or protect the face, or hide an object from view; usually of gauze, crepe, or similar diaphanous material.
VEILS.e: From Middle English veil, veyl, from Anglo-Norman and Old Northern French veil (“sail, veil, shroud”) (Francien Old French voil, French voile), Latin vēlum (“cloth, covering”). Displaced Middle English scleire, scleyre, sleyre, slyre (“veil”) (compare German Schleier). Doublet of...

VEINS.d: Plural of VEIN: A blood vessel that transports blood from the capillaries back to the heart.
VEINS.e: From Middle English veyne, borrowed from Anglo-Norman veine, from Latin vēna (“a blood-vessel; vein; artery”) of uncertain origin. See vēna for more. Doublet of vena. Displaced native edre, from ǣdre (whence edder).

VELDS.d: Plural of VELD: The open grassland or pastureland of South Africa and neighbouring countries.
VELDS.e: Borrowed from Afrikaans veld, or from its etymon Dutch veld (“field; open country”) (formerly spelled veldt), ultimately from Proto-Germanic *felþuz (“field, plain”), possibly from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₂- (“flat”). Doublet of field.

VENDS.d: Plural of VEND: Synonym of sell, now especially to sell through a vending machine.
VENDS.e: From French vendre, from Old French vendre, from Latin vendere, from vēnum (“(something for) sale”) + dare (“to give”).

VENTS.d: Plural of VENT: An opening through which gases, especially air, can pass.
VENTS.e: Partly from Middle French vent, from Latin ventus and partly from French éventer. Cognate with French vent and Spanish viento (“wind”) and ventana (“window”). Doublet of wind.

VERBS.d: Plural of VERB: A word that indicates an action, event, or state of being.
VERBS.e: From Middle English verbe, directly from Latin verbum (“word, verb”), reinforced by Old French verbe, from Proto-Indo-European *werdʰo-. Doublet of verve and word.

VERTS.d: Plural of VERT: A green colour, now only in heraldry; represented in engraving by diagonal parallel lines 45 degrees counter-clockwise.
VERTS.e: From Middle English vert, borrowed from Old French vert, from Vulgar Latin virdis, syncopated from Classical Latin viridis. Doublet of virid, which was borrowed directly from Latin.

VESTS.d: Plural of VEST: A sleeveless garment that buttons down the front, worn over a shirt, and often as part of a suit; a waistcoat.
VESTS.e: From French veste (“a vest, jacket”), from Latin vestis (“a garment, gown, robe, vestment, clothing, vesture”), from Proto-Indo-European *wéstis, from *wes- (“to be dressed”) (English wear). Cognate with Sanskrit वस्त्र (vastra) and Spanish vestir.

VEXED.d: Past tense of VEX: To annoy, irritate.
VEXED.e: From Middle English vexen, from Old French vexer, from Latin vexāre (“disturb, agitate, annoy”). Doublet of quake. Displaced native Old English dreċċan and gremman.

VEXES.d: Plural of VEX: To annoy, irritate.
VEXES.e: From Middle English vexen, from Old French vexer, from Latin vexāre (“disturb, agitate, annoy”). Doublet of quake. Displaced native Old English dreċċan and gremman.

VIALS.d: Plural of VIAL: A glass or plastic vessel or bottle, especially a small tube-shaped bottle used to store medicine, perfume or other chemicals.
VIALS.e: From Middle English vial, viole, a variant of fiole, phiole, phial (“small bowl or cup for liquids, etc.; flask”) [and other forms]: see further at phial. Doublet of phiale.

VIBES.d: Plural of VIBE: An atmosphere or aura felt to belong to a person, place or thing.
VIBES.e: Apocopic form of vibration, vibrator, etc.

VICED.d: Past tense of VICE: Bad or immoral behaviour.
VICED.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English vice, from Old French vice, from Latin vitium (“fault or blemish”). Displaced native Old English unþēaw.

VICES.d: Plural of VICE: Bad or immoral behaviour.
VICES.e:
PIE word
 *dwóh₁
From Middle English vice, from Old French vice, from Latin vitium (“fault or blemish”). Displaced native Old English unþēaw.

VIEWS.e: From Middle English vewe, from Anglo-Norman vewe, from Old French veue f (French vue f), feminine past participle of veoir (“to see”) (French voir). Cognate with Italian vedere, as well as Portuguese and Spanish ver. Doublet of veduta and vista.

VINED.d: Past tense of VINE: Any plant whose stem requires support and which climbs by tendrils or twining.
VINED.e: From Middle English vīne, from Anglo-Norman vigne, from Vulgar Latin vīnia, from Latin vīnea (“vines in a vineyard”), from vīneus (“related to wine”), from vīnum (“wine”), from Proto-Italic *wīnom, from Proto-Indo-European *wóyh₁nom (“vine, wine”), from *weh₁y- (“to twist, wrap”)...

VINES.d: Plural of VINE: Any plant whose stem requires support and which climbs by tendrils or twining.
VINES.e: From Middle English vīne, from Anglo-Norman vigne, from Vulgar Latin vīnia, from Latin vīnea (“vines in a vineyard”), from vīneus (“related to wine”), from vīnum (“wine”), from Proto-Italic *wīnom, from Proto-Indo-European *wóyh₁nom (“vine, wine”), from *weh₁y- (“to twist, wrap”)...

VIOLS.d: Plural of VIOL: A stringed instrument related to the violin family, but held in the lap between the legs like a cello, usually with C-holes, a flat back, a fretted neck and six strings, played with an underhanded bow hold.
VIOLS.e: Borrowed from Middle French viole, from Old French viol, from Old Occitan viola (modern Occitan viula), from Medieval Latin vitula (“stringed instrument”). Doublet of viola.

VISAS.d: Plural of VISA: A permit to enter and leave a country, normally issued by the authorities of the country to be visited.
VISAS.e: From 1831, "official signature or endorsement on a passport," from French visa, from Latin charta vīsa (“paper that has been seen”) from feminine perfect passive of Latin vidēre (“to see”). Compare vision, video, vista.

VISES.d: Plural of VIS: Force; energy; might; power.

VISIT.e: From Old French visiter, from Latin vīsitāre.

VIVAS.d: Plural of VIVA: Long live ... ! (used to express acclaim or support).
VIVAS.e: Borrowed from Spanish viva and Italian viva.

VOICE.e: From Old French vois, from Latin vōx.

VOIDS.d: Plural of VOID: Containing nothing; empty; not occupied or filled.
VOIDS.e: From Middle English voide, voyde, from Old French vuit, voide, vuide (modern vide), in turn from Vulgar Latin *vocitum, ultimately from Latin vacuus.

VOLED.d: Past tense of VOLE: Any of a large number of species of small rodents of the tribes Arvicolini, Ellobiusini, Clethrionomyini, Pliomyini, Phenacomyini and Prometheomyini.
VOLED.e: Borrowed from Norn vollj, from Old Norse vǫllr (“field”), from Proto-Germanic *walþuz (“forest”). The Orkney dialectal term vole mouse, lit. “field mouse”, was introduced to general English by George Barry in 1805; John Fleming in 1828 was first to refer to the creature by the ep...

VOLES.d: Plural of VOLE: Any of a large number of species of small rodents of the tribes Arvicolini, Ellobiusini, Clethrionomyini, Pliomyini, Phenacomyini and Prometheomyini.
VOLES.e: Borrowed from Norn vollj, from Old Norse vǫllr (“field”), from Proto-Germanic *walþuz (“forest”). The Orkney dialectal term vole mouse, lit. “field mouse”, was introduced to general English by George Barry in 1805; John Fleming in 1828 was first to refer to the creature by the ep...

VOLTS.d: Plural of VOLT: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of electrical potential and electromotive force (voltage); the potential difference across a conductor when a current of one ampere uses one watt of power. Symbol: V
VOLTS.e: Named after Italian physicist Alessandro Volta. For the surname, see Italian Volta.

VOTED.d: Past tense of VOTE: A formalized choice on legally relevant measures such as employment or appointment to office or a proceeding about a legal dispute.
VOTED.e: From Latin vōtum, a form of voveō (“I vow”) (cognate with Ancient Greek εὔχομαι (eúkhomai, “to vow”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁wegʷʰ- (“to promise, to vow”). Doublet of vow.

VOTES.d: Plural of VOTE: A formalized choice on legally relevant measures such as employment or appointment to office or a proceeding about a legal dispute.
VOTES.e: From Latin vōtum, a form of voveō (“I vow”) (cognate with Ancient Greek εὔχομαι (eúkhomai, “to vow”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁wegʷʰ- (“to promise, to vow”). Doublet of vow.

VOWED.d: Past tense of VOW: A solemn promise to perform some act, or behave in a specified manner, especially a promise to live and act in accordance with the rules of a religious order.
VOWED.e: Inherited from Middle English vowe, voue, that from Old French vut, in turn from Latin vōtum (“a promise, dedication, vow”), from vovēre (“to promise, vow”). Not related to avow. Doublet of vote.

WACKS.d: Plural of WACK: Annoyingly or disappointingly bad, in various senses; lousy, corny, cringy, uncool, messed up.
WACKS.e: Back-formation from wacky. Alternatively, possibly a blend of white + black, in the sense that it may appear black on the outside, but it's really white on the inside. Compare oreo.

WADED.d: Past tense of WADE: To walk through water or something that impedes progress.
WADED.e: From Middle English waden, from Old English wadan, from Proto-West Germanic *wadan, from Proto-Germanic *wadaną (“to go, pass through”), from Proto-Indo-European *weh₂dʰ- (“to go”). Cognates include Saterland Frisian waadje (“to wade”), West Frisian wâdzje (“to wade”), Dutch wade...

WADES.d: Plural of WADE: To walk through water or something that impedes progress.
WADES.e: From Middle English waden, from Old English wadan, from Proto-West Germanic *wadan, from Proto-Germanic *wadaną (“to go, pass through”), from Proto-Indo-European *weh₂dʰ- (“to go”). Cognates include Saterland Frisian waadje (“to wade”), West Frisian wâdzje (“to wade”), Dutch wade...

WAFTS.d: Plural of WAFT: To (cause to) float easily or gently through the air.
WAFTS.e:
From Middle English waften, of uncertain origin. Possibly from unattested Old English *wafettan, from wafian (“to wave”) + -ettan, or perhaps borrowed from Middle Dutch wachten (“to guard, provide for”).
See also German wabern (“to waft”), Faroese veiftra (“to wave”) and Icelandi...

WAGED.d: Past tense of WAGE: An amount of money paid to a worker for a specified quantity of work, usually calculated on an hourly basis and expressed in an amount of money per hour.
WAGED.e: From Middle English wage, from Anglo-Norman wage, from Old Northern French wage, a northern variant of Old French gauge, guage (whence modern French gage), Medieval Latin wadium, from Frankish *waddī (cognate with Old English wedd), from Proto-Germanic *wadją (“pledge”), from Pro...

WAGES.d: Plural of WAGE: An amount of money paid to a worker for a specified quantity of work, usually calculated on an hourly basis and expressed in an amount of money per hour.
WAGES.e: From Middle English wage, from Anglo-Norman wage, from Old Northern French wage, a northern variant of Old French gauge, guage (whence modern French gage), Medieval Latin wadium, from Frankish *waddī (cognate with Old English wedd), from Proto-Germanic *wadją (“pledge”), from Pro...

WAIFS.d: Plural of WAIF: An article of movable property which has been found, and of which the owner is not known, such as goods washed up on a beach or thrown away by an absconding thief; such items belong to the Crown, which may grant the right of ownership to them to a lord of a manor.
WAIFS.e: The noun is derived from Late Middle English weif (“ownerless property subject to seizure and forfeiture; the right of such seizure and forfeiture; revenues obtained from such seizure and forfeiture”) [and other forms], from Anglo-Norman waif, weif [and other forms] (compare Angl...

WAILS.d: Plural of WAIL: To cry out, as in sorrow or anguish.
WAILS.e:
c. 1300, Middle English weilen, waylen (“to sob, cry, wail”), from Old Norse væla (“to wail”), from væ, vei (“woe”), from Proto-Germanic *wai (whence also Old English wā (“woe”) (English woe)), from Proto-Indo-European *wáy.
The verb is first attested in the intransitive sense; t...

WAINS.d: Plural of WAIN: A wagon; a four-wheeled cart for hauling loads, usually pulled by horses or oxen.
WAINS.e:
From Middle English wayn, from Old English wæġn, from Proto-West Germanic *wagn, from Proto-Germanic *wagnaz, from Proto-Indo-European *woǵʰnos, from *weǵʰ- (“to bring, transport”). Doublet of wagon, borrowed from Middle Dutch.
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian wein, Dutch wagen...

WAITS.d: Plural of WAIT: To delay movement or action until some event or time; to remain neglected or in readiness.
WAITS.e: From Middle English waiten, from Anglo-Norman waiter, waitier (compare French guetter from Old French gaitier, guaitier), from Frankish *wahtwēn (“to watch, guard”), derivative of Frankish *wahtu (“guard, watch”), from Proto-Germanic *wahtwō (“guard, watch”), from Proto-Indo-Euro...

WAKAS.d: Plural of WAKA: A kind of classical Japanese poem.
WAKAS.e: Borrowed from Japanese 和歌 (waka), from Middle Chinese 和 (ɣwa), a gloss for 倭 (ʔwa, “Japan”) + 歌 (ka, “song”).

WAKED.d: Past tense of WAKE: (often followed by up) To stop sleeping.
WAKED.e:
A merger of two verbs of similar form and meaning:
* Middle English waken, Old English wacan, from Proto-West Germanic *wakan, from Proto-Germanic *wakaną.
* Middle English wakien, Old English wacian, from Proto-West Germanic *wakēn, from Proto-Germanic *wakāną.

WAKES.d: Plural of WAKE: (often followed by up) To stop sleeping.
WAKES.e:
A merger of two verbs of similar form and meaning:
* Middle English waken, Old English wacan, from Proto-West Germanic *wakan, from Proto-Germanic *wakaną.
* Middle English wakien, Old English wacian, from Proto-West Germanic *wakēn, from Proto-Germanic *wakāną.

WALED.d: Past tense of WALE: A ridge or low barrier.
WALED.e: The noun is from Middle English wāle (“planking, welt”), from Old English walu (“ridge, bank; rib, comb (of helmet); metal ridge on top of helmet; weal, mark of a blow”), from Proto-Germanic *waluz (“stick, root”), from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, wind, roll”). Akin to ...

WALES.d: Plural of WALE: A ridge or low barrier.
WALES.e: The noun is from Middle English wāle (“planking, welt”), from Old English walu (“ridge, bank; rib, comb (of helmet); metal ridge on top of helmet; weal, mark of a blow”), from Proto-Germanic *waluz (“stick, root”), from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, wind, roll”). Akin to ...

WALKS.d: Plural of WALK: To move on the feet by alternately setting each foot (or pair or group of feet, in the case of animals with four or more feet) forward, with at least one foot on the ground at all times. Compare run.
WALKS.e: From Middle English walken (“to move, walk, roll, turn, revolve, toss”), a conflation of Old English wealcan (“to move round, revolve, roll, turn, toss”) (ġewealcan (“to go, traverse”)) and Old English wealcian (“to curl, roll up”); both from Proto-West Germanic *walkan, from Pro...

WALLS.d: Plural of WALL: A rampart of earth, stones etc. built up for defensive purposes.
WALLS.e: From Middle English wal, from Old English weall (“wall, dike, earthwork, rampart, dam, rocky shore, cliff”), from Proto-West Germanic *wall (“wall, rampart, entrenchment”), from Latin vallum (“wall, rampart, entrenchment, palisade”), from Proto-Indo-European *welH- (“to turn, win...

WANDS.d: Plural of WAND: A hand-held narrow rod, usually used for pointing or instructing, or as a traditional emblem of authority.
WANDS.e: From Middle English wand, wond, from Old Norse vǫndr (“switch, twig”), from Proto-Germanic *wanduz (“rod”), from Proto-Indo-European *wendʰ- (“to turn, twist, wind, braid”). Cognate with Icelandic vendi (“wand”), Danish vånd (“wand, switch”), German Wand (“wall, septum”), Gothic ...

WANED.d: Past tense of WANE: A gradual diminution in power, value, intensity etc.
WANED.e:
From Middle English wane, from Old English wana (“defect, shortage”), from Proto-West Germanic *wanō, from Proto-Germanic *wanô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weh₂- (“to leave, abandon; empty, deserted”).
Cognates
See also wan-, want, and waste. Compare also Dutch waan (“insanity”)...

WANES.d: Plural of WANE: A gradual diminution in power, value, intensity etc.
WANES.e:
From Middle English wane, from Old English wana (“defect, shortage”), from Proto-West Germanic *wanō, from Proto-Germanic *wanô, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weh₂- (“to leave, abandon; empty, deserted”).
Cognates
See also wan-, want, and waste. Compare also Dutch waan (“insanity”)...

WANTS.d: Plural of WANT: To wish for or desire (something); to feel a need or desire for; to crave, hanker, or demand.
WANTS.e: From Middle English wanten (“to lack, to need”), from Old Norse vanta (“to lack”), from Proto-Germanic *wanatōną (“to be wanting, lack”), from *wanô (“lack, deficiency”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁weh₂- (“empty”). Cognate with Middle High German wan (“not full, empty”), Middle ...

WARDS.d: Plural of WARD: A warden; a guard; a guardian or watchman.
WARDS.e: From Middle English ward, from Old English weard (“keeper, watchman, guard, guardian, protector; lord, king; possessor”), from Proto-Germanic *warduz (“guard, keeper”), from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to heed, defend”). Cognate with Dutch waard, German Wart.

WARED.d: Past tense of WARE: Goods or a type of goods offered for sale or use.
WARED.e:
From Middle English ware, from Old English waru, from Proto-West Germanic *waru, from Proto-Germanic *warō (“attention”) as in beware, in the sense of “an object of care, a valuable”, from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to watch, keep guard”), whence also ward.
Cognate with Saterlan...

WARES.d: Plural of WARE: Goods or a type of goods offered for sale or use.
WARES.e:
From Middle English ware, from Old English waru, from Proto-West Germanic *waru, from Proto-Germanic *warō (“attention”) as in beware, in the sense of “an object of care, a valuable”, from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to watch, keep guard”), whence also ward.
Cognate with Saterlan...

WARMS.d: Plural of WARM: Of a somewhat high temperature, often but not always connoting that the high temperature is pleasant rather than uncomfortable.
WARMS.e: From Middle English warm, werm, from Old English wearm, from Proto-West Germanic *warm, from Proto-Germanic *warmaz, either from Proto-Indo-European *wór-mo-s, from *wer- (“to burn”), or Proto-Indo-European *gʷʰor-mo-s, from the root *gʷʰer- (“warm, hot”). Cognate with West Frisi...

WARNS.d: Plural of WARN: To make (someone) aware of (something impending); especially:
WARNS.e: From Middle English warnen, warnien (“to warn; admonish”), from Old English warnian (“to take heed; warn”), from Proto-Germanic *warnōną (“to warn; take heed”), from Proto-Indo-European *wer- (“to be aware; give heed”). Cognate with Dutch waarnen (obsolete), German Low German war...

WARPS.d: Plural of WARP: The state, quality, or condition of being twisted, physically or mentally:
WARPS.e:
From Middle English warp, werp, from Old English wearp, warp (“a warp, threads stretched lengthwise in a loom, twig, osier”), from Proto-Germanic *warpą (“a warp”), from Proto-Indo-European *werb- (“to turn, bend”).
Cognate with Middle Dutch warp, Middle Low German warp, German w...

WARTS.d: Plural of WART: A type of deformed growth occurring on the skin caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV).
WARTS.e: From Middle English warte, werte, from Old English wearte, from Proto-West Germanic *wartā, from Proto-Germanic *wartǭ. Cognate with Dutch wrat, German Warze, Hunsrik Waarz, Swedish vårta and Danish vorte.

WASPS.d: Plural of WASP: Any of many types of stinging flying insect resembling a hornet.
WASPS.e:
Etymology tree
Proto-Indo-European *webʰ-
Proto-Indo-European *wóbʰseh₂
Proto-Germanic *wapsō
Proto-West Germanic *wapsu
Old English wæps
Middle English wasp
English wasp
Inherited from Middle English wasp, waspe, waps, from Old English wæsp, wæps, from Proto-West Germanic *wapsu...

WASTS.d: Plural of WAST: second-person singular simple past indicative of be; wert.
WASTS.e: From Late Middle English wast; equivalent to was + -est.

WATER.d: A transparent liquid essential for life.

WATTS.d: Plural of WATT: In the International System of Units, the derived unit of power; the power of a system in which one joule of energy is transferred per second. Symbol: W
WATTS.e: Named after Scottish engineer James Watt. For the surname, see Watt.

WAVED.d: Past tense of WAVE: To move back and forth repeatedly and somewhat loosely.
WAVED.e:
From Middle English waven, from Old English wafian (“to wave, fluctuate, waver in mind, wonder”), from Proto-West Germanic *wabōn, from Proto-Germanic *wabōną, *wabjaną (“to wander, sway”), from Proto-Indo-European *webʰ- (“to move to and from, wander”).
Cognate with Middle High ...

WAXED.e:
From Middle English wax, from Old English weax, from Proto-Germanic *wahsą, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *woḱ-so-.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Woaks (“wax”), West Frisian waaks (“wax”), Dutch was (“wax”), German Wachs (“wax”), German Low German Wass (“wax”), Luxembourgish...

WAXES.e:
From Middle English wax, from Old English weax, from Proto-Germanic *wahsą, possibly from Proto-Indo-European *woḱ-so-.
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Woaks (“wax”), West Frisian waaks (“wax”), Dutch was (“wax”), German Wachs (“wax”), German Low German Wass (“wax”), Luxembourgish...

WEALS.e: From Middle English wele, from Old English wela (“wellness, welfare, prosperity, riches, well-being, wealth”), from Proto-West Germanic *welō, from Proto-Germanic *walô (“well-being, wellness, weal”). Cognate with German Wohl, Danish vel, Swedish väl.

WEANS.d: Plural of WEAN: To cease giving breast milk to an offspring; to accustom and reconcile (a child or young animal) to a want or deprivation of mother's milk; to take from the breast or udder.
WEANS.e:
From Middle English wenen, from Old English wenian (“to accustom; habituate; train; prepare; make fit”), from Proto-West Germanic *wannjan, from Proto-Germanic *wanjaną (“to make wont; accustom”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to strive for; wish; love”).
Cognate with Dutch ...

WEARS.d: Plural of WEAR: To have on:
WEARS.e:
Inherited from Middle English weren, werien, from Old English werian (“to clothe, cover over; put on, wear, use; stock (land)”), from Proto-West Germanic *waʀjan, from Proto-Germanic *wazjaną (“to clothe”), from Proto-Indo-European *wes- (“to dress, put on (clothes)”).
Cognate to...

WEEDS.d: Plural of WEED: Any plant unwanted at the place where and at the time when it is growing.
WEEDS.e:
From Middle English weed, weod, from Old English wēod (“weed”), from Proto-West Germanic *weud (“weed”).
Cognate with Saterland Frisian Jood (“weed”), West Frisian wjûd (“weed”), Dutch wied (“unwanted plant, weed”), German Low German Weed (“weed”), Old High German wiota (“fern”)....

WEEKS.d: Plural of WEEK: Any period of seven consecutive days.

YAWPS.d: Plural of YAWP: To yelp, or utter a sharp cry, as in intense pain, or another raucous noise.
YAWPS.e: From Middle English yolpen, of imitative origin.

YEARS.d: Plural of YEAR: A period of time akin to the time taken for the Earth to undergo a full cycle of seasons.
YEARS.e:
From Middle English yeer, yere, from Old English ġēar (“year”), from Proto-West Germanic *jār, from Proto-Germanic *jērą (“year”), from Proto-Indo-European *yóh₁r̥ (“year, spring”). Doublet of hora and hour.
Cognates
Cognate with Scots year (“year”), North Frisian iir, Jaar, juar...

YELLS.d: Plural of YELL: To shout; holler; make a loud sound with the voice, especially to express intense emotions such as anger or excitement.
YELLS.e: From Middle English ȝellen, yellen, from Old English ġiellan, from Proto-Germanic *gellaną. Cognate with Saterland Frisian gälje (“to yell”), Dutch gillen (“to yell”), German Low German gellen (“to yell”), German gellen (“to yell”).

YELPS.d: Plural of YELP: An abrupt, high-pitched noise or utterance.
YELPS.e: From Middle English ȝelp, yelp, from Old English ġielp (“boasting, arrogance, pride”), from Proto-West Germanic *gelp, from Proto-Germanic *gelpą (“boasting”), from Proto-Indo-European *gʰel- (“to shout”).

YETIS.d: Plural of YETI: An unidentified humanoid animal said to live in the Himalayas.
YETIS.e: Borrowed from Tibetan གཡའ་དྲེད (g.ya' dred, “rock bear”), compound of གཡའ (g.ya', “rocky or rocky place”) and དྲེད (dred, “bear”).

YOGAS.d: Plural of YOGA: Any of several Hindu or Buddhist disciplines aimed at training the consciousness for a state of perfect spiritual insight and tranquillity; especially a system of exercises practiced to promote control of the body and mind.
YOGAS.e: Borrowed from Sanskrit योग (yóga, “yoking, union”), from Proto-Indo-Aryan *yáwgas, from Proto-Indo-Iranian *yáwgas, from Proto-Indo-European *yéwg-o-s, from *yewg- (“to join”) (whence also yoke).

YOGIS.d: Plural of YOGI: A devotee or adherent of yoga.
YOGIS.e: From Hindi योगी (yogī), from Sanskrit योगिन् (yogin), from the verbal root yuj (class 7 present युनक्ति (yunakti, “to connect”)), from Proto-Indo-European *yugóm.

YOKED.d: Past tense of YOKE: Senses relating to a frame around the neck.
YOKED.e:
From Middle English yok, yoke, ȝok from Old English ġeoc (“yoke”), from Proto-Germanic *juką (“yoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *yugóm (“yoke”), from *yewg- (“to join; to tie together, yoke”). Doublet of yuga, jugum, yoga and possibly yogh.
Senses 3.1 (“area of arable land”) and ...

YOKES.d: Plural of YOKE: Senses relating to a frame around the neck.
YOKES.e:
From Middle English yok, yoke, ȝok from Old English ġeoc (“yoke”), from Proto-Germanic *juką (“yoke”), from Proto-Indo-European *yugóm (“yoke”), from *yewg- (“to join; to tie together, yoke”). Doublet of yuga, jugum, yoga and possibly yogh.
Senses 3.1 (“area of arable land”) and ...

YOLKS.d: Plural of YOLK: The yellow, spherical part of an egg that is surrounded by the white albumen, and serves as nutriment for the growing young.
YOLKS.e: From Middle English yolke, yelke, ȝolke, ȝelke, from Old English ġeolca, ġeoloca, ġioleca (“the yellow part, yolk”), from ġeolu (“yellow”).

YONIS.d: Plural of YONI: The vulva or vagina, or a symbol of them, especially as an object of veneration within certain types of Hinduism, Buddhism, and other cultures.

YORES.d: Plural of YORE: A time long past.
YORES.e: From Middle English yore, yoare, yare, ȝore, ȝare, ȝeare, from Old English ġeāra (“long ago”), of unclear origin but probably from Proto-Germanic *jērǫ̂ (literally “of years”), the genitive plural of Proto-Germanic *jērą (“year”). More at year.

YOUNG.d: In an early period of life.

YOURS.d: Plural of YOUR: Belonging to you; of you; related to you (singular; one owner).
YOURS.e: From Middle English your, youre, ȝour, ȝoure, from Old English ēower, īower (“your”, plural), from Proto-West Germanic *iuwar, from Proto-Germanic *izweraz. Cognate with Saterland Frisian jou (“your”), Dutch jouw (“your”), German Low German jo, jos (“your”), German euer (“your”, ...

YOWLS.d: Plural of YOWL: A prolonged, loud cry, like the sound of an animal; a wail; a howl.
YOWLS.e: From Middle English youlen, goulen, from Old Norse gaula (“to low, bellow, howl, scream”), related to Icelandic gaula (“to yell, howl, roar”), Faroese geyla (“to bawl, squall, shout, yell, bellow”), Norwegian gaule (“to roar, howl, whine, weep noisily”), dialectal Swedish gjöla, ...

YUANS.d: Plural of YUAN: The basic unit of money in China.
YUANS.e: From Mandarin 元 (yuán), from 圓／圆 (yuán, “circle > round coin”) referring to the piece of eight. Compare Japanese 円(えん) (en), Korean 원(圓) (won). Doublet of yen and won.

YUCKS.d: Plural of YUCK: Uttered to indicate disgust usually toward an objectionable taste or odour.
YUCKS.e: Perhaps imitative. Akin to Dutch jakkes (“disgusting”). First appeared in the 1960s. Compare also Scots yeuk (“anything that disgusts”), Middle English yuke (“an itchy skin disease" akin to middle Dutch "joke" and modern Dutch "jeuk"”) .

YUGAS.d: Plural of YUGA: In Hindu theology, a period of a few hundred or thousand years, or an epoch or era within a cycle of four ages: the Satya Yuga (or Krita Yuga), the Dvapara Yuga, the Treta Yuga and finally the Kali Yuga, with lengths ranging from 432,000 to 1,728,000 years.
YUGAS.e: From Sanskrit युग (yuga). Doublet of yoke.

YURTS.d: Plural of YURT: A large, round, semi-permanent tent with vertical walls and a conical roof, usually associated with Central Asia and Mongolia (where it is known as a ger).
YURTS.e: Borrowed from French yourte or German Jurte, from Russian ю́рта (júrta, “yurt”), from a Turkic language, from Proto-Turkic *yūrt (“dwelling place”).

ZEALS.d: Plural of ZEAL: The fervour or tireless devotion for a person, cause, or ideal and determination in its furtherance; diligent enthusiasm; powerful interest.
ZEALS.e: From Middle English zele, from Old French zel, from Late Latin zēlus, from Ancient Greek ζῆλος (zêlos, “zeal, jealousy”), from Proto-Indo-European *yeh₂- (“to search”). Related to jealous.

ZEBUS.d: Plural of ZEBU: A domesticated ox native to Asia and Africa, having a large fleshy hump on its back and a dewlap (Bos taurus indicus).
ZEBUS.e: From French zébu, from Tibetan (perhaps མཛོ་པོ (mdzo po, “male bull–yak hybrid”), whence also zobo).

ZEINS.d: Plural of ZEIN: A protein derived from corn/maize, having many industrial applications.

ZEROS.d: Plural of ZERO: The cardinal number occurring before one and that denotes no quantity or amount at all, represented in Arabic numerals as 0.
ZEROS.e: Collectively borrowed from Early Modern Spanish zero, Middle French zero, and (their etymon) Old Italian zero, from Medieval Latin zēphirum, from Arabic صِفْر (ṣifr, “nothing; cipher”), itself calqued from Sanskrit शून्य (śūnyá, “void; nothingness”). Doublet of cipher and chiffre...

ZESTS.d: Plural of ZEST: The outer skin of a citrus fruit, used as a flavouring or garnish.

ZETAS.d: Plural of ZETA: The sixth letter of the modern Greek alphabet (Ζ, ζ) preceded by epsilon (Ε, ε) and followed by eta, (Η, η); or the seventh letter in the ancient Greek alphabet, in which it is preceded by digamma (Ϝ, ϝ)
ZETAS.e: From the Ancient Greek ζῆτα (zêta). Doublet of zed.

ZINCS.d: Plural of ZINC: A chemical element (symbol Zn) with an atomic number of 30, a blue-silvery metal that is slightly brittle at room temperature and tarnishes slightly in moist air.
ZINCS.e: Borrowed from German Zink, related to Zinke (“point, prong”), from Middle High German zinke, from Old High German zinko (“prong, tine”), allied to zint (“a jag, point”), from Proto-Germanic *tindaz (“prong, pinnacle”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₃dónts (“tooth, projection”). Cogn...

ZINGS.d: Plural of ZING: A short high-pitched humming sound, such as that made by a bullet or vibrating string.

ZITIS.d: Plural of ZITI: A type of macaroni pasta in the form of long smooth hollow tubes.
ZITIS.e: From Italian zite or ziti, plural of zita, zito, from a Southern (Neapolitan or Sicilian) word likely from Vulgar Latin pittitus (“small, worthless”), originally denoting a young boy or girl. See also petty.

ZONED.d: Past tense of ZONE: Each of the five regions of the earth's surface into which it was divided by climatic differences, namely the torrid zone (between the tropics), two temperate zones (between the tropics and the polar circles), and two frigid zones (within the polar circles).
ZONED.e: From Latin zōna, from Ancient Greek ζώνη (zṓnē, “girdle, belt”).

ZONES.d: Plural of ZONE: Each of the five regions of the earth's surface into which it was divided by climatic differences, namely the torrid zone (between the tropics), two temperate zones (between the tropics and the polar circles), and two frigid zones (within the polar circles).
ZONES.e: From Latin zōna, from Ancient Greek ζώνη (zṓnē, “girdle, belt”).

ZOOMS.d: Plural of ZOOM: A humming noise from something moving very fast.
ZOOMS.e: Uncertain. The verb was first attested c. 1892, as a noun in 1918 and as an interjection in 1942. Apparently related to Scots soom (“to buzz, hum”), dialectal English and Scots soom, swoom, sweem (“to spin or twirl at high speed”). Compare also dialectal English sweem (“to swoon,...

ZULUS.d: Plural of ZULU: A member of an African ethnic group living mainly in the KwaZulu-Natal Province in eastern South Africa.
